<SLUG> BC-FB0-KENNETH-DAVIS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FORMER BILLS PLAYER DAVIS TEACHING LESSONS LEARNED AS HIGH SCHOOL
COACH
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MIKE JONES 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS _ Kenneth Davis is the first to admit that he could well
be doing other things than taking on a relatively monumental task
as head coach at Bishop Dunne _ a small, Catholic-church affiliated
high school in South Oak Cliff that hasn't had a winning football
season this decade.
</P>
<P>
   Financially secure after nine NFL seasons with the Green Bay
Packers and Buffalo Bills, the former TCU All-America running back
(1984) hasn't returned to the game he loves seeking glory or
support for his wife and two daughters.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't get rich coaching high school football,'' Davis said
with a laugh. ``If I needed money, I'd be down there at I-35 and
Laureland turning bolts with my brothers at the shop \RDozen Davis
Automotive\S.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most of all, I wanted to get back close to the game. I could
be scouting for an NFL team right now, but I'm tired of living out
of a suitcase, and I want to be with my family. I'm enjoying what
I'm doing. And most of all, I have a lot of love and compassion for
my kids.
</P>
<P>
   ``This program hasn't had a winning season in almost 10 years,
so I've got a long road to go down. But I like the odds I'm up
against.''
</P>
<P>
   Davis, 36, retired from the NFL in 1994. During the next three
years, he said he ``mostly slept and rested my body.'' But he also
found time to fulfill a pledge to his mother. On May 11, 1996, he
walked across a stage and received his diploma from TCU.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was an emotional time for me,'' Davis said. ``It was the
first time since the incident at TCU that I had walked around the
campus. I actually had tears in my eyes because of so many of the
things that had transpired there. Now, I see all these young kids
with so much in front of them ...''
</P>
<P>
   The incident. As much as Kenneth Davis will be remembered as the
first Horned Frogs All-American since Bob Lilly (1959) and the
driving force in the 1984 Bluebonnet Bowl season (8-4), so too is
he linked with the scandal that broke in September 1985. He was a
central figure in the exposure of numerous NCAA violations that
included an alumni-sponsored slush fund that dealt weekly payments
to players and resulted in loss of scholarships, television money
and three years of probation.
</P>
<P>
   Davis left school the night the scandal broke, after one game of
his senior season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I eventually made peace with myself over it,'' Davis said.
``But I don't think it will ever go away. I sit back and think I
had a chance to win the Heisman Trophy _ I had the heart and the
ability _ and know I can never go back and do that again.''
</P>
<P>
   As a generation has passed, the memory of that time lives on
only in the minds of those who were aware.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't know anything about that,'' Dunne quarterback Myron
Hawthorne said, ``until coach Davis told us about it.''
</P>
<P>
   Rather than hide the skeleton in his closet, Davis has used the
incident in his lesson plan for life.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's good to let kids know that we're not all perfect,'' Davis
said. ``We've all made mistakes, had faults in our lives. I try to
convey to them that it's all right to make mistakes; you just try
to limit them. And you can have your ups and downs and still be
successful in life. I've had my ups and downs and I want to share
them with my kids.''
</P>
<P>
   Davis is in only his second year of coaching. He spent last
season as offensive coordinator at a private academy in his wife's
hometown, Alexandria, La. When Dunne officials decided to make a
coaching change, Dunne alumni with TCU connections pushed the idea
of interviewing Davis.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were looking for new energy, and Kenneth was the perfect
fit,'' Dunne athletic director Stephen Guerrero said.
</P>
<P>
   The team has won only once in five games this season. But
Guerrero said Davis' fledgling tenure has already shown results.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kenneth is very energetic, very smart and he knows his
stuff,'' Guerrero said. ``I've already noticed that the kids play
with fundamentals that were previously lacking. They have really
taken to him, but he's very much the disciplinarian.
</P>
<P>
   ``And we've had a lot of \Rparents of perspective students\S who
have called or come by to visit just because Kenneth is the coach.
We've also begun to tap into some local businesses who will sponsor
scholarships for kids who can maintain a 3.0 grade-point average
and are also excellent on the field. We stress the scholar-athlete.
</P>
<P>
   ``Word is getting around that Kenneth is here and it's helping
the school. He's a big supporter of the entire program.''
</P>
<P>
   Davis dreams of building a championship program. Though he and
other teachers and administrators operate on one-year contracts,
Guerrero says Dunne is committed to doing everything it can to keep
Davis long enough for him to accomplish that goal. But Kenneth has
other missions.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope I can instill in my kids just one trickle of
information that can help them move on in life,'' he said. ``The
self-discipline they need not only on the football field, but in
life. To have respect for people, for the game and for their
bodies. And that there are more good things in life than bad.''
Kenneth Davis profile A former all-state running back from Temple,
Davis gained 1,611 yards in 1984 at TCU to break Jim Swink's
29-year-old school record for rushing yards in a season. He led the
nation with an average of 7.64 yards per carry and was third
nationally with 146.5 yards per game and with 17 touchdowns. He had
seven runs of more than 50 yards and finished fifth in the Heisman
Trophy balloting. He played in four Super Bowls with the Buffalo
Bills.
</P>
</TEXT>
