A5664 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-MOORE-COLUMN14-CO     10-14 0582
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-MOORE-COLUMN14-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    These Yanks aren't as good as their hype
 &HT;    By Terence Moore
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ These aren't the '27 Yankees. These aren't even the
'96 Yankees. These are nothing more than the lucky owners of a
pretty record during the regular season that doesn't mean much in
October.
</P>
<P>
   These Yankees barely managed a second trip to the World Series
in three years Tuesday night at Yankee Stadium with a 9-5 victory
against a team without a No. 1 starter, with barely a No. 2 starter
and with a manager who makes stranger moves in the postseason than
the old Bobby Cox.
</P>
<P>
   So did Hargrove really start Richie Sexson over David Justice
Sunday on a hunch? And why did Hargrove order his hottest hitter in
Omar Vizquel Tuesday to attempt a sacrifice bunt with two strikes
in the first?
</P>
<P>
   Vizquel struck out.
</P>
<P>
   In sum, these Yankees can be had by the Braves, by the Padres,
by anybody who doesn't believe the hype. These Yankees carried a
.198 batting average into this decisive Game 6 of the American
League Championship Series. Even so, they were rolling to their
35th pennant after one of their rare offensive explosions during
the playoffs gave them a 6-0 lead through five innings, but then
came the sixth.
</P>
<P>
   After the Indians scored five runs that included a grand slam,
they changed the focus of the Yankees' howling faithful. They
definitely were howling. They were howling over the Yankees in
general (both with delight and disgust) and over David Justice in
particular.
</P>
<P>
   As for Justice, it's one thing for this former Braves slugger to
tell the truth about the sitting dead at Atlanta sporting events.
It's another for him to use his honest tongue to trigger World War
III inside the Yankee Nation.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, the Yankees' David Wells fired the first shots when he
didn't have to. Among the prerequisites for being a pro athlete is
having the ability to become deaf on the road. Nobody apparently
told Wells.
</P>
<P>
   Since pitching the Yankees to a 3-2 lead in the series Sunday in
Cleveland, Wells still fumes while ranking Indians fans with the
scum of Lake Erie. That's because some of those Indians fans spent
Game 5 yelling ugly things about Wells' deceased mother.
</P>
<P>
   Justice acknowledged that those Indians fans were out of line,
but he also mentioned that they definitely learned how not to act
from their New York counterparts.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've heard everything about my mother, about my history,
too,'' Justice said. ``We all know, everybody knows, how rough they
can be. They can't get any rougher, unless they show up with
Uzis.''
</P>
<P>
   Let's just say Justice's ears are still ringing from the jeers
he received whenever his No. 23 came into view. A group of fans
even dropped pictures featuring an Uzi over the edge of the upper
deck whenever a Yankee pitcher struck out an Indian batter.
</P>
<P>
   Those in the Yankee Nation were battling the enemy in ways
foreign to their ancestors. During the 1978 World Series, the
Dodgers were pelted by batteries. Three years ago, Mariners manager
Lou Piniella pulled his team off the field during a Division Series
game, because of objects thrown its way. Once, the Indians' Mel
Hall had a frozen chicken tossed at him.
</P>
<P>
   This time, they mainly threw words _ at the Indians and at the
Yankees.
</P>
<P>
   Terence Moore writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga. E-mail: tlmajc(at)aol.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
