<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-USC-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BACKFIELD A WORK IN PROGRESS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SCOTT WOLF  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ USC's tailback situation remains jumbled, as
injuries and fumbles continue to affect the depth chart.
</P>
<P>
   Tailback Chad Morton (sore back) ran some light plays Tuesday,
his first practice in pads since the Florida State game more than
two weeks ago but hardly looked ready to play a game.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's far better, but I can't get too excited just yet,'' USC
coach Paul Hackett said. ``I'm not willing to say yet that Chad is
back.''
</P>
<P>
   Morton seemed unsure if he would be able to play Saturday
against Washington State.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know the percentage I'm at, but I'm really looking
forward (to playing),'' Morton said. ``I'm healing up and it's
looking pretty good. The turf will be pretty hard so I'd probably
get hurt if I land on it. I can't do anything about it but tighten
up and play on it.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, coaches decided that freshman Frank Strong will
receive considerably fewer carries this week, thanks to his
penchant for fumbling. Strong, who strained his knee Tuesday, has
fumbled three times in the past three games.
</P>
<P>
   With Morton ailing and Strong's stock falling, that leaves
Petros Papadakis as the starter, but Hackett said that junior
Jabari Jackson would also get a chance to play against Washington
State. Jackson ran some plays with the first team Tuesday, although
he has only had three carries this season.
</P>
<P>
   Hackett praised Papadakis, who gained 118 yards against Cal.
</P>
<P>
   ``This guy took a step to make up for Chad and that makes a
difference,'' Hackett said. ``That means we have a semblance of a
running game even without Chad.''
</P>
<P>
   __ Parker repents: Wide receiver Larry Parker said he had
trouble sleeping and nearly made himself sick thinking about the
personal-foul penalty he received against Cal, which negated a
58-yard touchdown run by Papadakis.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that was the stupidest thing I've done in my whole
life,'' Parker said. ``I can't believe I did it.''
</P>
<P>
   USC led 31-18 at the time but fumbled two plays later and Cal
scored 14 straight points to win the game.
</P>
<P>
   Parker said he hit Cal's Nate Geldermann from behind, about
25-30 yards behind Papadakis, in retaliation for a hit Geldermann
made on a kickoff return.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a bonehead play,'' Parker said. ``Clearly, after
watching the tape, I hit him from behind. Honestly, I really
thought I was in front, but I wasn't at all.''
</P>
<P>
   Papadakis, who was deprived of a touchdown, said he was not
upset at Parker over the penalty.
</P>
<P>
   ``I talked to Larry. He apologized to me a couple times,''
Papadakis said. ``Stuff like that happens. It was no big deal.''
</P>
<P>
   __ Captains picked: The players elected four captains for the
remainder of the season: linebacker Chris Claiborne, kicker Adam
Abrams, wide receiver Billy Miller and Morton.
</P>
<P>
   __ Welch still out: Right tackle Matt Welch, who did not play
against Cal after being bothered by shoulder and neck injuries, did
not practice. He is considered questionable for this week.
</P>
<P>
   Linebacker Mark Cusano (sore thigh, ankle) also missed practice
but is expected to play.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
