<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-KEISSER-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRAVES: HOLD THE DEATH NOTICE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BOB KEISSER  
 c.1998 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The concept of any baseball team coming back from a 0-3 deficit
in a seven-game series is logically absurd. It's never happened
before.
</P>
<P>
   But no player had ever hit 70 home runs in a season before 1998,
either. No rookie had ever struck out 20 batters in a game, no
Yankee had pitched a perfect game in 42 years, and both the Cubs
and the Red Sox played postseason games.
</P>
<P>
   So anything could happen in the two games remaining in the
National League Championship Series, especially with the Braves
involved. Asked before the playoffs to name the team most capable
of overcoming an 0-3 start, the Braves or Yankees would have been
the first choice of most people.
</P>
<P>
   The Padres still play in Atlanta tonight with a 3-2 edge in
games, but Bruce Bochy's decisions in Game 5 have given the Braves
a huge psychological advantage.
</P>
<P>
   Bringing Kevin Brown into the game was an attempt to drop the
hammer on the Braves right there. If it works, manager Bochy is a
genius and the Padres enter the collective mythology of postseason
play.
</P>
<P>
   But it didn't. Brown looked unhittable and unbeatable prior to
his relief effort Monday, but Michael Tucker's home run makes Brown
suddenly mortal. If the Braves get to a Game 7 by winning tonight,
they will not look at Brown as an immovable object. ...
</P>
<P>
   Bochy deserves credit for managing as aggressively as he has
this postseason. The fact that he got the Padres to a 3-0 lead
without their 50-homer bat in the lineup, Greg Vaughn, has been
widely overlooked.
</P>
<P>
   Moreso than the Brown decision, Bochy will likely be vexed
longer by Tucker's previous at-bat. The Braves' number 8 hitter
came to the plate with two out and a runner on second in the top of
the sixth. Rather than have Andy Ashby walk Tucker and take his
chances with pitcher John Smoltz, Bochy pitched to Tucker, who
singled to tie the game at 2-2.
</P>
<P>
   If Tucker is walked, Bobby Cox has to decide whether to leave
Smoltz in the game. If Tucker is walked and Ashby gets Smoltz, the
Padres take a 2-1 lead into the bottom of the sixth.
</P>
<P>
   Everything that happened after the Tucker non-decision impacted
the game the score of the game, how Cox uses his bullpen, whether
Ashby starts the seventh inning, whether Bochy feels the need to go
to Brown, and who the Braves send to the plate in ensuing innings.
...
</P>
<P>
   The Fox heirarchy was not pleased at all by the embarrassing
turn of events involving Felipe Alou.
</P>
<P>
   New Dodgers' General Manager Kevin Malone obviously believed
Alou was the right fit and that he could deliver him. The Foxies
have no problem with that decision, but they wish he had been a
little less public about things.
</P>
<P>
   Having Jim Leyland and Felipe Alou so publicly stiff the team is
a bit embarrassing for the owners, who are still hearing snickers
about the Mike Piazza trade. ...
</P>
<P>
   Malone has clearly reduced the speed of the search. He
apparently will take some time in assessing the remaining
candidates, and he's fleshed the list out from where it was Sunday,
when Davey Johnson and Kevin Kennedy were the only two names.
</P>
<P>
   A quick form chart on some of the candidates:
</P>
<P>
   Kevin Kennedy, 3-1: The one-time Dodger minor league manager was
fired twice, but his players in Boston and Texas respected him.
Working the NLCS for ESPN Radio, Kennedy aggressively threw his cap
into the ring during Monday's pregame show, saying he would love
the opportunity to manage the Dodgers.
</P>
<P>
   Kennedy, who lives in L.A., managed Dodgers like Eric Karros and
Raul Mondesi in the minors before moving on. Biggest detriment: He
and Tommy Lasorda are not compadres. Kennedy and Angels' manager
Terry Collins both felt Lasorda helped stall their careers because
he feared they were after his job.
</P>
<P>
   Davey Johnson, 9-2: The former Reds, Mets and Orioles manager
took each team to the postseason, and he won a World Series with
the Mets. But he was fired by each team because of a strained
relationship with management. Malone was the assistant G.M. in
Baltimore when Johnson was manager.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson will also cost the Dodgers $6 million if they hire him.
Johnson and Bobby Bonilla did not get along in Baltimore, and it's
hard to see them co-existing here. If the Dodgers couldn't find
some sucker to trade for Bonilla and his $6 million pact, they'd
have to eat it.
</P>
<P>
   Dusty Baker, 10-1: Johnnie B. would be a great choice. But he's
been a Giant now for six years, and he's enjoyed beating his former
team. Baker's one-for-all-for-one managing style would take a hit,
too, if he tried to get out of his Giants contract (he has two
years left) to manage the Dodgers. Baker said in September that he
had no desire to manage anywhere else.
</P>
<P>
   Phil Garner, 12-1: A lot of baseball people felt Garner, who
ended his career as a Dodger reserve, would be a great manager in
the N.L., because of his philosophy on handling pitchers and
playing long ball. But in their first year in the N.L., the Brewers
were a disappointment. He got a vote of confidence from management
this season, never a good sign.
</P>
<P>
   Bobby Valentine, 15-1: Valentine was the hot name when Lasorda
was the G.M. His hiring (he has a year left on the Mets contract)
would cause Malone PR problems. But if the list gets short enough,
who knows?
</P>
<P>
   Davey Lopes, 30-1: If Malone gets to the point where he doesn't
want a Johnson or can't get a Baker, he might reconsider his desire
for an experienced major league manager and go with Lopes. It's a
longshot at best.
</P>
<P>
   The field, 50-1: This would include Larry Bowa, Ray Knight, Doug
Radar, Phil Regan, Cito Gaston and Rene Lachemann, all one-time
managers who are now coaches, sportscasters or unemployed.
</P>
<P>
   If Malone gets this far into the list, Fox can go ahead and tear
down Dodger Stadium, because no one in Los Angeles will care
anymore.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-14-98 0009EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
