<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSINESS-TRAVEL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS TRAVEL: MILAN AIRPORT SHIFT; AIR-SAFETY SPENDING; FREQUENT
FLIER
</HEADLINE>
   (DUPLICATION WARNING: The following story is also being
transmitted with a ``t'' category code) 
(bl) 
 By JANET PIORKO   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Travelers flying into Milan from other European cities after
Oct. 25 may want to double-check their destination before they
leave. According to a compromise worked out last week by the
European Commission and the Italian government, most major European
airlines are scheduled to move about two-thirds of their flights on
that date from Linate Airport, which is only five miles from the
center of the city, to Malpensa International Airport, which is 33
miles out.
</P>
<P>
   Malpensa, where a new terminal is set to open later this month,
is already used by U.S. carriers flying from the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Though minor points in the compromise were still being worked
out Tuesday, according to Sarah Lambert, a spokeswoman for Neil
Kinnock, European Transport Commissioner, major issues have been
settled. The airlines involved, including British Airways,
Scandinavian Airlines System, Air France, Lufthansa and Alitalia,
are expected to use both airports until road and rail improvements
to Malpensa are completed in 2000.
</P>
<P>
   The Italian government had originally decreed that all flights
would move to Malpensa except those on routes with more than 2
million passengers a year, Ms. Lambert said, an exception that
applied, notably, to Alitalia's shuttle between Milan and Rome. The
European airlines complained to the European Commission that the
plan was discriminatory: ``Why should Alitalia be able to feed its
hub in Rome when the rest of the European carriers cannot feed
their hubs from Milan?'' said Hans Ollongren, director of European
public affairs in Brussels for SAS.
</P>
<P>
   There is no direct rail link yet to the new airport, and roads
are inadequate, he said. A three-lane highway serving both the
airport and other regional traffic has no emergency lane, and ``if
there is an accident it is quite complicated,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   While not ruling out the possibility that SAS would contest the
commission's compromise in an Italian court because of the
difficulty of moving operations on such short notice, Ollongren
said his airline was generally going ahead with plans for the
switch.
</P>
<P>
   The airlines can decide which flights will go to which airport.
A minimum of 18 flights a week at Linate is guaranteed to the
various carriers.
</P>
<P>
   Because it is not part of the European Union, Swissair faces the
prospect of moving all its Milan flights to Malpensa; the carrier
will ``pursue the necessary legal actions,'' according to Jackie
Pash, a spokeswoman. ``In particular, we are preparing an appeal to
the administrative court in Rome,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, passengers traveling to Malpensa should also check
their cash when they land. The taxi to the city runs at least $80.
</P>
<P>
   Spending for Safety
</P>
<P>
   Korean Air, having been ordered by the Korean government to cut
its domestic service by 20 percent for six months while safety
inspections are carried out, said it would spend more than $110
million to improve safety equipment and procedures. The airline has
been involved in a series of minor accidents since one of its
Boeing 747s crashed on a hillside in Guam last year, killing 228
people. The airline subsequently faulted the crew's performance.
</P>
<P>
   ``Any airline that has been flying globally for almost 30 years
hits some rough spots along the way,'' said Penny Pfaelzer, a
spokeswoman for the carrier. ``These past 14 months have been
ours.''
</P>
<P>
   Traffic alert and collision avoidance systems have been
installed in the airline's fleet. Safety specialists are being
recruited to provide additional training to captains, first
officers and flight engineers. All new aircraft will be equipped
with enhanced ground proximity warning systems, which give pilots
earlier and more detailed warning about local terrain.
</P>
<P>
   Starting Oct. 25, the carrier will have to cut 138 flights on 10
domestic routes a week for six months. There is no cutback in
service from the United States; in fact, the airline is adding
flights some routes, as it usually does this time of year, Ms.
Pfaelzer said.
</P>
<P>
   Frequent-Flier Upgrades
</P>
<P>
   American Airlines has introduced a new automated upgrade system
for top-tier members of its AAdvantage frequent-flier programs.
Members in four categories _ Executive Platinum, Platinum, Gold and
AAirpass _ can request an upgrade when they make a reservation.
</P>
<P>
   American's Sabre computer reservation system will process the
request at the time a member becomes eligible _ for example, 24
hours before departure for a Gold member. The member is notified if
the upgrade is confirmed, by the option he or she has selected _
fax, phone, e-mail or pager. If the upgrade cannot be confirmed,
Sabre will keep trying to process the request up to two hours
before departure; if there is still no confirmation, passengers can
find out when they check in at the gate.
</P>
<P>
   The system eliminates the need for customers to call to confirm
an upgrade.
</P>
<P>
   Ottawa-New York Service
</P>
<P>
   Air Canada will start nonstop service between La Guardia Airport
in New York and Ottawa on Oct. 26, with three daily flights on
weekdays. The carrier already flies between Newark International
Airport and Ottawa, but will cut the frequency on that route from
four weekday flights to three on Nov. 2. Weekend schedules vary. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
