<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OBIT-GILL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ROBERT GILL, 87, COLLECTOR OF AMERICAN ANTIQUES 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By ROBERTA SMITH   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Robert Lee Gill, a longtime member of the New York
Stock Exchange and a prominent collector of American antiques, died
Sept. 24 at his home in Manhattan. He was 87.
</P>
<P>
   Gill was born in South Orange, N.J., in 1911 and attended
Choate. He joined Shields &AMP; Co. in 1932, and in the late 1940s
formed a company with three other members of the stock exchange,
but for most of his career he worked independently.
</P>
<P>
   Gill's interest in Americana began at the Metropolitan Museum of
Art, where he was a regular visitor to the American collection from
the time it opened, in 1927, until his death. In the late 1930s he
began collecting first-edition books and Currier &AMP; Ives prints. He
also made regular visits to the Upper East Side gallery of Israel
Sack, a dealer in Americana and American antiques, becoming part of
what was then the small world of serious collectors of American
antiques, with members including Henry Ford, Henry Francis du Pont
and Ima Hogg.
</P>
<P>
   In 1942 Gill bought his first antique, a lowboy once owned by
John Hancock. Over the next few decades he formed an exceptional
collection, primarily 17th- and 18th-century Boston, Federal and
Newport furniture. He was known for his eye and the striking
arrangement of the collection in his apartment. In the late 1980s,
Gill also began collecting Chinese porcelain.
</P>
<P>
   In the 1970s, the U.S. government bought two pieces from his
collection, a small painting of the White House under construction
and a late Federal card table, which are still displayed in the
White House.
</P>
<P>
   Last year Gill endowed a research fellow scholarship at the
Henry Francis du Pont Winterthur Museum in Delaware.
</P>
<P>
   Gill's first wife, Caroline Townsend Chapman Gill, died in 1984.
He is survived by his wife, Melanie; a son from his first marriage,
Peter Gill of Bronxville, a stepson, Jack Chapman of Fort Pierce,
Fla.; two sisters, Barbara Betts of West Hampton Beach, N.Y., and
Mary Roby of Rochester, and five grandchildren.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-14-98 0012EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
