<SLUG> BC-SOC-FRENCH-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BATTLE WITH BOTTLE LEADS TO REHAB
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SCOTT FRENCH  
 c.1998 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Paul Gascoigne's long spiral downward hit bottom last weekend,
when a drinking binge in Ireland -- the latest in a lifetime of
drinking binges -- left him with no choice but to enter an alcohol
rehab program.
</P>
<P>
   Whether he'll emerge sober or not is a matter of great
speculation in Britain, where the controversial star has towered
over soccer since emerging as the greatest talent of his generation
in the late 1980s.
</P>
<P>
   Paul Merson and Tony Adams, who have won battles with the
bottle, have long tried to steer Gascoigne toward getting help for
his problem, but for too long he's denied he's had one. Now, after
three drunken days in Dublin and with prodding from current club
Middlesbrough, he's out to beat his addiction.
</P>
<P>
   ``Gazza has got a problem, and it's been building up for quite a
few years,'' said Middlesbrough manager Bryan Robson, a former
England teammate of Gascoigne's. ``We're going to try to help the
lad. We're not like other people saying they want to help him
because they've done nothing but try to destroy him. ... There's no
help coming from the outside.''
</P>
<P>
   It's been a tough year for the 31-year-old Gazza. First, he was
booted off England's squad prior to the World Cup because of poor
fitness (going ``berserk'' when he was cut, according to England
coach Glenn Hoddle's post-Cup tell-all book). Then, his wife of two
years, Sheryl, announced she was divorcing him, citing
``unreasonable behavior.'' Then, his friend David Cheek was found
dead after a night of drinking with Gascoigne and his best friend,
Jimmy ``Five Bellies'' Gardner.
</P>
<P>
   All of it has been fodder for Britain's tabloids. ``We saw what
happened to Princess Di, and people said things were going to
happen within the media to combat things like that happening
again,'' Robson said. ``But since Princess Di passed away, Gazza
has taken over, and he's in the paper every single day. It can be
absolutely anything. It's just nonsense, and all it's done is build
up tension, put pressure on the lad all the time, and that's got to
him. He's been starting to feel real stress.''
</P>
<P>
   Steve Jacobs, an addiction counselor who helped Adams in his
battle with alcoholism, says he fears Gascoigne will ``end up in
the gutter, in prison, or he will die'' unless he succeeds in this
latest battle. ``At the back of my mind, I have this horrific fear
that one of these days I'm going to pick up the paper and read that
Paul Gascoigne has committed suicide. If he doesn't change, I am
certain he will never celebrate his 40th birthday.''
</P>
<P>
   The Sun, one of the tabloids that have covered Gazza from every
angle, threw its support to him and announced it would ``hate him
to slip back into old habits.'' In that spirit, it promised a case
of Newcastle Brown ale -- chosen because Gascoigne is from
Newcastle -- to the first reader that spots him in a pub.''
</P>
<P>
   WHERE'S JORGE?
</P>
<P>
   Jorge Campos' return to Los Angeles comes four days late, but
he'll be at the Coliseum tonight to lead Pumas UNAM against Mexican
rival Guadalajara in the semifinals of the Coliseum Cup.
</P>
<P>
   Campos should have been in a Chicago Fire uniform on Saturday
night at the Rose Bowl, but an unprecedented -- and worrisome --
maneuver by Major League Soccer enabled him to leave early to join
his Mexican club. Campos, who starred for the Galaxy in MLS's first
two season, returned to Mexico on the eve of the playoffs because
a) Zach Thornton had won the Fire's starting goalkeeper job, and b)
Pumas needed him.
</P>
<P>
   Campos asked MLS brass for permission to go, and they granted
it. It sets a precedent that begs the question: How seriously
should MLS be taken if it allows its top stars to skip the most
important part of the season?
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that in the unique kind of relationship that we have
with the Mexican League, where we might get an accommodation like
that in the future, it was just one of those things that happen,''
said MLS commissioner Doug Logan. Said deputy commissioner Sunil
Gulati: ``If he was the starting goalkeeper or was going to be the
starting goalkeeper, it would be a non-issue. Jorge's commitment
was to be here and he certainly would have stayed.''
</P>
<P>
   So, because he's not a starter, that commitment wanes? It
doesn't make much sense, but the Fire isn't complaining. Thornton
led the league in goals-against average and saves, and although
Campos is supposed to return to the league next spring, it's likely
he'll end up in San Jose, where Alan Rothenberg is now running
things.
</P>
<P>
   But tonight he'll be in L.A. Pumas-Guadalajara goes off at 9
p.m., with Argentina's Gimnasia y Esgrima facing Guatemala's
Comunicaciones at 7.
</P>
<P>
   CORNER KICKS
</P>
<P>
   --Major League Soccer unveiled the finalists for its year-end
awards, and there weren't many surprises. The Galaxy has three
people up for honors, with Coach Octavio Zambrano -- one of three
Coach of the Year nominees announced Tuesday -- joining MVP
contender Cobi Jones and Defender of the Year candidate Robin
Fraser. Chicago's Bob Bradley and D.C. United's Bruce Arena join
Zambrano on the coaches list. Also announced Tuesday were the
Rookie of the Year finalists, with -- no surprise -- D.C.'s Ben
Olsen, Chicago's Josh Wolff and Columbus' Andy Williams the
contenders.
</P>
<P>
   --Finalists for MLS's Goal of the Year Award are Brian McBride,
Damian Alvarez and Jaime Moreno, and it's up to fans to determine
the winner. Voting is taking place at MLS's website,
www.mlsnet.com; my pick is Columbus' McBride, for an acrobatic
half-volley against Chicago, in part because he should have won in
'96.
</P>
<P>
   --David Regis, the French defender who played left back for the
United States at the World Cup, received a five-game European ban
as penalty for a red card he earned in FC Metz's UEFA Cup
first-round, second-leg match with Red Star Belgrade. Metz was
eliminated by Red Star, so Regis will serve his suspension the next
time his club qualifies for European play.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-14-98 0013EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
