<DOCNO> NYT19981014.0015 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-14 00:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5679 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBC-TOLEDO-LADN     10-14 1867
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-TOLEDO-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRUIN A NEW IMAGE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BILLY WITZ  
 c.1998 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Let's play a word association game. Take the words
UCLA and national championship and what do you think of?
</P>
<P>
   Basketball, naturally - it's hard to miss the banners at Pauley
Pavilion.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps volleyball or soccer. Or even softball or water polo.
</P>
<P>
   All those teams have won NCAA titles in the '90s.
</P>
<P>
   Football?
</P>
<P>
   Well, the Bruins did win a national title in 1954, but they've
rarely been in sniffing distance since. Just go to the Rose Bowl
every few years, beat USC more often than not and the natives are
happy.
</P>
<P>
   So it was that when newly hired football coach Bob Toledo
addressed his team for the first time in January, 1996, the
audience couldn't help but click their tongues and roll their eyes.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we all sat in that first team meeting and he started
talking about a national championship, we all kind of snickered at
him,'' said Kris Farris, a fourth-year junior offensive tackle.
``It wasn't in our mindset then.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I first came here I didn't even think about it. I would
have thought SC would have won two national championships, but I
never thought we'd be in the hunt for it.
</P>
<P>
   Well, they are now.
</P>
<P>
   In less than three seasons, Toledo has UCLA working on a
school-record and nation-leading 14-game winning streak and ranked
No.2 in the nation, the highest since it was No.1 for one week in
1988.
</P>
<P>
   If the Bruins (4-0) finish the regular season unbeaten they are
all but assured of playing for the national championship Jan. 4 at
the Fiesta Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   So, just how did they get here from there?
</P>
<P>
   It all starts at the top, where the expectations aren't the only
thing Toledo has reshaped.
</P>
<P>
   He's put a heavy emphasis on mental and physical toughness,
overhauled the coaching staff and proved to be a willing listener
as well as a masterful motivational speaker. He's helped create a
family atmosphere, all the while not compromising in the areas of
discipline or academics.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, hindsight makes it easy to wonder why UCLA ever
bothered offering the job to Northwestern's Gary Barnett or wooing
Colorado's Rick Neuheisel or Glen Mason, then at Kansas, before
turning to Toledo, who had been an offensive coordinator under
Terry Donahue the previous two seasons.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bob's really exceeded my expectations,'' said UCLA athletic
director Pete Dalis. ``He's been much more than I thought he'd be
when I hired him, but it's like Terry Donahue used to say: Nobody's
born a head coach.''
</P>
<P>
   Nobody would agree more than Toledo.
</P>
<P>
   He had twice been a head coach before, having two successful
seasons at UC Riverside in the mid-70s, but after three seasons as
USC's secondary coach, he struggled to a 14-30 record at Pacific,
which fired him at the end of his fourth season.
</P>
<P>
   Toledo spent the next six seasons as the offensive coordinator
at Oregon and five years in the same position at Texas A&AMP;M before
he was fired by head coach R.C. Slocum.
</P>
<P>
   ``The experience, the age and being around more has made me
better,'' said Toledo, who has just four holdovers from Donahue's
staff. ``That's part of being a head coach before - growing up and
learning from different situations you've been put in. It's called
experience.''
</P>
<P>
   The experience has led Toledo to confidently embrace great
expectations, a marked contrast from Donahue, who would publicly
fret about playing Cal State Fullerton.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's great. I think it's exciting,'' Toledo said at
Pac-10 media day when the Bruins were picked to win the conference.
``I'm not sitting up here beating my chest saying we're going to
win the national championship, but I'm saying that yes, we'd like
to compete for it.''
</P>
<P>
   Toledo has had little trouble getting that through to his
players. He has made his mark most emphatically as a motivator.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has a great feel for when guys need to be kicked in the
butts and when you've got to loosen the reigns,'' quarterback Cade
McNown said. ``He relates real well to the guys.''
</P>
<P>
   Toledo wanted his players to be physical against Arizona last
year, so he paired players up in the locker room before the game
and had them go through hitting drills. The fired-up Bruins led
20-0 in the first quarter and won handily.
</P>
<P>
   He challenged his defense two weeks ago against Washington
State, winning the coin flip and allowing the Cougars to have the
ball first. UCLA came up with three turnovers in the first quarter
and the Bruins won easily.
</P>
<P>
   He brings in speakers during the season, ranging from a Las
Vegas comedian to someone discussing racial reconciliation. He
shows his team a video tape of great comebacks each year to get
across another point: don't ever give up.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think motivation is overlooked a lot,'' Toledo said. ``A lot
of coaches assume because you've got Xs and Os, that's going to win
the game. Or because you've got better players you're going to win
the game. But they're still young people and they need to be
motivated to play. Somehow you've got to find a way to motivate
them.''
</P>
<P>
   One of Toledo's first orders of business was to change the UCLA
image of The Gutty Little Bruins, who were often perceived as being
as soft as their powder blue uniforms.
</P>
<P>
   The bigger, badder Bruins are the product of one of Toledo's
first hires: strength coach KevinYoxall, whose fu-manchu mustache,
clean-shaven head and drill sergeant's voice do nothing to diminish
the suggestion that he means business.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no getting around Yox,'' said guard Andy Meyers, a
fifth-year senior. ``I attribute so much of our success to Yox and
all the strength coaches. We wake up in the morning (in the
offseason) and go in there and do the hardest workout I've ever
done and the hardest running I've ever done and then you go out the
next day and it's even harder.''
</P>
<P>
   The weight room, which used to be painted blue and yellow is a
more stark blue and white. Gone are the weight machines, replaced
by free weights.
</P>
<P>
   ``It used to be all pretty and nice,'' Meyers said. ``Now, it's
just work.''
</P>
<P>
   Also gone is the infamous Red Army, the legion of players in red
jerseys who, with backward baseball caps, would ride the stationary
bikes that once lined the practice field. Now if a player is too
hurt to practice, he rides a bike inside.
</P>
<P>
   ``I always thought UCLA was a finesse team and not very
physical,'' Meyers said. ``Coach Toledo has taken a real blue
collar approach. It's old style football - more of a Nebraska
approach. You hammer it out day in and day out.''
</P>
<P>
   Toledo admits it took him a while to come around to this
philosophy.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was always going to drop back and throw the ball 50 times a
game,'' said Toledo, an accomplished quarterback at San Francisco
State. ``I always believed that you win it by throwing it. I was a
quarterback and I threw a lot of passes. But as you grow and
realize what's really important you realize if you don't run the
football you become one dimensional and I think the other problem
that goes along with that is your defense becomes a little soft.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you're going to be tough on defense and going to have a
tough mentality on offense, you have to run the ball. To do that,
you have to be physical.''
</P>
<P>
   The players have taken this to heart - in some cases, too much
so. Toledo was repeatedly stopping practice in August because it
was too physical.
</P>
<P>
   The old image took a fatal beating Saturday at Arizona, where
the Bruins hadn't won in 10 years.
</P>
<P>
   They lined up with two tight ends virtually all night and rushed
for 297 yards in a 52-28 win, prompting Arizona coach Dick Tomey to
say, ``They were tougher than we were. We have to admit that.''
</P>
<P>
   Another area of emphasis for Toledo is the Bruin Family.
</P>
<P>
   He often reminds others that while he's a football coach, he's
coaching people, too.
</P>
<P>
   When receiver Brad Melsby was distraught last season about his
difficult recovery from knee surgery, Toledo allowed him to leave
the team for several months.
</P>
<P>
   He allows married players, like seniors DuVal Hicks and Shawn
Stuart, to live with their spouses instead of the dorms during
two-a-days. And he gives his assistants Thursday nights off so they
can spend time with their families. Toledo, 52, who has three
children with his wife Elaine, has lamented watching too many
colleagues ruin their marriages through neglect.
</P>
<P>
   Toledo also makes a point of putting leadership in the players'
hands, even forcing soft-spoken Larry Atkins, an All-American
safety candidate, to address students at a Friday pep rally.
</P>
<P>
   ``We used to have a lot of player meetings where we'd start out,
`We need to do this, we need to do that, we need to play harder,'
'' said Farris. ``After 20 minutes it would turn into the offense
yelling at the defense and the defense yelling at the offense. So
what (the captains) did last year was say, `No more of those.'
We're having one player meeting and that's it. We're going about
this as a team. No finger pointing.''
</P>
<P>
   That atmosphere played no small part in helping UCLA land what
several recruiting services labeled the best freshman class in the
nation this season.
</P>
<P>
   DeShaun Foster, one of the nation's top running back recruits,
was surprised how warmly he was treated by the two upperclassmen,
Jermaine Lewis and Keith Brown, who's job he is after.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Thomas, a nationally recruited linebacker from Imperial,
was also pursued by USC, Florida State, Texas and Notre Dame.
</P>
<P>
   ``The coaches here never lied to me,'' Thomas said. ``Notre Dame
didn't seem like they really cared and Coach Toledo was a lot
different than Bobby Bowden.
</P>
<P>
   ``It seems like you can always to talk to the coaches when you
need to. It didn't seem like that at the other schools. When you go
away to school, you're away from your family, away from a lot of
your friends. You need some older people that you can look up to.
If I ever had a problem, I'd never be embarrassed or shy to talk to
him. I know I'm always welcome in his room.''
</P>
<P>
   Toledo, though, has proved more than capable of tough love.
</P>
<P>
   He didn't play nose guard Damon Smith against USC last year
because of his behavior at practice. He has benched cornerback
Marques Anderson for not hustling and he suspended Lewis for his
involvement in a fight, even though Lewis - by all accounts - did
not throw the first punch.
</P>
<P>
   ``He demands that the team members adhere to his policies,''
said Dalis. ``He really expects them to behave in a certain manner
and the kids really respond to it because he does what he says he's
going to do.''
</P>
<P>
   He told somebody (Smith) he wasn't going to play him and he
didn't care if cost us the game.''
</P>
<P>
   UCLA has shown its appreciation by ripping up Toledo's original
four-year contract. He was recently presented a new one, good
through 2003, for $453,000 per year, nearly doubling the deal he
initially signed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not going anywhere,'' Toledo said. ``I'd like to stay here
the rest of my life.''
</P>
<P>
   Dalis said the deal was done to ensure that Toledo be at UCLA
for a long time. Which may just lead to a new word association.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
