<SLUG> BC-TEKELEC-SHARES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEKELEC STOCK UP 14 PERCENT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY BEN SULLIVAN  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES -- Shares in telecommunications equipment maker
Tekelec rose more than 14 percent on news that Sprint will buy $4
million to $5 million worth of its switching equipment.
</P>
<P>
   Tekelec shares gained $1.9375, or 14.02 percent Tuesday, to
close at $15.75. More than 1.4 million shares traded hands Tuesday,
or 2.3 times the issue's six-month average daily volume.
</P>
<P>
   The boost is a welcome respite for Tekelec investors, who last
week saw their shares hit a 52-week low of $10.625 on general
weakness in the telecom sector. With Tuesday's gain, Tekelec shares
have risen 48.23 percent since Oct. 7.
</P>
<P>
   The Sprint deal comes on the heels of a similar purchase by AT&AMP;T
in September for that company's wireless telecom service. Both
deals are seen as a vote of confidence for Tekelec's Eagle line of
switching equipment, which routes and forwards calls.
</P>
<P>
   ``They've got a lot of opportunity ahead of them,'' said analyst
Kevin Slocum at SoundView Technology Group in San Francisco. ``This
is another in a series of fairly visible wins, and that's got to
strengthen the confidence of prospective customers.''
</P>
<P>
   Tekelec, founded in 1979, was once known primarily for its
diagnostic equipment. If a problem arose on a computer network,
Tekelec's tools could help figure out why data was not being
properly delivered from one point to another.
</P>
<P>
   While it still makes diagnostic products, increasingly the
company has come to rely on sales of its switching equipment used
in data and telecom networks.
</P>
<P>
   All five analysts covering the company have it rated a ``buy''
or ``strong buy.'' Tekelec had 1997 earnings of $29 million on
$125.1 million in sales.
</P>
<P>
   X X X
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
