<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-SHAUGHNESSY </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FLAG DAY ALMOST ANNUAL HOLIDAY IN NEW YORK 
</HEADLINE>
 COLUMN-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAN SHAUGHNESSY  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ It's hard not to be jealous. Do these people know how
good they have it?
</P>
<P>
   Social Security-aged Yankee fans basked in the warm glow of Lou
Gehrig and Joe DiMaggio. Baby Boomers remember Whitey, Yogi, and
the Mick winning every autumn. Today's Wall Street lions watched
Thurman, Billy, and Reggie. And now a new generation of New Yorkers
grows up believing the World Series is a baseball birthright.
</P>
<P>
   The New York Yankees won the 1998 American League pennant
Tuesday night, burying the Cleveland Indians, 9-5, to take the AL
Championship Series, four games to two. (We all know the Red Sox
should have been here, anyway.)
</P>
<P>
   And so for the 35th October since buying Babe Ruth from Boston,
the men in pinstripes will represent the American League in the
World Series. Think about that for a moment. Thirty-five World
Series. That is almost half of all the Fall Classics since the
Bambino delivered for the first time in 1921. Yankee Stadium's red,
white, and blue bunting doesn't stay in mothballs very long.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think our celebration was restrained,'' said Yankees
manager Joe Torre. ``To me, the tensest part is just geting to the
World Series. And to do it against a team like this is especially
satisfying.''
</P>
<P>
   Not to bring up a sore subject, but in the period in which the
Yankees have won 35 pennants, your Boston Red Sox have won but
four, losing the World Series in seven games each time.
</P>
<P>
   These Yankees don't plan on losing. Whether they meet the Padres
or Braves (which would be a delicious rematch from 1996), they
believe they are destined to win the World Series. They won an
AL-record 114 regular-season games, and their mission won't be
complete until they have 125 wins and rings on their fingers.
</P>
<P>
   It was a pretty wild night at the Stadium. Outraged by insults
hurled at David Wells in Cleveland, and by David Justice's
subsequent remark that Yankee fans do everything short of bringing
Uzis to the park, the New York legions came ready to razz the
Tribe. It was feared that you wouldn't be able to find a package of
AA batteries within 3 miles of Yankee Stadium, but most fans
resisted the urge to fire objects at the Indians. It didn't hurt to
see an impressive assemblage of New York's finest _ many in riot
gear _ in and around the park. Andy Sipowicz must have been the
only cop left in Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   Fans were wild with anticipation when the Yankees took a 6-0
lead in the first three innings. Veteran David Cone knew what to do
with a six-run lead: throw strikes. Unfortunately for Cone, Jim
Thome launched one of the strikes into the third deck (where George
Brett took Rich Gossage in the 1980 ALCS) for a fifth-inning grand
slam that chiseled the lead to 6-5.
</P>
<P>
   Cone left after five and gave the ball to Ramiro Mendoza, one of
a seemingly endless supply of capable Yankee hurlers. Pitching
depth and bench strength are what make this team smarter than your
average Berra Yankee champion.
</P>
<P>
   Unfazed by Thome's grand slam, the Yankees scored three times in
the bottom of the sixth to make it 9-5. The Indians weren't going
to spoil this Bronx bash. (Did Cleveland actually lead this ssries,
2-1, Friday night?) Yankee fans chanted, ``1948,'' in the eighth
inning. That's the last year in which the Indians won a World
Series. Ouch.
</P>
<P>
   Mendoza pitched three innings of one-hit ball before turning it
over to Mariano Rivera. Scott Brosius, who hit a three-run homer in
the third, made his second spectacular play of the night on Enrique
Wilson to start the ninth. Then Kenny Lofton fanned and Omar
Vizquel grounded to Rivera to end it.
</P>
<P>
   The riot-gear gang burst onto the field after the final out.
Amazingly, no fan tried to penetrate the thick blue line and the
Yanks celebrated among themselves on the diamond while Sinatra's
``New York, New York,'' blared over the public address system (it
was played nine consecutive times leading into this morning). In
compliance with Stadium tradition, the crowd showered itself with
confetti and full cups of beer.
</P>
<P>
   Yankee players went straight to the clubhouse for their
champagne bath. There were no curtain calls on the field, no
ballplayers taking victory laps on police horses. In New York, they
hold off on the real celebration until the World Series is won.
</P>
<P>
   The Series begins Saturday night. In New York. At Yankee
Stadium. Again.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-14-98 0040EDT &QL; 
