<HEADLINE>
CULTURE NOTES: 150 SARGENTS; HEAVY SECURITY FOR `AIDA'; DAVIS ON
ROBESON; AN ARCHITECT NOT FORGOTTEN 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Mass., N.Y.)   (mk) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The cosmopolitan American artist John Singer Sargent (1856-1925)
is the subject of the major autumn exhibition at the Tate Gallery
in London. Opening Thursday and continuing through Jan. 17, this
show, assembled from public and private collections around the
world and made up of paintings, watercolors, oil studies and
drawings for murals, is described as the first to display the full
variety of the artist's work.
</P>
<P>
   The 150 paintings range from Sargent's daring ``Madame X,''
which caused a scandal at the Paris Salon of 1884, to his late
landscape oils of Venice and Switzerland, his Impressionist works
and his grand society portraits. The exhibition will run at the
National Gallery of Art in Washington from Feb. 21 to May 31 and at
the Museum of Fine Arts in Boston from June 23 to Sept. 26.
</P>
<P>
   Under Wraps
</P>
<P>
   Egyptian authorities are deploying heavy security, including
roadblocks and hundreds of policemen, during weeklong performances
of Verdi's ``Aida'' on the Pyramids plateau outside Cairo. Nearly
3,000 opera devotees from around the world who came to the opening
on Monday were required to identify themselves. Last November, 58
foreign tourists and four Egyptians died in an attack by Islamic
militants in Luxor a month after ``Aida'' was performed there.
</P>
<P>
   Times Remembered
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The actor and author Ossie Davis will discuss his
friendship with Paul Robeson Thursday as part of an observance of
the centennial of Robeson's birth organized by the 160,000-member
Local 1199 of the National Health and Human Services Employees
Union. Davis is speaking at 11 a.m. and again at 12:30 p.m. before
some 1,000 elementary and high school students in the union's
auditorium at 310 W. 43rd St., as a presentation of Bread and
Roses, 1199's cultural arm.
</P>
<P>
   Civic Virtues
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Many of his landmark works have vanished. But the
mastery of the architect George Post (1837-1913) still shapes New
York City: the domed Williamsburg Savings Bank, the floor of the
New York Stock Exchange with its 72-foot-high ceiling, the
Gothic-style City College campus and the building now known as the
Brooklyn Historical Society.
</P>
<P>
   Gone are Post's eight-story Equitable Life Assurance Society,
the first office building to use elevators; his 20-story World
Building, once New York's tallest, and his Cornelius Vanderbilt
Mansion. But Post and his achievements have not been forgotten. The
architect is the subject of an exhibition at the New-York
Historical Society. ``George B. Post: Great American Architect,''
which opened Tuesday, runs through Jan. 10.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
