<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-STADIUM-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CSUN STADIUM SITE WILL FACE OPPOSITION
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The three most important words in building a new
facility are location, location, location.
</P>
<P>
   Just ask Cal State Northridge officials. The Big Sky Conference.
Area residents.
</P>
<P>
   CSUN wants to build a football stadium. The Big Sky Conference
has all but mandated it. But where to put the facility so it won't
cause an uproar with area residents is why an appointed site
committee has been meeting weekly during the last two months.
</P>
<P>
   And CSUN insiders say the perfect site for a 12,000- to
15,000-seat stadium might be just 100 yards south of North Campus
Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   When the 12-person Athletic Facility Site Committee meets
tonight at 6:30 at CSUN's satellite student union, the site near
the current stadium will be introduced.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't please everyone,'' site-committee chairman David
Honda said. ``We'll do the pros and cons of it, like we do all the
sites.''
</P>
<P>
   But area residents have offered staunch opposition. They don't
want a new stadium on CSUN's campus because they believe it would
create extra traffic and too many night events.
</P>
<P>
   The Matadors currently play in what is regarded by even their
own coaches as the worst facility in the league, and perhaps
Division I-AA. It holds 7,500 but has poor lighting, inadequate
coaches' boxes and locker rooms, a poor press facility and lacks a
college-type atmosphere, Big Sky commissioner Doug Fullerton has
said in the past.
</P>
<P>
   The estimated cost of building an on-campus stadium is $12-$15
million.
</P>
<P>
   Renovating North Campus Stadium isn't an option because a
multimillion dollar biotech complex is going to be built on that
site. But Honda said there is enough room on the south portion of
the North Campus _ where the dirt hill is located _ to build a
stadium.
</P>
<P>
   CSUN athletic director Paul Bubb said a site for the stadium
depends on how important the school views its football program.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's the commitment the institution wants to make to
itself?'' said Bubb, a committee member and proponent of an
on-campus stadium. ``What is the message we want to send to our
conference? Do you want to be one of the top programs in the
conference or do you just want to get by?''
</P>
<P>
   The site committee is supposed to present CSUN President Blenda
Wilson with recommendations by Dec. 1.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have a judgment about it,'' Wilson said. ``Except for big
Division I universities that have big teams and big crowds and big
records _ those universities can use civic arenas because they can
draw that kind of attention _ I don't know of any Division I-AA
athletic program in the country that would not have its athletic
facilities on campus. And that's partly because athletics create a
sense of community.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the North Campus site, another site being
examined by the committee is on the main campus, just off Zelzah
Avenue and adjacent to the athletic administration building.
</P>
<P>
   The site committee is also studying a $1 million renovation of
Pierce College. But Pierce College athletic director Bob Lyons, who
stands to gain the most if CSUN was to renovate Pierce's stadium,
said CSUN shouldn't wander off campus to play football.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would think they're better off building it on campus,''
Lyons said. ``It would mean better school spirit. If I was the
athletic director at Cal State Northridge, my first choice would be
on campus. Pierce would be the next logical choice.''
</P>
<P>
   Those opposing the building of a new stadium want CSUN to
renovate a local high school or junior college field, but Fullerton
said that was unacceptable because it didn't meet Big Sky
requirements.
</P>
<P>
   Area residents opposed to an on-campus stadium point toward UCLA
and USC as schools that play off campus, though both of those
schools play at the Division I-A level. CSUN plays at the much less
visible Division I-AA level and averages less than 4,500 fans per
game.
</P>
<P>
   The Lindley West Coalition, the Northridge Townhome Estate
Homeowners Association and the La Villa Nueva Homeowners
Association have argued against an on-campus stadium.
</P>
<P>
   Honda said a new stadium on the North Campus could bring flack
from the Lindley group, but the other two associations might
welcome the move. It would also be more difficult for a residential
group to block a new stadium on North Campus because a stadium
already exists there.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
