<DOCNO> NYT19981014.0030 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-14 01:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5718 &Cx1f; tth-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBC-COUGAR-SPI &LR;      10-14 0711
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-COUGAR-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POOR KICK COVERAGE HAS PRICE SCRAMBLING FOR SOLUTIONS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ANGELO BRUSCAS  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ First there were breakdowns in blocking fundamentals,
then bad tackling and a simple lack of effort.
</P>
<P>
   Washington State coach Mike Price has a lot to be disappointed
about in his team's 0-3 start in the Pac-10, but nothing disturbs
him more than explaining why his team has failed to adequately
cover punts and kickoffs in the three straight losses to Oregon,
UCLA and Cal.
</P>
<P>
   Against Oregon last week, Duck return specialist Michael
Fletcher returned one punt 61 yards for a touchdown and had another
touchdown called back because of a penalty as the Cougars gave up
158 total return yards in their 51-29 loss.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm just so disappointed in that with our team,'' Price said
Tuesday when asked about Oregon's success.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe it's Fletcher, maybe he's the greatest punt returner in
America,'' Price said, searching for answers. ``But they had a
`safe' punt return on'' and Fletcher still was able to shred the
Cougar punt coverage.
</P>
<P>
   The Cougars now plan a different sort of coverage this week for
USC, which leads the Pac-10 in punt return yardage after six games
(23 returns for 346 yards and a 15-yard average).
</P>
<P>
   Price has ordered punter Kareem Anderson and kicker Rian Lindell
to kick every ball away from USC's most explosive returner, junior
R. Jay Soward, who returned a kickoff 95 yards against the Cougars
last year and had a 78-yard kickoff return against WSU as a
freshman.
</P>
<P>
   In USC's 32-31 loss to Cal last Saturday, Soward had an 80-yard
punt return for a touchdown, his second of the year, and he is
averaging a touchdown every six times he touches the ball (25 TDs
on 151 plays).
</P>
<P>
   ``He better not touch the football on a punt or a kickoff,''
Price warned. ``I mean it. I'm serious. We're not punting that ball
to him and we're not kicking that ball to him.''
</P>
<P>
   USC coach Paul Hackett believes the Trojans' play on special
teams could be the deciding factor in Martin Stadium, where a long
return or two could take the crowd out of the game. But he says
Soward isn't the only Trojan player to be concerned about.
</P>
<P>
   Senior Larry Parker is seventh in the conference in punt returns
(6.1 yards per return), and USC defenders has blocked four punts
and two field goals this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``The special teams have been the most consistent part of our
football team,'' Hackett said. ``We have had some really tremendous
play.''
</P>
<P>
   With both teams having difficulty moving the football on
offense, Hackett likes his team's chances of winning the game with
special teams, especially in light of the success Oregon had in
Pullman.
</P>
<P>
   Because of the AstroTurf, the hostile crowd and uncertain
weather conditions, ``I think it becomes even more important,''
Hackett said.
</P>
<P>
   ``This particular time, with an offense struggling a little bit,
it really has been a weapon for us. And we have to take a very,
very close look at the things we may or may not be able to do
against Washington State.''
</P>
<P>
   If the Cougars elect to punt away from Soward, expect USC to go
for blocks. Anderson had two punts blocked against UCLA and is
still nursing a broken finger ligament from that game.
</P>
<P>
   ``The concern we would have is that they would kick away from R.
Jay, which wouldn't give us a chance to do anything (on the
return),'' Hackett said. ``We'll have to adjust accordingly.''
</P>
<P>
   Price noted that his team's poor first-half performance against
Oregon was largely set up by blunders in kickoff and punt coverage.
Fletcher's up-the-middle TD return of WSU's second punt made the
score 21-0 with 5:21 still left in the first quarter.
</P>
<P>
   ``The field position was lousy, but it was the result of poor
special teams,'' Price said. ``Not getting the kickoffs back, poor
coverage on punts, those are things we haven't had problems with
before. It was kind of disgusting.''
</P>
<P>
   The problem appears to start with lack of effort, and Price
seems to take it personally.
</P>
<P>
   ``A punt return where you see a guy maybe not giving 100
percent, you can't say that very often about the Cougs and about
the teams that I've coached in the past,'' Price said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
