<SLUG> BC-BKN-NBA-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LABOR PAINS WRACK NBA
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By HOWARD BECK  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The NBA's legacy of labor peace is gone and with
it the first two weeks of the 1998-99 season.
</P>
<P>
   The longest streak of uninterrupted play in North American
professional sports history ended bitterly Tuesday when labor
strife caused the NBA to cancel regular-season games for the first
time in 51 years _ a span of 35,001 games.
</P>
<P>
   A too-little, too-late bargaining session Tuesday produced a
glimmer of progress but nothing that could avert a decision that
had long appeared inevitable. Ninety-nine contests scheduled from
Nov. 3 to Nov. 16 _ including 14 games each for the Los Angeles
Lakers and Los Angeles Clippers _ were wiped out by the
3{-month-old labor stalemate.
</P>
<P>
   ``We held out as long as we possibly could, hoping for some kind
of a miracle, but it didn't occur,'' commissioner David Stern said
in a conference call.
</P>
<P>
   The man who has presided over two decades of unbridled
prosperity and remarkable labor peace told the Associated Press he
felt ``lousy, disappointed.''
</P>
<P>
   ``My job is to put on games for the fans, not to cancel them.
It's terribly disappointing.''
</P>
<P>
   More cancellations could be announced in the coming weeks if NBA
owners and players cannot find a mutually agreeable formula for
dividing the league's $2 billion in annual revenues.
</P>
<P>
   Player representatives tried to address owners' concerns over
exorbitant player contracts with an 11th-hour proposal for a luxury
tax. But NBA officials said the concept needs analysis, and that
the proposal was insufficient to save the start of the season.
</P>
<P>
   The league announced the cancellations shortly after the 3{-hour
negotiating session in New York ended. ``Needless to say, that was
a very difficult announcement for us to have to make,'' deputy
commissioner Russ Granik said.
</P>
<P>
   Seventeen players and five owners participated in Tuesday's
talks. No players or owner representatives from the Lakers and
Clippers were in attendance.
</P>
<P>
   NBA owners declared a lockout of players July 1 and the sides
have negotiated only three times since, with little movement. The
league, saying owners need cost certainty, have sought a hard cap
on player salaries. The players' association opposes changes to the
current ``soft'' cap.
</P>
<P>
   The players now propose a ``superstar tax,'' to be imposed on
high-end contracts that fall under the current ``Larry Bird
exception.'' The Bird clause _ which owners want to abolish _
allows teams to pay any amount to re-sign their free agents and has
resulted in contracts such as Kevin Garnett's six-year, $126
million deal.
</P>
<P>
   Under the players' proposal, Bird contracts that exceed a
certain amount would be taxed and the fees collected would be
redistributed among low-revenue teams. Major League Baseball
adopted a similar concept in lieu of a salary cap following the
1994 players' strike.
</P>
<P>
   Sources said the union proposed that contracts exceeding $18
million per year be taxed at a rate of 50 cents for every dollar
over the limit (e.g. a $19 million contract produces a $500,000
tax). The figures are presumed to be negotiable, however.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our intention was to put something bold on the table,'' said
Billy Hunter, executive director of the players' association. ``The
message here is that we're trying. What kind of response they make
will determine what kind of progress we can make and whether we can
salvage the rest of the November schedule _ or the rest of the
season.''
</P>
<P>
   Granik said a luxury tax ``could be a worthwhile instrument''
but said the league is ``not at all confident a tax will provide
the needed relief for the owners.'' The league hopes to respond to
the proposal by the end of the week.
</P>
<P>
   All that is certain is the upcoming season, if it is played at
all, is destined to be pockmarked by asterisks. Stern and Granik
indicated that games lost probably will not be made up. Worse, the
remaining schedule probably cannot be rewritten to allow for a
balanced schedule; in other words, teams might not play the same
number of home and away games, division games and games inside and
outside their conferences.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fact is, we really don't have a lot of flexibility. Most
of our arenas are booked most of the time,'' Granik said. ``We're
likely to end up with a season that's not perfectly satisfactory to
everybody.''
</P>
<P>
   The canceled games represent one-twelfth of the season, equating
to about $85 million in player salaries. Players will miss their
first paychecks Nov. 15.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
