<SLUG> BC-COLUMN-THIEL-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TYSON TEST RESULTS LACK A CERTAIN BITE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ART THIEL  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Yet another reason has come along to reinforce my
decision not to have become a pro boxer.
</P>
<P>
   Aside from a mild aversion to getting hit in the mouth, I hate
it when my five-day mental evaluation by a six-doctor panel from
Massachusetts General Hospital is made public.
</P>
<P>
   Really spoils my morning.
</P>
<P>
   Mike Tyson had his evaluation released Tuesday. Given his
history when he discovers his mornings spoiled (or when anything
else causes him to cock his eyebrow), the expectations were grim.
</P>
<P>
   But a funny thing happened:
</P>
<P>
   Nothing.
</P>
<P>
   Not only did the doctors find no compelling emotional,
psychological or neurological reason to deny Tyson a renewal of his
Nevada boxing license, none of the doctors ended up with teethmarks
on their ears. In fact, they kept their own teeth pretty much in
the same shape as when they began the evaluation.
</P>
<P>
   Hard to know what was more remarkable: the fact that a prominent
athlete had his head publicly examined, or that the people doing
the examining lived to tell about it.
</P>
<P>
   I'm not exactly sure what the point was of the exercise. If it
was to determine Tyson's fitness to box, my question is: What is
the proper measurement?
</P>
<P>
   A minimum IQ? Or a maximum IQ?
</P>
<P>
   And if IQ is not the issue, what standard of comparison do
doctors use when judging whether a subject is psychologically safe
enough to be permitted to thrash someone?
</P>
<P>
   Is Tyson compared to Israeli commandos, bears, Islamic
terrorists, IRS agents or flu viruses?
</P>
<P>
   In fact, wading through the excerpts of the report released
Tuesday, that very disclaimer leaped out:
</P>
<P>
   ``We emphasize,'' the doctors wrote, ``that because of the lack
of an appropriate comparison group, caution must be taken in the
interpretation of these test results.''
</P>
<P>
   In other words, since we've never examined anybody like this to
judge fitness for this kind of activity ... who knows?
</P>
<P>
   With due respect to the medical personnel involved, the more
revealing analysis of Tyson was in this month's Playboy. No pun
intended.
</P>
<P>
   Former Sports Illustrated writer Mark Kram talked with Tyson
recently in two long interview sessions in New York where he ranged
from ``brooding silence to manic free association,'' underlined
with a steady drumbeat of rage, according to the writer.
</P>
<P>
   Kram's conclusion: ``Tyson is the darkest figure in sports I've
ever encountered. I left thinking that I have never before met a
32-year-old man so eaten up by rage, so hostile, despondent and
absolutely convinced of his irredeemability.''
</P>
<P>
   The most telling segment of the interview illustrated Tyson's
volatility as well as the frequently contradictory nature that
makes his behavior impossible to anticipate.
</P>
<P>
   ``Don't interview me like I'm some maniac that might explode at
any minute,'' Tyson said. ``I think you've got the wrong
impression.''
</P>
<P>
   Kram: ``What makes you think we've got the wrong impression?''
</P>
<P>
   Tyson: ``Maybe it's me, because I'm so bitter and defensive.
Maybe it's not you at all. I'm just always ready to attack. Please,
sir, don't take it personally. I'm a very hateful (expletive) right
now, a hateful individual. I'm really (expletive) at the world.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm always trying to be cool, take care of my children, not
kill nobody, not say anything anymore. I always do my best to be
cool. I know I'm going to blow one day.''
</P>
<P>
   Kram: ``Blow in what way?''
</P>
<P>
   Tyson: ``I know I'm going to blow one day. But I'm going to make
sure that when I blow, my kids are fine. There's not much more of
this (expletive) I can take. I'm going to blow one day. I try very
hard. I'm doing a very good job, sir. I'm doing a very good job.
I'm just really angry these days. Really, really angry.''
</P>
<P>
   Kram: ``Do you get any easier to live with as you get older?''
</P>
<P>
   Tyson: ``It gets more intense. I have no one to blame but
myself. Even though many people contribute to it, I have to carry
the weight of the fool alone.''
</P>
<P>
   Tyson is all too aware of the apparent inevitability of his
self-destruction, and is convinced the world is against him. Some
of his anger is well-earned, given his wretched upbringing and his
continual exploitation as an adult.
</P>
<P>
   But at some point in every functional adult life, victimhood
becomes useless and accountability begins. Tyson knows that and
sometimes sounds ready to accept the consequences of his actions.
But his admitted readiness to attack and the belief that he will
again erupt, perhaps fatally, virtually certifies he is no more in
control now than when he went cannibal on Evander Holyfield.
</P>
<P>
   It's not likely Tyson is going to bite anyone's ear again. But
if he is re-licensed, the weight of the Vegas casinos, a cable
network, his handlers and family and most of boxing will once more
bear down upon the shoulders of a man who is ``really, really
angry'' at nearly all of them.
</P>
<P>
   If the five members of the Nevada State Athletic Commission
re-license Tyson, the good doctors in Massachusetts might want to
open their appointment calendars for five more head exams.
</P>
<P>
   Art Thiel is a P-I columnist
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
