<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-14 01:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5721 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-ALCS-HNS &LR;      10-14 1014
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-ALCS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOSEPH DUARTE  
 c. 1998, Houston Chronicle  
NEW YORK _ Whether the New York Yankees will be considered among
the greatest teams ever in baseball still remains to be seen, but
after Tuesday night one thing is clear: They're the best in the
American League this year.
<TEXT>
<P>
   One of the sport's most tradition-rich and storied institutions
added another chapter as the Yankees finished off the Cleveland
Indians 9-5 in Game 6 of the AL Championship Series to qualify for
their 35th World Series.
</P>
<P>
   New York won the ALCS four games to two and will attempt to add
a 24th world championship to its collection against either San
Diego or Atlanta. The World Series is scheduled to begin Saturday
at Yankee Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was something we fought hard all year for,'' said David
Wells, who was voted ALCS Most Valuable Player for his two
victories. ``These guys are wonderful.''
</P>
<P>
   Scuttling the mismatch most expected in the best-of-seven
series, the Indians made the Yankees work for their second trip to
the World Series in three years. That proved little consolation as
an unmerciful crowd of 57,142 began chants of, ``1948! 1948!'' _
the last time the Indians won a World Series _ during the final two
innings.
</P>
<P>
   ``To me, this is probably the tensest part of it,'' Yankees
manager Joe Torre said. ``Getting there (to the World Series) is
such a tough mountain to climb. To do it against a club like the
Cleveland Indians is satisfying.''
</P>
<P>
   Playing in intermittent drizzle throughout the game, the Yankees
teed off on Cleveland righthander Charles Nagy for six runs in the
first three innings. Then, they held on for dear life as Cleveland
finally found a solution for 20-game winner David Cone with a
five-run fifth inning, four of those coming on one swing of Jim
Thome's bat.
</P>
<P>
   Ahead 6-0, Cone, who struck out seven of the first 15 batters he
faced, ran into trouble in the fifth. He allowed three straight
singles, the last one by Omar Vizquel hitting second-base umpire
Ted Hendry to load the bases with nobody out.
</P>
<P>
   Cone then walked David Justice to bring in a run and, following
a strikeout of Manny Ramirez, surrendered a monstrous 405-foot
grand slam to Thome that landed in the upper deck in right field
and pulled the Indians within 6-5. Thome's six home runs during the
playoffs tied the major-league record held by four players. The
Yankees' Bernie Williams accomplished the feat most recently in
1996.
</P>
<P>
   Cone allowed five runs and seven hits in five innings before
being relieved by Ramiro Mendoza to begin the sixth. Cone struck
out eight and walked three.
</P>
<P>
   ``David Cone gets it done,'' Torre said. ``It wasn't one of his
stellar performances, but winning is what this game is all about.''
</P>
<P>
   Mendoza allowed Cleveland just one hit over the next three
innings, and Mariano Rivera closed things out in the ninth.
</P>
<P>
   Any chance Cleveland had of overtaking the Yankees and forcing a
deciding seventh game ended on a costly error by the least likely
of players. Vizquel, a five-time Gold Glove shortstop, cleanly
fielded a grounder by Scott Brosius leading off the New York sixth
but overthrew first to begin a three-run inning for the Yankees.
The error, one of three by Cleveland, snapped Vizquel's string of
46 career postseason games and 237 chances without an error.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't give any extra outs to a big-league team, much less
one with the caliber of talent as the Yankees,'' Cleveland manager
Mike Hargrove said. ``We played with fire all night long and got
burned by it.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Torre: ``I never dreamed of that. I took it (Vizquel's
error) as a sign. If he's not the best in the business, I don't
know who is.''
</P>
<P>
   Brosius advanced to second on a wild pitch by reliever Dave
Burba, and two batters later, Derek Jeter cleared the bases with a
two-run triple that bounced off the right-field wall, increasing
the Yankees' lead to 8-5. Williams, who went 3-for-4 with two RBIs,
singled to right field to drive in the final run.
</P>
<P>
   In typical fashion, Cleveland trailed after the first inning.
The Indians were outscored 17-3 during the first inning of this
year's playoffs, but this time it was not the result of a lack of
opportunity.
</P>
<P>
   Kenny Lofton singled to lead off the game, beating out a bunt
down the third-base line. But Cone struck out the next three
batters to end the inning. The Indians had two runners on base in
the second inning, only to watch Cone again escape danger with two
more strikeouts.
</P>
<P>
   New York wasted little time jumping on Nagy, scoring twice in
the first inning. Jeter and Paul O'Neill hit consecutive one-out
singles, and Williams followed with an RBI single up the middle.
Chili Davis, who drove in five runs during the last three games of
the series, provided the Yankees' second run with a sacrifice fly
to right field.
</P>
<P>
   Joe Girardi delivered a one-out single in the second inning, and
Chuck Knoblauch, the goat in Game 2 after his fielding gaffe handed
Cleveland a victory, doubled into the left-field corner.
Cleveland's Brian Giles played the bounce perfectly, but as he
positioned to throw, the wet ball slipped from his grasp, allowing
Girardi to score from first base.
</P>
<P>
   ``What a great team we've got,'' Knoblauch said. ``They gave me
a lot of support when I was down. We don't have to worry about that
now.''
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees appeared to blow the game open with three more runs
off Nagy in the third. Williams led off with a single, and Davis
reached one batter later when Enrique Wilson's throw to second on a
potential force was ruled to have pulled Vizquel off the bag.
Brosius made the Indians pay for the mistake with a 416-foot,
three-run homer to pad New York's lead to 6-0.
</P>
<P>
   Nagy, who had allowed only two earned runs in 14 playoff innings
this year, was tagged for six runs (three earned) and eight hits in
three innings.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm absolutely disappointed that we didn't go on,'' Hargrove
said, ``but we have to recognize the Yankees have a very good
ballclub and they played better than we did.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-14-98 0117EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
