<HEADER>
A5723 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-NLCS-HNS &LR;      10-14 0710
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-NLCS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CARLTON THOMPSON  
 c. 1998, Houston Chronicle  
ATLANTA _ The Atlanta Braves bill themselves as ``America's Team,''
and they do have quite a following around the country. But many
opposing players despise the Braves and cite arrogance as the main
reason.
<TEXT>
<P>
   It might have sounded arrogant, cocky and maybe even boastful
when the Braves vowed to make the National League Championship
Series interesting despite losing the first three games of the
best-of-seven set to the San Diego Padres.
</P>
<P>
   As the saying goes: It ain't bragging if you can do it.
</P>
<P>
   The Braves continue their quest to become the first team in
major-league history to overcome a three-game postseason deficit
when they host the Padres in Game 6 this afternoon at Turner Field.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, it is not the position we wanted to be in, but we
felt we had a chance, and we still do, because of our pitching and
how we're starting to swing the bats,'' said Braves lefthander Tom
Glavine, who will start today's game. ``We felt if anyone can come
back from 0-3, we can.''
</P>
<P>
   Padres manager Bruce Bochy left the decision with ace Kevin
Brown regarding his team's starting pitcher for today's game.
Brown, who pitched 1 relief innings and took the loss in Game 5,
opted to bypass today's start in favor of Game 7, if necessary.
</P>
<P>
   Lefthander Sterling Hitchcock, who won Game 3, will start for
the Padres today. If the Braves win, Brown will face Greg Maddux in
Thursday's series finale.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're still in the driver's seat,'' said Padres left fielder
Greg Vaughn, who has recovered enough from a strained left
quadriceps muscle to be in the starting lineup tonight for the
first time since Game 1. ``The pressure is still on them. We split,
we win.''
</P>
<P>
   But perhaps the Braves like the pressure. Monday's victory
improved their record to 8-4 all-time, including 8-2 this decade,
when facing elimination in the NLCS.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want to say that the momentum is ours when we're still
down in the series,'' Braves pitcher John Smoltz said. ``We haven't
tied the series yet, but when you're in a position like they (the
Padres) were in, you want to end it. Anything possible can happen
in a Game 7, and we have been through our share of Game 7s.''
</P>
<P>
   But, of course, there will be no Game 7 if the Braves don't win
today at Turner Field, which is expected to be sold out for the
first time this postseason.
</P>
<P>
   ``They wanted to wrap it up (in San Diego), and we wanted to
prolong things to get back to Atlanta, and that's what we did,''
Glavine said. ``But they're still one win away from clinching, and
we have to win both games. The Padres are still in a better
position than we are, obviously, because we still have our backs to
the wall.
</P>
<P>
   ``If there is any momentum, it's only because we're obviously
rooting like hell to extend this thing. The Padres wanted to get it
over and go on to the next series. We've been on that side of the
fence. When you're on the verge of getting into the World Series,
there can be a letdown when you don't do it as soon as you'd like.
I just know that they (the Padres) are going to be ready to play,
so I don't know how long this momentum will last.''
</P>
<P>
   The general rule of thumb in baseball is that momentum is only
as good as your next day's starting pitcher. In that case, almost
anyone would give the nod to the Braves today. But it should be
noted that the unheralded Hitchcock has beaten Maddux and Randy
Johnson in his last two starts.
</P>
<P>
   Obviously, matching up against the elite pitchers in the game
doesn't make Hitchcock uneasy. As Brown was walking off the field
in Game 5, Hitchcock went to Padres pitching coach Dave Stewart and
asked for the ball in Game 6.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have confidence in Hitch, and we still like our chances,''
Padres right fielder Tony Gwynn said. ``I don't think anyone in
this clubhouse feels any pressure _ just the opposite. We're pretty
relaxed. No one is afraid of it (being back in Atlanta). No one
feels any pressure. I think the pressure is still on the Braves.
They can't look past one game. It's been that way for two days now.
If we win, it's over.''
</P>
<P>
   And if they don't, the pressure will be on the Padres in a
hurry.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
