<DOCNO> NYT19981014.0036 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-14 01:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5725 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-ROBERTSONCOLUMN-H     10-14 0817
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-ROBERTSONCOLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
DaleRobertson
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; c. 1998, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
ATLANTA _ It is impossible to come back from a 3-0 deficit in the
postseason.
</P>
<P>
   Of course it is. Come on. Get real. It can't happen. The Braves
are only deluding themselves. No baseball team has ever done it. No
NBA team, either, for that matter. Some things simply cannot be
done. They run so counter to the laws of probability that to
suggest their feasibility is to risk being presumed daffy.
</P>
<P>
   If you believe Atlanta can defeat San Diego four times in a row,
after losing to San Diego three times in a row, you are also no
doubt capable of thinking it's within the realm of possibility for
a man to bash 70 home runs in a single season and win the homer
championship by only four.
</P>
<P>
   You would probably try to tell us Cal Ripken could remove
himself from the Orioles' lineup.
</P>
<P>
   Or dare suggest a rookie pitcher could strike out 20 batters in
a game.
</P>
<P>
   Or envision Greg Maddux earning a save and Kevin Brown suffering
a loss in relief _ on the same night.
</P>
<P>
   You could probably even picture Randy Johnson wearing an Astros
uniform.
</P>
<P>
   You, sir or madam, would be deemed mad.
</P>
<P>
   Have I made my point? In any other year, in any normal season,
the Braves would fall quietly on their tomahawks and, chop, chop,
we could start contemplating the World Series. They would never
have gotten out of San Diego alive, certainly not after trailing
twice entering the seventh inning.
</P>
<P>
   The din alone in Qualcomm Stadium, where the fans behaved more
like those of the football variety, should have shattered Atlanta's
spirit. But baseball is, if nothing else, the most capricious of
pursuits. Bats come alive on a moment's notice; arms and brains go
dead. The hero-to-goat metamorphosis, and vice versa, can be sudden
and unpredictable.
</P>
<P>
   The home-field ``advantage,'' as all the ultimately meaningless
Qualcommotion revealed, means less on the diamond than it does on
any other playing surface. Ditto momentum. It's the most overrated
intangible in baseball, which is the least emotion-driven team
sport.
</P>
<P>
   ``Baseball teams can sometimes be at their very best for a short
period of time,'' Braves general manager John Schuerholz points
out, speaking from experience. ``Ten games, 15 games. Then, all of
a sudden they hit the wall and are no longer doing the things they
are capable of.''
</P>
<P>
   Rewind to 1996. The Braves, trailing 3-1 in the NLCS, up and
destroyed the Cardinals thrice, then whipped the Yankees
back-to-back to start the Series. Cripes, Atlanta scored 48 runs in
five games, yielding but two.
</P>
<P>
   Then nothing. Zip. Zero. Zilch. The Yankees took the world
championship with four victories in a row.
</P>
<P>
   We learned nothing revealing about Atlanta as it embarked, with
no advance warning, on its Mission Valley revival. We already knew,
for example, the Braves could win. They had won 109 times, counting
the Division Series sweep. And we knew, or should have known, they
could hit home runs, because they hit 215 in the regular season.
</P>
<P>
   We knew Andres Galarraga was an RBI machine. Statistical
probability told us he was overdue to collect a bunch, and so he
did with a monster grand slam in Game 4, the broom-breaking blow
that likely ensured our return to Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   After that shot, you sensed an edginess in the Padres during
Game 5 once they went ahead 4-2. They wanted it over a little too
badly, which is why Brown was turned into an emergency setup man.
</P>
<P>
   Uh, Kevin, don't quit your day job.
</P>
<P>
   But don't go assuming the Padres are now devastated by what
happened to them. Manager Bruce Bochy, in fact, said ``devastated''
was far too strong a word. He is still confident enough to have
concluded that saving Brown for a possible Game 7 is the most
prudent way to go.
</P>
<P>
   Brown could pitch Game 6 today _ his arm is fine, though his
nerves might be a bit frayed _ but he won't. Even if the Padres are
left to come to grips with three defeats in a row, Bochy knows a
fourth isn't inevitable. Going 0-3 didn't throttle Atlanta, did it?
</P>
<P>
   Therefore, Sterling Hitchcock gets the nod for San Diego against
Tom Glavine, setting up the strong, and wonderful, possibility of a
winner-take-all showdown between the National League's pre-eminent
righthanders, Brown and Maddux, Thursday night.
</P>
<P>
   Exactly the crescendo this best of all baseball seasons should
deliver as a prelude to the World Series.
</P>
<P>
   Brown knocked out the Braves on Florida's behalf last year and
shut them out for the Padres in Game 2. Now, we wonder, can they
gain a full measure of revenge? One Michael Tucker homer, albeit a
big one, does not full atonement make.
</P>
<P>
   Or are the Padres, baseball's fastest-pedaling team at the
outset of the season, capable of finding a way to finish what they
started?
</P>
<P>
   Either is possible. Anything is possible, it seems.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
