<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-14 01:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5726 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-MODESTI-COLUMN-LA     10-14 0873
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-MODESTI-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DODGERS' MANAGER SEARCH IS CLASSIFIED ENDEAVOR
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEVIN MODESTI  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Help wanted:
</P>
<P>
   Applicants sought for supervisor position in prestigious
midsized company. Experience required. Proven ability preferred.
Bilingualism a plus. A little charisma wouldn't hurt. Competitive
salary. Former holder of job is willing to advise. Contact: Los
Angeles Dodgers. An equal opportunity employer since 1987.
</P>
<P>
   -0- -0-
</P>
<P>
   No, the Dodgers haven't resorted to a want ad, yet.
</P>
<P>
   Their search for a field manager to replace Glenn Hoffman,
``reassigned'' two weeks ago, continues on a don't-call-us,
we'll-call-you basis.
</P>
<P>
   General manager Kevin Malone is making the calls, setting up
interviews. So far, he'll point out, he technically has been turned
down by only one candidate, because he actually has offered the job
to only one candidate.
</P>
<P>
   But how much longer before it turns desperate?
</P>
<P>
   And how much longer before it gets downright embarrassing?
</P>
<P>
   Not long, if the Dodgers try, as it appears they will, to woo
Dusty Baker away from the San Francisco Giants, whom he has no good
reason to leave. In fact, he told the San Francisco Chronicle he's
staying.
</P>
<P>
   Not long, if the Dodgers continue to tease Davey Johnson, the
most obviously qualified (never worse than second in 10 full
seasons as a manager) and most obviously available (he's out of
work) candidate.
</P>
<P>
   Not long, if they end up hiring their fifth choice, former
Boston Red Sox, Texas Rangers and Albuquerque Dukes manager Kevin
Kennedy, and his mixed reputation.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, some would say this whole endeavor, made unusually
public by Malone's chatty personality, is already embarrassing.
</P>
<P>
   Because Jim Leyland, forecast as the ``next'' Dodgers manager
since April, told them no even before they asked, saying it's not
their team he dislikes, it's their entire city.
</P>
<P>
   Because the Dodgers made their first offer to Felipe Alou, a
63-year-old with not so much as a division title to his credit,
only the distinction of having ``overachieved'' with the penny-ante
Montreal Expos.
</P>
<P>
   Because Malone and Dodgers president Bob Graziano flew to the
Dominican Republic to make their pitch to Alou at his winter home,
only to ultimately be turned down after the Expos offered a
contract extension reported to be worth triple the $600,000 a year
he was getting.
</P>
<P>
   How could the Dodgers' manager job be less attractive than the
Montreal Expos'?
</P>
<P>
   We know, Alou is loyal to his longtime club, his wife is from
Montreal, the quality-of-life issues favored Montreal. Also, there
were hints Alou was put off by the prospect of Tom Lasorda looking
over his shoulder.
</P>
<P>
   But next season, he'll be the age at which Walter Alston served
his 23rd and final year as Dodgers manager, so he's nearing the end
of a career in which he has never had a chance to win. Given the
opportunity to join the Dodgers, who would give him
championship-quality players, Alou stayed with the Expos, who will
give him pleasant memories of Pedro Martinez.
</P>
<P>
   If it came down to money, how did the Fox Group get outbid by
the henhouse in Montreal?
</P>
<P>
   It couldn't be because Malone and Graziano underestimated the
going rate for top managers. The week before they made their
approximately $1 million-a-year offer to Alou, the Colorado Rockies
committed $2 million a year to sign Leyland.
</P>
<P>
   So is it that they've set an unreasonably low budget for the
most important hire they'll make (this year)?
</P>
<P>
   And you thought the problem with Fox owning the Dodgers was they
would overspend.
</P>
<P>
   If you've been an L.A. sports fan for long, you're not used to
watching the Dodgers rejected, not to mention the upheaval in the
dugouts and locker rooms of local teams in general.
</P>
<P>
   When most of us were kids, Alston was the manager, John Wooden
was the basketball coach, John McKay was the football coach and
that was that. There was a five-year period in the early '60s when
only one of Southern California's major teams changed coaches or
managers, the Rams replacing Bob Waterfield with Harland Svare
during the '62 season.
</P>
<P>
   And now: In the 4{ years since Del Harris was hired by the
Lakers, the L.A.-Anaheim area's 10 major teams have all changed
coaches and managers, including the Angels twice, the Kings twice,
the Mighty Ducks twice, USC football twice, USC basketball twice,
the Clippers twice and the Dodgers three times.
</P>
<P>
   The Clippers and Dodgers still have vacancies. Nice company.
</P>
<P>
   Eventually, the Dodgers will get their man. Only two questions
will matter in the end: Who is he, and how much dignity will Malone
and the club have lost in the process?
</P>
<P>
   The only thing more embarrassing than losing out to the Expos
would be begging the Giants for permission to talk to Baker.
</P>
<P>
   The only thing more embarrassing than both of those would be
waiting so long to interview Johnson that the Detroit Tigers snap
him up.
</P>
<P>
   This much seems certain: Nothing will be kept secret, every
meeting, every phone call, every ``no thanks'' on the air and in
headlines.
</P>
<P>
   So why not:
</P>
<P>
   -0- -0-
</P>
<P>
   Hello, Classified? We'd like to place an ad...!off!
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-14-98 0125EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
