A5731 &Cx1f; tic-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-GOMEZ-NLCS-AZR &LR;      10-14 0689
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-GOMEZ-NLCS-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MANAGERS STEAL NLCS SPOTLIGHT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By PEDRO GOMEZ  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The two biggest figures in what has already turned
into an incredible and memorable National League Championship
Series are not named Maddux, Gwynn, Galarraga or Brown.
</P>
<P>
   The names of the key people in this series are Bruce Bochy and
Bobby Cox, the managers of the San Diego Padres and Atlanta Braves,
respectively.
</P>
<P>
   Their chess match will enter its sixth stage tonight and a
tie-breaking and deciding seventh match seems imminent, at least if
the baseball gods have their way.
</P>
<P>
   For the first three games, Bochy was Bobby Fischer to Cox's
Boris Spassky, dominating with every move and looking like a genius
in the process.
</P>
<P>
   But suddenly, Cox has begun to rally. In each of the past two
games he's made brilliant moves, ones Bochy has not been able to
counter.
</P>
<P>
   Each manager also had made his share of questionable moves.
</P>
<P>
   Bochy bringing in Kevin Brown to relieve in the seventh inning
Monday night seemed as if it would go down as one of the most
memorable and timely playoff moves ever. But allowing Brown to
remain in the game and pitch the eighth after he retired all three
batters he faced the previous inning was asking a little too much,
even from someone who never turns down an opportunity to pitch.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Tucker's three-run home run off Brown will serve as a
bitter reminder of that point for Bochy. In truth, however, who
would not have stuck with Brown in that situation?
</P>
<P>
   The Braves were only six outs away from elimination, and Brown's
impressive track record against Atlanta (he has suffocated them
three times in the LCS in the past two seasons) surely had the
Braves spooked.
</P>
<P>
   In retrospect, maybe Bochy should have gone to Donne Wall or Dan
Miceli and then turn things over to nearly impenetrable closer
Trevor Hoffman, the Dennis Eckersley of this era.
</P>
<P>
   Leaving a tired Joey Hamilton in for one too many innings in
Game 4 also cost the Padres, who were leading, 3-2, when Atlanta
scored six runs in the seventh inning for its first win of the
series.
</P>
<P>
   There was also that move to bring in Randy Myers in the same
game. Myers has not looked good for some time, and he wound up
loading the bases before giving way to Miceli, who gave up the big
blow of the inning, the grand slam by Andres Galarraga.
</P>
<P>
   But Bochy was pure genius in the first three games, using his
bullpen nearly flawlessly in the 10-inning victory in Game 1. Game
3 may have been Bochy's crowning moment in the series, which also
earned him Player of the Game honors from the FOX television
announcers.
</P>
<P>
   Cox, on the other hand, basically got his hat handed to him in
the first three games. Almost every move he made backfired.
</P>
<P>
   Cox was ready to hear second-guessing over his move to lift Greg
Maddux for a pinch-hitter after five innings in Game 3, the same
game Cox burned his best bat on the bench, Ryan Klesko, by allowing
him to bat with first base open and a runner on second. Klesko, of
course, was intentionally walked.
</P>
<P>
   Later in the same inning, Cox used his best pinch-hitters _
Michael Tucker and Greg Colbrunn _ and was left having to leave
Keith Lockhart to bat with the bases loaded and one out in the
eighth inning. Lockhart flied to shallow left, and the inning ended
one batter later when Javier Lopez struck out.
</P>
<P>
   Suddenly, though, Cox has redeemed himself. Bringing in Maddux,
who had not made a relief appearance in 11 years, for the final
three outs of Monday's game will be talked about for years.
</P>
<P>
   There will be more buttons to be pushed tonight and possibly
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Overall, the puppeteers of this series have made mostly
brilliant moves. Each knows his club's strengths and weaknesses and
for the most part has put his players in the best position to
succeed.
</P>
<P>
   Sit back and soak in the moves during Game 6 tonight. It's all
part of the game within the game, which can be a beautiful thing to
watch when done masterfully. &QL; 
Pedro Gomez can be reached at pedro.gomez(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-14-98 0130EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
