<HEADLINE>
NBA OWNERS OVERESTIMATE  GAME'S ALLURE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By DAN BICKLEY  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   People who are rich assume they are smart. Even if they tripped
over their own feet and landed in a wheelbarrow of cash, their
windfall was born of higher intelligence.
</P>
<P>
   Or so they begin to believe.
</P>
<P>
   The same principle now applies to the NBA, a league that has
jumped to some dangerous conclusions.
</P>
<P>
   As the first two weeks of the season have been officially wiped
out, here's the truth:
</P>
<P>
   The NBA has overestimated its hold on you. The NBA thinks it's a
vital part of American culture when it was merely flavor of the
month. The NBA believes it will prosper without the golden calf,
that someone will simply step up and replace the impact of Michael
Jordan.
</P>
<P>
   The NBA is in for a rude awakening.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe they weren't paying attention, but there is sorry
precedent everywhere. The NHL still hasn't recouped its losses from
the 1994 lockout. Baseball needed the best season in its rich
history to extinguish the lingering brushfires. The NFL tried
replacement players, and it was a complete disaster.
</P>
<P>
   Up until now, the NBA always stood on the pedestal of
righteousness. The working model for all leagues. The only one that
never lost a game due to labor strife.
</P>
<P>
   Somewhere along the way, the perspective became skewed.
</P>
<P>
   The NBA is 51 years old. The youngest of the four major
professional leagues. The only league that can't fall back on
tradition when all else fails.
</P>
<P>
   The NBA doesn't market its past because its past is shady, at
best. Grainy film of men taking set shots. Dark arenas with 3,000
people in attendance. Coaches who called newspapers after the game
and begged for publicity. Rampant drug use. Teams going bankrupt.
And just 18 years ago, in Magic Johnson's rookie season, the NBA
Finals were shown on tape delay.
</P>
<P>
   Without the bicoastal rivalry of Magic and Bird, one-upped by
the otherworldly talents of Jordan, the NBA would never have
exploded, never grown into a global entity, never blossomed into a
league where the commissioner makes nearly $7 million a year.
</P>
<P>
   To think it will always be this way is a vision clouded by
money. And to think that Jordan is currently dropping hints that
he'd like to play another season, hints that are going unheeded by
the commissioner and owners, is proof of their newfound arrogance.
</P>
<P>
   Take away the Jordan story line from last year's NBA Finals and
the only thing left was bad basketball. Take away Jordan from the
NBA and the only thing left is a league of impostors.
</P>
<P>
   If I'm the commissioner and Jordan says he wants to play another
season, I put both sides in a room until the deal is done. I resume
my spot at the cash register. End of lockout.
</P>
<P>
   Problem is, the owners don't want to budge and the commissioner
is in their corner. They want to abolish the Larry Bird exemption,
even though basketball should have a soft cap, a way to keep stars
in one community and avoid the mercenary-go-round plaguing
baseball.
</P>
<P>
   They want to put a ceiling on labor costs when they should
realize, without the players, they have no product.
</P>
<P>
   No matter who you side with, and the odds are you side with no
one, there is little chance of this being resolved quickly. When
the networks pulled the plug on NFL replacement games in 1987, the
strike was settled within 72 hours.
</P>
<P>
   No matter how long this lockout lasts, NBA owners still receive
their television money this season. That's $23 million per team as
part of a $2.6 billion deal with NBC and TNT, although revenue from
games not played must be paid back at the end of the deal.
</P>
<P>
   Yeah, right. Put it on their tab.
</P>
<P>
   So much for incentive, and so much for the league that always
avoided these quagmires.
</P>
<P>
   Now, they are willing to risk everything. Willing to push
greed-sickened fans over the edge. Willing to watch Jordan walk
away from basketball for the same reason he did baseball.
</P>
<P>
   Willing to believe your tolerance has no boundaries. And that's
the most dangerous conclusion of all. &QL; 
Dan Bickley can be reached at dan.bickley(at)pni.com. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
