<HEADLINE>
KLASSEN TO MISS REST OF FALL LEAGUE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB COHN  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Diamondbacks infielder Danny Klassen has a shoulder injury that
will cause him to miss the rest of the Arizona Fall League season.
But he is expected to be ready by the start of spring training.
</P>
<P>
   Klassen, who probably will compete with Tony Batista for the
starting shortstop job, suffered a slightly torn labrum in his left
(non-throwing) shoulder on Sunday. The labrum is a type of
cartilage.
</P>
<P>
   Playing for the Scottsdale Scorpions in Peoria against Sun
Cities, Klassen jammed his shoulder diving back to first base on a
routine pickoff play.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to take the conservative, which is to say the
non-surgical approach, and rehab it,'' General Manager Joe
Garagiola Jr. said. ``(Team physician Dr. David) Zeman feels he
will return in the spring and be as good as new. If it was his
throwing shoulder, we would have more concern.''
</P>
<P>
   Klassen was scheduled to return home to Florida today and begin
his rehabilitation.
</P>
<P>
   ``Knowing Danny, he will follow that religiously,'' Garagiola
said. ``We're all very confident we will get a complete, healthy
player in Tucson next spring.''
</P>
<P>
   Garagiola said the Diamondbacks are working on coming up with a
replacement for Klassen on the Scorpions.
</P>
<P>
   Klassen hit .194 in 108 at-bats for the Diamondbacks after being
called up from Triple-A Tucson in midseason. He missed several
weeks after he was sent back Tucson and suffered a fracture in his
left shoulder. This injury, however, is unrelated.
</P>
<P>
   ``Danny was really looking forward to having a successful Fall
League, based on the time he missed in Tucson,'' said Tommy Jones,
the Diamondbacks' director of minor league operations. ``But he'll
get to start from scratch in the spring. The people in this
organization are very aware of what his capabilities are.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, two other Diamondbacks prospects are unsure where
they will play this winter. Outfielders Rob Ryan and Mike Stoner,
who were with Tucson last season, were set to play for La Romana of
the Dominican Republic winter league. But Hurricane Georges
virtually wiped out the team's facilities.
</P>
<P>
   The pair might be re-assigned to one of the four remaining
Dominican teams (San Pedro de Macoris also had to cancel its
season), or, more likely, one of the other Latin American winter
leagues. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
