</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-COYOTES_ISBISTER-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SCHOENFELD: COYOTES HAVEN'T GIVEN UP ON ISBISTER  
 IMMEDIATE ROLE REMAINS CLOUDY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB MCMANAMAN  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Coyotes fans were asking a ton of questions after the team's
dreadful opening night loss to the Ottawa Senators.
</P>
<P>
   Where was the offense? Where was the defense? What's wrong with
the power play? Who should skate with who?
</P>
<P>
   Oh yeah, and where was Brad Isbister?
</P>
<P>
   Coyotes Coach Jim Schoenfeld asked himself that same question
over and over again during the preseason, when the talented young
left wing virtually disappeared. They weren't ready to put his
picture on a milk carton, but after recording only two assists in
seven games, Isbister was definitely missing.
</P>
<P>
   And that's why the 6-foot-4, 227-pounder was missing from Sunday
night's lineup. He was benched; a healthy scratch. The same thing
might happen Thursday when the Coyotes host the Colorado Avalanche,
a team they haven't beaten since moving to Phoenix three seasons
ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've talked about Izzy before, about our expectations and our
aspirations, but he just didn't have a good preseason,'' Schoenfeld
said. ``He sort of played himself off the initial roster for Game
1. But it doesn't mean he won't be in for Game 2.''
</P>
<P>
   Nothing is certain at this point. The 21-year-old Isbister might
break out in a big way or he could stay stuck in a slump. He might
stay in Phoenix. He could be sent to the team's affiliate in
Springfield, Mass. He might play. He could continue to sit.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was pretty disappointed the other night, of course,'' he
said. ``You never want to sit out a game. It was a coach's decision
and there's nothing I could do about it. But I'll get my chance to
show that I belong and that I want to stay in the lineup.''
</P>
<P>
   He had plenty of chances to score during the preseason. At one
point, his 13 shots on goal were tied for the team lead. But his
point production ranked the same as the number he wears on his
sweater (16).
</P>
<P>
   That isn't close to being good enough, according to Schoenfeld
and General Manager Bobby Smith, each of whom have gone on record
as saying they expect Isbister to be a future, 30- to 35-goal
scorer in the NHL. He has all the tools, from his size to his speed
to his shot. They weren't banking on it happening this season, but
they felt safe in suggesting he'd vastly improve on the nine goals
and 17 points he posted in 66 games last season.
</P>
<P>
   Especially by pairing him with veterans such as Jeremy Roenick,
Rick Tocchet and Cliff Ronning in the preseason. And by carving his
name into the second power-play unit, a role he was given at the
very start of camp.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes we try to force young guys into a role that they
aren't ready to handle yet, and that may have been the case with
Brad,'' Schoenfeld said. ``Last year, we played him on a line with
JR and Toc for a large portion of the year. This year, we didn't
know if Keith (Tkachuk) was going to be here, and before we got
Greg Adams, that left side was pretty vacant. . . .
</P>
<P>
   ``But you can't hurry the maturing process. You're 17 until
you're 18, and you can't be 18 any damn quicker, no matter how much
you want. Look how long it took a guy like (Ottawa's Alexei)
Yashin. It happens on nature's time. It doesn't happen on your
wish. With Brad, it might be a situation where we have to be a
little bit more patient.''
</P>
<P>
   A fourth-round draft pick in 1995 after scoring 45 goals and 89
points for Portland in the Western Hockey League, Isbister probably
won't get much, if any, ice time with the club's top two forward
lines. Tkachuk and Adams have those spots nailed down at left wing.
</P>
<P>
   Schoenfeld said he could put Isbister on the third line, which
at times, will be more of a checking line. But by doing that, does
Isbister lose his effectiveness as a point scorer? Maybe. Dropping
him to the fourth line, where he's been practicing lately, doesn't
increase his offense, either. But that's probably where he'll play.
If he plays at all.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's not better than Tkachuk, he's not better than (Dallas)
Drake, he's not better than Adams, at this point in his career,''
Schoenfeld said.
</P>
<P>
   What about moving him to right wing? Isbister has a right-handed
shot and that's the position he played the most in juniors.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's not better than Tocchet. He's not better than (Shane)
Doan. He's not better than (Bob) Corkum, who we had over there on
Sunday,'' Schoenfeld said.
</P>
<P>
   ``But that doesn't mean that the door is closed. He's young.
This is his second year. This is Doaner's what, third or fourth
year? Look, Izzy is a strong, devoted, hard-working kid, but it
doesn't happen because you want it to.''
</P>
<P>
   But nobody's giving up on him.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's important to this team and he's important to this
organization,'' Tkachuk said. ``He's a big, strong kid who can make
things happen and we're counting on him to get back into the lineup
and get the job done.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
