A5749 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-MCHALE-COLUMN-LAD     10-14 0833
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-MCHALE-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HEART, CHARACTER WIN CO-MVP
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MATT McHALE  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Vicki and Big Sal got engaged during a pitching
change, for crying out loud. Who did you expect to win?
</P>
<P>
   You don't ask when 57,142 fans run through five choruses of
Sinatra's ``New York, New York'' and hit every high note.
</P>
<P>
   You don't ask when Scott Brosius hits a three-run homer and
looks like Graig Nettles from some long-ago Dodgers nightmare,
taking away extra-base hits at third base and a whole lot of
momentum.
</P>
<P>
   And you don't ask with Darryl Strawberry owning this town from a
hospital bed.
</P>
<P>
   The New York Yankees are champions of the American League. They
were at their best, just when their worst looked like it was
rounding third and heading for home.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday's 9-5, pennant-clinching victory over the Cleveland
Indians was their record 121st of the season and to win it, they
drew on each and every one of those elements.
</P>
<P>
   David Cone lasted just five innings and gave up a grand slam to
Jim Thome that nearly gobbled up a 6-0 Yankees lead. But he got the
next two outs and turned it over to the bullpen. Cleveland was
never heard from again.
</P>
<P>
   ``All I can say about David Cone was that he won,'' weary
manager Joe Torre said. ``You give him a little bit more rope
because of his heart.''
</P>
<P>
   Kind of like his team.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees clearly were baseball's best all season, never
challenged during the regular season or the first round of the
playoffs. There were heroes like Bernie Williams, who won the
American League batting title, and Derek Jeter, who played
shortstop as it has never been played in this team's storied past.
</P>
<P>
   But it was the heart and character of the team Torre brought
together that was the true MVP. It's an ingredient the Dodgers had
in mind when they tried to hire Felipe Alou and thought about Dusty
Baker.
</P>
<P>
   Everything was about the team. It sounds easy. It isn't.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was such a great year in baseball with all the excitement
and the home run records,'' Cone said. ``But this is a team game
and we won this pennant as a team.''
</P>
<P>
   Everybody played a part, even the crowd. Especially the crowd.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly a week ago, their second baseman, Chuck Knoblauch, was
nearly booed off the field here after a colossal lapse in judgment
cost the Yankees a victory and apparently their immortality.
</P>
<P>
   When they lost Game 3 and trailed 2-1 in the series, baseball
Armageddon didn't seem far behind. That's the way it is in New
York. But the Yankees took the next three and now await the winner
of Atlanta-San Diego to see who they play in the World Series.
</P>
<P>
   The rest of the country hates this city, but there isn't much
bad you can say about its ballteam.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday's game started out in cold and rain, but winter seemed a
long way off.
</P>
<P>
   Knoblauch grounded out to open the bottom of the first, but his
presence clearly set the tone. He walked to the plate amid cheers.
The fans hadn't forgotten, but business is business.
</P>
<P>
   Cone was spotted a 6-0 lead after Brosius crushed a 416-foot
homer to dead center. Cone caught a break earlier in the inning
when Indians second baseman Enrique Wilson pulled Omar Vizquel off
second base trying to complete a force play. The Indians argued
that Vizquel was on the bag and replays were inconclusive. This
much is fact. If Cleveland makes that play, Brosius never comes to
bat.
</P>
<P>
   It was that kind of night. Vizquel, who came in without an error
in 46 consecutive postseason games, finally made one. And Brosius
came up with two incredible fielding plays. The first came in the
sixth, an inning after the Indians jumped back in the game. Sandy
Alomar Jr. hit a hot smash over the third-base bag. Brosius, traded
last winter from exile in Oakland, dived to his right. Alomar is a
slow runner, but no need to break the mood. Brosius jumped to his
feet and threw him out.
</P>
<P>
   It happened again in the ninth. Mariano Rivera was in to close
it out, but Wilson hit a sure double down the third-base line.
Brosius backhanded the ball and threw out Wilson by a step.
</P>
<P>
   ``All year he made big plays and had big hits,'' said Williams,
who opened the Yankees scoring with a first-inning RBI single.
``And he has been doing most of it from the ninth spot in the
order.''
</P>
<P>
   When Rivera got the final out, players mobbed the field. Later,
Torre was asked if he thought the celebration was subdued.
</P>
<P>
   ``No, but this was the hard part,'' he said. ``Not to take
anything away from the World Series, but that is kind of a reward.
Getting here is so tough.''
</P>
<P>
   And now the World Series, the only championship that will do for
this team. Do they want Atlanta or San Diego? It's a tough question
you can only ask in a tough town.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want the Padres to win,'' said ALCS MVP David Wells, a San
Diego native, who defeated Cleveland in games 1 and 5. ``I guess
I'll have to beat up a few people to get more tickets.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
