<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-14 01:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5752 &Cx1f; tic-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OLY-CHRISWITTY-AZR &LR;      10-14 0760
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-CHRIS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A NAME TO REMEMBER  
 OLYMPIAN WITTY HAS CHANCE TO MAKE HISTORY 
</HEADLINE>
 WITTY-AZR   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By JEFF METCALFE  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The assistant principal at Frank Borman Middle School in Phoenix
has enough to deal with shuttling groups of 500 students in and out
of two assemblies and preserving general order.
</P>
<P>
   He can be excused for an introduction that doesn't capture the
magnitude of one of the Olympic guests.
</P>
<P>
   Not that Chris Witty is insulted.
</P>
<P>
   The unassuming speedskater/cyclist, America's only two-time
medalist at the Nagano Winter Olympics, knows in this U.S. Olympic
Committee Champions of Life context that her story is no more
important than those with whom she shares the stage.
</P>
<P>
   So the seventh- and eighth-graders marvel at Margaret Ambrosia,
80, whose chance to dive at the Olympics in 1940 was taken away by
World War II. And at Paralympian Corbin Beu of Phoenix, whose
wheelchair and persuasive speaking easily grab their attention.
</P>
<P>
   But of the autographs collected on lined notebook paper and even
orange-juice boxes, Witty's is the one to cherish. She has a chance
in 2000 to become the second Olympian ever to medal in the Summer
and Winter Games.
</P>
<P>
   Think how valuable an Eddie Eagan autograph would be today.
</P>
<P>
   It was Eagan, literally living by the code of his dime-novel
hero Frank Merriwell, who rose from poverty in Denver to an
education at Yale, Harvard Law School and Oxford. And to an Olympic
gold medal in boxing in 1920 and 12 years later an Olympic gold in
bobsled, three weeks after taking up the sport.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's kind of the big picture and the small picture,'' Witty
said of vying for the rarified air of Eagan and seven other U.S.
Summer/Winter Olympians. ``As an athlete, we don't really look at
the big picture all the time. Only once in a while do you look back
and say, `Wow, this is really something big we're doing.'
</P>
<P>
   ``My goals are more looking at each sport and what I need to do
and not necessarily looking at `Can I be the first (woman) to do
this?' ''
</P>
<P>
   There are those who think the 23-year-old should not try. She
won a silver medal in the 1,000-meter, her world-record event, and
a bronze in the 1,500 at Nagano.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some are all for it,'' she said. ``Some say why don't you do
that after Salt Lake (2002 Winter Olympics)? Forget about Sydney
(in 2000), do Athens (in 2004). That's something I might consider
if this (speedskating) season and the following season are not up
to par.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been so close (to a skating gold), I can't chance that.
You only have so many opportunities.''
</P>
<P>
   Cycling, though, has similar allure, and Witty's best event, the
500-meter time trial, was added to the women's Olympic program for
the first time in Sydney. She was fourth, .065 seconds out of a
medal, at the World Cycling Championships in August.
</P>
<P>
   ``It did take until later in the summer for me to really start
performing up to par,'' said Witty, a 1996 Olympic cycling
alternate. ``Actually I was very happy with the season. I think
it's more feasible (to medal in both sports). The thing I have to
balance out is how can I do that? At what point do I need to take a
break and at what point do I need to train really hard?
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a little bit behind in speedskating, but I have to look at
the reality of it. I can't medal at every World Cup right now if I
want to do both. I have to just focus on the World Championships
(in February and March).
</P>
<P>
   ``It's kind of hard to do because when you're actually at the
races, you're thinking `I want to win.' I have to realize I can't
do that right now.''
</P>
<P>
   Connie Paraskevin-Young, who joined Witty in Phoenix for the
U.S. Olympic Congress that concluded Tuesday, agrees with that
approach. She is a speedskating/cycling Olympian who won a
match-sprint bronze medal at the Seoul Summer Games in 1988, and
she worked with Witty leading up to this year's cycling nationals.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never took a break in between the two,'' Paraskevin-Young
said. ``The day after the World Championships in cycling, I'd start
my running. The cyclists thought I was nuts, but I loved it.
</P>
<P>
   ``An athlete in Chris' position, if she's seriously trying to do
both sports, can't take that month break in between. She's got to
be an athlete 12 months out of the year.''
</P>
<P>
   Witty, in fact, took a month holiday after Nagano, although she
continued traveling.
</P>
<P>
   ``With two peaks each year, you can rest your body so you can
perform well,'' she said. ``It's mentally how I get through.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-14-98 0149EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
