<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-14 01:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5754 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-YANKEES-INDIANS-B     10-14 1006
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-YANKEES-INDIANS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YANKEES DEEP-SIX INDIANS FOR AL PENNANT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GORDON EDES  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ There is the divine right of kings, the inalienable
rights of Jefferson, and the assumed rights of the New York
Yankees, whose sense of entitlement to the World Series knows no
bounds.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday night was no exception as the Yankees achieved passage
to the World Series for the 35th time in their history with a 9-5
win over the Cleveland Indians that clinched the American League
Championship Series, four games to two.
</P>
<P>
   ``To me, this is the tensest part, getting there,'' said Yankees
manager Joe Torre, whose sunken eyes filled with tears as he hugged
his wife, Alice.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we win the World Series, we'll celebrate, it'll be
magnificent, but getting there is the tensest part. This is very
satisfying.''
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees' advancement to this World Series seemed inevitable
through a record-setting regular season in which the only real
danger they faced came when a 500-pound steel joint fell in Yankee
Stadium back in April, forcing the postponement of two games.
</P>
<P>
   And when they scored six runs in the first three innings
Tuesday, the last three coming on a home run off Indians starter
Charles Nagy by third baseman Scott Brosius, it seemed time to
break out the champagne that has been on ice since Mother's Day.
</P>
<P>
   But there would be one last throat-clutching moment of tension
for the Yankees. The Indians, who came within two outs of winning
the World Series last year, mounted a fifth-inning comeback with
five runs off starter David Cone, with the redoubtable Jim Thome
hitting a grand slam into the third deck, his record fourth home
run in the ALCS.
</P>
<P>
   What Cone had intended to be his defining moment instead
threatened to become a last-second reprieve for the Indians, who
drew within 6-5. Suddenly, the Yankees were more concerned with
simple survival than manifest destiny.
</P>
<P>
   But a throwing error by usually impeccable shortstop Omar
Vizquel opened the way to three more Yankee runs in the sixth.
</P>
<P>
   ``That error turned the whole perspective of the game,'' said
Vizquel, who lobbed the ball over the head of Thome at first,
allowing Brosius to reach on a routine bouncer to short. ``Error on
the leadoff guy, a walk after that. We paid for that error.''
</P>
<P>
   Brosius advanced to second on a wild pitch, and Indians reliever
Dave Burba walked Joe Girardi on a full count.
</P>
<P>
   Chuck Knoblauch fouled off a third-strike bunt attempt for one
out, but Derek Jeter then hit a drive that confounded right fielder
Manny Ramirez, who turned his back to the plate and leaped onto the
wall like a rock climber _ while the ball landed at the base of the
fence. Two runs scored on what was ruled a triple, and one out
later, Bernie Williams made it 9-5 with a single, his third hit of
the night.
</P>
<P>
   ``Like a knife stuck in your heart,'' Vizquel said of Jeter's
hit. ``Your whole body just goes stone cold. And when Bernie
Williams gets another base hit, that's even worse.''
</P>
<P>
   Burba had entered in the fourth inning in relief of Nagy, who
was taken deep by Brosius after another controversial call by
umpire Ted Hendry, who was at the vortex of the Game 2 firestorm
surrounding Knoblauch.
</P>
<P>
   Hendry drew Knoblauch's ire _ and brain lock _ when he declined
to find Travis Fryman guilty of interference after his bunt in the
12th inning of Game 2. On Tuesday night he ruled that Enrique
Wilson's throw had pulled Vizquel off the bag on an attempted force
of Williams, who had singled to open the third.
</P>
<P>
   Wilson's throw to second was slow and to the left-field side of
the bag, but replays showed that Vizquel, stretching like a first
baseman, was anchored to the bag long enough to record the out.
</P>
<P>
   That play would take on enormous significance. Nagy retired the
next two batters, Tino Martinez (strikeout) and Rickey Ledee (fly
ball), but instead of having the inning over, he had to face
Brosius, who homered to center.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was clearly out,'' Indians general manager John Hart said
calmly. ``It was a bad call. It cost us three runs. That's the game
of baseball. Little things can cost you.''
</P>
<P>
   Even then, Thome put the Indians back in the game. Cone had
struck out seven in the first four innings, but three straight
singles, the last striking Hendry in the backside, loaded the bases
with no outs in the fifth.
</P>
<P>
   Cone walked David Justice to force in Cleveland's first run,
which prompted a visit from Torre and assistant trainer Steve
Donohue. Cone remained in the game, striking out Ramirez for the
first out, but Thome sent Cone's next pitch on a majestic arc into
the upper deck, drawing the Indians within a run.
</P>
<P>
   But then the Yankees exploited the error by Vizquel, who had
been flawless afield in 46 consecutive postseason games and had
made just five errors in 720 total chances during the season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I saw the ground ball,'' said Burba, ``and as soon as he
fielded it, I said to myself, `One out _ let's get the next guy.'
Then the ball sailed over Thome's head.
</P>
<P>
   ``I tried to get the monkey off Omar's back. I probably feel
worse than he did. I didn't pick him up.''
</P>
<P>
   Vizquel sat on top of his chair in front of his cubicle in the
mummified losers' quarters.
</P>
<P>
   Was he shocked when he made the error?
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm still in shock,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   And the Yankees are in the World Series. Winners of a
league-record 114 games during the regular season, they have
anniversaries galore to observe in their pursuit of history.
</P>
<P>
   Seventy-five years in Yankee Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   Twenty-five years of George Steinbrenner.
</P>
<P>
   Twenty years after Bucky Dent's screen shot.
</P>
<P>
   Two years after they won their last World Series, helped
immeasurably by a home run by Jim Leyritz, who may be on the other
side this go-round if the San Diego Padres can hold off the Atlanta
Braves.
</P>
<P>
   Oh, and did we mention that it has been 80 years since the Red
Sox won their last World Series, then sold Babe Ruth?
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-14-98 0152EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
