<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-DODGERS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BAKER NOT INTERESTED
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) (UPDATE RE DAVEY
JOHNSON) 
By MATT McHALE  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ One day after the Los Angeles Dodgers appeared ready
to ask the San Francisco Giants for permissiong to talk to Dusty
Baker about their vacant manager's position, Baker said there is no
need.
</P>
<P>
   ``Don't bother calling, I have no interest in managing the
Dodgers,'' Baker told the San Francisco Chronicle on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   It was unlikely the Giants were going to grant permission even
if Baker hadn't responded to reports of the Dodgers' interest.
</P>
<P>
   Giants general manager Brian Sabean said Tuesday at the club's
organizational meetings. ``(Baker) is under contract, that's all I
can say,'' alluding to the two-year extension that kicks in this
season.
</P>
<P>
   Baker led the Giants to a wild-card playoff game against the
Chicago Cubs this past season after winning the National League
West in 1997. He will earn $700,000 this coming season. At the time
Baker signed the extension, the Giants said they wanted him to be
with the club in 2000 when they open their new ballpark.
</P>
<P>
   Because he is under contract, the Dodgers have to receive
permission to negotiate.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Dodgers general manager Kevin Malone has set up an
interview Saturday with Davey Johnson, who also is being considered
for the manager's job in Detroit.
</P>
<P>
   After rushing to hire Felipe Alou, who stayed with Montreal,
Malone said he will be more patient in the next round of
discussions. He hopes to have a manager in place by his own
organizational meetings, Oct. 28-Nov. 1 in Vero Beach, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Since the Tigers' payroll is not expected to climb above $30
million next season, Johnson clearly is hoping the Dodgers act
soon. They are expected to have a $75 million payroll in 1999.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-14-98 0218EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981014.0062 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-14 03:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5837 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-VISAS-HIGHTECH-SFCHRO     10-14 0452
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VISAS-HIGHTECH-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CONGRESS REVIVES SKILLED WORKER VISAS 
</HEADLINE>
   By LOUIS FREEDBERG  
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ After suffering a near-fatal setback last week, a
measure sought by Silicon Valley firms allowing them to hire
additional temporary foreign workers has been revived. It will be
included in a huge spending bill being negotiated by the White
House and Republican leaders.
</P>
<P>
   Unless there is a complete breakdown in budget negotiations, the
bill is expected to be approved by Congress and signed by President
Clinton within the next few days.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a big victory for the economy, which is being fueled
in large part by our high-tech industries,'' said Sen. Spencer
Abraham, R-Mich., the chief sponsor of the bill, which also
received the strong backing of California Sens. Dianne Feinstein
and Barbara Boxer. ``The legislation strikes the right balance in
safeguarding America's competitive edge and protecting U.S. jobs.''
</P>
<P>
   The White House also welcomed the measure's inclusion but
cautioned that nothing is final until the budget talks conclude.
</P>
<P>
   ``The White House, Spencer Abraham, Sen. Boxer and others have
all been pressing hard for this to be included in the bill, and
while nothing's over 'til it's over, the prospects for its
inclusion are looking quite good,'' said Gene Sperling, chairman of
the White House National Economic Council.
</P>
<P>
   The bill, which has already been overwhelmingly approved by the
House, would increase the number of visas issued to temporary
workers from 65,000 to 115,000 for each of the next two years, and
set it at 107,500 for one year after that.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton had earlier agreed to increasing the number of skilled
worker visas but insisted on including several other provisions,
including requiring employers to pay $500 for each foreign worker
they hire. The fee would go into a fund to retrain American
workers.
</P>
<P>
   Friday, Sen. Tom Harkin, D-Iowa, who is closely allied with
labor organizations, blocked passage of the bill by placing a
``hold'' on the bill, a common parliamentary procedure. Harkin said
he does not believe there is a sufficient shortage of skilled
American workers to justify importing extra foreign workers to fill
computer-related jobs.
</P>
<P>
   Because the legislative session is expected to end this week,
there would have been no time to use normal parliamentary practices
to overrule Harkin, and high-tech industry representatives feared
the bill would die altogether.
</P>
<P>
   But Abraham, along with high-tech lobbyists, went around Harkin
and persuaded Republican leaders to include the bill in the Omnibus
Appropriations Bill, a measure that includes financing for most
federal programs.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-14-98 0354EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981014.0063 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-14 03:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5838 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-STANFORD-NOBELWINNER-     10-14 0883
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STANFORD-NOBELWINNER-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STANFORD PROF WINS NOBEL FOR BREAKTHROUGH QUANTUM THEORY 
</HEADLINE>
   By CARL T. HALL and BILL WORKMAN  
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
    SAN FRANCISCO _ Robert B. Laughlin of Stanford University won
the Nobel Prize in physics Tuesday for a groundbreaking explanation
of a bizarre sideways dance performed by ensembles of electrons
trapped in a two-dimensional space.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Two other physicists, Horst L. Stormer of Columbia University
and Daniel C. Tsui of Princeton University, shared in the prize for
earlier experiments that set the stage for Laughlin's work.
</P>
<P>
   The Royal Swedish Academy of Sciences also awarded Nobels in
chemistry Tuesday to scientists at U.S. universities for pioneering
work in quantum theory.
</P>
<P>
   Walter Kohn at the University of California at Santa Barbara and
John Pople of Northwestern University in Chicago, both prominent in
the field of computational chemistry, were recognized for
developing new tools to predict the behavior of chemicals.
</P>
<P>
   Each Nobel comes with a cash award of $978,000, shared by the
winners in each category. It is the fourth year in a row that a
Stanford physicist has won the honor.
</P>
<P>
   Laughlin learned of the award from his 13-year-old son, Todd,
who fielded the call from Sweden on a Mickey Mouse phone in his
room.
</P>
<P>
   A Nobel favorite for years, Laughlin joked that he had begun to
feel ``kind of like being the only kid on the block who doesn't
have one'' after working among such past Stanford laureates as
Steven Chu, Douglas Osheroff and Martin Perl.
</P>
<P>
   Laughlin, 47, was honored for startling insights published in
1983 while he was a staff scientist at Lawrence Livermore National
Laboratory, and which developed from work he did at the old Bell
Labs.
</P>
<P>
   His theories followed the experimental findings of Tsui and
Stormer, which had set the physics world abuzz by establishing a
so-called fractional quantum Hall effect _ where groups of
electrons act as if they are quarks, or fractions of a single
electron.
</P>
<P>
   The work has since become a keystone of a new field of quantum
physics, distantly related to a classic discovery in 1879 named for
physics pioneer Edwin Hall.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were a lot of implausible explanations,'' recalled
Laughlin's longtime colleague, Livermore physicist Stephen Libby,
``and then Bob came out with this gorgeous and obviously brilliant
explanation.''
</P>
<P>
   In almost any introductory physics class, students learn that
electrons moving along a strip of metal will deflect sideways if
subjected to a magnetic charge operating perpendicular to the
strip. This sideways move puts more electrons on one side than the
other, creating a charge.
</P>
<P>
   The stronger the magnetic field, the higher the charge. The
physicist Klaus von Klitzing, who won the Nobel in 1985, applied
the principles of quantum physics to show that under special
conditions of two-dimensional space, the same particles would move
in a stair step fashion.
</P>
<P>
   In essence, each ``jump'' was equivalent to a single electron's
``unit charge.'' The Tsui-Stormer experiments that won the shared
Nobel took that a step further, showing that under colder
temperatures and higher-powered magnetic fields, the electrons
could move in steps within the steps.
</P>
<P>
   Because there was no actual splitting of any electrons into even
smaller particles, no theoretician could explain it until Laughlin
came along.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was incredibly puzzling. It was a totally puzzling
result,'' said Richard Fortner, head of the physics lab at
Livermore.
</P>
<P>
   The theory took quantum mechanics to new plateaus, unleashing a
bizarre new vocabulary that is still puzzling enough to anyone
unfamiliar with such concepts as ``composite bosons'' and
``magnetic flux.''
</P>
<P>
   The practical utility of such fundamental discoveries is yet to
be made clear, either, although experts insist that such advances
as super-efficient computers and power-generation are coming.
</P>
<P>
   Laughlin, a self-taught composer and pianist who frequently
takes friends and family hiking near his cabin in the Sierra,
seemed perturbed by repeated questions as to the usefulness of his
work.
</P>
<P>
   Colleagues noted that Laughlin has long maintained a fierce
advocacy for basic research.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not going to make technology tomorrow, although I could
be wrong about that,'' Laughlin said Tuesday. ``Our business is
finding what is truth and distinguishing what is not true.''
</P>
<P>
   He decried those who might abandon support of the kind of
theoretical research that he and his Nobel colleagues have been
encouraged to pursue.
</P>
<P>
   ``I, for one, am very pessimistic about the chances for even one
generation younger than I to have the opportunity to be where I am
today,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The chemists who were honored Tuesday won for work considered
more clearly linked to product payoffs, such as making the process
of drug discovery less reliant on painstaking experiments to find
out how certain molecules behave.
</P>
<P>
   Work by Pople, in particular, laid a foundation for the modern
pharmaceutical industry, said Peter Kollman, a professor at the
University of California at San Francisco's School of Pharmacy.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are probably 2,000 people who do this now in industry
and at universities, and they all rely on the work that he did,''
Kollman said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
