<HEADLINE>
STARS' BELFOUR MASTERS HAWKS AGAIN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MIKE HEIKA 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS _ The statistics don't show it, but Ed Belfour continued
his mastery of his old team last night.
</P>
<P>
   The Stars goalie had only 13 saves, but that was enough to give
him a 3-1 victory and keep him undefeated in four tries against the
Chicago Blackhawks.
</P>
<P>
   ``It definitely is a challenge,'' he said. ``I played there 10
years. I definitely enjoy competing against them.''
</P>
<P>
   The victory pushes the Stars to 2-0 this season and was a
``playoff caliber'' test, coach Ken Hitchcock said. The Stars
outshot the Blackhawks, 31-14, and at times tilted the rink so
heavily that the Stars' end of the ice was in pristine condition.
Only Chicago goalie Jeff Hackett's performance kept his team in the
game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought the goalies were the two best players on the ice,''
Hitchcock said.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, the Stars had plenty of contributions that forced
Hackett into his dazzling performance: Mike Modano had a gritty
rebound goal off a Brett Hull shot and was a frustrating penalty
killer, as well. He added three takeaways and had a 15-11 night in
the faceoff circle. Pat Verbeek had his second goal in two games
and never backed down when the game got physical. In fact, he set
up his own power-play goal by forcing Blackhawks defenseman
Christian LaFlamme into the penalty that gave the Stars the man
advantage. Derian Hatcher and Richard Matvichuk were bruising in
their protection of Belfour, dishing out 12 hits (Hatcher had
seven) and shutting down a good performance by Blackhawks center
Doug Gilmour.
</P>
<P>
   The list goes on. Defenseman Darryl Sydor had two assists. Jamie
Langenbrunner and Dave Reid were again strong in combination with
Verbeek. Defenseman Craig Ludwig dished out five hits in only 12:21
of ice time.
</P>
<P>
   ``Both teams played extremely hard. And if you didn't play hard,
you were exposed pretty simply,'' Hitchcock said.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the Stars' only real mistake of the game came when
center Guy Carbonneau fumbled a puck behind his own net midway
through the first period. Gilmour, who joined the Blackhawks as a
free agent in the off-season, scooped it up and fed linemate Chad
Kilger for an easy shot from the slot.
</P>
<P>
   That put the Stars behind, 1-0, at the 12:53 mark. But a team
that was 7-14-3 last season when allowing an opponent to score the
first goal, bounced back and took control.
</P>
<P>
   Verbeek scored walking into the slot after a pass from
Langenbrunner to tie the score at the 18:17 mark of the first
period.
</P>
<P>
   Then, Modano gave the Stars the lead, scoring only 44 seconds
into the second period. Brett Hull, who has 10 shots and two
assists in his first two games with the Stars, took a pass from
Sydor and circled around the back of the net, drifting out to the
high slot where he found himself alone. Hull whipped a
cannonball-shot at Hackett and the Blackhawks goalie wasn't able to
completely smother it. Modano needed two pokes to finally push in
the game-winner _ his second game-winner in two games.
</P>
<P>
   Belfour had faced only four shsthat time, and the Stars at one
point had outshot the Blackhawks, 20-4. But Belfour, who is 4-0 and
has given up only two goals in four games (0.50 goals against
average) against his former team, came up biggest in the second
period when Chicago had a five-on-three for 52 seconds.
</P>
<P>
   The save of the game came when burly Blackhawks winger Eric Daze
was alone in front of Belfour on a mad scramble and rocketed a shot
for the lower left corner 12 minutes into the second period.
Belfour, falling backward, made a toe save, lost his stick and
still was quick enough to recover for another flurry that came
seconds later.
</P>
<P>
   ``Eddie had two great saves on that five-on-three,'' Hitchcock
said. ``That was huge.''
</P>
<P>
   He was just as strong in the third period, holding a 2-1 lead
until the final second when Matvichuk scored from 130 feet into an
empty net.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
