<SLUG> BC-BBA-YANKEES-INDIANS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YANKEES RAISE AMERICAN FLAG
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOHNNY PAUL 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Few remember the 1906 Chicago Cubs.
</P>
<P>
   Their single-season record of 116 victories became little more
than a notation for baseball's record books after the Chicago White
Sox won the World Series that season.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees, who advanced to their 35th World Series with last
night's 9-5 victory against the Indians in Game 6 of this American
League Championship Series, wish to avoid a similar fate.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess anybody is vulnerable,'' said left-hander David Wells,
the series most valuable player for his victories in Games 1 and 5,
``but we're just fighters.''
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees, whose 114 regular-season victories established a
league record, demonstrated that in the game's decisive sixth
inning after the Indians _ who once trailed by six runs _ rallied
within one.
</P>
<P>
   Right-hander Dave Burba induced what appeared to be a routine
ground ball from third baseman Scott Brosius. But Omar Vizquel _
the game's best-fielding shortstop _ launched an errant throw, and
the Indians' hopes of forcing Game 7 began to unravel.
</P>
<P>
   Burba issued a walk to catcher Joe Girardi, and a one-out triple
by shortstop Derek Jeter gave the Yankees an 8-5 lead and ensured
that baseball's winningest team this season would participate in
the Fall Classic.
</P>
<P>
   ``We played with fire all night long with three errors, and we
got burned by it,'' said manager Mike Hargrove, whose Indians
allowed five unearned runs in a four-run loss.
</P>
<P>
   Right-handed reliever Ramiro Mendoza, whom Yankees manager Joe
Torre summoned from the bullpen in the sixth inning to replace
starter David Cone, never gave the Indians a chance to mount a
threat.
</P>
<P>
   Mendoza, who retired nine of 10 batters, pitched three scoreless
innings. Yankees closer Mariano Rivera pitched a perfect ninth
inning and terminated this series by inducing a weak ground ball in
front of the mound from Vizquel for the game's final out.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees' early 6-0 lead appeared insurmountable with Cone _
one of the major leagues' four 20-game winners this season _ on the
mound and in control as seven strikeouts through four innings would
suggest.
</P>
<P>
   Indians second baseman Enrique Wilson, center fielder Kenny
Lofton and Vizquel loaded the bases, though, with consecutive
fifth-inning singles, and designated hitter David Justice drew a
walk to force across the Indians' first run.
</P>
<P>
   Cone responded with a strikeout of right fielder Manny Ramirez
for the inning's first out, but first baseman Jim Thome returned
the suspense to the series. The left-handed power hitter unleashed
his bat on Cone's first-pitch fastball and deposited it into the
upper deck's right-field seats for a 405-foot grand slam.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees built their six-run lead against right-hander
Charles Nagy, who Monday acknowledged the Indians' glaring
weakness. ``I don't think we have a No. 1 guy on our staff,'' Nagy
said of the Indians' rotation.
</P>
<P>
   Nagy, who this season went 15-10 with a 5.22 earned-run average,
certainly cannot be classified as a No. 1 starter and demonstrated
such during his three-inning appearance. Brosius drove that point _
not to mention three runs _ home with his third-inning, 416-foot
home run that gave the Yankees a 6-0 lead.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-14-98 0951EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
