</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RODEO-REPORT-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PBR HELPS RODEO BREAK THROUGH TO BIG CITIES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRETT HOFFMAN 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Several years ago, legendary professional rodeo champion Jim
Shoulders made a very astute observation out of concern for the
sport's desperate need to attract more fans.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to make it a priority to hold rodeos in places like
Chicago, cities were masses of people live, instead of towns like
the Mineral Wellses and Chickasha, Oklahomas,'' Shoulders said.
</P>
<P>
   Good point. In Mineral Wells, with a 15,000 population, the
annual May rodeo's attendance figure is less than desirable. Cities
such as Chicago and Los Angeles, with populations in the millions,
are markets that must be viewed as the new frontier.
</P>
<P>
   Though I agreed with Shoulders], the question lingered in my
mind: How can a sport such as rodeo reach the masses in
metropolitan areas, especially when the majority of Americans have
no firsthand exposure to agriculture and ranching?
</P>
<P>
   The answer has come in recent years: The Professional Bull
Riders Bud Light Cup Tour. It is rodeo's star running back, banging
into the major urban areas and carrying the message to the masses.
</P>
<P>
   Yesterday, PBR officials announced that the association's World
Finals will move to Las Vegas' Thomas and Mack Center next year,
the beginning of a five-year contract. The championships have been
scheduled at Las Vegas' MGM Grand for the past four years.
</P>
<P>
   Moving to the 19,000-seat Thomas and Mack Center gives the
growing and crowded PBR finals about 2,000 more seats. The new
contract also promises more hefty prizes. For the past three years,
the purse for The Nashville Network-televised finals has been about
$1 million. Next year, the finals purse is expected to be $1.5
million.
</P>
<P>
   The bull-riding tour has become a big belt buckle for rodeo.
With its simple format and the element of danger _ a cowboy
attempts to stay on a bull for eight seconds _ bull riding is a
show that contact-sports fans from every strata of society can
cling to.
</P>
<P>
   When Chris Woodruff of Weatherford produced the PBR Bud Light
Cup Tour show last weekend in Columbus, Ohio, the small, 6,000-seat
venue was filled to the brim each night and fans were turned away.
Granted, the bull riding was held in conjunction with a
high-profile horse show (the American Quarter Horse Association
Congress); nonetheless, it was successful in a city that doesn't
thrive on ranching and agriculture. Organizers are talking about
holding two shows in Columbus next year on back-to-back weekends.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this year, the PBR Cup Tour show filled venues in
unlikely cities such as Landover, Md. (15,000 in attendance in the
Washington suburb) and Tampa, Fla. (16,000). Tampa was among 24
cities on the 1998 PBR Bud Light Cup Tour; some others are St.
Louis, Anaheim, Calif., Worcester, Mass., and Fort Worth, which
last year was billed as the top regular-season show.
</P>
<P>
   Next year, the PBR's $5.5 million tour, which includes a stop
March 12-14 in Fort Worth, is expanding to at least 28 stops. Some
new stops include Salt Lake City and Phoenix, which previously held
shows that were produced by a defunct organization called Bull
Riders Only.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps Jim Shoulders spoke prophetically when he said that
rodeo must find a way to reach the masses in cities. After all, in
Shoulders' heyday in the 1950s, rodeo's marquee show was staged in
New York's Madison Square Garden.
</P>
<P>
   In the past three decades, Shoulders sadly watched the sport
settle for rural towns in the heartland. Now that the PBR has taken
the bull by the horns, at least one rodeo event is on its way back
to the big cities.
On the NFR trail When Australia native Scott Johnston finally
acquired a visa last summer that would allow him to compete on the
North American rodeo circuit, the De Leon resident had lots of
catching up to do.
</P>
<P>
   Johnston began his quest for a National Finals Rodeo berth
during the bustling July 4 weekend. Though he got off to a late
midseason start, Johnston ranks 17th in the saddle-bronc-riding
race, two slots away from the elite top 15. After earning a little
more than $6,000 last weekend, he is almost $13,000 behind
15th-ranked Ty Murray.
</P>
<P>
   Moving into the top 15, the criterion for qualifying for the NFR
when the regular season ends Nov. 8, is an uphill battle Johnston
thinks he can win. ``It can be done still,'' Johnston said of
reaching the NFR in Las Vegas in December. ``I'm confident I can
get there, all with God's help.'' He got there last year for the
first time and won the NFR average in saddle bronc riding.
</P>
<P>
   Last weekend, Johnston, 25, won the saddle-bronc title at the
Heart of Texas State Fair Rodeo in Waco. He also paced the field at
Professional Rodeo Cowboys Association shows in Minot, N.D., and
Industry, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   With four weekends remaining in the regular season, Johnston
said he will travel hard.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wouldn't be out here rodeoing if I didn't think I could do
it,'' he said. On fire to win After finishing second in the
goat-tying race last year in the North Texas High School Rodeo
Association, Lacy Averhoff is determined to snare the title in the
1998-99 season.
</P>
<P>
   The Boswell High School senior took the lead in the title race
by winning the goat tying at last weekend's Trinity Rodeo in
Saginaw. After five regular-season rodeos, Averhoff leads the race
with 331 points, 50 more than second-place Jennifer Dennis of
Trinity.
</P>
<P>
   ``This year, I'm expecting to win a saddle,'' said Averhoff,
speaking of the trophy saddle that is awarded to the champion.
``Last year, I didn't win the title, even when I was working really
hard for it. And that's the main reason why I want to win it this
year. It's a goal that I haven't yet accomplished.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition to her strong start goat tying, Averhoff has helped
Boswell take the lead in the team race; Boswell leads Mansfield
1,667-1,652, and third-place Northwest has 1,625 points.
</P>
<P>
   Boswell also has benefited from the efforts of Joe Hub Baker,
who leads the boys' rookie title race, and Travis Forehand, who is
in the top 15 in calf roping and team roping.
III. THE BUZZ
Colleges The men's and women's teams from Hill College won titles
last weekend at the Sam Houston State Rodeo, the National
Intercollegiate Rodeo Association's Southern Region season opener.
Other highlights for Hill at the region's first of 10 season
rodeos: Former South Grand Prairie High School standout Jason
Bennett won the men's all-around title; Eastland native Pecos Pogue
paced the field in saddle-bronc riding; and former Sanger standout
Katie Webster won goat tying.
</P>
<P>
   After finishing second at the Vernon Regional Junior College
Rodeo last weekend, Tarleton State's women lead the NIRA's
Southwest Region team title race over Western Texas, 914 to 625.5.
Tarleton's men won the Vernon rodeo's team title and rank second in
the regional team race with 747, 12 points behind West Texas A&AMP;M.
Bull riding Australia native Troy Dunn of Stephenville enters this
weekend's Professional Bull Riders Bud Light Cup Series
regular-season-ending show in Anaheim, Calif., leading the title
race. After finishing sixth overall last weekend in Columbus, Ohio,
Dunn leads Terry Don West of Henryetta, Okla., 7,149 to 6,365
points. The series concludes with the Nov. 6-8 Las Vegas World
Finals. Stock contracting Fans at Saturday's PBR show in Columbus
were wowed by five final-round scores in the 90s. Four of the bulls
that helped provide the unusually high marks were owned by
Louisiana producer James Harper and Claude Kimbelin, who ranches in
Aubrey. The four bulls were Rampage (Dunn scored 95.5), Nitro
(Chris Shivers, 93.5), Gambler (Norman Curry, 92) and Henry (K.J.
Pletcher, 90).
</P>
<P>
   The other animal that bucked a finalist into the 90s was Terry
Williams' Red Wolf, billed as the PBR's top bull last year. In the
final, Columbus winner Donald Owens turned in a 92.5 atop Red Wolf.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything was in place this weekend, and I'm not just saying
that because I won,'' Owens said. ``The bull riders rode well, the
bulls bucked hard, and there wasn't an empty seat in the house.''
Women's rodeo The Women's National Finals Rodeo is scheduled Oct.
30-Nov. 1 at Cowtown Coliseum in Fort Worth. For information, call
(817) 625-1025.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
