<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-LYONS-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ASSISTANTS SURVIVE IN NFL IF PRIZED PUPILS CAN MAKE THE GRADE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEVIN LYONS 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRVING, Texas _ So there is no confusion, let me get this out of
the way now: Chan Gailey's staff has been a great match for an
offensive unit that was boring, mistake-prone and generally
ineffective in 1996 and 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Gailey is a leading candidate for NFL coach of the year.
</P>
<P>
   But let's look at the offensive staff that was here before
Gailey.
</P>
<P>
   Offensive coordinator Ernie Zampese was criticized here for
being too predictable and for not developing young players. All
Zampese did, of course, was piggy-back on a system that had won two
Super Bowls before he arrived in 1994 and would win another one in
1995.
</P>
<P>
   So what is the ``boring'' Zampese up to now? Coordinating a New
England Patriots offense that scored 40 points against a Kansas
City Chiefs defense that was ranked No. 1 in the league before
Sunday. (By the way, the Cowboys have not scored 40 points in a
regular-season game since 1994).
</P>
<P>
   And what about the other Cowboys offensive assistants swept out
of Valley Ranch when Jerry Jones replaced Barry Switzer with
Gailey? Wide-receivers coach Hubbard Alexander? Tight-ends coach
Robert Ford? Running-backs coach Joe Brodsky?
</P>
<P>
   Alexander, who could never develop another wide receiver
opposite Michael Irvin, looks pretty good ``coaching'' Randy Moss,
Cris Carter and Jake Reed in Minnesota. Brodsky coaches the leading
rookie rusher in the NFC, Curtis Ennis. Ford is now coaching wide
receivers at Miami, where injuries have limited the Dolphins'
passing production.
</P>
<P>
   But the message remains: There are a few great coaches in this
league. And there are a few bad ones. The rest are only as good or
as bad as the players they employ. What does Michael think?
Speaking of coaching, Irvin's take on Gailey is that he is an
intelligent coach who is confident of his plan, and that the sooner
players realize Gailey's intelligence level, the better off they
will be.
</P>
<P>
   ``I see the direction we're headed, and it's a positive
direction. Everybody is upbeat and comes to work ready to work.
It's good to be back on track with that,'' Irvin said. ``Chan is
totally in control of the whole team. In meetings, he breeds
confidence. All we got to do is listen and do what he says and
we'll be okay.'' Backup success Several former backup Cowboys
quarterbacks led charmed lives last weekend.
</P>
<P>
   Wade Wilson (1995-97) threw a 68-yard pass to James Jett with
1:28 to go as the Raiders beat the San Diego Chargers, 7-6. Rodney
Peete (1994) rushed for one touchdown and threw another as the
Eagles beat the Washington Redskins, 17-12. Steve Beuerlein
(1991-1992) completed 18 of his first 19 passes, but the Panthers
lost to the Cowboys.
</P>
<P>
   And we can't leave out the guy who gave the Cowboys a hand in
Super Bowl XXX. On Sunday, he threw a 25-yard touchdown pass to
give the Bengals a 25-20 victory against the Pittsburgh Steelers.
</P>
<P>
   Nice going, Neil O'Donnell. Inside the locker room With three
interceptions and two touchdowns on returns, Deion Sanders is
having his best season in a Cowboys uniform. He is one of the
leading candidates for NFL most valuable player. And he is quickly
becoming one of the most electrifying players in Cowboys history,
joining Bob Hayes, Herschel Walker (pre-1989 trade) and Tony
Dorsett. ``Deion is a phenomenal athlete, like the Michael Jordan
of football or as close as you can get to it,'' Irvin said. ``For
me, he is the greatest athlete I've ever seen.'' Sanders, by the
way, will be up for a new contract after next season, but team
owner Jerry Jones said he is certain that Sanders will remain with
the Cowboys for the rest of his career. ... James Bates, the son of
Cowboys defensive-line coach Jim Bates, didn't make it as a Cowboys
linebacker this summer, but he is doing fine in Hollywood. James
has starred in several Pizza Hut commercials and has a part as a
football player in the upcoming movie ``Water Boy'', starring Adam
Sandler. Later this year, James is expected to be in a
yet-to-be-named movie starring Al Pacino and Dennis Quaid.
 &LR; tagtop:Kevin Lyons, (817) 390-7237
 &LR; tagbottom:lyonsnfl &LR; star-telegram.com
</P>
<P>
   Yardsticks: How far do the Cowboys have to go?
First-and-10
</P>
<P>
   The best Monday-morning quarterbacking is done by Cowboys
officials who watch film the day after games and chart tackles.
Minutes after the Carolina game, Greg Ellis was credited with five
tackles. But a review of the film showed he had nine. Fred
Strickland (six to 10) and Dexter Coakley (four to eight) also had
better games than what the naked eye showed.
Halftime break
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys have outscored their opponents, 84-26, in the second
half. Coach Chan Gailey would like to think that the club's
conditioning has been a big factor. ``We're able to able to come in
the locker room and recover at halftime and go out and play at a
high level,'' he said.
Third quarter of life
</P>
<P>
   Cowboys owner Jerry Jones turned 56 yesterday. Gailey ended
yesterday's news conference joking, ``I need to go get \RJones\S a
card.'' Jones then joked about his ride to work through a
neighborhood yesterday morning. ``The \Rpoliceman\S stopped me. I
said, `You know it's my birthday.' He said, `You shouldn't be
driving at your age.' ''
</P>
</TEXT>
