 ENTERTAINMENT SUMMARY No 406 - October 14, 1998   ENTERTAINMENT
SUMMARY -- No. 406 -- Oct. 14, 1998 We are offering the following
articles for sale. Please contact us for availability your country.
Best regards, Karl Horwitz
<TEXT>
<P>
   1. MISTER MTV : AT 18, THE ROCK CHANNEL IS STILL ``PRETTY COOL''
Being the coolest rock-music channel on television is one thing,
but staying cool year after year, while expanding around the world,
is quite another. In this interview, Tom Freston, the head of MTV,
offers his insights into the world of pop, the tastes of today's
young people, globalization, American cultural dominance and more.
He also tells how he went from selling toilet paper to selling rock
music -- and explains how those teenage icons Beavis &AMP; Butthead
will change, just a bit, when they start speaking Russian. From Der
Spiegel. 1,000 words. Q&AMP;A format. (English translation available.) 
____________________________________________________________________
____ 2. CHEAP THRILLS IN MAINSTREAM CINEMA Pornographic violence
and explicit sex - once the realm of the 'B' movie - elbow their
way into mainstream cinema very regularly today. The idea of the
difficult-to-watch imagery is not merely to shock or entertain, but
to convey a certain hyperrealism in the service of a sweeping
social or political message. By Diane Cardwell. From The New York
Times Magazine. 1,000 words. 3. BRYAN ADAMS, SINGING FOR AN
AUDIENCE OF ONE Brian Adams has recorded 10 albums and sold more
than 55 million records. His name is in the Guinness World Book of
Records (for the longest-standing No. 1 single in British music: 16
weeks for ``Everything I Do, I Do It For You.'') But as he marks
the release of his new album, ``On A Day Like Today,'' he claims to
be indifferent to the reactions of audiences, critics or even
record buyers. At this stage, he says, he writes songs solely to
please himself. In this interview Adams talks about the album, his
new, more upbeat outlook on life, why he usually takes so long to
put together an album and how his globetrotting youth as the son of
a Canadian diplomat - and his early exposure to war and the drug
world - affects his music to this day. By Bonnie Siegler. 1,400
words + photo. 4. THE THIRD COMING OF SHARON STONE Since she
uncrossed her legs and caught everyone's attention in ``Basic
Instinct,'' Sharon Stone has become serious, being nominated for an
Oscar in ``Casino'' (1996,), playing a Death Row inmate in ``Last
Dance'' (1997) and now playing a very realistic mother of a
disabled child in ``The Mighty.'' In this interview Stone talks
about the new film, the impact of her marriage to San Francisco
publisher Phil Bronstein, how she knows what it is to be taunted as
a child and why she recently said no to ``Basic Instinct 2.'' By
Ian Spelling. 1,200 words + photo. 5. FACE VALUE : BACK TO BASICS?
SHARON STONE Artist Vince Lehmkuhl offers an intriguing cartoon of
Sharon Stone in ``The Mighty,'' as her hard-working mother
character opens a door to discover a calendar of her in the1992
film ``Basic Instinct.''
_______________________________________________________________ 6.
ASHES TO ASHES AT BURNING MAN '98 Participants at the annual
Burning Man Festival, held in a dry lakebed in Nevada, expose their
creative inner selves by shedding Armani suits or Gap jeans and
reinventing themselves in neon glitter body paint, jewels or
feathers. Almost everyone is naked, in one way or another. By
Brooke Comer. From The Hollywood Reporter. 1,800 words + photo.
_______________________________________________________________ 7.
SANDRA BULLOCK PRACTICES 'MAGIC' WITH HER LATEST FILM In
``Practical Magic,'' an engaging romantic comedy with a
supernatural edge, Sandra Bullock and Nicole Kidman play sisters
who happen to be witches. The magical realism of the story appealed
to Bullock, she says, since her own life is full of things she
can't rationally explain. ``There really is a higher connection. I
believe in karma, I believe in destiny,'' she says. By Joshua
Mooney. BPI. 1,200 words + photo.
________________________________________________________ 8. THE
FAR-RANGING WORLD OF QUEEN LATIFAH Queen Latifah has reinvented
herself numerous times - even her name is her own inspiration - but
now she is in overdrive. The rap star has a hot new album, ``Order
in the Court,'' a new film, ``Living Out Loud,'' and even a book in
the works. In this interview she talks about the film, why she's
devoting her next album to jazz songs, how she dealt with the 1996
near-fatal shooting of a close friend and what she thinks of her
image as a legendary tough cookie. By Cindy Pearlman. 1,400 words +
photo.
