</P>
<P>
   CERABINO-COLUMN _ WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ The last time I had
seen Amy Ballinger, she was on stage and waving a cucumber. That
was about 12 years ago. I paid her a visit on Tuesday. Amy's 89
years old now and living in a retirement complex in Lantana, Fla.
``There are 92 single women here and six widowers,'' she said.
``There was seven but one of them died last week.'' Tough odds for
Amy. (Cerabino, Palm Beach Post) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   BORDERS-COLUMN _ (Cox Net working, Paul will budget this story)
Editor and publisher of the Nacogdoches Daily Sentinel. (Borders,
Nacogdoches Daily Sentinel)
</P>
<P>
   KELSO-COLUMN _ AUSTIN, Texas _ On Monday, Dr. Ferid Murad, a
professor and department chairman at the University of Texas Health
Science Center at Houston, was one of three scientists awarded the
1998 Nobel Prize in physiology or medicine for their work with
nitric oxide. Twenty-two years ago, Murad discovered the common air
pollutant gas is produced by cells, and is needed to relax muscles
and blood vessels in the human body. As it turns out, the blue
Viagra pills, an extremely popular new male impotency drug, work by
boosting the gas's effects in the blood vessels of, shall we say,
Ernie. (Kelso, Austin American-Statesman) MOVED.
</P>
