<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KELSO-COLUMN15-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Guys think this Nobel's a real gas
 &HT;    By John Kelso
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ The University of Texas blew a golden
opportunity for a load of big-time free publicity Monday night when
it didn't light the Tower Viagra blue.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, Dr. Ferid Murad, a professor and department chairman
at the University of Texas Health Science Center at Houston, was
one of three scientists awarded the 1998 Nobel Prize in physiology
or medicine for their work with nitric oxide.
</P>
<P>
   Twenty-two years ago, Murad discovered the common air pollutant
gas is produced by cells, and is needed to relax muscles and blood
vessels in the human body.
</P>
<P>
   As it turns out, the blue Viagra pills, an extremely popular new
male impotency drug, work by boosting the gas's effects in the
blood vessels of, shall we say, Ernie.
</P>
<P>
   When Murad discovered the muscle relaxation function of nitric
oxide, he wasn't doing research along those lines. He was studying
the lungs.
</P>
<P>
   So though you couldn't make the claim that Murad was
instrumental in inventing the male engine, so to speak, you could
say he was at least inadvertently responsible for getting it
running again after 300,000 miles.
</P>
<P>
   Why didn't UT seize on this opportunity for even more national
recognition by hanging a Viagra banner from the Tower?
</P>
<P>
   The thing I like about this is that here is a case where the
Nobel Prize has been given for something the average guy can
understand. This is not always the case with Nobel Prizes. Often
the prize is given for rather obscure egghead scientific stuff.
</P>
<P>
   For example, in 1996, two Rice University chemistry professors
won the Nobel Prize for the discovery of fullerenes, or
``buckyballs,'' a molecular form of carbon.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, most guys don't know what ``molecular form of
carbon'' really means. So when they hear the term ``buckyballs,''
they probably figure it's some kind of disgusting toy you can find
on the shelf at Toys 'R Us, right next to the plastic barf.
</P>
<P>
   Or they think it's a medical condition that may or may not be
covered by your health care provider. ``Buckyballs'' aren't the
only items that have ever won a Nobel Prize that might make the
general public wonder, ``What the heck is that supposed to mean?''
For example, in 1977 Ilya Prigogine of UT-Austin won the Nobel
Prize in chemistry for his contributions to the concept of
non-equilibrium thermodynamics.
</P>
<P>
   Ask the average American guy what non-equilibrium means and
he'll tell you it's what happens to you if you suck down the entire
six-pack during the first half.
</P>
<P>
   So it's nice the Nobel Prize is being given this year for
something most guys can comprehend. But there are some other major
finds that have yet to be honored by the Nobel committee that
should be.
</P>
<P>
   How come the Nobel Prize has never been given to the person who
discovered the plastic worm? And how about the trolling motor?
</P>
<P>
   And how come the pop-top creator has never bagged the Nobel?
Remember how difficult life was when guys used to have to go around
asking each other, ``Do you have a can opener?''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, if guys hadn't spent so much time looking for can
openers, guys might not need to take so much Viagra these days.
</P>
<P>
   But that's another matter for Nobel scientists to look into at a
later date.
</P>
<P>
   John Kelso writes for the Austin American-Statesman, Austin,
Texas. E-mail: jkelso(AT)statesman.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
