A6160 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BORDERS-COLUMN15-COX     10-14 0898
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BORDERS-COLUMN15-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    A fine book about Texas singers, writers
 &HT;    By Gary Borders
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   NACOGDOCHES, Texas _ A happy coincidence occurred this week,
when I bought Lyle Lovett's latest CD, ``Step Inside This House,''
and the book fairy brought a review copy of Jay Milner's
``Confessions of a Maddog'' in the mail, both in the same week. I
</P>
<P>
   guess the stars were in the proper alignment, the moon was in
the seventh house and all that. This fine collection of songs, and
Jay's memoirs of hanging around the state's best singers and
writers during the past four decades, fit together like red beans
and rice.
</P>
<P>
   Let's back up. First, Jay's book (University of North Texas
Press, 248 pp.) was long-awaited for those of us who know and
admire him. He's written a book-review column for this newspaper
for going on two decades. His column can be found today in its
usual spot on our book page.
</P>
<P>
   Jay has lived what can only be described as a varied life. He
played on a championship high school football team in West Texas,
got into journalism and eventually ended up as managing editor of
Hodding Carter's Greenville, Miss. Delta-Democrat Times before
heading to the Big Apple to work for the late, lamented New York
Herald-Tribune. He published a novel in the 1960s,
</P>
<P>
   didn't make any money, wrote for Sports Illustrated for a while,
and eventually came back to Texas, where he taught journalism at
SMU and TCU, ran a music magazine, worked for PBS, and hung out
with a fellow group of Maddogs (his term) that included Larry L.
King (the non-CNN Larry who wrote ``Best Little Whorehouse in
Texas); Willie Nelson; Billie Lee Brammer, author of the best book
ever written about Texas politics, ``The Gay Place,''; Jerry
</P>
<P>
   Jeff Walker; Billy Joe Shaver; Bud Shrake, known lately as
collaborator on golf god Harvey Penick's ``Little Red Book'' and
its sequels; and a long line of literary and musical luminaries
from the 1970s and 1980s.
</P>
<P>
   Jay is 74 years old now, and though I haven't seen him in a few
years, unless something has changed he still looks a
decade-and-a-half younger. He's a quiet giant of a man, an
observer, a fine writer, and a gentle soul.
</P>
<P>
   Jay never got rich writing, never got anywhere close, unless
he's holding out on me. I don't think he is. His philosophy of book
reviewing is simple: Review only the books you like. If you read
something you don't like, don't waste your time putting it down.
He's broken his rule a few times, but only rarely. He's one of the
best bargains in this paper at $25 a week for a review by someone
who loves books even more than I do.
</P>
<P>
   I read Jay's book in one sitting, as the first cold front of the
season came in last week, thunder rattling the windows and the
coffee turning cold.
</P>
<P>
   On the stereo, Lyle Lovett sang the songs written by many of the
people Jay was writing about: Guy Clark, Townes Van Zandt and Steve
Fromholz, to name a few. He sang songs like ``If I Needed You,'' by
Van Zandt, who died last year of a heart attack after a long hard
life. It's a song I would take to the desert island with me, to
sing alone if necessary:
</P>
<P>
   If I needed you
</P>
<P>
   Would you come to me
</P>
<P>
   Would you come to me
</P>
<P>
   And ease my pain
</P>
<P>
   If you needed me
</P>
<P>
   I would come to you
</P>
<P>
   I'd swim the seas
</P>
<P>
   For to ease your pain.
</P>
<P>
   I've spent many hours in smoky bars listening to Fromholz,
Willis Alan Ramsey, Jerry Jeff, and Willie (when I could get a
ticket). I still do, whenever these pickers come around, those who
are left. I'll still buy a ticket and endure the drunken college
kids to hear Lyle, or his A&AMP;M roommate, Robert Earl Keen. Or
Lucinda Williams, Chris Wall, or any number of fine Texas singers
and writers.
</P>
<P>
   Music and fine writing still define my life, still keep the
dragons at bay. And that's why Lyle's versions of these songs of my
collegiate youth struck a chord with me, especially as he sang
Walter Hyatt's classic, ``I'll Come Knocking.''
</P>
<P>
   When you want me
</P>
<P>
   I'll come knockin'
</P>
<P>
   At your door
</P>
<P>
   At your door
</P>
<P>
   One of these days now
</P>
<P>
   You'll be rockin'
</P>
<P>
   You'll be rockin'
</P>
<P>
   In my arms once more.
</P>
<P>
   Man. That's great.
</P>
<P>
   Back to the book. Jay spends the last few chapters talking about
his friendship with Joe Murray, who has the World's Greatest Job as
a columnist for Cox Newspapers, the company that signs my paycheck.
Joe goes where he wants and writes about what he wants, because
he's great at what he does. Joe at times makes me want to give up,
to fly up the white flag and surrender this column-writing gig.
He's the best, in my book.
</P>
<P>
   Jay's closing chapter about how he repaired to Lufkin to lick
his wounds, take care of his mama, and eventually learned how to
become friends and bull-shooters with Joe and his merry band of
good ol' boys, is one of the finest parts of this book.
</P>
<P>
   Buy the book. Buy Lyle's CD to go with it. Brew up a strong pot
of coffee and kick back. Pour a little bourbon in the cup if that's
your inclination.
</P>
<P>
   Then thank God you live in Texas, and go ahead and sing along
with some fine songs.
</P>
<P>
   It doesn't get much better than this. Heck, it doesn't need to.
</P>
<P>
   Gary Borders is editor and publisher of the Nacogdoches Daily
Sentinel. His e-mail address is gborders(AT)coxnews.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
