<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MILNER-COLUMN15-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    ``The Ordways'' still one of my favorite books
 &HT;    By Jay Milner
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Speaking of ``The Ordways'' by the late William Humphrey, which
we were doing in this space last Sunday, I just finished reading it
again and I was right. It is one of the best novels I've ever read.
</P>
<P>
   It's not Faulkner, as some would say, including Mr. Humprey
himself before he died last year, but it's in the same ballpark
with the sly old grouch from Oxford, Mississippi, which would be
more than enough to please most writers, unless they were so
competitive they saw it all as a contest like boxing, as Hemingway
and Norman Mailer seemed to do at times.
</P>
<P>
   Humphrey saw himself as a destroyer of myths, despite being a
Texan and a Southerner, according to a new book called ``William
Humphrey: Destroyer of Myths'' by Bert Almon (U. of North Texas
Press). He resented being categorized by state or region, in point
of fact, as he repeatedly stated and implied in letters and
journals and essays quoted by Almon in his fascinating book, which
can be enjoyed by anyone who is interested in reading whether or
not they are Humphrey fans.
</P>
<P>
   Humphrey apparently resented being referred to as either Texan
or Southerner, despite his admiration for William Faulkner, an
admiration alternately spiced with declarations of disdain. But
``The Ordways'' is filled with stories that are as Texan and
Southern as anything written or passed along verbally by J. Frank
Dobie.
</P>
<P>
   It is difficult, if not impossible, to tell stories, fact or
fiction, set
</P>
<P>
   realistically in Texas, or the South for that matter, without
including episodes or stories that seem to have sprung from or are
rooted in myth. Humphrey, his repeated dissent notwithstanding,
tells story after story of mythic proportions in ``The Ordways.''
Those stories and episodes are, in fact, what make the book so
appealing.
</P>
<P>
   The opening episodes are set in an East Texas cemetery where
families have gathered for the annual grave cleaning ritual,
renewing old acquaintances and family ties. And as the graves are
cleaned, the old timers there pass along family tales. Myths, if
you please, or tales that will become mythic in the retelling over
the decades.
</P>
<P>
   Many of these stories are humorous, and some are tragic. One of
my favorites tells of the high falluting family with a colored
butler who went around the dinner table collecting the cobs of the
roasting ears the guests had eaten. He collected the cobs on a
silver tray. ``Our Uncle Hugh happened to be seated next to the
hostess and by the time the white gloved butler got to him the
silver platter was piled high... noticing him at last Uncle Hugh
</P>
<P>
   inspected his soggy offering and in his back country accent,
said, ``No thank you, just the same, don't believe I'll have
any.'''
</P>
<P>
   Then there's the one about Great-Granduncle Giles who was
extremely absent-minded. (I think I've heard this one in my family
somewhere in the distant past .) Great-granduncle Giles once bought
himself a horse and buggy, the first he had ever owned, to go on a
trip to a town that was a three-day ride away. His business
concluded there, he took the train home. About a week later, he
remembered his horse and buggy and bought a round
</P>
<P>
   trip ticket to go get it.
</P>
<P>
   Another uncle had heard that one man's lifetime wasn't long
enough for him to count to one million. He set out to prove this
wrong and commenced counting. Weeks and months later people would
ask him how it was coming along and he would say, ``Three hundred
and eighty-six thousand, four hundred and twelve..now thirteen,''
or whatever it happened to be at the time. He eventually got
secretive about his totals and just how far he finally got no one
ever knew. ``For though he was vouchsafed twelve years more than
his allotted three score and ten, and did hardly anything else
towards the last, his dying words were, 'Tell them that fellow was
right. It can't be done. I only got up to...' And there he stopped
counting.''
</P>
<P>
   As previously stated, not all the Ordway stories were amusing.
``There was Inez Ordway, my grandfather's second cousin. One of her
babies was eaten alive by a sow. Poor Inez never got over it and
wound up with her mind cracked.''
</P>
<P>
   Jay Milner writes for Cox Newspapers. He is the author of the
new book ``Confessions of a Maddog.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
