<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CERABINO-COLUMN15-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Still crazy after all these years
 &HT;    By Frank Cerabino
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ The last time I had seen Amy Ballinger,
she was on stage and waving a cucumber.
</P>
<P>
   That was about 12 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   I paid her a visit on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Amy's 89 years old now and living in a retirement complex in
Lantana.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are 92 single women here and six widowers,'' she said.
``There was seven but one of them died last week.''
</P>
<P>
   Tough odds for Amy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Three of the widowers are already taken,'' she said. ``But
I've got to start working on a guy who just lost his wife.''
</P>
<P>
   She cackled at her own words. Amy Ballinger, still crazy after
all these years.
</P>
<P>
   Ballinger may just be the oldest living stand-up comedienne,
although for now, she needs a cane to stand up.
</P>
<P>
   Her neighbors at the stately Lakeside Village probably have no
idea just how bawdy the cherubic-faced Ballinger can be.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike me, they hadn't been treated to her nightclub comedy act,
a raunchy set of one-liners delivered in a droll, raspy voice.
</P>
<P>
   Imagine Henny Youngman on Viagra. ``No,'' she said. ``I could
never do my act here. They have prayer groups here, and Baptists.
</P>
<P>
   ``I did a condo once, and they asked for their money back.''
</P>
<P>
   This year, Ballinger hasn't been performing at all. She needed
knee surgery in March and hip surgery in August.
</P>
<P>
   It'd be enough to get most people down. But not Amy. She has
spent too many years laughing at herself and others. Within no time
at all, she's telling me Clinton jokes I hadn't heard yet, and
rehearsing some of her old one-liners on me.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm so old, I remember when only clothes came out of the
closet,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``At my age, my back goes out more than I do.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm so dumb, I thought Alexander's Ragtime Band was a sanitary
belt.''
</P>
<P>
   Amy, please! We're in the lobby of a retirement home.
</P>
<P>
   I hear a young woman employee behind a reception desk trying to
laugh quietly. I had come to visit Amy to see her collection of
return address labels. She's got more than a thousand of them.
</P>
<P>
   Naturally, Amy thinks it's funny.
</P>
<P>
   She wrote me a letter recently and put 34 return address labels
on it, all of them with different designs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I give a little bit of money to charities and they send me
back address labels,'' she said. ``What am I going to do with all
these address labels? I write about two letters a week, and I'm 89.
</P>
<P>
   ``And besides, I e-mail now.''
</P>
<P>
   We page through her label collection. Heart, lungs, kidneys,
diabetes, Alzheimer's, leukemia, March of Dimes, a couple of
cancers, Veterans of Foreign Wars, Paralyzed Veterans, Mothers
Against Drunk Driving, National Wildlife Federation . . .
</P>
<P>
   ``Look at how nice some of these are,'' she said. ``I wish they
wouldn't waste money by sending me any more.''
</P>
<P>
   Amy said she tried to send some back, but they still keep
coming.
</P>
<P>
   After seeing Amy, I spoke to Vince Arch, the executive director
of the American Diabetes Association of South Florida.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a trend with charities,'' he said. ``Statistics show that
if you give somebody something, it has a positive effect in them
continuing to support you.''
</P>
<P>
   Once you give money to a charity, you're likely to get address
labels for years to come.
</P>
<P>
   We figure out some use for Amy's labels.
</P>
<P>
   In between Amy telling me one-liners, we go to the retirement
home library, and she turns her label collection into a cloak and
crown.
</P>
<P>
   The queen of stand-up comedy is sitting down and laughing in her
address dress.
</P>
<P>
   Life is still a hoot.
</P>
<P>
   ``In August, I'm going to be 90,'' she said. ``And I'm having a
big party. It'll be a show.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ninety,'' she said to herself in amazement. ``That's a hell of
an age to still be on stage.''
</P>
<P>
   Frank Cerabino writes for the Palm Beach Post, West Palm Beach,
Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
