<DOCNO> NYT19981014.0081 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-14 10:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6169 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FRAMPTON-ALIVE15-COX     10-14 1030
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FRAMPTON-ALIVE15-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Frampton still comes alive in concert
 &HT;    By Charles Passy
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ If there were a test to determine
whether you're a rock has-been, Peter Frampton would pass with
flying colors.
</P>
<P>
   Appeared on an album of children's songs? Check.
</P>
<P>
   Moved to Nashville? Check.
</P>
<P>
   Started going bald? Check.
</P>
<P>
   Things have changed so much for the 48-year-old rock legend,
whose classic Frampton Comes Alive remains the best-selling live
album of all time, that when he plays Friday at the Coral Sky
Amphitheatre, he'll be opening for Lynyrd Skynyrd, a band that lost
much of its original membership in a 1977 plane crash.
</P>
<P>
   Frampton survived the Disco Decade, but not without watching his
glory days pass by. But say this for the once shaggy-haired
guitarist: He's got a sense of humor about it.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the Rubik's Cube thing,'' he says with a laugh, likening
his career trajectory to that of another once mighty '70s
pop-culture icon. ``You're just a flavor-of-the-month.''
</P>
<P>
   Frampton's ``flavor'' was a tuneful, guitar-thick rock that
managed to catch the public's attention before the disco beat took
over. It was also a music meant to be heard live. Back then, it was
one man, one guitar _ and a million screaming fans.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, 17 million fans, if you count all the people who
purchased Frampton Comes Alive. The album continues to sell a
respectable 100,000 copies yearly _ and that figure should increase
with the recent release of a digitally remastered version.
</P>
<P>
   As Frampton tells it, he always knew the album, which yielded
such hits as Show Me the Way, Baby I Love Your Way and Do You Feel
Like We Do?, would sell well. Just not that well. He recalls that
after its release, he took ``a breather'' before hitting the road
to promote it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I went away for eight days or something and came back,'' he
says by phone from Evansville, Ind., where the Lynyrd Skynyrd tour
was set to open. ``And suddenly, we didn't just have one date in
Detroit, we had like five sold-out shows. And this was my first
tour as a headliner.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, Frampton wasn't a complete rock neophyte. The
British-born musician's career had started in the '60s, when he
joined an English band called the Herd that enjoyed a bit of
teeny-bop fame. Then came a stint with the blues-rock outfit Humble
Pie.
</P>
<P>
   From there, Frampton released four solo albums, setting the
stage for the mass hysteria that would greet Frampton Comes Alive.
</P>
<P>
   Frampton handled the success _ until it started to handle him.
``A lot of money came in quickly, it seemed like it was never going
to stop,'' he says, speaking like the subject of a weepy VH-1
Behind the Music documentary.
</P>
<P>
   The result of Frampton's runaway success? In a word, greed.
``Not my greed,'' he insists, but rather his record company's.
Frampton was cajoled into making another album right away, I'm in
You, which featured the guitarist in a bare-chested pose that
accentuated his sexy, rising star status. Even though it sold more
than three million copies, it was considered a disappointment after
Frampton Comes Alive.
</P>
<P>
   In a way, Frampton became the first of rock's boom-or-bust
stars, paving the way for the likes of Hootie &AMP; the Blowfish, who
suffered a similar downward fate after their gazillion-selling
debut, Cracked Rear View.
</P>
<P>
   And then there's Alanis Morissette, whose second album (due in
November) will no doubt be measured heavily against her first, the
alt-rock sensation Jagged Little Pill.
</P>
<P>
   ``Poor girl,'' says Frampton with genuine concern. ``I so
empathize with her.''
</P>
<P>
   After I'm in You, Frampton essentially lost his way. First,
there was his disastrous 1978 film debut in Sgt. Pepper's Lonely
Hearts Club Band with the Bee Gees and George Burns. Then came a
series of ill-received albums in the '80s. And finally, just when
Frampton had hopes for jump-starting his career by teaming up with
Humble Pie cofounder Steve Marriott, the musician died in a house
fire in 1991.
</P>
<P>
   Frampton takes a, well, meteorological view of his career.
``It's like one of those outdoor thermometers where you've got a
line that pushes it up and down and (says), `This was the high mark
and this was the low mark.'''
</P>
<P>
   But there's a positive side to winding up at the bottom: ''I've
got nothing to lose,'' Frampton says.
</P>
<P>
   And so the rock legend is reinventing himself. Part of the plan
involves a move to Nashville, where Frampton lives with his third
wife and the couple's two kids.
</P>
<P>
   No, Frampton hasn't gone country. But like a lot of one-time
rock stars, he appreciates the fact that the city has ``studios up
the wazoo'' and a wealth of veteran musicians to draw upon for
recordings. ``You can get a classically trained violinist or a
blues guy. Whatever you want, you've got it,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   Although he still sings his classic rockers in concert, he
recently hooked up with Disney for a Winnie the Pooh album. Next up
is a recording of lullabies. ``This is what I really want to do,''
he insists, adding that he wasn't cool with his children until he
appeared on The Simpsons as _ what else? _ a rock has-been at a
concert called Homerpalooza.
</P>
<P>
   As far as maintaining his chops, Frampton is doing quite well,
thank you. Critics have taken note of his recent performances with
Ringo Starr's band and on VH1's Hard Rock Live show. And when he
was on tour this summer, The Dallas Morning News had this to say:
``The singer-guitarist and his three-man band did a good job of
mixing the golden oldies with a few new tunes _ one groovin'
guitar-rocker was better than most of the new Dave Matthews band
disc.''
</P>
<P>
   About the only change in Frampton's life that isn't part of the
plan is his thinning hair. He'd like his long locks back but
accepts the situation like the good-humored rock dinosaur he is.
</P>
<P>
   And what happens when one of his kids finds an old picture of
him in all his big-haired glory?
</P>
<P>
   ``I put it like this: `Daddy used to be really good looking.'''
</P>
<P>
   Charles Passy writes for the Palm Beach Post, West Palm Beach,
Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
