<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Clothes people actually wear: Ann Taylor
 &HT;    (EDS: First in a series. Part two moved Tuesday.)
 &HT;    By Cara Anna
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ There is no Ann Taylor.
</P>
<P>
   Ann Taylor is a name chosen for its marketing value alone. An
All-American name. ``Taylor'' for tailoring.
</P>
<P>
   It beats Mimi Lieberskin or Richard Lieberskin, the names of the
husband-and-wife team that created the company in 1954.
</P>
<P>
   Now Patti DeRosa runs the company. Age 45, size 6. She started
in sales. Like other women in the office, DeRosa test-drives new
clothing ideas. Wears them, washes them.
</P>
<P>
   Some companies don't keep an eye on what walks the fashion
runways. Not this one. ``Our customer is very fashion-sensitive,''
DeRosa says. Call it ``updated classic.''
</P>
<P>
   ``She's not going too far out, but she's fashion-appropriate,''
she says.
</P>
<P>
   The target customer also is interested in fine wine, gardening
and travel. She likes to keep fit. Odds are, she has a career.
``But she's at the soccer field on the weekends,'' DeRosa says.
</P>
<P>
   The median age of the company's customer is 36.
</P>
<P>
   They try to keep her coming back by changing the color theme in
stores every month. In keeping with the big-name designers, gray is
the hot color for fall and winter.
</P>
<P>
   Two items DeRosa says the company always has in stock: A little
black dress and a black suit.
</P>
<P>
   Someone is always shopping for those two.
</P>
<P>
   Company: Ann Taylor
</P>
<P>
   Design philosophy: ``Can a lot of different women be comfortable
in this product? Does it travel well? Can you wear it to dinner and
the office?''
</P>
<P>
   Price range: Cheapest offering, a $20 cotton T-shirt. Most
expensive, a $398 leather jacket.
</P>
<P>
   Sizes: 2 to 16, with a petites division.
</P>
<P>
   Cara Anna writes for the Palm Beach Post, West Palm Beach, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
