<SLUG> BC-CONVENTION-PROPOSAL15-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    7 bid for convention center hotel job
 &HT;    By R. Michelle Breyer
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Seven developers, including several Texas
companies, are vying for the job of building Austin's convention
center hotel.
</P>
<P>
   Bob Hodge, director of the Austin Convention Center Department,
said he was pleased with the list of companies, which includes H.L.
Hotels and The Brentwood Group of Austin; The Duddlesten Companies
of Houston; USAA Real Estate Co. of San Antonio; Portman Holdings
of Atlanta; White-Leasure Development Co. of Boise, Idaho, and HBE
Corp. of St. Louis.
</P>
<P>
   The city plans to narrow down the list before requesting more
detailed proposals, Hodge said.
</P>
<P>
   With the city planning to double the size of its convention
center, officials want to make sure there will be enough hotel
rooms to accommodate the added conventioneers.
</P>
<P>
   City officials contend they already are losing business because
there aren't blocks of rooms large enough to satisfy meeting
planners.
</P>
<P>
   In August, they began advertising for bids to build an 800-room
hotel and a 1,000-car parking garage near the convention center, at
Cesar Chavez and Red River streets. Sites being discussed for a
hotel include land to the east, west and south of the convention
center.
</P>
<P>
   When the list of developers has been narrowed, Hodge said the
city will be better able to determine the cost of the hotel project
and the need for any financial incentives.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have no idea what those might be,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Hodge said city officials hope the hotel will be open by the
time the convention center expansion is completed in 2001.
</P>
<P>
   R. Michelle Breyer writes for the Austin American-Statesman,
Austin, Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
