A6175 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SMALL-BIZ-COLUMN15-co     10-14 0753
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SMALL-BIZ-COLUMN15-cox </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Austin CDC intensifies efforts to assist fledgling businesses
 &HT;    By Kim Tyson
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ When ANS Computers Inc. received a $50,000 loan
from Austin Community Development Corp. in February, the shot of
money came at a crucial time and helped the company nab some
important contracts.
</P>
<P>
   The loan came as the South Austin company, which installs
computer networks, was trying to win a $2 million contract with
Unisys Corp. The Austin-based company needed to hire more
experienced professionals to improve its credentials before it bid
for the major contracts _ and the grant money was key.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were like the spark we needed,'' says Joe Salinas,
president and co-founder of the company. Last year, the company's
revenues were $750,000. This year, they're expected to hit $3.5
million _ a growth that Salinas says is attributable largely to the
shot-in-the arm from CDC.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was really because of Austin CDC we were able to make that
leap,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   It is companies like ANS that the non-profit Austin CDC is
designed to help.
</P>
<P>
   High-tech entrepreneurs often can get loans from venture capital
companies willing to risk seed money for a stake in a potentially
fast-growing start-up. More established small businesses often can
get traditional loans from banks or even family members.
</P>
<P>
   But minority-owned small businesses and those in traditionally
economically depressed areas often have a tougher time getting
loans _ even though those areas need more employers who can create
jobs.
</P>
<P>
   Margo Weisz, executive director of the CDC, says South and East
Austin _ two areas of the city that have a large number of minority
residents and have traditionally been economically disadvantaged _
have about 25 percent fewer businesses per capita than the city
overall.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, the CDC got an additional $500,000 from the federal
government as part of an increased emphasis on lending to minority-
and low-income businesses.
</P>
<P>
   Along with the $500,000 in federal funding, the CDC got an
additional $500,000 from NationsBank, Chase Manhattan Bank,
Comerica Bank, Bank One, Wells Fargo Bank and Norwest Bank. The
banks contribute to the CDC and other groups as a way to meet
federal Community Reinvestment Act requirements.
</P>
<P>
   Weisz says the additional funding will let the group double the
amount it can lend to small companies in those areas and others.
The revolving loan fund, she says, will initially help two dozen
small Austin companies and create 300 jobs in economically
distressed areas.
</P>
<P>
   ``The neat thing about this $1 million is none of it is going to
cover the overhead of the Austin CDC,'' says Pat O'Beirne,
president of Austin CDC and manager of the small business lending
area at Bank One Texas. ``One hundred percent of that will go back
into the community.''
</P>
<P>
   Started in 1994 as a partnership between the City of Austin and
10 Austin banks, the CDC is designed to help stimulate business
activity in economically depressed areas of Austin by making loans
to minority- and women-owned businesses.
</P>
<P>
   The group, which receives about $75,000 a year in city support,
focuses on loans to help residents in 59 low-income census tracts
in Austin. The center makes loans from $20,000 to $100,000; its
average loan amount is $38,000.
</P>
<P>
   In the case of ANS Computers, the Austin CDC's money was matched
by a $50,000 line of credit by Bank One.
</P>
<P>
   Brothers Joe and Bob Salinas started the company _ which
previously went by the name Advanced Networking Solutions _ after
serving in the military and attempting various business ventures
that had them selling everything from nutritional supplements to
motivational tapes.
</P>
<P>
   Next year, the brothers say they expect the company to more than
triple its revenues to $12 million. They also are trying to
purchase a 20,000-square-foot building to relocate early next year.
</P>
<P>
   The company is located on South Congress Avenue, where it
employs 143 people _ about 85 percent of whom are women or
minorities.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are very, very committed to hiring from the community,''
Weisz says. ``It's not just about them making money. It's about
them hiring and giving kids a chance.''
</P>
<P>
   Kim Tyson writes for the Austin American-Statesman, Austin,
Texas. E-mail: ktyson(AT)statesman.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By The AMERICAN-STATESMAN, AUSTIN, TX
</P>
<P>
   AP-NY-10-13-98 2147E
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
