<HEADLINE>
EDITORS:
</HEADLINE>
  
 Wednesday, Oct. 14, 1998      The Hearst News Service will file the following stories for
Thursday. If you have questions, call Tim Spence at 202-298-6920.  
    (Slugline includes the ``HNS'' tag.)
   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL NEWS (``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   HIV-INFECTION (San Francisco) _ While the rate of AIDS deaths
nationwide continues to fall, the rate of new HIV infections has
not. In San Francisco, an ad campaign is being launched to
encourage people who think they may have recently been exposed to
enroll in a ``morning-after''-type regimen that aims to rid the
body of the virus before it can take root. By ULYSSES TORASSA.
</P>
<P>
   SCHOOL-UNIFORMS (Eagle Pass, Texas) _ The fairness of the Eagle
Pass school uniform policy may be decided in federal court. Eagle
Pass School District officials are accused of allowing children of
politically connected parents _ and not others _ to opt out of the
uniform requirement. By JEANNE RUSSELL.
</P>
<P>
   CALIF-BOXER (San Francisco) _ For Sen. Barbara Boxer, the event
in Chinatown had all the markings of a successful campaign stop.
She won endorsements from community leaders and drew a crowd of
reporters. But the event underscored the prospect that she is in
serious danger of losing the Asian American vote, which could
decide the election. By ZACHARY COILE.
</P>
<P>
   GERRY-ADAMS (Albany, N.Y.) _ For an Irish leader who shoulders
such a heavy burden of his island's troubled past, Sinn Fein
President Gerry Adams traveled light to Albany. He arrived in
shirtsleeves, with just a slim garment bag and small satchel. Adams
will need a large empty suitcase to carry back all the U.S. dollars
he has raised. By PAUL GRONDAHL.
</P>
<P>
   NY-DONOHUE (Albany, N.Y.) _ Mary Donohue, the Republican
candidate for lieutenant governor, touts herself as a former
prosecutor who put criminals in jail, and as a former judge who
kept them there. But in the 17 months that Donohue served on the
state Supreme Court, she never sentenced anyone to jail and never
presided over a criminal case, according to state records. By JOHN
CAHER.
</P>
<P>
   LIFESTYLE/FEATURES (``l'' category)
</P>
<P>
   MILAN-FASHION (Milan, Italy) _ As skies remain gray and somber
in this Italian fashion capital, the mood on runways is
considerably lighter, continuing to be led by U.S. designers
working abroad. Victor Alfaro's collection summed up the apparent
direction of women's ready-to-wear designs for spring 1999. By
LINDA GILLAN GRIFFIN.
</P>
<P>
   DESIGNER-FASHION (Milan, Italy) _ In the bleakness that has come
to characterize much of fashion in the 1990s _ mussed hair, hideous
makeup, dull clothes and footwear only a storm trooper could love _
happy moments are few and far between. Leave it up to an optimistic
American to bring back some fun. By LINDA GILLAN GRIFFIN.
</P>
<P>
   SF-POET (San Francisco) _ When he first came to San Francisco,
Lawrence Ferlinghetti liked what he saw. He doesn't like what he's
seeing now. He was inaugurated as San Francisco's first Poet
Laureate. By EDVINS BEITIKS.
</P>
<P>
   CAKEWALK-FOOD (Undated) _ Styles in cakes may come and go, but
school carnival cake walks and bake sales will always be with us.
How the cake walk evolved into a musical-chairs activity at schools
and churches doesn't seem to be well documented, but it has been
popular, at least in the South, for several generations. By ANN
CRISWELL.
</P>
<P>
   ADVICE-GUYS (Dallas) _ There was a time when free advice was
considered to be worth about what it cost, but now a two amateur
gurus have discovered a vein of humanity hungry for priceless
counsel. Nearly every Sunday for the past three years, Roderick
MacElwain and Neal Caldwell have spread their blanket beside a bike
path in Dallas and hung out their shingle: ``Free Advice.'' By JIM
HENDERSON.
</P>
<P>
   DISAPPEARING-WILDERNESS (San Francisco) _ California has been
losing 97 acres of wilderness a day for the past 19 years, despite
federal policies enacted to preserve it, according to a new report.
By ERIC BRAZIL.
</P>
<P>
   BUSINESS/FINANCIAL NEWS (``f'' category)
</P>
<P>
   CD-BOOKS (Undated) _ With the advent of easier, sleeker
compact-disc players, the tape cassette player is quickly going the
way of the dinosaur. But what does this bode for books on tape, an
industry with more than $2 billion a year in sales? By MELISSA
FLETCHER STOELTJE.
</P>
<P>
   FOOD (``d'' category)
</P>
<P>
   BBQ-SEASONING (Albany, N.Y.) _ Barbecue aficionados will tell
you the secret is in the seasoning, not the sauce. Call it a
pre-dinner rubdown, or just a good rub. The end result is the same.
A mixture of herbs and spices rubbed into beef, pork, poultry and
seafood creates bursts of flavor in the finished product, whether
it's grilled, baked or stir-fried. By DOUG BLACKBURN.
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   LYNCH-COLUMN (Albany, N.Y.) _ There Gerry Adams was, sitting in
the seat just in front of me in a van roaring into downtown Albany
from the airport, and I was bugging him about guns and bombs. I
wanted to know what it would take for him to agree to a mechanism
and a timetable to dispose of the Irish Republican Army's weapons.
It was not a question he cared for. By DAN LYNCH.
</P>
<P>
   ROBISON-COLUMN (Austin, Texas) _ The Texas capital, which not
too many years ago was still an overgrown town, has finally entered
the fast lane, and its residents are paying a price. The overall
quality of life is still good, better than in many other places,
but one essential ingredient to everyday living _ transportation _
has become a nightmare. By CLAY ROBISON.
</P>
<P>
   SALTER-COLUMN (San Francisco) _ For three days they met in San
Francisco to help one another learn to better swim against a
powerful tide. Like the rest of the nation, more than 70 percent of
Californians support the death penalty. But the swimmers _ 150
religious leaders from around the state _ know the majority can be
wrong. They believe capital punishment threatens the very soul of
America. By STEPHANIE SALTER.
</P>
<P>
   CANCER-SURVIVOR (Santa Cruz, Calif.) _ It's been almost a year
since I was diagnosed with breast cancer. As I glanced at my
kitchen calendar the other morning, already filling up with plans
and commitments, the date jumped out at me. That square seemed
larger than any of the others on the page. The number seemed to
pulsate. By CLAUDIA STERNBACH.
</P>
