 &HT;    Q &AMP; A ON THE NEWS
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q: I understand that Canada has enacted a new law on firearms
possession by its citizens. Can you explain what is involved?
</P>
<P>
   A: There are numerous provisions in Canada's Bill C-68, The
Firearms Act, which requires all gun owners in Canada to get
licenses and register their guns in a national database. Highlights
of the bill:
</P>
<P>
   All gun owners will need a license to possess or acquire
firearms by 2001.
</P>
<P>
   Before a license is issued, safety checks will be done on
applicants. Spouses and common-law partners with whom a new
applicant has lived within the past two years will be notified of
the application. New firearms applicants must pass the Canadian
Firearms Safety Test; those registering firearms already in their
possession will not be required to take a course or pass a test,
nor will their former partners be notified.
</P>
<P>
   All firearms must be registered by 2003. New firearms will be
registered when they are made, or at the point of sale on the day
of sale. Previously registered restricted and prohibited firearms
will have to be reregistered.
</P>
<P>
   By 2001, imported firearms brought into Canada by visitors will
have to be registered at the point of entry into Canada;
previously, shotguns and rifles did not have to be registered at
the border.
</P>
<P>
   Q: With the Dow Jones at over 9000 for a while, I was wondering:
How far would the stock market have to fall to equal the crash of
1929? Would the effect today be the same, or more or less?
</P>
<P>
   A: From its high near 386 in September 1929 to its low near 40
in July 1932, the Dow Jones Industrial Average lost almost 90
percent of its value. A similar drop from the July 1998 high of
about 9300 would take the Dow under 1000.
</P>
<P>
   World economies today are more industrialized than in the 1930s
and financial markets are more closely linked, so a similar crash
in 1998 would have considerably more global impact, experts say.
But many economists believe that misguided monetary policies
contributed to the 1929 crash and ensuing depression, and that a
repeat is unlikely given current knowledge.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Q&AMP;A reported that Kenneth Starr was appointed independent
counsel by a three-judge panel, made up of David Sentelle, John
Butzner and Joseph Sneed. But another article said Judge Peter Fay
of the 11th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals in Atlanta was on the
panel, along with Sentelle and Butzner. Which is correct?
</P>
<P>
   A: Both, because the makeup of the panel has changed. Sneed was
on the panel that appointed Starr on Aug. 5, 1994. The judges serve
two-year terms, but can be reappointed, said Marilyn Sargent of the
U.S. Court of Appeals, D.C. Circuit. Sneed's two-year term expired
Oct. 26, 1994, and he was not reappointed. Fay began his term on
that same date.
</P>
<P>
   Q: A statement is being sent around to the effect that Bill
Clinton, speaking in 1974 about President Richard Nixon, said Nixon
should resign and not put the country through an impeachment
because he had lied to the American people. Can you confirm?
</P>
<P>
   A: Clinton's comments were reported in the Arkansas Democrat on
Aug. 6, 1974, and in the Arkansas Gazette two days later. The two
articles can be found in their entirety on the Internet at
www.ardemgaz.com, the Web site for the Arkansas Democrat-Gazette
(click on ``Clinton's 1974 remarks on Nixon and impeachment'').
</P>
<P>
   At the time, Clinton was campaigning for Congress, trying to
unseat Rep. John Paul Hammerschmidt, who initially opposed Nixon's
resignation. Hammerschmidt had said, after Nixon admitted he lied
about his role in the Watergate coverup, that he wasn't sure
Nixon's actions legally were impeachable.
</P>
<P>
   As quoted by the Little Rock newspapers, Clinton didn't use the
words ``lie,'' ``lied'' or ``lying.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's plain that the president should resign and spare
the country the agony of this impeachment and removal proceeding,''
Clinton was reported as saying. ``I think the country could be
spared a lot of agony and the government could worry about
inflation and a lot of other problems if he'd go on and resign.''
Clinton, a law professor at the University of Arkansas, added that
there was ``no question that an admission of making false
statements to government officials and interfering with the FBI and
the CIA is an impeachable offense.''
</P>
<P>
   The White House, by the way, now brushes off questions about
Clinton's 1974 remarks, saying Watergate was much more serious than
the Monica Lewinsky scandal.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I noticed that when Yasser Arafat spoke in front of the White
House recently, his bottom lip seemed to be quivering. Does he have
a nervous condition?
</P>
<P>
   A: Arafat's quivering lips first came to public attention last
year after the condition was noticed during an interview on Israeli
television. At the time, the Palestinian leader's aides said it was
due to fatigue. ``Sometimes he gets exhausted because he does not
rest,'' said his spokesman, Marwan Kanafani. That view was seconded
by Ghassan Khatib, a former peace negotiator for the Palestinians,
who said he had seen the quivering lip many times over the years.
``That's Arafat when he's angry and when he's tired,'' Khatib said.
Israeli television reports last year said Arafat was seriously ill,
and other reports from Egypt said he fainted during an Arab summit.
But in the months since then, he has seemed to be his usual self in
public appearances.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What is the educational background of Mike McCurry, who
stepped down as President Clinton's press secretary? And will he be
teaching at some college or university?
</P>
<P>
   A: McCurry received a BA from Princeton University in 1976 and a
MA from Georgetown University in 1985. While his work history in
Washington certainly gives him a wealth of expertise for lecturing
_ among other jobs, press secretary to Sens. Harrison Williams
(D-N.J.), Daniel Patrick Moynihan (D-N.Y.) and John Glenn (D-Ohio);
press secretary to Arizona Gov. Bruce Babbitt; and director of
communications for the Democratic National Committee _ McCurry, 43,
hasn't indicated any such desire. At his final White House press
briefing Oct. 1, McCurry said his plans, other than corporate
consulting, were these: ``Play a little golf. Make a little money.
Do a lot of Little League coaching and volunteering in my
schools.'' McCurry often complained that his White House duties
kept him away from his three young children more than he would
like.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Ross Perot has called for a national petition to ask for
President Clinton to resign, but how can people add their names to
it?
</P>
<P>
   A: On the Internet, you can find information at www.perot.org,
the Web site for Perot's Reform Party USA. Complete the survey,
download the petition, sign and mail to: Ross Perot, P.O. Box 9,
Dallas, TX 75221. Or, call 972-450-8800 and request that a petition
be mailed to you.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What is the history of Major League Baseball's Gold Glove
award? Who gives them, and who receives them?
</P>
<P>
   A: In a 1956 spring training survey, Elmer Blasco, the
advertising, public relations and sales manager for Rawlings
Sporting Goods, found that 83 percent of all active Major League
players used Rawlings gloves or mitts. Nothing that Hillerich &AMP;
Bradsby, the Major Leagues' leading baseball bat supplier, awarded
Silver Bats to the leagues' top hitters, Blasco thought that
Rawlings should sponsor a fielding award.
</P>
<P>
   After his idea was accepted by Rawlings' management, Blasco
contacted the Brown Shoe Co. of St. Louis and obtained from it a
hide of gold lame-tanned leather used to make women's formal
slippers. A glove was crafted from this hide, laced and stamped as
a regular fielders glove, and attached to a metal fixture on a
walnut base with an appropriate engraved plate. Thus was born the
Gold Glove Award recognizing ``the importance of superior
individual fielding performance to the advancement of baseball as
America's national game.''
</P>
<P>
   Rawlings' annual Gold Glove Awards began with the 1957 season as
a combined selection for both leagues. Beginning in 1958, separate
teams were picked for each league (nine players in each league, by
position). Teams are selected by managers and coaches _ who cannot
vote for members of their own teams.
</P>
<P>
   These are members of the Rawlings Gold Glove Award Hall of Fame:
third baseman Brooks Robinson, 16 awards (1960-75); pitcher Jim
Kaat, also 16 (1962-77); center fielder Willie Mays, 12 (1957-68);
right fielder Roberto Clemente, 12 (1961-72); and catcher Johnny
Bench, 10 (1968-77).
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
