&HT;    
 &HT;    EDS: COX NEWS SERVICE IS MOVING NEWS-QUESTIONS IN TWO PARTS.
THIS IS PART ONE.
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Q &AMP; A ON THE NEWS
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Have a question about the news? Colin Bessonette will try to get
an answer. Call 404-222-2002, or write him at The Atlanta
Journal-Constitution, P.O. Box 4689, Atlanta, Ga. 30302, or e-mail
him at q&AMP;a(at)ajc.com
</P>
<P>
   Q: I read that U.S. Rep. Bob Barr once was sued for child
support, but there was no further explanation. What were the
circumstances?
</P>
<P>
   A: It became an issue in 1994 when incumbent Rep. Buddy Darden
used a TV commercial stating that Barr's former wife, Gail, had to
sue Barr for child support and medical bills. Barr countered by
having his former wife publicly decry the ad. She also demanded an
apology from Darden.
</P>
<P>
   In October 1994, Gail Barr, wearing a ``Barr for Congress''
sticker on her lapel, said the bitterness between her and her
former husband was vastly exaggerated in Darden's commercial. But
she didn't deny that, several years earlier, she had sued for more
than $600 in medical bills for the couple's sons. A Cobb County
(Ga.) Superior Court judge in 1989 ordered Barr to pay $126 of that
amount. ``I'm very disappointed with him (Darden) drawing myself
and my sons into his campaign,'' Gail Barr said. ``His campaign is
with Bob Barr, not with myself and my sons . . . Bob's a wonderful
father. He loves his sons very much. You couldn't ask for a better
father.''
</P>
<P>
   Darden, who refused to apologize, was defeated by Barr in the
election.
</P>
<P>
   Q: When will this year's holiday stamps be available? What is
the design?
</P>
<P>
   A: Two holiday stamps, one traditional and the other
contemporary, will be issued Oct. 15 and will go on sale nationwide
the next day. The traditional stamp will commemorate the Florentine
Madonna and Child, portraying a 15th century sculpture now at the
National Gallery of Art in Washington. The other stamp will feature
four wreaths.
</P>
<P>
   Q: In the Oct. 11 Winston 500 at Talladega, Ala., Dale Earnhardt
and Mark Martin complained about ``restrictor plates.'' What is
that? What is it supposed to do?
</P>
<P>
   A: It's a simple metal plate with holes drilled in it. It
reduces the engine's horsepower by reducing the flow of gas and air
from the carburetor to the intake manifold by restricting the
diameter of the carburetor's barrels. The less gas-air mixture that
can get to the manifold, the less horsepower the engine can
produce. Many drivers object to restrictor plates because the
plates force them to run with their throttles wide open all the
time, taking away the option of having power in reserve. With no
extra power and throttle to use, drivers say they can't maneuver
out of dangerous situations.
</P>
<P>
   First used in the early 1960s by Bill France Sr. to slow cars,
restrictor plates returned in 1988, the season following Bobby
Allison's horrendous accident at Talladega in which his car landed
on top of the fence separating the track from the stands. Since
then, qualifying speeds at Talladega and Daytona speedways, where
the plates are required by NASCAR, have been reduced to the low 190
miles per hour, and have been kept there by using increasingly
smaller holes in the plates.
</P>
<P>
   Q: How can I get an Entertainment book with information on
half-price dining and reduced-rate hotel accommodations throughout
the United States?
</P>
<P>
   A: Call Entertainment Publications, 1-800-445-4137.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Please refresh my memory. What was former Nixon aide Charles
Colson convicted of, and sent to prison for, after Watergate?
</P>
<P>
   A: Colson and six other people were indicted March 1, 1974, by
the Watergate grand jury for conspiracy to ``commit offenses
against the United States,'' for obstruction of justice, for their
political activities from 1969 to 1972 (which included conspiring
to impede the investigation of the June 1972 break-in at the
Democratic national headquarters at the Washington Watergate
complex) and for lying to investigative officials and agencies
about those activities.
</P>
<P>
   On June 21, 1974, Colson, former White House special counsel,
was sentenced to serve one to three years in minimum-security
prison, and to pay a $5,000 fine, for his confessed effort to
obstruct justice in the trial of ``Pentagon Papers'' defendant
Daniel Ellsberg. Colson had entered a surprise guilty plea before
U.S. District Judge Gerhard Gesell several weeks earlier, admitting
that he had worked to defame and degrade the credibility and public
image of Ellsberg in the press and with the public. Colson had
previously pleaded not guilty to charges of conspiracy and
obstruction of justice in both the Watergate cover-up case and the
Ellsberg break-in case. In February 1975, after serving seven
months of his sentence, Colson was released from jail.
</P>
<P>
   Q: People for the American Way is starting an ad campaign to
urge Congress to move on to issues affecting Americans such as
education, health care and Social Security. I'd like to support the
organization with a contribution. Do you have the address?
</P>
<P>
   A: People for the American Way, 2000 M St. N.W., Suite 400,
Washington, DC 20036 (1-800-326-7329). Or you can sign up online at
www.pfaw.org, the organization's Web site.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Is there a directory available showing the e-mail and regular
mail addresses of all members of Congress?
</P>
<P>
   A: Project Vote Smart publishes a Voter's Self-Defense Manual
with information on thousands of political candidates and elected
officials. A spokeswoman said it may not have all ``snail mail''
addresses for every individual, but it has the Senate and House
addresses and they will suffice, along with the person's name. For
a free copy of the 1998 issue, call the organization's Voter's
Research Hotline, 1-888-868-3762.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Q&AMP;A recently reported that the car depicted on the back of a
$10 bill is generic. I remember taking a tour of the Treasury
Department years ago and was told by our guide that it's a 1925
Hupmobile. Can you clarify?
</P>
<P>
   A: The Treasury Department's Bureau of Engraving and Printing
addresses the subject on its Web site,
www.moneyfactory.com/facts.cfm (click on Symbolism and Trivia). It
says the cars are of no specific make or model, and are a creation
of the designer who prepared the original model that was used later
by engraver Louis S. Schofield when he made the original
hand-engraved die of this vignette.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Does the District of Columbia have any sodomy laws similar to
those in some states?
</P>
<P>
   A: Sodomy between consenting adults has been legal in the
District of Columbia since 1993, when Congress allowed the local
law barring it to lapse. A repeal law passed by the D.C. Council
and signed by Mayor Sharon Pratt Kelly in May 1993 had been subject
to a 60-day review period, during which Congress could have
overturned the measure. But the review period ended without a word
of debate in the House or Senate.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Business articles often mention a ``hedge fund.'' What is
that, and how does it work?
</P>
<P>
   A: A hedge fund allows a group of investors to pool their
capital and hire professional management in much the same way as a
mutual fund, said Myron Greene, publisher of the Mutual Fund Timing
Guide. Hedge funds are organized as limited partnerships and are
available only to ``accredited investors'' _ those whose net worth
is more than $1 million, or who have annual income of more than
$200,000.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike mutual funds, there is little government regulation of
hedge funds, the presumption being that wealthy investors are
sophisticated enough to take care of themselves, Greene said. Many
early hedge funds used an investment technique called ``hedging,''
which involves buying and selling related securities, and futures
contracts simultaneously. In theory, hedging allows an investor to
profit in both up and down markets while limiting risk. These days,
hedge funds pursue a variety of investment strategies, Greene said,
many of which don't involve hedging at all.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What's the difference, if there is one, between the Blue
Ridge Mountains and the Great Smoky Mountains? I live in the North
Georgia mountains and am embarrassed not to know.
</P>
<P>
   A: Don't be embarrassed. Both are ranges of the Appalachian
Mountains, a mountain system of eastern North America extending
about 1,600 miles from Newfoundland, New Brunswick and southern
Quebec to central Alabama. The range includes the Allegheny, Blue
Ridge, Great Smoky and Cumberland mountains. The Blue Ridge range
extends from southern Pennsylvania to northern Georgia. The Great
Smoky range extends along the North Carolina-Tennessee border.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I'm 56 and I wonder if there are more people living who are
younger than I, or more who are older. In other words, exactly what
is the median age in our country?
</P>
<P>
   A: According to U.S. Census Bureau estimates, the median age in
1998 is 35.2 (meaning half of Americans are older and half are
younger than 35.2.) Census figures are broken down into five-year
age groups. The Census Bureau estimates that the number of people
54 and younger is 213 million; the number 55 and older is 57
million. An estimated 12.5 million Americans are in your age group,
55-59. The bureau based these 1998 estimates on 1990 Census
figures; in 1990, the median age was 32.8.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Is Rep. Jim Bunning, who spoke so eloquently during the House
impeachment debate, the same Jim Bunning who once pitched for the
New York Yankees?
</P>
<P>
   A: Bunning (R-Ky.) was a professional baseball player between
1950 and 1971, but not for the Yankees. During his pro career, he
pitched for the Detroit Tigers, Philadelphia Phillies, Pittsburgh
Pirates and Los Angeles Dodgers. Highlights included throwing a
no-hitter for the Tigers in 1958 and a perfect game for the
Phillies in 1964. He retired from baseball with a 224-184 record.
</P>
<P>
   Bunning, 66, served on the Fort Thomas, Ky., City Council
(1977-79) and in the Kentucky state Senate (1979-83). He was an
unsuccessful candidate in the election for Kentucky governor in
1983. In 1986, he was elected to represent Kentucky's 4th
Congressional District.
</P>
<P>
   And in August 1996, Bunning was inducted into the National
Baseball Hall of Fame in Cooperstown, N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I was in Atlantic City recently and I did some jogging along
the boardwalk there. I didn't see any information about how long it
is. Do you know?
</P>
<P>
   A: The boardwalk stretches along the Atlantic Ocean for 4 1/2
miles in Atlantic City. It continues for 2 more miles in Ventnor
City, a community to the south.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Since Bill Clinton, as president of the United States, is
commander in chief of the armed forces, why can't he be tried by a
military court for his alleged extramarital activities?
</P>
<P>
   A: This issue was brought up last month at a Washington news
conference, and was answered by Defense Secretary William Cohen.
All those who are in the military serve under the Uniform Code of
Military Justice, which prohibits adultery, Cohen said. But even
though the president is commander in chief, he is a civilian, and
therefore doesn't have to follow military rules prohibiting
adultery.
</P>
<P>
   MORE
</P>
