<DOCNO> NYT19981014.0094 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-14 11:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6229 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-JOURNAL-CHINA-$ADV15-     10-14 0723
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JOURNAL-CHINA-$ADV15-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    JOURNAL: A CHINESE FRIEND WONDERS ABOUT CLINTON
 &HT;    With photo mugs of Kunstel and Albright in the International
folder on the Cox Server.
 &HT;    Moving in both the (i) International and (k) Commentary
categories.
 &HT;    For Use Thursday, Oct. 15 And Thereafter.
 &HT;    By MARCIA KUNSTEL and JOSEPH ALBRIGHT 
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BEIJING _ Of all the places and people perplexed by America's
preoccupation with the Clinton sex scandal, China and the Chinese
may be the most.
</P>
<P>
   It was the foremost topic on the mind of the first Chinese
friend we ran into recently upon our return from home leave in the
United States. Zipping through the requisite polite queries as to
vacation and travels, our young friend quickly pounced on the
issue.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's been a lot of news about Clinton here. Every day on
television we see reports that the American people are supporting
him,'' said our friend, confirming that the Chinese media's
softball coverage had continued in our absence. A woman in her
mid-20s, she works for the Chinese government and thus wishes not
to be identified.
</P>
<P>
   She ventured that Special Prosecutor Kenneth Starr -- though she
didn't know his name -- is ``too aggressive,'' then suggested the
Monica Lewinsky affair is ``too private'' anyway to be aired all
over newspapers and television. Her Chinese friends are shocked and
embarrassed, she said.
</P>
<P>
   Her questions all trailed to the basic imponderable of how this
can be happening, and how to square Clinton's position as leader of
a great world power with this humiliating public probing into his
most intimate life?
</P>
<P>
   It could not happen in China. And understanding the phenomenon
here requires jumping a cultural and political chasm.
</P>
<P>
   The Chinese official media has made only glancing reference to
the Washington charges of perjury and witness tampering, and these
legal issues were lost on our friend. Probably they were lost on
most Chinese who retain much goodwill for the charming American
president they got to know via their own television screens just
this summer -- Clinton savoring their cultural achievements,
debating their president, talking to their university students and
business leaders and new homeowners.
</P>
<P>
   Thus our awkward attempt to explain how the rule of law applies
to everyone in a democracy didn't gain much ground with our friend.
Nor our belabored argument that the American system of checks and
balances works even when it looks out of kilter.
</P>
<P>
   That, we suspect, is partly because China has neither the
equitable rule of law nor any check on the ruling Communist Party.
</P>
<P>
   And it is in part because critiques of Clinton, including a
Chinese-language book exploring his peccadilloes, have been
suppressed by a Chinese government that has become one of the
staunchest ``Friends of Bill'' since the presidential visit.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton has gotten almost the same shielding a Chinese leader
might enjoy.
</P>
<P>
   For a decade, for example, outsiders have known that the late
Chairman Mao Tse-tung fancied lovely young women, who sometimes
were brought to his bedchamber two or three at a time and were
known to distract him from matters of state.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes, I heard about this lately, but only orally. I never read
it,'' our friend said, referring carefully to the tell-all book
written by Mao's private physician. The book is banned in China.
</P>
<P>
   This aspect of the Great Helmsman's life has been described in
the most respected foreign history books for years, we noted, and
added that sex often has been an appendage to power throughout the
world.
</P>
<P>
   Our friend paused to think, then expressed her curiosity, ``And
have you read the same about Zhou Enlai?''
</P>
<P>
   We had not read any such commentary about China's long-time
number two Communist revolutionary leader, who since his death in
1976 has become increasingly respected as a force of stability and
sanity. But this educated young woman had to ask foreigners for the
truth about her leaders, knowing there are some things she will not
read or learn from the state-controlled media any time soon in
China. Not only things about sex.
</P>
<P>
   That is something to ponder for Americans who think they are
getting a surfeit of information.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
