<HEADLINE>
EXECUTION RULING ANOTHER BLOW TO THE 9TH CIRCUIT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By STEVE MILETICH  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   By quickly brushing aside a stay of execution in the case of
Washington state convicted murderer Jeremy Sagastegui, the U.S.
Supreme Court revived its longstanding battle with the 9th U.S.
Circuit Court of Appeals on the issue of capital punishment.
</P>
<P>
   Sagastegui, 27, was put to death by lethal injection at the
Washington State Penitentiary at Walla Walla at 12:43 a.m. Tuesday,
hours after the Supreme Court cleared the way for the execution of
the triple murderer.
</P>
<P>
   The Supreme Court lifted the stay a day after it was granted.
</P>
<P>
   In doing so, it sent yet another pointed message that it takes a
dim view of the nation's largest appeals court intervening at the
last minute in what the justices have previously described as the
``sovereign power'' of states to punish death-row inmates.
</P>
<P>
   With its emphatic 7-2 decision Monday night, the Supreme Court
added to the tensions that have existed with the lower court since
1992, when the justices, in an all-night frenzy of bicoastal
dueling, lifted four last-minute stays granted to Robert Harris,
the first person executed in California in 25 years.
</P>
<P>
   The two courts also have skirmished over a broader range of
legal issues in recent years, leading to an unusually high reversal
rate of 9th Circuit decisions.
</P>
<P>
   In general, the 28-member appeals court has been branded as too
liberal and California-dominated, although that tag doesn't always
neatly fit.
</P>
<P>
   During the 1996-97 term, the Supreme Court reversed 28 of 29
cases it accepted from the 9th Circuit, compared with a two-thirds
reversal rate for all cases. In the 1997-98 term, 14 of 17 cases
from the 9th Circuit were reversed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Many think the Supreme Court has been gunning for the 9th
Circuit in recent years,'' said Laurie Levenson, a law professor at
Loyola University in Los Angeles. ``The Supreme Court has stepped
in in an unusual number of cases with the 9th Circuit, including
death-penalty matters.''
</P>
<P>
   Some Republicans in Congress, including Sen. Slade Gorton,
R.-Wash, have repeatedly urged that the circuit be divided.
</P>
<P>
   But a commission appointed by Congress to study the issue fell
short of recommending that course, when it suggested last week that
the circuit, which now covers nine Western states and two Pacific
territories, be split into three geographical divisions, with a
central body to resolve conflicting decisions.
</P>
<P>
   The stay granted in Sagastegui's case marked the first time the
9th Circuit has granted a last-minute reprieve to a death-row
inmate in Washington since the state resumed executions in 1993
after a 30-year absence.
</P>
<P>
   In the two previous executions, Charles Campbell didn't seek a
last-minute stay before his 1994 execution, although the 9th
Circuit was criticized for the time it took examining his initial
appeals, and Westley Allan Dodd eschewed federal appeals before he
was hanged in 1993.
</P>
<P>
   The stay in Sagastegui's case was granted by Judges David
Thompson and Stephen Reinhardt in a 2-1 ruling.
</P>
<P>
   Reinhardt, an outspoken liberal and death-penalty foe appointed
by President Carter, attacked the high court four days after the
Harris execution, condemning the justices for their actions.
</P>
<P>
   ``The court has made it plain that constitutional principles are
no longer its primary concern,'' Reinhardt said in an address at
the Yale Law School. ``What matters to the overwhelming majority of
this court is not whether an individual was convicted in an
unconstitutional manner or will be executed in an unconstitutional
manner.''
</P>
<P>
   His role in Sagastegui's case almost certainly was noted by the
Supreme Court, which has reversed a large number cases of all types
in which Reinhardt has participated or written the opinion.
</P>
<P>
   ``Reinhardt is more liberal than anyone on the Supreme Court,''
said Erwin Chemerinsky, a law professor at the University of
Southern California. ``On the other hand, he is a careful and
meticulous judge.''
</P>
<P>
   But it was Thompson, an appointee of President Reagan, who wrote
the comprehensive, 34-page opinion that the Supreme Court, without
comment, overturned. A third 9th Circuit judge, Andrew Kleinfeld,
who was appointed by President Bush, dissented in the opinion.
</P>
<P>
   ``Thompson is sort of a conservative, moderate Republican,''
Chemerinsky said. ``So you can't just say this is the liberal Judge
Reinhardt.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I think there is a majority on the current (Supreme) court
that wants to see stays of execution only in extraordinary
instances,'' Chemerinsky added.
</P>
<P>
   The 9th Circuit, with headquarters in San Francisco, has
jurisdiction over cases from Montana, California, Arizona, Nevada,
Washington, Oregon, Idaho, Alaska, Hawaii, Guam and the Northern
Mariana Islands.
</P>
<P>
   The three-judge panels on the 9th Circuit are randomly chosen by
a computer program, which matches judges so they sit with each
other an equal number of times over a given period. Currently, the
pool consists of 22 judges because of six vacancies.
</P>
<P>
   Reinhardt and Thompson agreed to a last-minute stay in
Sagastegui's case after finding that his mother had raised
substantial questions about her son's mental competency to waive
appeals.
</P>
<P>
   State attorneys asked the Supreme Court to lift the stay,
arguing Sagastegui's mother had no standing to bring an appeal on
his behalf.
</P>
<P>
   The two Supreme Court justices who agreed that a stay was
appropriate were Stephen Breyer and John Paul Stevens.
</P>
<P>
   But their slim minority stance reflected the court's growing
hostility to death-penalty appeals.
</P>
<P>
   In April, the court issued what was widely viewed as a clear
message to the federal appellate courts when it overturned a 9th
Circuit decision and cleared the way for California to execute
Thomas Thompson.
</P>
<P>
   The court rebuked the 9th Circuit for intervening in the case
two days before Thompson was to die in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   The last-minute reprieve, after 13 years of unsuccessful
appeals, was a ``grave abuse of discretion,'' Justice Anthony
Kennedy said in a 5-4 ruling that he read from the bench.
</P>
<P>
   ``At some point, the state must be allowed to exercise its
sovereign power to punish offenders,'' Kennedy said.
</P>
<P>
   During oral arguments in the case, Justice Antonin Scalia called
the 9th Circuit's handling of the matter ``unseemly,'' suggesting
that the reprieve was a deliberate attempt to skirt limits placed
on death-penalty appeals by Congress and the high court.
</P>
<P>
   In the broader range of cases, the justices have overturned 9th
Circuit rulings that declared a constitutional right to
doctor-assisted suicide and that upheld local records checks under
the Brady gun law. In the 1996-97 term, the court reversed nine
cases, including two favoring abortion rights, without even holding
a hearing.
</P>
<P>
   But the 9th Circuit's liberal label couldn't be automatically
applied in those cases, because nearly half of the overturned
decisions were written by Republican appointees, who make up about
half the court's judges.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're on the cutting edge of a lot of cases,'' Chief Judge
Proctor Hug Jr. said at the time. ``If a ruling creates a lot of
heat, that's why we have life tenure.''
</P>
<P>
   Hug has said it would be unwise to break up the circuit, but
Kennedy, who once served on the 9th Circuit, has supported the
idea.
</P>
<P>
   ``To say a three-judge panel can represent one-fifth of the
people in the United States puts an undue burden'' on the circuit,
Kennedy said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
