</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WORKPLACE-COLUMN-RAMSEY-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MINIMUM-WAGE MEASURE IS ALSO ABOUT VALUES AND BELIEFS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By BRUCE RAMSEY  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Washington state Initiative 688 would raise the state minimum
wage to $5.70 next year, $6.50 in 2000, then index it. It's a hot
issue, and only partly of economics. It is mostly about values and
beliefs.
</P>
<P>
   So let's get the economics out of the way. The statistical
effects of a minimum wage are clear enough. A lot of people get a
small raise and a few people lose their jobs. At the relatively low
levels at which the minimum wage has typically been set, a 10
percent increase will cut teenage employment by about 1 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The Northwest Policy Center at the University of Washington did
the classic study. It looked at the state minimum wage hikes in
1989 and 1990. Back then, the economy was at a peak, wages were
rising and a recession was just around the corner. In other words,
it was much like today.
</P>
<P>
   Here's what resulted. The law raised the wages of 6 percent of
workers in Washington, about 110,000 people. A similar number
enjoyed raises to keep them above those being paid the minimum.
About 0.3 percent of the total work force, 5,400 people in 1989 and
6,300 in 1990, lost their jobs.
</P>
<P>
   Some prices went up. Some profits went down. By 1990, 25 percent
of employers had become fussier in screening job applicants.
</P>
<P>
   Poverty was little affected. Low-wage workers are in families at
all income levels. Said the report, ``the proportion of low-wage
households living in poverty continued to be substantially the
same.''
</P>
<P>
   This year Oregon has posted a minimum of $6, the highest in the
nation. No study has been done, but its state economist, Paul
Warner, says the increase has had ``some small negative effect on
employment, and a small positive effect on wages and income.''
</P>
<P>
   In the Seattle area, demand has been pushing wages above the
$5.15 federal minimum. Starting pay at company-owned McDonald's in
Washington ranges from $5.40 to $6.50. Wages are higher in Bellevue
than in Tacoma because ``the demand for labor is higher,'' says
human resources manager Will Lew.
</P>
<P>
   Dick's Drive-Ins just raised its starting pay from $6.75 to $7.
</P>
<P>
   The market, however, tends to raise wages only where economic
conditions demand it. Advocates of the minimum wage want it
universal. They typically argue, ``No one should get less than X.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We believe in fairness,'' says Liz Pierini, president of the
League of Women Voters. ``If you work full-time, you shouldn't live
in poverty.''
</P>
<P>
   This is an argument to base wages on need. It is not a principle
of the market, but of social work.
</P>
<P>
   Need depends on how many mouths one has to feed. Supporters of
I-688 focus on the group with the greatest needs. A $6.50 minimum
puts a single mother with two kids barely above the poverty line,
says John Burbank, executive director of Seattle's Economic
Opportunity Institute. (And what's needed to get mothers off
welfare, Pierini says, is a wage of $8.)
</P>
<P>
   Opponents of I-688 focus their argument on teenagers, the group
with the least needs. ``The minimum wage was never meant to be a
living wage,'' says Russ Goodman of the Washington Restaurant
Association. It's a training wage that allows employers to try out
someone new.
</P>
<P>
   Real life has examples of all of the above. I-688 applies to
teenagers (29 percent of those affected), single parents with kids
(8 percent), part-timers (54 percent), people in families living on
less than $10,000 per year (18 percent) and in families earning
$60,000-plus per year (17 percent). It applies to farm workers, new
immigrants and inmates out of prison. It applies indoors and out,
to an immense variety of work.
</P>
<P>
   Everyone will see this issue through his own values and
experience. My first newspaper job was for a wage of zero. I wrote
stories, but was just a kind of volunteer. My employer, a sickly
tabloid called the Daily Commercial News, evaded the minimum wage
law by never hiring me. If they had had to pay it, I would have
been out on the street.
</P>
<P>
   Did I undercut myself? Well, I'm the one to judge that. If I
agree to work for nothing, or ten cents per hour, I may be foolish.
I may undercut someone else's bargaining power. But it is my right,
if my labor belongs to me.
</P>
<P>
   A job is a transaction between me and an employer. The voters
are not a part of it. They don't know my needs, my employer's
needs, or the value of the work I am to do. They are not competent
to set my wages.
</P>
<P>
   And that's what the U.S. Supreme Court decided 75 years ago.
Alas, the court changed its mind during the New Deal, and ever
since, wages in burger joints, movie theaters and tabloid
newspapers have become matters of public policy. But the argument
goes on, and it is never solely about economics.
</P>
<P>
   Bruce Ramsey is a reporter and columnist for the P-I. His e-mail
address is bruceramsey(at)seattle-pi.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
