<SLUG> BC-BBQ-SEASONING-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SEASONING IS KEY TO GOOD BARBECUE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By DOUG BLACKBURN  
 c.1998 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ Barbecue aficionados will tell you the secret is
in the seasoning, not the sauce.
</P>
<P>
   Call it a pre-dinner rubdown, or just a good rub. The end result
is the same.
</P>
<P>
   A mixture of herbs and spices rubbed into beef, pork, poultry
and seafood creates bursts of flavor in the finished product,
whether it's grilled, baked or stir-fried.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think a good rub is very important. You want spices that
complement the meat,'' said Carolyn Wells, executive director of
the Kansas City Barbecue Society. ``This is something the experts
have been using for years that the rest of the world hasn't heard
of.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the new deal for backyard cookers,'' added Wells, whose
society serves as a national clearinghouse and sanctioner of
barbecue cook-offs.
</P>
<P>
   Prepared rubs are available in supermarkets and specialty food
shops. Paul Prudhomme's name appears on some Cajun and Creole
spices, for example.
</P>
<P>
   There is one prepared rub that does more than merely season,
though. It goes by the name Char Crust, and is the only rub I've
found that actually coats the meat, sealing in the juices while
adding a new layer to the meat.
</P>
<P>
   Char Crust comes in five flavors (original hickory grilled,
hickory and molasses, roasted garlic peppercorn, smoky spicy
southwest and roto roast). The roto roast would be better with less
paprika, and anyone concerned about sodium would be wise to proceed
with caution because all five flavors are plenty salty.
</P>
<P>
   The original and roto roast flavors were created in the 1950s
for a Chicago steakhouse, and today are used by a number of
restaurants. The roasted garlic peppercorn and smoke spicy
southwest debuted during the past year.
</P>
<P>
   Char Crust, like most store-bought rubs, is probably as easy to
make at home as it is to apply. But precious time is saved by
having the rub sitting in a box in your pantry, waiting to be
applied. A 3.5-ounce box of Char Crust (sells for $3.95 through
Char Crust, 800-311-9884, or through the nationally distributed
catalog Grill &AMP; Gourmet, 800-664-1994) will thoroughly coat a dozen
large split-backed chicken breasts.
</P>
<P>
   I was introduced to Char Crust this summer at the International
Fancy Food Show in New York. The Char Crust booth was a popular
spot, with patrons returning for more than one helping of sliced
pork loin grilled with the hickory and molasses seasoning coating
the meat.
</P>
<P>
   I have experimented with all five flavors in the past few
months, and have found that the best way to use Char Crust is
baking. (I still haven't tried stir-frying with it.)
</P>
<P>
   On a hot grill, the seasoning tends to blacken and become too
crusty. But in the oven, the Char Crust takes effect in a slower
fashion, forming a thin coat that seals in juices.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
