<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-DONOHUE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEMOCRATS SAY GOP CANDIDATE MISREPRESENTS COURT RECORD 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOHN CAHER  
 c.1998 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ Mary Donohue, the Republican candidate for
lieutenant governor, touts herself in advertisements as a former
prosecutor who put criminals in jail, and as a former judge who
kept them there.
</P>
<P>
   But in the 17 months that Donohue served as a New York Supreme
Court justice, she never once sentenced anyone to jail and never
once presided over a criminal case, according to state Office of
Court Administration records.
</P>
<P>
   Donohue did, however, reject a series of routine habeas corpus
motions, attempts by incarcerated criminals to get out of prison on
the grounds that their confinement is illegal. The motions are
rejected by judges with rubber-stamp regularity.
</P>
<P>
   ``There they go again,'' said Sandra Frankel, the Democratic
candidate for lieutenant governor. Donohue ``misrepresented
herself.'' Frankel said the Republicans have a history of
exaggerating their criminal justice accomplishments, and noted that
despite claims by Gov. George Pataki that crime is down because of
his leadership, crime is actually on the increase in many upstate
communities.
</P>
<P>
   Eileen Long, campaign spokeswoman for Donohue, said the
advertisements are accurate and appropriate.
</P>
<P>
   ``When Mary was a judge she had murderers and other violent
criminals come before her in habeas corpus appeals in an effort to
be released from prison, and denied their requests,'' Long said.
``So, she kept violent criminals in prison.''
</P>
<P>
   Donohue, of Brunswick, was elected to a 14-year term as a state
Supreme Court justice in 1996 but resigned last May to run for
lieutenant governor on the Republican ticket with Pataki. In an ad,
titled ``Mary,'' released last week, Donohue says: ``As district
attorney I prosecuted violent criminals. And as a judge, I kept
them in prison and off the streets. ... New York is a safer place
to be because George Pataki is our governor.''
</P>
<P>
   In her brief tenure as a judge, Donohue primarily handled civil
cases and was never assigned a criminal term, according to state
records. Frankel said the new television advertisement falsely
leaves the impression that Donohue sentenced criminals to jail.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is a matter of trust, and when campaign ads are misleading
or distorted ... it raises serious questions about ethics,''
Frankel said.
</P>
<P>
   As a prosecutor, Donohue did indeed personally prosecute several
violent felony cases and her office boasted a conviction rate of 98
percent.
</P>
<P>
   However, many of those convictions stemmed from plea bargains,
even though as a candidate for Rensselaer County district attorney
in 1992 Donohue promised ``no more plea bargains.'' After unseating
incumbent Democrat Louis Catone and taking office as that county's
top law enforcement officer, Donohue plea-bargained scores of
cases, including several involving the sexual abuse of a child.
Virtually every district attorney plea-bargains criminal cases.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-14-98 1326EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
