<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-14 13:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6451 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BREAST-IMPLANTS-2TAKE     10-14 1206
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BREAST-IMPLANTS-2TAKES-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WOMEN AGAIN ASKING FOR IMPLANTS; SALINE TOUTED AS SAFER THAN
SILICONE GEL 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Refiling for those needing)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By CLIFFORD PUGH  
 c.1998 Houston Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ A few years ago, Houston cosmetic surgeon Dr. Henry
Mentz rarely met a patient who wanted breast implants. Instead,
many women with silicone-gel implants were clamoring to have them
removed amid reports they might be unsafe.
</P>
<P>
   But now, his office is swamped with women who are lining up for
the surgery _ this time for saline implants.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know if we're obsessed, but American women like to
have bigger breasts,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   Plastic surgeons nationwide are reporting the same thing.
</P>
<P>
   Despite continued health concerns about the safety of implants
and an ongoing debate about what constitutes feminine beauty, a
growing number of women are again opting for cosmetic surgery to
enlarge their breasts.
</P>
<P>
   The American Society of Plastic and Reconstructive Surgeons
reports that the number of breast-implant procedures has soared
nationwide nearly 40 percent in the past two years to more than
122,000 annually.
</P>
<P>
   The figures rival peak levels of eight years ago, when breast
augmentation was the No. 1 form of cosmetic surgery in the nation.
</P>
<P>
   Many women say they are opting for the procedure because it
makes them feel better about themselves. They see implants as just
another way to enhance their appearance, like dying their hair or
wearing makeup.
</P>
<P>
   One Houston socialite who has appeared on the Houston
Chronicle's Best Dressed list says she had implants about a year
ago in order to fit better into the body-conscious styles that are
the rage in stores.
</P>
<P>
   ``I personally had no desire to be real large. I didn't want to
go out and be dancing at Rick's. I just wanted to fill out my
clothes a little more,'' she says. ``Now I have a lot more freedom
when I go shopping.''
</P>
<P>
   When Stacy Thompkins lost weight during the past year, her
breasts decreased in size, along with her self-confidence.
</P>
<P>
   So about six months ago, the 28-year-old interior designer had
breast-augmentation surgery that boosted her from a 34B to a 34D
cup.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's amazing what a difference it's made in my appearance,''
she says. ``People just treat you differently. I hate to say it,
but it's true. A lot more doors open for me.''
</P>
<P>
   Thompkins says she decided to undergo surgery after researching
the subject on the Internet and convincing herself that the surgery
was safe.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of my friends tried to talk me out of it, but once I had
it done, now they want to do it,'' she says. ``I guess it's sad in
a way, but that's the way our society is. I had the means to better
myself, so I did.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite such testimonials, some experts suspect the resurgence
in the procedure and other types of cosmetic surgery is based more
on the unrelenting pressures on women to conform to unrealistic
ideals than the drive for self-betterment.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's really a whole issue of how we deal with aging,'' says
Patricia Yongue, associate professor of women's studies at the
University of Houston. ``Are we going to be allowed to grow old
naturally or are we going to be put under the gun to look like
Cher?''
</P>
<P>
   Six years ago, the Food and Drug Administration banned
silicone-gel implants amid growing concerns that the gel might leak
and trigger such auto-immune diseases as lupus and scleroderma.
</P>
<P>
   The number of breast-implant procedures plummeted from an
estimated 120,000-150,000 in 1990 to nearly 33,000 in 1992, the
year the FDA ban took place. Many women with the silicone-gel
implants had them removed and some opted for saline implants, which
were touted as a safer, more natural alternative.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Franklin Rose, who built a large practice in the boom years
of the 1980s with a clientele that included models and topless
dancers, estimates he removed 1,000 pairs of silicone-gel implants
from frightened women after the FDA ban.
</P>
<P>
   Now, he is again performing several breast-augmentation
surgeries every week. He usually works with saline implants,
although he occasionally uses silicone-gel implants in an
FDA-approved experimental program.
</P>
<P>
   He says his typical client is a thirtysomething mother who wants
to have her breasts restored to pre-pregnancy perkiness.
</P>
<P>
   ``The desire for an attractive breast goes back to antiquity,''
Rose says. ``Certainly our culture places a great importance on
it.''
</P>
<P>
   But experts say that hasn't always been the case. During the
Middle Ages, the ideal breast was the size of a walnut, says
Lorraine Stock, an associate professor of English at the University
of Houston whose speciality is the study of medieval times.
</P>
<P>
   She points out that in the 1920s the ``flapper'' look was so
popular that busty women bound their breasts to fit into skimpy
chemise dresses.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is a specific mark of our particular time in history that
women have been convinced that large breasts are more feminine or
more womanly than small breasts,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   Mentz, whose practice is performing five times more augmentation
procedures than two years ago, believes the numbers have
skyrocketed, in part, due to pent-up demand.
</P>
<P>
   He says women desiring bigger breasts held off from having the
surgery until they could gather more information about the safety
and durability of saline implants.
</P>
<P>
   ``Patients are satisfied about the research that has been
done,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   Saline implants have not been linked to health problems,
although scar tissue can harden around the implants in some cases
and cause discomfort.
</P>
<P>
   In some thin patients, the implant shell may wrinkle noticeably
under the skin. Some patients complain of reduced sensation in the
breast area after the surgery. As with any surgery, there is also
the risk of infection and complications from anesthesia.
</P>
<P>
   Implants also can interfere with mammography and make it more
difficult to detect cancer in early stages, says Dr. Mark
Schusterman, a cosmetic surgeon who specialized in breast
reconstruction at University of Texas M.D. Anderson Cancer Center
in Houston before going into private practice last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``I try to tell (implant) patients that especially as they
approach 40, they need to have mammograms, and they need to be done
in a very specific manner,'' says Schusterman.``It's something
patients need to understand before they get involved with them.''
</P>
<P>
   But such drawbacks have not deterred women from flocking to the
procedure, which costs from $4,000 to $8,000 in Houston and is
usually not covered by health insurance.
</P>
<P>
   Some women who have received implants say they are surprised by
the increased attention they get.
</P>
<P>
   For several months before undergoing the surgery, a 39-year-old
Houston teacher wore falsies to determine if she could handle the
added scrutiny.
</P>
<P>
   ``In terms of attention and the `babe factor,' it's much more
than I had ever imagined,'' she says. ``There's definitely big
power in big breasts.''
</P>
<P>
   The surgery, in which saline implants were placed under the
pectoral muscle for a natural, realistic look, was so painful that
she could not open a refrigerator door for a month.
</P>
<P>
   (MORE ... MORE)
</P>
<P>
   Even so, she is pleased with the outcome, although she is
sometimes bothered by some reactions.
</P>
<P>
   ``I do find some men will speak to my breasts. They won't speak
to me, and that's pretty outrageous,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   One Houston woman who had her breast implants removed after
seven years says men noticed her when she had them, but for all the
wrong reasons.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now that I look back on it, I got a lot of attention from men
who ended up being not worth two seconds of my time,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   ``Do you really want a man who is going to give you attention
because your breast size is bigger?''
</P>
<P>
   She says she originally got implants because she was newly
divorced and felt terribly insecure. She later met a wonderful man
(now her husband) who asked her to consider removing the implants.
</P>
<P>
   ``What if you won't like me anymore?'' she asked.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I could fall in love with you with those fake breasts, I
can learn to love you with natural breasts,'' he replied.
</P>
<P>
   After having the implants taken out, her breasts returned to
their natural shape within three months. She's happy with her real
breasts and can't imagine why she felt compelled to enhance them in
the first place.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, they're a little droopy, but they're real, and they're
natural, and they're proportional to my body,'' she says. ``I feel
so much more feminine without (implants).''
</P>
<P>
   There are some subtle signs that Hollywood image makers, who
have been accused of manufacturing an ideal of sexiness that no
woman could maintain, are changing their attitude about implants.
</P>
<P>
   Jenny McCarthy, the big-busted actress who shot to stardom on
MTV, advises young girls not to get breast implants. Hers just
``gave me something to make fun of,'' she told Redbook magazine,
adding she was contemplating having her implants removed.
</P>
<P>
   Actress Sally Kirkland recently underwent surgery to remove
breast implants that had given her problems for years.
</P>
<P>
   ``Many women look to celebrities as role models for their
appearance,'' she said. ``I don't want to feel responsible in any
way that I might be the cause of another woman getting implants and
having to suffer the way I have for 10 years.''
</P>
<P>
   Such actresses as Meryl Streep, Michelle Pfeiffer, Kristin Scott
Thomas and Calista Flockhart of the TV hit ``Ally McBeal'' have
resisted the urge to ``go bigger'' and are models of class and
intelligence.
</P>
<P>
   Even with the new role models, some observers believe there is
still tremendous pressure in our society to conform to a standard
of beauty defined by TV shows such as ``Baywatch,'' movies and
magazine covers featuring braless babes, and the models in
Victoria's Secret catalogs.
</P>
<P>
   The pressures may be especially acute in Texas, where in many
cases, bigger is considered better.
</P>
<P>
   Nationally, Texas trailed behind California and Florida in the
number of breast-implant procedures performed last year, but women
in the Lone Star state requested bigger implants than those in any
other state.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's always been the case,'' says Dr. Jim Moore. ``I guess
it goes with big blonde hair and Texas.''
</P>
<P>
   Moore says that the average size of an implant requested in
Texas is more than double that in the Northeast.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's not my decision. I have women put on a leotard and put
breast implants in front and look in the mirror. They decide what
size they want to be. We honor that entirely,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   Others attribute the bigger size, in part, to the fact that
implants were originally invented in Houston and are considered
more acceptable.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think women like to be sexier here, and they see breasts as
part of their sexy look,'' says Dr. R. Scott Yarish, who does more
than twice as many breast-augmentation surgeries as a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most women tell me they just want to fill out their clothes or
they want to be back to where they were before they had babies, but
I think it also involves a little bit of showmanship. Women are
flashier here than anyplace I've ever been. That's part of the
flash.''
</P>
<P>
   It also may be a cultural thing. Dr. German Newall, whose
practice includes patients from South America, Central America and
Mexico, says those patients are usually more concerned than U.S.
</P>
<P>
   women about appearing too big.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's blueprinted in the Latin American mind that big breasts
are not cosmetically appealing. It's the medium size they're aiming
for,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   Recently, Newall performed breast reduction surgery on some
teen-age girls from Merida, Mexico, who were embarrassed about what
they considered to be large breasts.
</P>
<P>
   ``To us it would have been very attractive large breasts. For
them it was just monstrous,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   When considering implant surgery, women should make sure the
surgeon is certified by the American Board of Plastic Surgery and
have all the facts before making a decision, says Schusterman.
</P>
<P>
   When patients ask him if implants are safe, he replies,
``They're as safe as any other piece of plastic you want to implant
in your body.''
</P>
<P>
   He says that in 10 percent to 20 percent of cases, scar tissue
hardens around the implants to the point that additional surgery is
necessary to remove the tissue. In some cases, the area around the
implants may become infected and have to be taken out.
</P>
<P>
   The implants also need to be monitored by a doctor for as long
as the woman has them in her body, he says.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think it is a bad option as long as women understand
what they're getting into,'' says Schusterman.
</P>
<P>
   He adds that 95 percent of women who have breast-implant surgery
nowadays are happy with it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously a majority of women feel like it's a worthwhile
thing,'' he says. ``I wouldn't recommend my daughter having it
done. But if she wanted it, I'd guess I'd say, `Fine, if that's
what you want.'''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
