<HEADLINE>
CALIFORNIA LOSING WILDERNESS AREAS DESPITE FEDERAL RULES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ERIC BRAZIL  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ California has been losing 97 acres of
wilderness a day for the past 19 years, despite federal policies
enacted to preserve it, according to a new report.
</P>
<P>
   ``Two Decades of Destruction,'' released Tuesday by the
California Wilderness Coalition, is the first detailed study of the
state's 6.3 million acres of land not accessible by roadways since
a 1979 inventory conducted by the U.S. Forest Service.
</P>
<P>
   The Davis-based group, which represents some 80 environmental
organizations, found in its report that logging, road construction
and off-road vehicle use have contributed to the decline of
California's wilderness.
</P>
<P>
   Furthermore, the report concludes that the Forest Service's
response to President Clinton's 1997 directive to develop a policy
to manage remote national forest areas is inadequate as well as
unimplemented.
</P>
<P>
   The Forest Service's second Roadless Area Review and Evaluation
(RARE II) identified 372 areas in California totaling 6.3 million
acres. Of that total, 1,826,212 have been officially designated
wilderness, while 3,867,802 acres remain roadless but unprotected.
</P>
<P>
   The Wilderness Coalition's report focuses on 675,449 acres that
have been permanently lost and concludes that ``we cannot afford to
lose another acre.''
</P>
<P>
   Northwestern California was the biggest loser of potential
wilderness, 248,921 acres, according to the study.
</P>
<P>
   Modoc National Forest in the northeastern part of the state lost
53 percent of its roadless land _ a far greater percentage than any
other national forest.
</P>
<P>
   The Wilderness Coalition contends that the Forest Service's
proposed roadless-area management policy is inadequate because it:
</P>
<P>
   _ Exempts 1.25 million acres of potential wilderness in
California from a ban on road construction.
</P>
<P>
   _ Provides no protection for roadless areas not included in
uninventoried potential wilderness.
</P>
<P>
   _ Does not apply to logging, off-road vehicle use or other forms
of development.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. Forest Service spokesman Alan Polk said his agency had
received 65,000 public comments on the proposed policy and that
``we're finalizing the evaluation. We anticipate that there will be
an interim rule by the middle of next month.''
</P>
<P>
   Once the interim rule is on the books, ``we will be developing a
Forest Service transportation policy which will take us well into
the 21st century,'' Polk said.
</P>
</TEXT>
