u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MCNAMARA-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      10-14 0788
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MCNAMARA-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NURSING HOME EMPLOYEES GET A DAY OF RECOGNITION, HELP FOR SCHOOL
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 bY EILEEN McNAMARA 
c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   They do not warrant our attention until one of their number is
arrested for theft or abuse.
</P>
<P>
   They do not merit our interest until one of our own is in need
of their care.
</P>
<P>
   But tonight, at the Park Plaza Hotel in Boston, hundreds of
celebrants will gather to honor the men and women who change the
sheets, serve the meals, and monitor the health of the 50,000
patients living in nursing homes in Massachusetts.
</P>
<P>
   The occasion is the 10th annual dinner gala sponsored by the
Massachusetts Long Term Care Foundation to fund scholarships for
employees trying to make the leap from nurse's aide to practical
nurse, from practical nurse to nurse practitioner.
</P>
<P>
   These are not the kind of feats that attract the notice of the
Nobel Prize committee; they are the kind that remind us that hard
work and education are still the fuel that propels individual lives
forward in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Lives like those of John Kungu, Jian Hua Liu, and Erin O'Connor,
three of this year's 88 scholarship recipients whose efforts to
balance work, school, and family have required no less a commitment
than that shown by the Nobel winners announced in Stockholm this
week.
</P>
<P>
   John Kungu lives in Chelsea. For the last three years, he has
worked as a licensed practical nurse at Bear Hill Nursing Center in
Stoneham. It was not his career choice when he emigrated from Kenya
eight years ago. Taken aback by the pace and complexity of American
life, he says it ``took a while to adjust to a culture and
traditions totally different'' from his own.
</P>
<P>
   A summer job at a nursing home convinced Kungu he had made a
false start by enrolling in a computer science program. ``I
realized how much I had to offer to fellow human beings in need,''
he says. ``Working with the elderly in the nursing home had found a
place in my heart. There was no turning back.''
</P>
<P>
   In the next few years, while working nights and weekends as a
nurse's aide in Stoneham, Kungu earned his certificate from Quincy
College as an LPN. Two years ago, he enrolled in the College of
Nursing at the University of Massachusetts in Boston. He will earn
his nursing degree as the century turns. ``This is something my
body agrees with,'' he says. ``This is something my hands love to
do.''
</P>
<P>
   There were no false starts for Jian Hua Liu, only delays imposed
by what sometimes seemed an insurmountable language barrier.
</P>
<P>
   She had worked as a registered nurse in her native Beijing for
more than seven years before leaving China for the United States in
1989. Her training at Beijing Nursing School and her experience at
Beijing Geriatric &AMP; Research Center gave her the clinical skills to
nurse the frail and the aged, but her trouble speaking English
threatened to keep her at a nurse's aide position.
</P>
<P>
   As millions of immigrants have done before her, Jian Hua Liu
charted her future from a table in a public library. ``I had no
friends, no relatives, and no money,'' she recalls. ``I studied at
the Brookline Public Library every day after work. When I could
afford, I bought nursing books and studied them. I reaped the
benefits of my hard work when I became an RN in the United
States.''
</P>
<P>
   With scholarship assistance _ the Massachusetts Long Term Care
Foundation has awarded more than half a million dollars to more
than 300 nursing home employees in the last decade _ Jian Hua Liu
is less than a year away from earning an undergraduate degree in
nursing from UMass-Boston.
</P>
<P>
   ``My long-term goal is to pursue a master's degree to become a
nurse practitioner in geriatrics,'' she says. ``I feel like I have
the knowledge. I have the heart. I want to help people.''
</P>
<P>
   So does Erin O'Connor. She has wanted to be a nurse as long as
she can remember. ``I was basically raised at Keith Hill Nursing
Home in Grafton, where my mother was employed as a registered nurse
for over 20 years until it closed in 1995,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can remember going to work with my mother to visit the
residents. I can remember brushing the ladies' hair, making them
look beautiful, and I can remember sitting with them for hours on
end listening to their stories.''
</P>
<P>
   O'Connor began working in the kitchen at the nursing home when
she was 16. Now 22, she is a nurse's aide at Beaumont Nursing Home
in Northbridge. Someday, she says, she hopes to be a registered
nurse like her mother but ``for right now, I just want to be an
LPN.''
</P>
<P>
   Tonight, when the crowd in the Imperial Ballroom salutes her
dream, O'Connor might just decide that someday is sooner than she
thinks.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-14-98 1359EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
