<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-14 14:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6528 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NYHAN-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      10-14 0960
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NYHAN-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LOOK FOR MOON OF MENINO TO GO TO BAT FOR PLANET HARSGBARGER
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID NYHAN 
c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Ann Kramer, who spent a lot of years hauling water for the
Republican Party as a state committee member before the past eight
years of GOP governors, knows how the election tides run along the
shoreline of Massachusetts politics.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the `prenatal' Democrats I worry about,'' she has said in
this space once already this fall. A look at the registration
figures, please: unenrolled (that's independents) 49 percent;
Democrat, 38; GOP 13. Barely one in eight voters registers
Republican. Half are independents, but Democrats still outnumber
registered Republicans by 3 to 1.
</P>
<P>
   The defection of the usual suspects among
Democrats-who-can-be-had to Acting Governor Paul Cellucci is not
surprising. Any governor has a grab bag full of goodies with which
to woo wooable Democrats, and a number of those succumbing to the
Guv's blandishments are lined up at the trough. Election Day means
Halloween to Democrats who agree to defect when the governor is
handing out the candy.
</P>
<P>
   Eight years ago, in the throes of recession, the number of
independents first surpassed the Democrats. And it is crucial to
Cellucci's survival that he run strong in that segment of suburban,
mostly college-educated swing voters who preferred Bill Weld to
John Silber or Mark Roosevelt, the last two Democrats who failed to
clinch the sale with the unenrolled.
</P>
<P>
   For Scott Harshbarger to nose past the incumbent in what most
insiders expect will be an election settled by a single-digit
margin, the challenger must gain ground among independents. He has
19 days to do it. He's getting help from the biggest names in the
Democratic Party. Two Kennedys are on board, all the congressional
delegation, the leaders of both House and Senate (though we'll put
an asterisk next to Speaker Tom Finneran's endorsement) and,
expected this week, Mayor Tom Menino.
</P>
<P>
   Arguably the most popular mayor this century _ we didn't have
polls for pols in the first half, but approval ratings in the 80
percent range are astronomical _ Menino has so far kept Harshbarger
at arm's length, cool to the point of chilly. But the gravitational
pull of politics is expected to put the Moon of Menino closer to
Planet Harshbarger before this week is out. A lot of the party
regulars were initially cool to the independent-minded attorney
general, whose 16 years as a prosecutor (eight as Middlesex DA,
eight as AG) saw his office prosecute a lot of politicians or their
pals.
</P>
<P>
   For that he caught considerable grief. But for lack of skillful
self-promotion, Harshbarger has so far been denied the concomitant
lift among independents, who in theory would go for a guy who has
not shied away from taking on his party's insiders when they skated
close to the line.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no way that Cellucci should be leading Harshbarger
among independents,'' said a prominent Bay State Democrat after a
recent Globe poll gave Cellucci the nod with the unenrolled.
</P>
<P>
   Harshbarger needs a stronger debate showing than he managed in
his first encounter with Cellucci. The challenger has already
sharpened his criticism of Cellucci's personal debt, last estimated
at around $740,000, which is a whopping figure for a governor whose
salary is $90,000 a year.
</P>
<P>
   The front-runner's TV ads slam Harshbarger for being fiscally
irresponsible. On that score Cellucci is living in a house with
acres of windowpanes. It would make sense for the Democrats to
respond energetically to Cellucci's ``Harshbarger can't be
trusted'' ads with skeptical queries about how a guy who's been
governor or lieutenant governor for eight years has rung up
$740,000 in personal debts. Joe Malone kept asking.
</P>
<P>
   The Menino endorsement will be the final piece in the
endorsement mosiac for Harshbarger. How fervent will it be? A
Menino intimate phrased it this way: Menino went all-out for Ted
Kennedy and stiffed Roosevelt's losing 1994 bid for governor.
Menino went ``in-between'' for John Kerry, and that's about what
Harshbarger will get from Hizzonor: No prominent City Hall types
will waltz publicly with Cellucci; any Menino acolyte who wants to
work for Harshbarger will be allowed.
</P>
<P>
   Even a halfhearted Menino endorsement will help. Right now, for
instance, there's a 20-phone union phone bank office in Brighton
that is not staffed full-time. When Menino formally embraces
Harshbarger, those phones should crank up.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Finneran endorsement wouldn't mean much in terms of
bodies,'' said one shrewd elected official. ``But Menino brings
people to the table. Look what the Mayor did for Tom Reilly,'' who
defeated Lois Pines by 6 percent in a primary race for attorney
general where Menino's influence loomed large.
</P>
<P>
   In his methodical, sometimes mechanical manner, Harshbarger has
reassembled a Democratic campaign with all the major pieces,
centered around labor unions. Even Finneran, the conservative
Democrat who would not be speaker except for Republican votes in
the House, decided to sign on.
</P>
<P>
   Finneran is billed as the ``Annual Victory Banquet'' speaker of
the Christian Coalition of Massachusetts at Worcester the night
after the election, before an audience that takes a dim view of
Democratic politicians. That should be a pro-Cellucci crowd. But
given the pulling power of the not-always-in-harness Democratic
coalition, a Harshbarger victory could cast a pall over the
speeches. Those who swung in line behind Harshbarger will get a
shot at those jobs and contracts Cellucci's been spraying about. A
lot of ``prenatal'' Democrats want to be postelection job
recipients.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
David Nyhan is a Globe columnist.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-14-98 1404EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981014.0132 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-14 14:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6529 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RELIGION-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      10-14 0904
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RELIGION-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DUEL OF FAITH AND REASON RAGES STILL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DIEGO RIBADENEIRA  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Few people have so greatly influenced the moral arena of the
20th century, particularly in the &UR;  &LR; battle between faith and reason,
than Sigmund Freud and C.S. Lewis. With their luminous literary
gifts, Freud articulated a materialist, secular world view, while
Lewis countered with a spiritual framework.
</P>
<P>
   The debate between these two competing ideologies still rages.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, Pope John Paul II, concerned with what he views as the
exaltation of human reason without moral underpinnings, is soon
expected to release a major encyclical on faith and reason. Freud
and Lewis helped shape the divergent philosophical worlds the pope
is trying to reconcile.
</P>
<P>
   The two men are receiving heightened attention this year because
it is the 100th anniversary of Freud's founding of psychoanalysis
and the 100th anniversary of Lewis's birth.
</P>
<P>
   ``Freud's philosophical writings ... have played a significant
role in the secularization of our culture,'' Armand M. Nicholi,
associate clinical professor of psychiatry at Harvard Medical
School, said last week during a series of three lectures on Freud
and Lewis at Harvard's Memorial Church.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the 17th Century, people turned to the discoveries of
astronomy to demonstrate what they considered the irreconcilable
conflict between science and faith; in the 18th century, (they
turned) to Newtonian physics; in the 19th century, to Darwin; and
in the 20th century, to Freud,'' said Nicholi, who teaches a
popular course on Lewis and Freud at Harvard College.
</P>
<P>
   Lewis, on the other hand, who fascinates scholars because he
began his academic life as an avowed atheist, is ``perhaps the
century's most popular proponent of faith based on reason,''
Nicholi said. ``If Freud serves as a primary spokesman for the
materialist world view in this century, Lewis serves as a primary
spokesman for the specific world view Freud attacks.''
</P>
<P>
   In Freud's philosphical works, which Nicholi says are more
widely read than his research into human sexuality, the Austrian
intellectual divided the world into believers and nonbelievers.
</P>
<P>
   Freud clearly sided with the nonbelievers, claiming his view of
the world to be scientific because it rested on the premise that
knowledge could only come from the scientific method.
</P>
<P>
   Once he carved out this intellectual space, Nicholi said, Freud
appeared to have had an intense emotional need to attack the
religious world view, and did so in unequivocally strong terms.
</P>
<P>
   ``He says no intelligent person can accept the `absurdities' or
`fairy tales' of the religious world view,'' Nicholi said. ``He
writes that the doctrine that the `universe was created by a being
resembling a man, but magnified in every respect ... as an
idealized superman, reflects the gross ignorance of primitive
peoples.'''
</P>
<P>
   As for the world's great religions, Nicholi noted that Freud
said they ``must be classed among the mass delusions.'' Freud
referred to the teachings of Jesus as ``useless.''
</P>
<P>
   He argued that the belief in God was simply a manifestation of
human beings' deep-seated wishes, born out of a sense of
helplessness, for a protector or a parent-like figure. ``Acording
to Freud, God does not create us in his image; we create God in our
image,'' Nicholi said.
</P>
<P>
   Lewis, a giant among scholars at Oxford University whose books
still sell widely around the world, was well-versed in Freud's
arguments and stood ready to rebut every one.
</P>
<P>
   He counters ``Freud's wish-fulfillment argument with the
assertion that the Biblical world view involves a great deal of
despair and pain and is certainly not anything one would wish
for,'' Nicholi said.
</P>
<P>
   Lewis strongly rejected Freud's promotion of the scientific
method. ``The scientific method simply cannot answer all questions,
cannot possibly be the source of all knowledge,'' Nicholi said,
quoting Lewis.
</P>
<P>
   Lewis came to Christianity slowly and uneasily. From early on,
Lewis said, he often experienced an intense longing, though he was
unsure for what. Later, at Oxford, Lewis realized that many of his
close friends and the great writers he admired had embraced some
type of spiritual view.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lewis writes that he began to feel his `Adversary' _ the one
he wanted desperately not to exist _ closing in on him,'' Nicholi
said. Finally, Lewis makes a dramatic decision to ``open his mind,
to examine the evidence.''
</P>
<P>
   Eventually, in a profound moment, Lewis came to God. Quoting
Lewis, Nicholi says: ```I gave in and admitted that God was God and
knelt and prayed: perhaps, that night the most dejected and
reluctant convert in all England.'''
</P>
<P>
   In the end, Nicholi concluded in his final lecture Wednesday
night, it is possible that Freud and Lewis ``represent conflicting
parts of ourselves: A part ... that yearns for a relationship with
a source of love, joy, hope, and happiness, and another part that
raises its fist in defiance and rebelliousness and says with Freud,
`I will not surrender.'''
</P>
<P>
   Whichever part we choose, Nicholi said, not only determines the
``purpose and quality of our lives, but also our identity and our
destiny.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
