<SLUG> BC-SF-POET-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POET LAUREATE SPEAKS IN FRANK PROSE ABOUT SAN FRANCISCO 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By EDVINS BEITIKS  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ When he first came to San Francisco, Lawrence
Ferlinghetti liked what he saw. He doesn't like what he sees now.
</P>
<P>
   At his inauguration as San Francisco's first Poet Laureate
Tuesday night, Ferlinghetti told a standing-room-only crowd in the
Main Library that San Francisco looked Mediterranean when he saw it
in the afternoon light _ ``A small, white city. I thought it was
Atlantis, rising from the sea, as beautiful as any place in all
Europa.''
</P>
<P>
   In those days, in the 1950s, Ferlinghetti saw San Francisco as
``this far-out city on the left side of the world, a frontier for
the free poetic life.'' As co-founder of City Lights bookstore,
Ferlinghetti rolled up his sleeves to publish the works of beat
poets, including Allen Ginsberg, whose ``Howl'' was deemed obscene
by the San Francisco police in 1957, leading to arrests and
headlines in local papers like, ``Cops Don't Allow No Renaissance
Here.''
</P>
<P>
   Ferlinghetti, along with Ginsberg and Jack Kerouac and a host of
others, added to San Francisco's signature reputation as a haven
for the odd and loving, the ragged and laughing, teeming reapers of
the spoken word, the hoyden and the hungry and the working man. But
that was then, Ferlinghetti said. Things have changed.
</P>
<P>
   ``All that made this city so unique in the first place seems to
be going down the tube at an alarming rate,'' he told the audience.
He quoted from newspaper reports describing San Francisco as ``just
another American city, a corporate city.''
</P>
<P>
   The evidence is everywhere, Ferlinghetti said.
</P>
<P>
   ``This past weekend North Beach looked like a theme park,
overrun by tourists. Kitsch was king. ... What's happening to North
Beach?''
</P>
<P>
   The car, for one thing, Ferlinghetti said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're being destroyed by the car culture,'' he said as he
urged the city to kill the Central Freeway project and ``give
bicycles and pedestrians absolute priority over automobiles.''
</P>
<P>
   As soon as possible, he said, North Beach should be made into a
historic district, like the French Quarter in New Orleans, to keep
out chain stores, ``which are killing off the local color, the
local tradition.''
</P>
<P>
   He also suggested a ``poets' cottage'' on Treasure Island or in
the Presidio as a site for readings and annual poetry festivals.
</P>
<P>
   Ferlinghetti, 79, read a selection of his San Francisco works,
including ``A North Beach Scene,'' ``In Golden Gate Park that
Day,'' ``The Artist,'' ``I Saw One of Them'' and ``Baseball
Canto.''
</P>
<P>
   The readings were greeted with warm applause and more than one
``Bravo,'' with a standing ovation awaiting the end.
</P>
<P>
   Ferlinghetti offered half a dozen suggestions to give San
Francisco new life, including closing downtown to cars, uncovering
the city's rivers and creeks to let them run free, ``painting the
Golden Gate Bridge golden,'' and ``tilting Coit Tower. Just half an
inch, that's all I'm asking. Look what it did for Pisa.''
</P>
<P>
   But, in truth, it may be too late to bring back the city he
knew, Ferlinghetti said. ``It sure seems like it is,'' he said as
he signed autographs following his presentation.
</P>
<P>
   What he's seeing, Ferlinghetti said, is ``a total gentrification
of this city'' with high rents.
</P>
<P>
   That's a far cry from the affordable city he came to in the
50's, he said, ``a city that always seemed to me more like an
island, separate from all the other cities in America, mentally and
physically.''
</P>
<P>
   Ferlinghetti first came to San Francisco, via New York and Paris
and points West, because he'd heard it was wine-raising country.
</P>
<P>
   ``For someone who consumed red wine in the quantities as I did
back then, it was reason enough to see what was here,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   HE said he came to love the place and loves it still, even as it
festers and bloats.
</P>
<P>
   ``How could I refuse being Poet Laureate?'' he asked. ``San
Francisco has never conducted illegal wars against other peoples,
never dropped bombs on other countries, never subjected others to
the horrors they've had to live with in Nicaragua ... ''
</P>
<P>
   At the beginning of the evening, Mayor Willie Brown offered a
proclamation in honor of the poet, saying the choice for Poet
Laureate was ``a no-brainer.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
