<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ROBISON-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TIME FOR POLITICS TO TACKLE TRAFFIC SAFETY 
 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By CLAY ROBISON 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN _ This city, which not too many years ago was still an
overgrown town, has finally entered the fast lane, and its
residents are paying a price.
</P>
<P>
   The overall quality of life is still good, better than in many
other places, but one essential ingredient to everyday living _
transportation _ has become a nightmare.
</P>
<P>
   People in Austin, of course, don't expect much sympathy from
people in Houston or Dallas, who have been living through traffic
nightmares most of their lives.
</P>
<P>
   But Austin has outdone Houston, Dallas and every other major
city in Texas in one particularly unsettling, deadly statistic.
Austinites are killing themselves and each other on the city's
streets and freeways at a higher rate per capita than people in any
of the state's other metropolitan areas.
</P>
<P>
   Travis County, where Austin is located, led Texas' six largest
counties in traffic fatality rate for the second year in a row in
1997, according to a recent story in the Austin American-Statesman.
</P>
<P>
   Citing findings by the Trans Texas Alliance, a coalition of
transportation groups, the newspaper reported that Travis County
had 1.53 traffic deaths for every 10,000 people. Dallas County was
second with 1.29 fatalities per 10,000.
</P>
<P>
   While traffic fatalities were dropping 6.2 percent statewide in
1997, they were increasing 11 percent in Travis County.
</P>
<P>
   Part of the problem obviously is Austin's recent rapid growth,
fueled in large part by the high-tech boom and articles published
in national magazines a few years ago about the high quality of
life here.
</P>
<P>
   Subdivisions started mushrooming, especially in the hills west
of the city. And streets and freeways suddenly (or so it seemed)
became overloaded.
</P>
<P>
   According to the American-Statesman, about one-fourth of the
traffic deaths in the Austin area occur on Interstate 35. The
portion that goes through Travis County is one of the most heavily
used _ and deadliest _ stretches of freeway in the country.
</P>
<P>
   A shortage of police officers patrolling the streets and writing
tickets also may have contributed to the carnage. The Austin police
force fell more than 100 officers short of its authorized strength
last year, the Austin newspaper reported.
</P>
<P>
   But, getting to the nitty-gritty, police said unsafe speed and
alcohol or drug use were the main factors in 65 percent of Travis
County's traffic deaths last year.
</P>
<P>
   And, in a follow-up article, the American-Statesman reported
that tailgating _ or following the car in front of you too closely
_ was the most common factor in local accidents in which someone
was injured, but not killed.
</P>
<P>
   The more crowded the streets and freeways become, the more
difficult it is for many drivers to exercise common sense, it
seems. And it's not just an Austin problem. Even though traffic
fatalities dropped statewide last year, 3,508 men, women and
children still died on Texas roadways.
</P>
<P>
   During this pre-election season, we are hearing countless
political candidates promise to get tough on crime. That posture is
fine, but it's also a no-brainer, since there aren't many
constitutional ways left to toughen anti-crime laws in Texas.
</P>
<P>
   On any given day, I am much more concerned about a member of my
family being the victim of an auto accident than I am about him or
her falling prey to a criminal.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes, I think it would be a welcome change for politicians
to vow to tackle traffic safety. But, in reality, there's only so
much that government can do to force people to drive responsibly _
short of beefing up police patrols to the extent that most
taxpayers wouldn't want to pay for them, or lowering the highway
speed limit again, which most Texans probably would protest.
</P>
<P>
   The Legislature in recent years has toughened some laws against
drunken driving, but not nearly to the extent that some other
states have done. Some tougher proposals, including a lower
driving-while-intoxicated standard, may be worth a look.
</P>
<P>
   Some safety and insurance experts, meanwhile, think Texas may be
too lenient with traffic offenders. They question, for example,
whether we should continue to wipe a traffic ticket off a driver's
record if he or she takes a defensive driving course. We may be
hiding future crash risks, they argue.
</P>
<P>
   Austin native Rick Gentry has a double perspective on his
hometown's and the state's traffic problems. One view comes from
his office on the I-35 frontage road. He sees at least one wreck a
week. One car landed three feet from his office wall.
</P>
<P>
   The other view is from his role as executive director of the
Texas Insurance Organization, which represents most of the auto
insurance companies operating in Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Gentry said studies have shown that the biggest deterrent to
driving poorly is fear of bodily injury. The second is fear that a
driver's insurance rates may be increased.
</P>
<P>
   Gentry is the expert. But some people _ judging from the way
they drive _ no longer seem worried about the first possibility,
much less the second. &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXXEND OF STORY &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
