A6544 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NOLAN-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      10-14 0690
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NOLAN-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CALIFORNIA SEN. BOXER FIGHTS OPPONENT'S BLANDNESS, MODERATION?
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 bY MARTIN F. NOLAN 
c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ The Year of the Woman was then, not now, as
Barbara Boxer, battling for another Senate term, is discovering.
The feisty Democrat is also plagued by historical forces, including
California's fabulously short attention span.
</P>
<P>
   ``We differ on choice. We differ on guns. We differ on the
environment. We differ on campaign finance reform,'' Boxer, 57,
told television viewers in a Monday night debate against her
Republican opponent, state Treasurer Matt Fong. ``I have the
support of the Sacramento Bee and the San Francisco Examiner. He
has the support of Newt Gingrich and Oliver North.''
</P>
<P>
   On most issues, most Californians agree with Boxer, yet her
favorability quotient is shaky, in part because of what the Bee's
endorsing editorial called her: ``A high-profile, high-energy
politician with a bent for partisanship and self-promotion.''
</P>
<P>
   History underscores her plight. GOP control of Congress has kept
ambitious congressmen happily in the House and out of a primary
that Fong, 44, won with middle-of-the-road views. In '92, Boxer
narrowly defeated a far-right candidate.
</P>
<P>
   Californians, when they choose senators, eventually favor
blandness and moderation over fame and charisma. In 1964, voters
replaced White House spokesman Pierre Salinger with vaudevillean
hoofer George Murphy. In 1970, they rejected Murphy for John V.
Tunney, son of the former heavyweight champion. In 1976, Tunney was
KO'd by S.I. Hayakawa, noted linguist and scourge of campus
protests, who served six years. A synonym for ``high-profile,
high-energy'' politician is one-termer.
</P>
<P>
   Democrat Alan Cranston lasted four famously bland terms in the
Senate, even longer than blandly moderate Thomas Kuchel, who lost a
Republican primary in 1968 to a zealous pamphleteer, Max Rafferty,
who then lost to Cranston.
</P>
<P>
   The governorship is more important to Californians than a Senate
seat. In Sacramento, after the tempestuous reigns of Ronald Reagan
and Jerry Brown, the electorate has spent the last 16 years
swimming in the tapioca sea of George Deukmejian and Pete Wilson.
</P>
<P>
   Boxer's race has also been complicated by her relationship to
President Clinton, whose brother-in-law is married to Boxer's
daughter. More anxiously than most Democrats, she declared that
``it is time to move on ... to the issues that the people care
about. I think that's where the American people are, that's where
Californians are. And that's where I am.''
</P>
<P>
   Fong, an Air Force veteran, has learned how to target a sound
bite. When a panelist in Monday night's debate asked the senator
about her contrasting attitude toward Clinton and Republicans like
Bob Packwood, she claimed she was ``the second senator to speak out
on the floor of the Senate.'' Fong countered that she was not ``as
vitriolic'' about the ``shameful'' conduct of Clinton, whose
fund-raising help she welcomes, then said: ``Barbara Boxer, your
silence for that seven months is certainly deafening. But your
hypocrisy in the way you just presented yourself is
ear-splitting.''
</P>
<P>
   Boxer needs a big turnout, prompting her to plead: ``The pundits
and the pollsters and some of the cynics say you're just not going
to vote. I don't believe that's true.'' Fong's closing statement
called her ``a divider, not a fighter for California.''
</P>
<P>
   Women voters outnumber men in this election, which pleases
Boxer. ``I was a soccer mom before there was a name soccer mom,''
she said after the debate. But since 1992, Boxer has not widened
her base of women and liberals.
</P>
<P>
   Demographics have diminished the importance of abortion, an
issue on which her opponent's beliefs coincide with an evolving
majority. Fong favors parental consent, opposes late-term abortion,
and ``respects'' a woman's right to choose ``in the first
trimester.'' Most ominous of all for Boxer's senatorial career,
polls suggest that Republican women now choose party over gender.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Martin F. Nolan is a Globe columnist.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
