<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-14 14:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6548 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CAKEWALK-FOOD-HNS &LR;      10-14 1048
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAKEWALK-FOOD-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POPULAR CAKE WALKS SPOTLIGHT HOLIDAYS, SCHOOL CARNIVALS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By ANN CRISWELL 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Styles in cakes may come and go, but school carnival cake walks
and bake sales will always be with us.
</P>
<P>
   Cake walks date to at least the mid-19th century. In ``The
Dictionary of American Food and Drink'' (Hearst Books, 1994), John
F. Mariani describes the cake walk as an African-American pastime
in which participants strutted or danced fancifully to win the
prize of a cake. The date of 1840 is mentioned in ``American
Manners and Morals'' by Mary Cable (American Heritage Publishing,
1969).
</P>
<P>
   At early-day cake socials, cakes were sold to raise money for
charity. How the cake walk evolved into a musical-chairs activity
at schools and churches doesn't seem to be well documented, but it
has been popular, at least in the South, for several generations.
At the usual cake walk, people buy chances and walk around a
diagram of numbered squares. When the music stops, the person on
the square with the number of the prize cake wins. Numbers are
assigned at random by the cake committee.
</P>
<P>
   Another method is to give each participant a ticket. When the
music stops, a ticket number is read and the holder of the ticket
gets to choose a cake.
</P>
<P>
   Still another is to pick a chair with a number to sit in; when
the chairs are full, a number is called and the winner chooses a
cake. Sometimes, participants just draw a number out of a jar.
</P>
<P>
   In years past, Southern cake socials were graced by hand-beaten
pound cakes, lavishly frosted fruit- and nut-filled Lord and Lady
Baltimore and Lane cakes, feather-light white cakes with fluffy
frosting, and jelly and jam cakes.
</P>
<P>
   Many early cakes were based on dried and fresh fruit:
Tutti-Frutti Cake, Dried Apple Cake, Stack Cakes, Fig Preserves
Cake, Prune Cake, Date Cake, Pineapple and Apple Upside-Down Cakes,
and more recently, Fruit Cocktail Cake, Apple and Applesauce Cakes,
Pia Colada Cake and Hummingbird Cake.
</P>
<P>
   Such cakes hold scant appeal for today's cake-walkers, who
generally are kids. They go for chocolate with chocolate frosting
and/or miniature candy bars, colored sprinkles and other
decorations. Devil's food cake topped with Halloween symbols such
as ghosts and spiders or candies or frosting spider webs lure young
cake-walkers most.
</P>
<P>
   Many time-pressed parents buy cakes to donate from supermarkets
or bakeries. Because all the cakes are usually put out at one time
(or one batch in the morning, another in the afternoon), cakes must
be able to endure several hours outside, often in the heat. Cream
cheese, buttercream and more delicate frostings are not good
choices unless you can keep the cakes cool until it's time to bring
them out.
</P>
<P>
   It's better to decorate with powdered sugar, canned or packaged
frosting. Package or wrap cakes securely so they won't fall apart,
because they may be carried around for hours. The cake walk is most
popular near the end of the carnival, because the cakes can be
transported home immediately.
</P>
<P>
   At neighborhood schools a Cake Walk is part of the annual spring
festival. Cakes shaped like soccer balls, footballs, basketballs or
baseball caps are especially popular with boys. They also go for
cakes decorated or shaped like sports logos or the school mascot.
Plain chocolate, German Chocolate, strawberry and carrot cakes
appeal more to the grown-ups.
</P>
<P>
   Some cake-walk organizers prefer individual cakes, brownies and
cupcakes. Others say cupcakes are not as popular. Possibly that's
because plain cupcakes are more ordinary to the kids, and
individual items are harder to keep up with and sell.
</P>
<P>
   Tickets often sell three for $1, and each round on the cake walk
requires one ticket.
</P>
<P>
   At neighborhood Halloween carnivals, cupcakes and layer cakes
decorated with Halloween designs, coconut, confetti sprinkles and
miniature candies are money-makers.
</P>
<P>
   In honor of the 50th anniversary of the development of cake mix,
Betty Crocker SuperMoist is sponsoring the Betty Crocker Bake Sale
Competition. Schools and charitable organizations can win as much
as $5,000 by sharing their secrets for a successful bake sale.
</P>
<P>
   Entrants must submit four bake sale recipes. Rules are:
</P>
<P>
   One recipe must use Betty Crocker SuperMoist Devil's Food cake
mix made with Hershey's cocoa. Additional consideration will be
granted if other Hershey's products are used.
</P>
<P>
   One recipe must use another Betty Crocker dessert mix with
Hershey's ingredients such as brownies, muffins of cookies.
Additional consideration will be granted if other Hershey's
products are used.
</P>
<P>
   Any two additional bake sale recipes are the entrant's choice.
</P>
<P>
   Include five tips on how to produce a successful bake sale.
</P>
<P>
   List the names of three representatives of the charitable
organization or school.
</P>
<P>
   Submit a photograph of a bake sale table, and include the
recipes being submitted.
</P>
<P>
   Include name, complete address with ZIP code and daytime
telephone number. Also include the name of the nonprofit
organization and a copy of the exemption letter that reflects the
organization's status under U.S. Tax Exempt ID Code 501C3.
</P>
<P>
   Send entries to 50th Anniversary Bake Sale Competition, 245
Eighth Ave., Suite 236, New York, N.Y. 10011.
</P>
<P>
   Bake sales can be held anytime through mid-February 1999, but
offical entries must be postmarked by Feb. 15, 1999. Winners will
be announced about May 1.
</P>
<P>
   Judges will select one grand-prize winner and 20 runner-up
entries. Each runner-up will receive a $1,000 donation to the
charity identified on the entry form. The contest is open to all
legal U.S. residents except where prohibited, restricted or taxed
by law.
</P>
<P>
   To obtain complete rules, call 800-446-1898 or access the
Internet site: http://www.BettyCrocker.com on the World Wide Web.
</P>
<P>
   Cake mix was created after four years of development and two
years of extensive in-home testing. The first two, Devil's Food and
Party Cake, were introduced in 1948.
</P>
<P>
   The mixes have been reformulated through the years to reflect
consumer preferences. The newest change combines the Betty Crocker
and Hershey's brands in 34 chocolate dessert mixes, available
nationwide this fall. &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXXEND OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
