<SLUG> BC-DESIGNER-FASHION-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LEAVE IT TO AN OPTIMIST AMERICAN DESIGNER TO BRING BACK SOME FUN 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By LINDA GILLAN GRIFFIN 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MILAN, Italy _ In the bleakness that has come to characterize
much of fashion in the 1990s _ mussed hair, hideous makeup, dull
clothes and footwear only a storm trooper could love _ happy
moments are few and far between.
</P>
<P>
   Such a moment occurred here this week, bursting like a ray of
sunshine through the gray rain that has settled over this Italian
fashion capital during the showing of designer women's
ready-to-wear for spring 1999. Leave it up to an optimistic
American to bring back some fun.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Ford's Gucci collection emanated some of the steaminess of
his past collections, characterized by dark colors and barely
veiled sexuality. It even took the edge off the downer tour of the
new Gucci store on Montenapoleone, where merchandise is displayed
in museum-like cases amid a don't-touch atmosphere and one of the
interesting accessories is a pair of silver Gucci handcuffs.
</P>
<P>
   Described by the designer as ``Las Vegas hippie,'' Ford's spring
collection is replete with flower-child prints, beaded embroidery
and appliqus. He took the dark trousers from fall, removed the
buckles and let the glittering embroidery fall where it would. Torn
jeans featured feathers and beading in African and American Indian
motifs. Black leather high moccasin boots had laces up the front
and leather fringe around the tops. Ford's family comes from Santa
Fe, N.M., by the way, and he maintains a home there.
</P>
<P>
   The fuchsias and blue of Ford's ruffled flower prints, teamed
with black leather, looked bright enough for former Rudi Gernreich
model Peggy Moffit, who was in the audience and still sporting her
signature bowl cut. But just in case, the designer threw in
handbags and little sling-back shoes with princess heels, pairing
two and three colors from a palette that included turquoise,
orange, fuchsia, sunflower yellow, beige and black.
</P>
<P>
   Another American, Lawrence Steele, revved up the Italian fashion
week with a presentation of Greco-Roman-inspired bare tops and
halter-neck dresses, wrapped and tied with thin leather thongs.
There were bias-cut white linen and white jersey dresses, the
latter backless to the waist.
</P>
<P>
   In a fit of fish-and-fowl inspiration, Steele deftly segued from
a skirt of pale yellow feathers to one of large yellow sequins,
layered like fish scales. Then he cut pale beige chiffon into
jillions of feather shapes, layering them onto the lightest of
dresses.
</P>
<P>
   Narciso Rodriguez, an American of Cuban heritage, is another
innovator who has raised the bar for Italian designers. He
maintained the simplicity of his pieces and brought back the tube
toppers from his fall and winter collection.
</P>
<P>
   In shades of gray, silver, sea green, azure and white, Rodriguez
cut simple and sometimes complicated tops, skirts, dresses and
pants, then layered over them knit tubes such as soft corsets or
obi sashes. Khaki tops and pants were the casual end of a
collection whose evening pieces were of a silvery matelasse fabric
that has the effect of a rich screen.
</P>
<P>
   Byblos owner Donatella Girombelli, who replaced designer Richard
Tyler with the American John Bartlett, appears to have that line
back on track with lighthearted safari styles and modern basics.
</P>
<P>
   Bartlett used iridescent khaki, crumpled silk organza and
lacquered tulle to lighten up what might have been an intellectual
collection, with asymmetrical wrapping and caftans and the
same-old-same-old epaulets and patch pockets.
</P>
<P>
   Byblos also showcased what looks like the sleeper color of the
season for Italian designers, a greenish yellow, not quite
chartreuse. Max Mara, the Italian house known for its fine
tailoring, significantly lightened its view of the contemporary
woman, setting off coffee brown and khakis with the Pernod
yellow-green, glimpsed through slits and on the insides of pleats.
</P>
<P>
   Long, slim shapes, even in flared skirts, tie-dyed sweaters and
chartreuse snakeskin, moved Max Mara a tad off its traditional
image of producing classics. There were even India-style mirror
embroideries, albeit on beige. Moss greens and bright yellows
softened safari styles, and slits on the sides of skirts ensured
comfort even while stalking summer in the city. But this line
proves again that hat-weather urban dressing can be as simple as a
white camisole worn over a pleated taupe linen skirt.
</P>
<P>
   The Salvatore Ferragamo company, mourning the death last week of
designer Fiamma Ferragamo after her long bout with cancer, bought
out a refreshing line totally focused on a Chinese theme. From
several weights of Mao jackets with frog closures worn over easy,
roomy and often cropped pants, Ferragamo moved on to silks printed
with numerous signature motifs. These were worked into tiny Mao
jackets, tops and the cropped pants, using a tightly controlled
palette of black, white, beige and a little Chinese red.
</P>
<P>
   What made all the black and white drawstring pants so palatable
at Ferragamo was the use of metallic fobs on the end of the strings
instead of traditional knots. With little white leather jackets in
the Ferragamo tradition, these simple pairings look fresh and
young.
</P>
<P>
   At Emporio Armani, the show was noticeably shortened and
choreographed, from the perfection of the tailoring to the posing
of the line's designers on stage with Armani at show's end.
</P>
<P>
   This Armani secondary line focuses on the woman who wants the
designer's signature tailoring at a lower price. For spring, the
line also loosens up, mixing sporty looks with traditional ones.
Sage grays, pewter, beige, golden yellow, aquamarine and coral, as
well as some brushstroke and graphic patterns, figure in the
designs. Jackets resemble cardigans or lengthen into dusters worn
over pants or dresses, and there are lots of vests and bustier
tops.
</P>
<P>
   For evening, Emporio women take to lightweight Indian trousers
worn under dresses whose prints are superimposed with floral
embroidery. While there are touches of India and of Italian
tailoring in this collection, the overall sensibility seems to be
one of Asian austerity and serenity.
</P>
<P>
   There was no serenity in the Blumarine collection sent out by
designer Anna Molinari. Pink, fuchsia, beads, flowers, pointelle
cashmere sweaters _ every girly trick was there, and know what? It
all looked great. From a pink floral embroidered bikini to all-over
beaded sheaths, the pink froth was fun. Molinari's customers can
even dress up in Mama looks, thanks to the portrait neckline
wrap-and-tie jackets, based loosely on the kimono. And if there's a
chill to the air conditioning, try Molinari's fur-trimmed cardigan
on for size.
</P>
<P>
   Some design houses delight in giving fashion the bird. Moschino
did it literally this season, sending out a great, black flying
finger hat on one model, along with a bevy of other witty and
sometimes wearable designs. Miuccia Prada, on the other hand,
merely turned her back on what others are doing.
</P>
<P>
   While the models were not meant to look unattractive, as
sometimes seems the case at avant-garde fashion houses, the designs
still left one wondering what kind of life any woman who wears
these clothes might have. Who would want to strap a great hulking
bag on her behind? Who would wear a full pleated skirt that looks
like a school uniform, or skirts whose fronts and backs dangled
with pieces of mirror _ not sewn in, like Indian embroidery, but
sticking out every which way?
</P>
<P>
   Fabrics that had been stiffened to look like paper, shoes like
golf moccasins, large origami-type floral appliques along the
bottoms of A-line skirts _ well, it was all a puzzle to many in the
audience. And the program notes didn't help. Written in
stream-of-consciousness (or unconsciousness) style, they spoke of a
``sporty Alice in Pradaland.'' It is doubtful that many women will
follow the fashion rabbit down this design hole come spring.
</P>
<P>
   While Prada is to be applauded for her efforts to decorate the
mundane and her experiments with high-tech fabrics, it must be
remembered that most women do not dress to look silly. Groupies do
that. &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXXEND OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-14-98 1411EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
