<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-14 14:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6556 &Cx1f; tic-z
r d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-STATEFAIR-FOOD-AZR &LR;      10-14 2107
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STATE </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHAT'S COOKIN' AT THE ARIZONA STATE FAIR?  
 (ADV: INCLUDES RECIPES AT END) 
</HEADLINE>
 FAIR-FOOD-AZR   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By JUDY WALKER  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - In many ways, the Homemaking Arts Building at the
Arizona State Fair can be seen as one of the last shrines to the
domestic arts and sciences. Superintendent Lani Auwen and her crew
of 15 tend the flames of creativity that burn here for 18 days each
year, starting this season on Oct. 22.
</P>
<P>
   A look behind the scenes of the Homemaking Arts Department
reveals that much has changed over the years.
</P>
<P>
   Twenty years ago, a couple of women from St. Johns dominated the
canning category. Their husbands brought a pickup full of food to
the fair. One year, one of the ladies made an American flag quilt
composed of the hundreds of ribbons she had won through the years.
</P>
<P>
   In 1998, this old barrel-roof building is no longer the
exclusive territory of domestic goddesses.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've seen a dramatic increase in men entering the cooking,''
Auwen said, noting that men now make up almost 40 percent of the
entrants in the canning and baking classes. ``Men really picked up
on canning this year. They do cookies and pies,'' but women still
dominate the cake category.
</P>
<P>
   At least three married couples are competing against each other
in this year's fair.
</P>
<P>
   ``One couple even has their own little wager on it, over who
will win the most,'' Auwen said. ``They said, `The fair's going to
settle it once and for all, who's the better cook.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Male cooks are passionate about their efforts, the homemaking
workers have observed. Last year, there was only one woman who
entered in the two special piemaking contests, Auwen said. The rest
were an extremely competitive group of guys. The dean of pie bakers
is Lowell Ebrite, who has been entering and winning pie contests
``forever,'' or as long as the longtime homemaking arts workers can
remember.
</P>
<P>
   The special contests are one way to represent foods that can't
be displayed for the entire fair run. This year's contests include
pasta, Dutch-oven cooking, ice-cream making, a cookie bake-off for
kids and a ``Spice Up Your Life'' contest for hot and spicy dishes.
</P>
<P>
   One of the constants in the homemaking arts is that
practitioners of cooking as well as handcrafts are pressed for
time, Auwen says. However, she has found that there is a lot of
closet crafting crammed into our days. She notices people knitting
and making other things in all sorts of situations.
</P>
<P>
   Craft skills used to be passed from mother to daughter. Now,
demonstrations are one way that craft interest is sparked and
traditions passed along.
</P>
<P>
   ``We do see people wanting to do more with their hands,'' Auwen
said. ``The first reaction is, `Oh, that's too hard.' But they see
someone tatting, and they watch for a while, and they realize it's
not really that hard, but it does take time. And that's what we're
all pushed against. Time.''
</P>
<P>
   One newly popular craft is weaving.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have really extended our weaving'' categories, Auwen said.
``It's really been growing in the counties'' across the state.
``Some local community colleges have added weaving and spinning
classes.''
</P>
<P>
   The cross-stitch category has expanded greatly, too, and
dollmaking is more popular than ever.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, the entire class of wool garments has been
eliminated in sewing, Auwen said. A few years ago, there were
enough entries for a wool fashion show. Last year, one wool skirt
was entered. Although Arizona still has a wool industry,
woolgrowers' wives no longer have time to put into their auxiliary,
Auwen said.
</P>
<P>
   Clubs in general have gone by the wayside. Two women's clubs
that used to submit about 500 entries a year from their members now
send in less than 100. In the seven years that Auwen has been the
superintendent, most of the members of one of the big clubs, the
Busy Bees, have passed away.
</P>
<P>
   The steady stream of contests and demonstrations in the
Homemaking Arts Building is how the keepers of the flames fan the
embers. Auwen constantly is gathering information on what the
public wants to see.
</P>
<P>
   People who enter the fair are asked what they would like to see
in the future. Many people have asked for a fresh salsa contest,
for example.
</P>
<P>
   Among newer categories in food are sugar-free candies,
preserves, jams, jelly, marmalade and conserves, because people who
are diabetic have asked for these, Auwen said. A class added last
year was conserves, a mixture of several fruits cooked to a jamlike
consistency. Nuts are optional.
</P>
<P>
   Technology causes certain classes of items to wax and wane.
</P>
<P>
   Machine-made bread is now in the bakery cases; microwaved cakes
and cookies are eligible for judging.
</P>
<P>
   Categories are eliminated only when there have been no entries
for two or three years. Macrame was dropped only recently.
</P>
<P>
   One constant remains, as it has for all 114 years of the Arizona
State Fair: prizewinning recipes. A few years ago, the Homemaking
Arts staff compiled many of them into a book, ``Arizona State Fair
Blue Ribbon Recipes.'' Blue Ribbon Recipes include the cheesecake
recipe from a Mesa baker in his 70s, Bill Graves, who wrote that
his mother owned a stagecoach tavern in New Hampshire. Another
baker who usually enters is Bebe Reed, who comes to the fair from
Nogales every year. Her recipe for Our Special Birthday Cake was
handed down from her mother and grandmother.
</P>
<P>
   Beth Sternitzky of Apache Junction won the right to represent
the state with Arizona's Supreme Citrus Pie in the 1990 National
Pie Celebration, sponsored by Crisco, and was a runner-up. The
Apple Pie recipe, from Dianna Bennett of Phoenix, came from
techniques she was taught by both her grandmothers. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
Arizona State Fair Cheesecake
</P>
<P>
   (From ``Arizona State Fair Blue Ribbon Recipes'') &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Crust: 2 cups finely crushed graham crackers
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2 teaspoons cinnamon
</P>
<P>
   1/3 cup sugar
</P>
<P>
   1/4 pound butter, melted (1 stick)
</P>
<P>
   Butter a springform pan liberally. In a small bowl, combine
crackers, cinnamon, sugar and melted butter. Line pan firmly with
crumb mixture, covering bottom and up the sides about 2 inches.
Crumbs should be about 1/4-inch thick. Put in freezer to chill, or
into preheated oven and bake for 10 minutes at 350. Both ways work.
Set crust aside.
</P>
<P>
   Filling:
</P>
<P>
   2 packages (8 ounces each) cream cheese, softened
</P>
<P>
   1 cup sugar
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon vanilla
</P>
<P>
   1 16-ounce container sour cream
</P>
<P>
   4 eggs
</P>
<P>
   Preheat oven to 350. In a large mixer bowl, combine 2 packages
of cream cheese, sugar, vanilla and sour cream. Add eggs and beat
on medium speed until mixture is blended and smooth.
</P>
<P>
   Pour into graham crust and bake for 40 minutes. Then turn oven
off. Let cheesecake stay in oven for 1{ to 2 hours. Do not open
door.
</P>
<P>
   Topping
</P>
<P>
   8 ounces cream cheese, softened
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon vanilla
</P>
<P>
   1 small can (6 ounces) crushed pineapple, drained well
</P>
<P>
   1/3 cup sour cream
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons sugar
</P>
<P>
   In a small mixer bowl, combine cream cheese, vanilla, pineapple,
sour cream and sugar, and whip at high speed for 5 minutes. Spread
on top of cooled cake. Decorate with a slice of pineapple and fresh
raspberries, if desired.
</P>
<P>
   Makes 16 servings. Approximate values per serving: 429 calories,
30 g fat, 122 mg cholesterol, 36 g carbohydrates, 1 grams fiber,
282 mg sodium, 7 grams protein, 61 percent calories from fat.
</P>
<P>
   Our Special Birthday Cake
</P>
<P>
   (From Bebe J. Reed, Nogales)
</P>
<P>
   Cake
</P>
<P>
   1 cup shortening
</P>
<P>
   2 cups sugar
</P>
<P>
   4 eggs, separated
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2 teaspoons vanilla
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon almond extract
</P>
<P>
   3 cups cake flour
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon baking powder
</P>
<P>
   1/4 teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   1 cup milk
</P>
<P>
   3/4 cup chocolate chips
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup chopped cherries
</P>
<P>
   Chocolate Buttercream Frosting:
</P>
<P>
   1 pound softened butter
</P>
<P>
   2-pound package confectioners' sugar
</P>
<P>
   6 tablespoons vanilla (or other favorite flavoring)
</P>
<P>
   3/4 cup cocoa
</P>
<P>
   4 to 6 tablespoons milk
</P>
<P>
   Preheat oven to 375 degrees. Grease and flour three 9-inch cake
pans.
</P>
<P>
   In a large bowl, beat shortening and sugar until creamy and
fluffy. In a medium bowl, beat egg yolks; add to creamed mixture
and beat well. Stir in vanilla and almond extract. Into a separate
bowl, sift together cake flour, baking powder and salt. Add to
creamed mixture alternately with milk, beating well after each
addition. Fold in chips and cherries.
</P>
<P>
   In a large bowl, beat egg whites until stiff but not dry. Fold
into batter. Pour into the greased and floured pans. Bake for about
30 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Remove layers from pans and let cool completely. Recommended
frosting: Chocolate Buttercream.
</P>
<P>
   For frosting, in a large bowl, slowly add sugar to butter a
little at a time. Beat well after each addition. When frosting
becomes stiff, add flavoring; beat well. Add cocoa, beat well.
</P>
<P>
   Add milk to mixture 1 teaspoon at a time while beating, until
proper consistency.
</P>
<P>
   Note: This cake is good with butterscotch chips, mint chips and,
if you can get them, the cherry, coconut and blueberry chips that
are available in the Midwest (or through baking catalogs). To make
these for small children, I use minichips and cupcake pans.
</P>
<P>
   Makes 10 to 12 servings. Approximate values per cake: 1,055
calories, 54 g fat, 147 mg cholesterol, 143 g carbohydrates, 3 g
fiber, 7 g protein, 482 mg sodium, 45 percent calories from fat.
</P>
<P>
   Arizona's Supreme Citrus Pie
</P>
<P>
   (From Beth Sternitzky)
</P>
<P>
   1 deep-dish 9- or 9{-inch baked pie crust, cooled &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Fluffy filling:
</P>
<P>
   1 8-ounce package cream cheese, softened
</P>
<P>
   1 12-ounce can sweetened condensed milk
</P>
<P>
   1 6-ounce can frozen lemonade concentrate, thawed
</P>
<P>
   1 4-serving size package lemon-flavor instant pudding and pie
filling mix (not sugar free)
</P>
<P>
   1 cup whipping cream, whipped
</P>
<P>
   Combine cream cheese and sweetened condensed milk in large bowl.
Beat at low speed of electric mixer until smooth. Add lemonade
concentrate. Blend well. Beat in pudding mix until smooth. Fold in
whipped cream. Spoon into baked pie crust. Make shallow depression
in filling 1 inch inside of edge. Refrigerate.
</P>
<P>
   Clear filling:
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup cornstarch
</P>
<P>
   1/3 cup water
</P>
<P>
   4 egg yolks
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup fresh lemon juice
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2 cups granulated sugar
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2 cups water
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon butter or margarine
</P>
<P>
   Combine cornstarch and 1/3 cup water in small bowl. Stir to
blend. Combine egg yolks and lemon juice in medium bowl. Beat until
smooth. Combine granulated sugar and remaining water in medium
saucepan. Cook on medium heat until mixture comes to a boil. Stir
in cornstarch mixture slowly. Cook and stir until thickened and
clear. Remove from heat. Stir in egg yolk mixture slowly until
blended.
</P>
<P>
   Return to heat. Cook and stir 1 to 2 minutes or until mixture
comes to a boil. Remove from heat. Stir in butter until blended.
Cool completely. Spread gently over fluffy filling.
</P>
<P>
   Topping:
</P>
<P>
   1 cup whipping cream
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons confectioners' sugar
</P>
<P>
   3/4 teaspoon vanilla
</P>
<P>
   Beat whipping cream in small bowl at high speed of electric
mixer until stiff peaks form. Beat in confectioners' sugar and
vanilla. Spread over clear filling. Refrigerate until firm.
</P>
<P>
   Makes 8 to 10 servings. Approximate values per pie: 654
calories, 37 g fat, 190 mg cholesterol, 77 g carbohydrates, 0 mg
fiber, 408 mg sodium, 49 percent calories from fat.
</P>
<P>
   Apple Pie
</P>
<P>
   (From ``Arizona State Fair Blue Ribbon Recipes'')
</P>
<P>
   Crust
</P>
<P>
   2/3 cup Butter Flavor Crisco
</P>
<P>
   2 cups sifted all-purpose flour
</P>
<P>
   6 1/2 tablespoons cold water
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   Filling
</P>
<P>
   3 pounds Granny Smith apples
</P>
<P>
   1 cup sugar
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2 teaspoons cinnamon
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon nutmeg
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons flour
</P>
<P>
   Beaten egg white for brushing on top
</P>
<P>
   For crust: With two knives or a pastry cutter, cut shortening
into flour in a large bowl until mixture is the size of peas. Add
the water and salt to the mixture. Mix with hands only until
mixture is sticky. Divide in half. Roll out on a lightly floured
board into two crusts and put one into a 9-inch pan.
</P>
<P>
   Preheat oven to 350 degrees. Peel, core and slice apples into a
large bowl; mix in sugar, cinnamon and nutmeg. Sprinkle flour over
apples as you layer them into the pie crust. Add top crust; seal by
crimping edges, score across the top, and brush with egg whites.
Bake 50 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Makes 9 servings. Approximate values per serving: 401 calories,
16 g fat, 0 mg cholesterol, 63 g carbohydrates, 3 mg fiber, 241 mg
sodium, 35 percent calories from fat.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
