<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-14 14:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6557 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-JACKSON-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      10-14 0887
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JACKSON-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOMOSEXUALS YET TO GET A FAIR SHAKE FROM POLITICIANS
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 bY DERRICK Z. JACKSON 
c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The savage murder of Matthew Shepard has caused President
Clinton to urge Congress to expand federal laws on hate crimes to
acts done on the basis of sexual orientation, disability, and
gender. Shepard, a gay student at the University of Wyoming, was
lured out of a bar, beaten until he had a fractured skull, then
left tied to a fence in the cold and in such a comatose state that
when a bicyclist rode past him 18 hours later, the cyclist first
thought the form was a scarecrow.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope that in the grief of this moment for Matthew Shepard's
family and in the shared outrage across America, Americans will
once again search their hearts and do what they can to reduce their
own fear and anxiety and anger at people who are different,''
Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   If Clinton is sincere about Americans searching their hearts, he
had better do more than just hope. He needs to lead. While there
might be dutiful outrage this week over Shepard's death, Clinton
knows there is no shared agreement on whether Shepard was a full
human being in the first place.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the hardest hearts on homophobia are right in front of
Clinton's face, in Congress. Up to now, Clinton has been more an
accommodationist than a bold attacker of their views.
</P>
<P>
   To be fair, Clinton is the first president to openly court gay
and lesbian campaign support. He has a senior White House adviser
on gay issues. He has made 150 gay and lesbian appointments to his
administration.
</P>
<P>
   But his groundbreaking promise at the beginning of his first
term to end discrimination against gay and lesbian soldiers in the
military ended with those soldiers still in the closet under his
``don't ask, don't tell'' policy. Then, with reelection less than
two months away, Clinton signed a law that denies federal
recognition of gay and lesbian marriages.
</P>
<P>
   When Clinton signed the act, Elizabeth Birch, executive director
of the Human Rights Campaign, the nation's most prominent gay and
lesbian political organization, said:
</P>
<P>
   ``It is deeply disappointing that the president has chosen the
politically expedient course of action rather than standing up to
gratuitous gay bashing.''
</P>
<P>
   Since then, gay bashing has been a rite on Capitol Hill. This
summer, both Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott and House Majority
Leader Dick Armey both called homosexuality a ``sin.''
</P>
<P>
   Lott this year compared homosexuality to alcoholism, something
House Speaker Newt Gingrich did in 1994. Lott said, ``Others have a
sex addiction or are kleptomaniacs. There are all kinds of problems
and addictions and difficulties and experiences of this kind that
are wrong. But you should try to work with that person to learn to
control that problem.''
</P>
<P>
   This is the same Lott who successfully opposed federal laws
banning discrimination against gay and lesbian workers because he
fears such laws are ``part of a larger and more audacious effort to
make the public accept behavior that most Americans consider
dangerous, unhealthy, or just plain wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   Just to make sure no one would mistake Lott for an
equal-opportunity employer, he blocked the nomination of James
Hormel as ambassador to Luxembourg this summer. Hormel would have
been the nation's first openly gay ambassador.
</P>
<P>
   Armey, who three years ago called gay Representative Barney
Frank ``Barney Fag,'' seconded Lott's position that homosexuality
is a sin. ``The Bible is very clear on this,'' Armey said. Senate
Assistant Majority Leader Don Nickles, in approving Lott's blockade
against Hormel, said, Hormel has ``promoted a lifestyle and
promoted it in a big way, in a way that is very offensive.''
</P>
<P>
   These feelings run so hot that the Texas Republican Party this
summer denied an information booth at its statewide convention to
the Log Cabin Republicans, the nation's leading organization of gay
Republicans. In California, in the race for the US Senate,
Treasurer Matt Fong, the challenger to incumbent Barbara Boxer,
said Lott's comments were ``accurate.''
</P>
<P>
   In this atmosphere, Clinton looks good with little effort. He
and Vice President Al Gore still go to gay and lesbian political
dinners. But when Clinton calls for an expansion of hate crime
laws, one should remember that Lott was still able to block
Hormel's appointment even after the firestorm of outrage that
greeted Lott's remarks about homosexuality.
</P>
<P>
   Lott and his like-minded colleagues in the Republican Party have
yet to pay a political price for their homophobia. It is
meaningless for Clinton to ask Americans to search their hearts if
he does not summon within himself the passion for gay rights
necessary to openly fight the mixture of myth and paranoia that
tortures public discourse on homosexuality.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton has already bargained with the Republican leadership on
the military and gay marriages. There has to be a point where he
will bargain no more on the idea that gay and lesbian people are
not equal either in the eyes of Republican gods, and thus, not in
the laws of the land. If the death of Matthew Shepard cannot move
him to stop the bazaar of equality, nothing will.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Derrick Z. Jackson is a Globe columnist.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-14-98 1412EDT &QL; 
