</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CD-BOOKS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DISC DRIVES: ARE COMMUTER'S BOOKS ON TAPE GIVING WAY TO BOOKS ON
CD? 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By MELISSA FLETCHER STOELTJE 
C.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   With the advent of easier, sleeker compact-disc players, the
tape cassette player _ like its predecessor, the clunky, old
turntable _ is quickly going the way of the dinosaur.
</P>
<P>
   But what does this bode for the burgeoning books on tape
industry, which nowadays pulls in more than $2 billion a year in
sales? What does it mean for folks who relish a little taste of
``Into Thin Air'' or ``Bridget Jones' Diary'' in their cars on the
way to work?
</P>
<P>
   Are people having to chunk their favorite book tapes because
their cars have gone high-tech?
</P>
<P>
   In short, no. These days, most cars still come equipped with
tape cassette players, even the luxury-end variety, according to
Ward's Autoinfo Bank, which tracks such information. In 1997,
almost five million domestic cars produced came equipped with
cassette players only, compared to a mere 1.4 million with CD
players only. (Among imported cars sold, the difference was some
700,00 to 400,000, respectively.)
</P>
<P>
   A call to a few Mercedes-Benz and Lexus dealerships in Houston
confirmed that, indeed, most of those high models continue to come
with cassette players: You can get a CD player installed, but it
must be ordered as an option. Only ``about 10 percent'' of clients
ask for that frill, says the general manager of one Mercedes-Benz
dealership, who didn't want to give his name.
</P>
<P>
   But even if someone decides to go exclusively with a CD on the
dash, they're not out of luck when it comes to listening to books
on the road. They can simply buy books on CD.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're a little more expensive right now to produce, because
they're not a high-volume product, like tapes are,'' says Jim
Grant, vice-president of Earful of Books, a major, Austin-based
retailer of audiobooks. Grant says that, of the approximately 7,000
audiobook titles his company sells, more than 90 percent are on
tape.
</P>
<P>
   While books on tape can be as inexpensive as $14.95 or as costly
as $90 _ it all depends on the length of the book, and, thus, how
many tapes required to tell it _ books on CD are about 20 percent
higher, he says. (However, CD books do cost about the same as tapes
if you're just renting them, he adds.)
</P>
<P>
   Since many folks still have cassette players in their cars,
there is not a big demand for books on CDs, which results in the
higher cost.
</P>
<P>
   Another problem affecting their popularity, says Grant, is CDs
don't ``bookmark'' well. (If ejected, CDs resume play at the
beginning.)
</P>
<P>
   ``If you're playing an unabridged book, it may take five or 10
times to hear it,'' he explains. ``If you're in the middle, you
can't go right back to where you were; you have to jump around the
track. Whereas with a tape, the device stops, so you can pick right
back up where you were.''
</P>
<P>
   As books on CD technology improves, the audio book industry will
respond accordingly, says Grant, whose company handles the
audiobook accounts of more than 300 publishers nationwide. The
quality, by the way, is the same, no matter if you're listening to
tape or CD, he adds.
</P>
<P>
   John Reilly, spokesman for the Automobile Parts and Accessory
Association, predicts the dashboard landscape will change
drastically in the years ahead.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the next five years, it's very doubtful cars will be coming
out with tape players,'' Reilly says. Already, he says, the
``specs'' for many 1999 models reveal that many of the new,
high-end cars will be coming out equipped with CD players alone.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Tape cassette players) are just being faded out,'' he says.
``Look at the music industry, and people just aren't buying
cassettes.''
</P>
<P>
   He also predicts books on CD will become increasingly more
common, since demographically speaking, the people who buy luxury
cars tend to be the same ones who listen to audio books. And demand
feeds supply. &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXXEND OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
