</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MILAN-FASHION-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S. DESIGNERS WORKING ABROAD SET LIGHT RUNWAY MOOD 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By LINDA GILLAN GRIFFIN 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MILAN, Italy _ As skies remain gray and somber in this Italian
fashion capital, U.S. designers working abroad continue to set a
runway mood that is considerably lighter.
</P>
<P>
   Victor Alfaro's collection summed up the apparent direction of
women's ready-to-wear designs for spring 1999. Using soft colors of
khaki, ivory, pale yellow and a violet so subdued it looked gray,
Alfaro executed an American Indian theme with sensitivity and
precision.
</P>
<P>
   From the melodious flute-and-drum soundtrack to tastefully
beaded and fringed evening wear to the models' buttery suede boots,
the theme wound its way into the presentation but did not scream
ethnicity. The mood was one of serenity.
</P>
<P>
   The finest cashmere yarns were woven into tiny tops and
cardigans worn over calf-length skirts. For chillier days, there
were open-weave, hand-knit sweaters with three-quarter linen
dusters topping cropped linen pants. Evening saw loose and thin
gauze dresses, often with tracery beading, worn over featherweight
cashmere tubes.
</P>
<P>
   Another American, Rebecca Moses, the designer behind Donatella
Girombelli's Genny line for five years, is leaving that house to
concentrate on her own collection. Presented in a series of
tableaux in her showroom, her designs included beautiful knits and
lovely chiffons and jerseys for evening.
</P>
<P>
   Moses' palette ran from aubergine to lavender, Capri sea blue to
pale powder blue, lemon to mint, pink to coral. The cutest pieces
were cashmere sweaters, both pullovers and cardigans, that combined
colors _ pale lemon with mint, pink with lavender _ and cashmere
tops with beaded sheer, short sleeves.
</P>
<P>
   Her basics _ in black, beige, ivory and white _ included all the
pieces a woman counts on in a daily wardrobe or for traveling, with
a choice of straight-leg, toreador or satin pants, comfortable
jackets, long cardigans, overcoats and sweaters.
</P>
<P>
   Bergdorf Goodman is contracting with Moses to produce a
plus-size line.
</P>
<P>
   Like almost every other designer in Milan, expert tailors
Giorgio Armani and Antonio Fusco concentrated on luxury pieces but
with the softened lines they believe women want. This trend of
adding luxury pieces to the wardrobe appears to be the key to
taking women out of their stiff suits and jacketed dresses without
making them seem overly casual.
</P>
<P>
   Fusco was the more structured of the two, showing silky
shirtdresses and drawstring-waist skirts worn with easy jackets and
some pseudo-safari looks. Khaki and charcoal ribbed knits worn with
pin stripes and beaded starbursts on sheath dresses characterized
the collection. Special touches included a bare apron top and a
group of pretty matching beaded chiffon shawls and skirts worn with
knit tops.
</P>
<P>
   Armani, more than any other Milanese designer, focused intently
on gray. From charcoal to dove, the current of the Orient.
</P>
<P>
   Shirt jackets were worn like cardigans, fastenings were
invisible, and fabric weights were whisper-light. Tops and T-shirts
were small, while skirts and pants fell to the ankles. The palette
expanded to include dusty blue, wisteria green and palest purple.
</P>
<P>
   Armani's evening wear included prints on white, gray and
aquamarine silk gauze with transparent and iridescent sequins. Long
dresses appeared in jade, and there were bits of pink, mango and
Chinese orange-red.
</P>
<P>
   The overwhelming message of the collection, however, was an
outer layer of transparent fabric. Chiffon or organza layers topped
opaque pants and skirts. Sheer skirts and half-skirts topped narrow
pants. The effect was always one of veiling clothes to soften their
look.
</P>
<P>
   Jil Sander, another designer known for fine tailoring and
precisely fitted yet comfortable jackets, chose the casual path for
spring. Her shape of the season was an easy-fitting dress that was
folded, rolled and draped into shape with a smallish bodice and a
pear-shaped skirt.
</P>
<P>
   There were pressed and chintzed cottons, rayon with metallic
threads, rayon and rayon/wool blends and net jacquards. Ensembles
often included several fabrics of the same color _ black, powdery
blue, pale yellow, gray, beige or white. Pieces here and there were
a soft metallic gold.
</P>
<P>
   Alberta Ferretti chose tucking and paint, often used together,
to individualize her soft silhouettes. From straightforward tucks
that defined busts, waists and hips, she moved to random tucks that
created patterns on dresses. Sheaths had bias tucking, with prim
V-necks in front dipping to lower V's at the back.
</P>
<P>
   Colors included khaki, brown, toast, orange-red, blue and black,
and Ferretti loved mixing them, adding a floral sleeveless knit
pale-blue top over brown hip-slung pants with a checkered
waistband.
</P>
<P>
   For evening, tucks either ran vertically on organza dresses or
formed myriad patterns on dresses that resembled origami.
</P>
<P>
   ``Artistic'' is a fine way to describe the Dolce &AMP; Gabbana
collection. Building on the success of their fall/winter designs of
limited-edition painted Mylar and embroidered net dresses, Domenico
Dolce and Stefano Gabbana sent out schools of sardines painted on
long black lacquered silk dresses for spring. The marine theme was
based on Mediterranean aquatic life surrounding Sicily; there were
no prints in the collection. Silvery hologram fabrics were chosen,
Gabbana said at a news conference before the show, because they
reminded the designers of fish scales. Even black lace was pressed
onto latex.
</P>
<P>
   Eighty percent of the fabrics in the collection were treated to
some kind of lacquering, either for shine or texture. And like the
``sensual, sexy lines of fish,'' there was nothing square or
rectangular in the collection.
</P>
<P>
   Jackets were often cut in one piece, with seams only under the
arms and down the sides. The effect was almost of a kimono cut,
more casual than a tailored jacket.
</P>
<P>
   Some pants and jumpsuits were shaped at the knees to make the
garments appear as if they were in motion, even on their hangers.
When jumpsuits and corseted dresses were low-cut, like a bustier,
Dolce and Gabbana added tiny black cardigans that were barely more
than pairs of sleeves.
</P>
<P>
   The Gianni Versace collection is still shaped by the late
designer's sexy, low necklines and clinging skirts and dresses. But
his sister Donatella Versace's designs for spring doted on dresses,
either slithery, silky jerseys for day or long metal mesh or
layered chiffons for evening.
</P>
<P>
   Versace came up lacking, however, if she aimed to reproduce her
brother's emphasis on the female form. While dresses and tops, as
in her earlier Versus line, were often slashed from the collarbone
to the waist, putting half of each breast on view, the result
lacked sensuality. Evening dresses that combined Gianni's signature
metal mesh with some fiber resembling hairy blue or white cotton
candy looked uncomfortable, while the painted, beaded, sequined and
what-have-you-layered chiffons looked like arts-and-crafts
projects.
</P>
<P>
   These were not the fine clothes the Versace label has come to
represent. The lively violet, fuchsia and aquamarine were there
along with ``de rigueur'' black, in materials from nappa leather to
rice fiber. But there was no clear idea of the woman for whom
Donatella is designing. &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXXEND OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-14-98 1421EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
