<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-14 14:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6578 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HIV-INFECTION-HNS &LR;      10-14 0551
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HIV-INFECTION-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EFFORT LAUNCHED TO CUT RATE OF HIV INFECTION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ULYSSES TORASSA  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ While the rate of AIDS deaths nationwide
continues to fall, the rate of new HIV infections has not.
</P>
<P>
   The National Academy of Sciences' Institute of Medicine on
Tuesday issued a report saying HIV testing should be routinely
offered to all pregnant woman as part of prenatal care as a way to
keep the virus from being passed to children. A majority of
pregnant women currently undergo testing, but it is not universal.
</P>
<P>
   And in San Francisco, an ad campaign is being launched to
encourage people who think they may have recently been exposed to
enroll in a ``morning-after'' regimen that aims to rid the body of
the human immunodeficiency virus before it can take root.
</P>
<P>
   AIDS, the acquired immune deficiency syndrome, is an affliction
in which HIV weakens the immune system, subjecting the body to
serious infection. AIDS is most often spread through sexual
contact, sharing contaminated needles and infected blood products.
</P>
<P>
   Drugs are proving successful enough to drastically reduce the
chance of developing an HIV infection, as well as the chance that
an infected mother will pass the virus onto her newborn.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you can prevent an HIV infection, you will have done a
tremendous amount for the person and for the community as a
whole,'' said James Kahn, medical director of the PEP Project, a
joint program of the San Francisco Department of Public Health and
the AIDS Research Institute of the University of California at San
Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   The project offers free HIV drugs for a month, intensive
counselling and education about prevention to people who believe
they were exposed to the virus in the previous 72 hours.
</P>
<P>
   The medicines are the same used by people known to be infected
and are believed to be very effective in preventing HIV from taking
hold in the body, if given promptly.
</P>
<P>
   So far, 225 people have enrolled in the year-old program and no
one has yet tested positive for the virus, Kahn said.
</P>
<P>
   The new ad campaign, targeted at gay men, will appear on city
buses. More explicit posters will be in bar restrooms. They
emphasize that mistakes happen, but if people act quickly the
deadly infection may be avoidable.
</P>
<P>
   The study by the National Academy of Sciences reviewed a
mountain of literature that shows pregnant women treated with AIDS
drugs are far less likely to transmit the virus to their newborns.
</P>
<P>
   While mother-to-child transmission is much less of a problem on
the West Coast than in the East, where IV drug abuse by women is
more prevalent, officials at San Francisco General Hospital have
developed a program that has virtually wiped out the problem among
those they have treated.
</P>
<P>
   In San Francisco, only two infants have been born with HIV in
the past three years, both to mothers who did not seek prenatal
care, according to Karen P. Beckerman, director for the Bay Area
Perinatal AIDS Center at the hospital. That is out of a total of
more than 50 births to HIV-infected women, she said.
</P>
<P>
   She attributed the low rate to testing and follow-up treatment.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been advocating HIV testing for pregnant women for
years,'' she said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
