<P>
   JOURNAL-CHINA _ BEIJING _ Of all the places and people perplexed
by America's preoccupation with the Clinton sex scandal, China and
the Chinese may be the most. It was the foremost topic on the mind
of the first Chinese friend we ran into this week upon our return
from home leave. Zipping through the requisite polite queries as to
vacation and travels, our young friend quickly pounced on the
issue. (Albright/Kunstel, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   EDs: MOVED Tuesday, Oct. 13, in the (i) International and (k)
Commentary categories.
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-YOUNG _ BEIJING _ The Rev. Andrew Young and five other
U.S. church leaders gave China a cautious accolade on Wednesday for
allowing the growth of relatively free Christian worship for 10
million Chinese Protestants. ``We found no sign of religious
repression,'' said Young, appearing here as president-elect of the
National Council of Churches of Christ in the United States. ``Did
we find religious freedom in the U.S. sense? No. But we found no
religious repression or active persecution.'' Developing.
(Kunstel/Albright, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   EDs: To move by 1 p.m. EDT.
</P>
<P>
   YUGOSLAVIA-SCENE _ BELGRADE, Yugoslavia _ You would think that
with the NATO air strikes averted that the Serbs here would be
breathing a sighh of relief. Well, guess again? (Roughton, Cox News
Service).
</P>
<P>
   EDs: To move by 5 p.m. EDT.
</P>
<P>
   US-MIDEAST _ WASHINGTON _ Advance setting up the Middle East
summit meeting that begins Thursday between President Clinton,
Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu and Palestinian National
Authority President Yasser Arafat; and examining the U.S. role; and
expectations. Will top with 4:30 p.m. EDT briefing by U.S. Middle
East envoy Dennis Ross. (Deans, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   EDs: To move by 7:30 p.m. EDT.
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON
</P>
<P>
   SCHOOL-VIOLENCE _ WASHINGTON _ Education Secretary Richard Riley
releases a Clinton administration's report on school violence at
the 1 p.m. EDT White House briefing Wednesday. The report sets up
Thursday's White House conference on school safety. (Monroe, Cox
News Service).
</P>
<P>
   CENTENNIAL _ WASHINGTON _ House today will approve creation and
funding of the centennial of flight commission. this body will
promote and coordinate ceremonies in 2003 recognizing the 100th
anniversary of the Wright's first flight. (Joyce, Dayton Daily
News). 8.
</P>
<P>
   NATION
</P>
<P>
   RUDOLPH _ WASHINGTON _ Feds are supposed to hold a news
conference to announce they are charging Eric Rudolph for the
Atlanta bombs. We will ask how do they know he's not out riding
around and playing games, prosecution strategy, etc. (Scruggs,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   GLENNBOOK _ Short story that announces the book by Sen. John
Glenn, Back In Orbit. (Marcano, Dayton Daily News). 8.
</P>
<P>
   LAKE-OKEECHOBEE _ WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ South Florida water
managers agreed today to study a berm of weeds and muck that is
creating a new wall inside Lake Okeechobee. They are not as alarmed
as game and fish officials, but they do want to study it. Fishermen
fear the wall will separate fish from an area used to raise young
fish. Lake Okeechobee is a major sport and recreational lake in
central south Florida. (King, Palm Beach Post). 8-10. FILE GRAPHIC
AVAILABLE.
</P>
<P>
   MHMR-COMMISH _ The board of the Texas Department of Mental
Health and Mental Retardation is expected to select Karen Hale as
the new commissioner. Hale has been interim commissioner of the
ageny and if chosen will be the first woman to head the agency as
well as the first woman to head a major state agency byhdint of
hard work, not election. She is also making history by being part
of the first Texas couple to head state agencies because her
husband, Bill Hale, is executive director of the Texas Commission
on Human Rights. (Gamino, Austin American-Statesman).
</P>
