<DOCNO> NYT19981014.0151 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-14 14:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6621 &Cx1f; tab-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-SERBIA-BOMBING     10-14 0935
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-SERBIA-BOMBING-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A REPRIEVE BUT NO SOLUTION IN KOSOVO 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (To publish this ``separate buy'' article, it must be purchased
_ the rate is not prohibitive _ from one of these New York Times
Syndicate sales representatives: 
 &HT;    (--U.S., Canada and the Pacific: CONNIE WHITE in Kansas City at
1-800-444-0267 or 816-822-8448, or fax her at 816-822-1444. 
 &HT;    (--Europe and Asia: KARL HORWITZ in Paris at 47-42-17-11; fax,
47-42-80-44 or 47-42-18-81; telex, 282-942. 
 &HT;    (--Latin America: OLIVIA VASQUEZ in Los Angeles, 310-996-0075;
fax, 310-996-0089. 
 &HT;    
 By FLORA LEWIS  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
 &HT;    PARIS _ Of course it is better not to have to bomb Serbia than
to bomb Serbia in the hope of protecting Kosovar civilians.
 &HT;    But the rather vague agreement with Slobodan Milosevic, reached
only after NATO had lined up its planes and voted unanimous
authorization to use them, reflects the illogic of the whole
situation.
 &HT;    This is a bandaid measure, and only wishful thinking can see in
it a definite step toward resolution of the Kosovo problem, as has
been and is still the case with the Dayton solution in Bosnia. It
is better not to let killing continue, not to chase people out of
their homes into the rugged, frigid mountains.
 &HT;    But it isn't a policy or an idea even of how to sustain such
negative gains, let alone something positive, except indefinite
involvement in Bosnia's case of NATO, in Kosovo's case of civilian
monitors and the threat of NATO force.
 &HT;    The Bosnian peacekeeping mission now is costing some $7 billion
a year with no tapering off date on the horizon. Kosovo will be
less expensive, if it works, but it includes heavy responsibility
for humanitarian aid. Nothing has been said about who is to be
responsible for repairing all the deliberately destroyed villages
in the scorched-earth campaign.
 &HT;    The United States and the European powers backed themselves into
this situation without ever having made a clear decision of their
role in ex-Yugoslavia, what they are there to get done, but only
what they desperately hope to prevent continuing once the disaster
got well underway.
 &HT;    Despite all the official talk about not repeating the errors of
Bosnia, there has already been a replay of the dithering and now a
rather frightening renewal of what led to the intolerable seizure
of U.N. hostages in Bosnia.
 &HT;    The dispatch of 2,000 unarmed civilian ``monitors'' to make sure
the Serbs don't keep bashing the ethnic Albanians is to be
reinforced by NATO non-combat reconnaissance planes, both presented
as a big concession from Milosevic in allowing foreign intervention
on Serbian soil. But it was the presence of U.N. troops, armed but
not allowed to shoot unless shot at, that prevented the use of air
power in Bosnia until the United States sent in ground forces. It
could happen again.
 &HT;    There is no logic on Milosevic's side either. He has nothing to
gain by the scorched earth policy. It isn't going to replace 2
million ethnic Albanians with Serbian settlers, it only reinforces
the demand for Kosovar independence because Serbian rule is so
terrifyingly oppressive. Belgrade is simply trying to put down the
guerrilla force, which can have no more than short-term success.
 &HT;    The agreement to hold elections in a year is intriguing, but
opens endless questions. Who will run them? Who will be eligible?
What powers would the elected body have? If Milosevic really wanted
out of the box he has created for himself in Kosovo, this could be
a way to go but it isn't at all likely. The signs are that all he
wants is to cling to power as long as possible. Then what? He
doesn't seem to care.
 &HT;    There is a great, frustrating gap here between what the parties
involved would like to do and what they have to do it with. The
United Nations and NATO have imposed a painful embargo on Serbia,
which also hurts neighboring countries, but has only served as a
punishment, not as a deterrent. They can bomb, but destroying the
essentially irrelevant military targets provides no leverage on
political goals.
 &HT;    Some significant Serbian military and police will remain in
Kosovo because if they did pull out, independence would be quickly
proclaimed. But how and how much they will actually be constrained
by the presence of international monitors remains to be seen.
Friction, perhaps renewed crisis, may be unavoidable.
 &HT;    There is no available answer that would assure better results
and that the countries involved could agree on. It is already
remarkable that 15 NATO countries did agree, despite loud
objections from Russia. Outside factors, having nothing to do with
the Balkans, could change the atmosphere at another point.
 &HT;    Toying with the idea of keeping the peace, or at least stopping
war, without really being determined to do it inevitably leaves
this kind of dilemma that we aren't prepared to face but cannot
ignore.
 &HT;    It matters at least to be aware of these obstacles and not to be
misled by claim of diplomatic triumph, to be followed by dismay.
The world has changed some, in its disapproval of violence and
sense of a minimal responsibility to protect innocent civilians.
But there is no collective decision as to how far the world's
citizens want to go to protect other countries in need.
 &HT;    Instead of pretending a success, let us admit that and hope to
do better.
 &HT;     (Flora Lewis is the former foreign-affairs columnist for The
New York Times.) 
 &HT;     c.1998 Flora Lewis 
