<HEADER>
A6623 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AUTHOR-WILLIAMS-BOS &LR;      10-14 0926
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUTHOR-WILLIAMS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR THURGOOD MARSHALL, THE SUPREME COURT WAS THE EPILOGUE
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK FEENEY  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Who knows why Thurgood Marshall finally said yes? Supreme Court
justices rarely grant interviews, and Marshall, a man much scarred
by half a century of legal and racial battle, was more reticent
than most.
</P>
<P>
   Juan Williams, now 44, had been after Marshall to talk to him
for years. The letters had started when Williams, whose career at
The Washington Post had included tours as editorial board member
and White House correspondent, was at work on the book that
accompanied the award-winning 1987 PBS history of the civil rights
movement, ``Eyes on the Prize.'' Marshall finally agreed to talk in
July 1989, 3 1/2 years before his death.
</P>
<P>
   Marshall had long since ceased to be a flesh-and-blood
character. He had become a symbol _ and a caricature.
</P>
<P>
   The symbol was a civil-rights legend, the first black Supreme
Court justice. The caricature was a grumpy old man, ``out of sorts
and out of step,'' in Williams's words.
</P>
<P>
   Once a week, usually on a Wednesday or Thursday, Williams would
visit Marshall's chambers. Their sessions took place over the
course of the next six months. They'd last a couple of hours.
``He'd kick me out around lunchtime, when he'd have his soup,''
Williams recalled on a recent visit to Boston to promote his new
biography, ``Thurgood Marshall: American Revolutionary.''
</P>
<P>
   The tape recorder was on _ and Marshall would be off. Williams
was discovering that the man frequently described as the most
important lawyer (black, white, or otherwise) in 20th-century US
history was also one of its best storytellers. ``Oftentimes, it
felt like I was up to see the wizard and getting behind the curtain
and peeking,'' Williams said.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was able to tell me stories that made me feel as if I was
doing time travel. This was a guy who went to high school with Cab
Calloway, the singer, then he goes to college with Langston Hughes.
When he gets his first job in New York at the NAACP Legal Defense
Fund, his office is next to W.E.B. DuBois's. He's in Asia
confronting Douglas MacArthur over the treatment of black soldiers.
Branch Rickey calls him up to help with Jackie Robinson's finances.
I'd find myself saying, `Did you really know all those people?'
</P>
<P>
   ``He was there at Joe Louis fights. He remembers as a kid
watching Marcus Garvey's marches through Harlem. It's just
unbelievable that he touched so many other lives. In fact, I've
come to think it may be a function of segregation: that black
people were so concentrated back then they all knew each other.''
</P>
<P>
   It was Marshall who did more, perhaps, than any other individual
to end that era of racial separation. He masterminded the series of
court challenges to segregation that culminated in the Supreme
Court's landmark 1954 ruling in Brown v. Board of Education.
Marshall argued Brown himself, one of 32 cases he presented before
the court. He won 29 of them. He went on to become the second black
to serve as a federal Appeals Court judge and the first to serve as
solicitor general, before being named an associate justice of the
high court in 1967.
</P>
<P>
   In many ways, the period between 1967 and 1991, when he retired
from the court, was an epilogue to Marshall's career, not its
highlight. Williams devotes barely a seventh of his text to the
court years.
</P>
<P>
   ``You ask most people about Thurgood Marshall, they'll say, `Oh
yeah, Supreme Court.' Well, I think that's the biggest mistake.
President Johnson said this when he nominating Marshall to the
court: `Even if he were never elevated to the court, this is a man
who has made his mark on American history.' I think lots of people
forget that, especially the young brothers. They say, `Oh, he's the
old guy in the black robes.' A lot of people think of him as a
token, a Tom, and they didn't give Marshall much credit. So then
they see him in his later years, he's fat, he's got the big robes,
he's an establishment figure.''
</P>
<P>
   Williams got to know a man who had a robustly ribald sense of
humor and enjoyed the company of attractive women. He loved to play
cards and knew how to open a bottle. But he was also a man who felt
a world of hurt at being misunderstood by the post-segregation
America he had helped to create.
</P>
<P>
   ``He felt unappreciated by black Americans, which is a real
surprise. But if you think about it from his perspective: They're
making movies about Malcolm X, they got a holiday for Martin Luther
King. He's thinking, `I don't get it.'''
</P>
<P>
   For his book, Williams interviewed 10 present or retired
justices. Even in Marshall's later years, when the court had
shifted far from his liberal views, he continued to exert a moral
force on the court, a fact most clearly perceived by his fellow
justices, including his staunchest adversary.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was the one Supreme Court justice who'd represented people
on Death Row, who knew the reality of what a back-alley abortion
was, who'd had to go into prisons where people weren't getting
their appeals heard. He'd had those experiences and he could bring
that to the table. You know, Justice (Antonin) Scalia said to me _
and, remember, he was Marshall's ideological opposite _ `Anytime
you're in conference and Thurgood Marshall was sitting there at the
table you had to pay attention, knowing all he had done in civil
rights and the law. Even if he didn't say anything, he made a
difference just by sitting there at the conference.'''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-14-98 1436EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981014.0154 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-14 14:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6625 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LOBSTERS-MAINE-BOS &LR;      10-14 0736
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LOBSTERS-MAINE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAINE LOBSTER ILLNESS TAKES $2 MILLION TOLL
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER J. HOWE  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   An apparently growing number of lobsters are being found sick
and dead in traps and pounds off the Maine coast, mystifying
researchers who cannot yet determine the cause and worrying
lobstermen who fear for their industry's future.
</P>
<P>
   So far this year, more than $2 million worth of lobster have
been ruined by the plague, which seems to involve several strains
of bacteria infecting the normally hardy crustaceans.
</P>
<P>
   ``We know that lobsters are dying, but we don't know what's
going on precisely,'' said Robert Bayer, director of the Lobster
Institute at the University of Maine, who has organized a team of
researchers to attack the problem, which has been reported all
along the coast from York to Beals Island.
</P>
<P>
   ``It seems to have gotten worse in the last month, based on the
phone calls that we are getting from fishermen,'' Bayer said. ``We
were hoping it would go away, but instead, it seems to be getting
worse.''
</P>
<P>
   That worries lobstermen, not only because the problem is eating
into their $130 million annual revenues, but because they fear if
the public misunderstands the problem, it could drive people away
from eating Maine lobsters.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are scared the word will get out and ruin the lobster
industry,'' said one veteran Maine lobsterman who works a boat with
his son and asked not to be named. Some lobstermen have reported
hauling in a dozen dead or diseased lobsters a day.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Brown of the Maine Import/Export Lobster Dealers
Association said: ``We're concerned. This is big money.'' Maine
brings in an estimated one-quarter of all lobsters harvested in the
United States and Canada, more than 45 million pounds last year.
</P>
<P>
   Bayer and other specialists emphasized that the issue is not a
public health problem: Dead and sick lobsters are thrown out before
ever reaching fish markets, and any bacteria present in healthy
lobsters will be killed when they are boiled.
</P>
<P>
   ``The lobsters that are going to market are fine, and I would
eat them every night if I could afford to,'' Bayer said. ``It's not
a human health problem, but we know it's not going to be perceived
well by the public.''
</P>
<P>
   Bruce Estrella, Massachusetts state shellfish biologist, said
last week he had heard of the situation in Maine and understood it
to be a recent flareup of a longstanding, low-level problem of
infections that spread in pounds, where lobsters are stored so
dealers can sell them fresh when prices are high. Estrella said
there have been no reports of any similar outbreaks in
Massachusetts.
</P>
<P>
   A number of dead and sick lobsters were reported in Maine's Down
East coast last year, but the problem seemed to wane over the
spring and summer. In the last two months, however, lobstermen
working closer to the mid-coast and Casco Bay regions have reported
growing losses, Bayer said.
</P>
<P>
   Maya Crosby, a University of Maine microbiologist working with
Bayer and others, said several different bacteria have been found
in lobsters tested at the university's Darling Center in Walpole,
and the laboratory is seeking more samples of sick lobsters to
test.
</P>
<P>
   However, Crosby said, ``We've concluded that it's a secondary
infection, an opportunistic invader'' of lobsters that are being
weakened by some other, as yet unknown cause. ``We need to
understand the primary cause of the problem,'' Crosby said.
</P>
<P>
   Crosby and Bayer said scientists are far from having a working
hypothesis. Explanations such as rising sea-water temperatures have
been floated. Researchers are plotting the reported lobster deaths
and sickness on a map to see if there are any geographical trends.
</P>
<P>
   Tissue and blood samples from affected lobsters are also being
analyzed by researchers at the University of New Hampshire and
government biologists in Maine and New Brunswick.
</P>
<P>
   The outbreak has prompted the state to set up a Lobster Health
Hotline, 1-888-317-4666. Pat White of the Maine Lobstermen's
Association said the group is urging members to report any problems
they find rather than try to hush them up.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got to feed them as much information as possible.
They're the detectives,'' White said. ``We've got to get this down
to factual stuff.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Material from the Associated Press was used in this report.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
