<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-14 14:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6634 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DEPORT-TEXAS-BOS &LR;      10-14 1403
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DEPORT-TEXAS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOME LONGTIME US RESIDENTS FACE DEPORTATION FOR DRUNDEN DRIVING
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID L. MARCUS  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SOCORRO, Texas _ By almost every measure, David Balderrama is a
model immigrant: He worked in a sheet metal factory by day, fixed
houses by night, paid his taxes promptly every year, and then
retired to spend time with his family.
</P>
<P>
   But Balderrama also got behind the wheel of his pickup truck
after drinking beer with his relatives and union buddies. From 1988
to 1993, the police caught him driving drunk three times.
</P>
<P>
   That was one time too many for the US immigration service. On
Sept. 3, agents and police brandishing revolvers showed up at
Balderrama's adobe house. They announced that the 68-year-old
great-grandfather would be deported to Mexico, the country he left
42 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Balderrama is one of more than 500 people, most of them Mexican
laborers, who were rounded up by immigration agents in Texas and
threatened with deportation last month. The crackdown ensued when
the immigration service decided to enforce a little-known law
passed by Congress in 1996. It says that any non-citizen who has
committed an aggravated felony _ a violent crime, in other words _
can be deported.
</P>
<P>
   And in Texas, which led the nation last year in alcohol-related
driving deaths, three counts of drunken driving are considered an
aggravated felony.
</P>
<P>
   The roundup has led to charges of discrimination because most of
those targeted were poor men in the barrios of border cities, not
professionals in ritzy neighborhoods of Dallas or Austin. And
though immigration laws are supposed to be applied uniformly
throughout the country, the Immigration and Naturalization Service
has not gone after habitual drunk drivers in other states.
</P>
<P>
   ``Drinking and driving is a serious offense, but you can't
compare it to murder, rape, or drug dealing,'' said Balderrama's
youngest son, Mario, 32, who works as an environmental inspector
for the state. ``My dad hasn't hurt anybody and he has never been
involved in any kind of accident.''
</P>
<P>
   Said another son, Joe, 36, ``The federal government is picking
and choosing when to apply the law. ... What they're doing seems to
us to be based on race and who has political power.''
</P>
<P>
   Sitting in the house where he raised eight children, David
Balderrama is stoical. He is waiting for a deportation hearing in
nearby El Paso next month, and he'll see what happens. In the worst
case, he is prepared to move back to his birthplace in Chihuahua,
Mexico, a four-hour drive to the south.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not an outlaw,'' he said in Spanish. ``If they want to
throw me out of the country, I won't fight them. But they don't
have to storm my house and scare my family.''
</P>
<P>
   Balderrama's lawyer, Albert Aramandariz, is working with other
immigration lawyers to show that the DWI rule punishes those who
have already paid fines and gone through court-ordered
rehabilitation programs. The deportations will needlessly break
apart families and leave fatherless children with no option but
welfare, the lawyers say.
</P>
<P>
   The immigration service, expecting criticism, sought the support
of community groups such as Mothers Against Drunk Driving (MADD).
Those organizations say the crackdown has nothing to do with
ethnicity. ``If someone is deported, his family still has the
opportunity to get together, even if it's in another land,'' said
Dale Chavez, administrator of the MADD chapter in El Paso. ``But if
he kills somebody, then the victim's family can only get together
at the graveyard.''
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday night, two dozen anxious families met in a community
center in downtown El Paso, just a few blocks from the Mexican
border. Everyone had a father, brother, or uncle who was rounded up
in ``Operation Last Call,'' as the immigration service dubbed the
crackdown.
</P>
<P>
   While children played ping-pong, the parents spoke of their
fears. Marta Oliva said her husband, Joel Vargas, faithfully pays
child support for his three teenage children from a first marriage.
``If Joel is deported, who is going to pay those bills?'' Jesus
Marquez, a carpenter who has been arrested for DWI six times, said
he has stayed off alcohol for a year, thanks to a court-ordered
treatment program. ``I've never been in an accident, and now I'm
clean,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Carlos Spector, the lawyer who organized the families, says
statistics show that the immigration service is unfair. In the
roundup, 116 people have been arrested in El Paso and 101 in
Harlingen, another poor town. Yet only 76 were arrested in San
Antonio and none in Austin _ both cities where the Hispanic middle
class has political clout.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is an outrageous, ridiculous enforcement measure,'' said
Jeanne Butterfield, executive director of the American Immigration
Lawyers Association in Washington. Many of those arrested had DWI
offenses dating back to the 1970s and '80s, but the 1996 law is
retroactive, she said.
</P>
<P>
   At the Immigration and Naturalization Service office in El Paso,
spokeswoman Theresa Barraza said agents worked with the sheriff's
office and local police to find repeat DWI offenders. ``We didn't
single out Hispanics,'' Barraza said. ``We're on the border, and
the majority of the immigrants come from Mexico.''
</P>
<P>
   David and Marina Balderrama crossed the border into Texas in
1956 with their infant daughter, Lucy. They handed in their
documents and became legal residents. ``We were not mojados,''
Marina Balderrama pointed out, using the word for ``wetbacks.''
</P>
<P>
   The Balderramas had seven more children, all born in the United
States. David Jr. served in the Army's 82d Airborne Division.
George is the owner of a sheet metal company. Patsy works in a
hospital. Joe is a sheet metal worker. Peter is a produce manager
in a grocery store. Mario works for the state natural resources
department. All graduated from high school. Maritza, the youngest,
went on to college and is now working toward a master's degree.
</P>
<P>
   The children shared a single room until 1970, when the whole
family pitched in and built an addition to the house. David was a
loving and strict father who insisted that every child over age 5
help clean the house and do the dishes and the laundry. He used to
say, ``Do good in your job because your work represents who you
are,'' Joe remembers.
</P>
<P>
   For his three DWI arrests _ in 1988, 1992, and 1993 _ David
Balderrama pleaded guilty. If he had known that the three pleas
would haunt him in his old age, he might have requested a jury
trial, his family says. By the time David got around to applying
for American citizenship a few years ago, he was rejected. His
family blames the drunken-driving arrests.
</P>
<P>
   ``The children are grown up and it's just the two of us left
here,'' said Marina Balderrama as she sat inside the house, which
is adorned wih porcelain figurines and photos of her 22
grandchildren and one great-grandchild. ``I have diabetes and
sometimes I have to go to the emergency room. Who is going to take
me?''
</P>
<P>
   David Balderrama says Alcoholics Anonymous sessions taught him
the gravity of drinking and driving. In his carport is a broken red
Chevy pickup with a bumper sticker that speaks to another time. ``I
don't have a drinking problem. I drink. I get drunk. I fall down.
No problem!'' it says.
</P>
<P>
   Balderrama's family agrees that drunken driving is a serious
offense. ``Since I became a father, it's always been, `DWI? Get
them off the street, take their license away,''' Joe said. But he
wonders if his father would be threatened with deportation if he
were a European immigrant, not a retired sheet metal worker from
Chihuahua.
</P>
<P>
   A few miles away, at the MADD office, volunteers update a set of
statistics every month. So far this year, the tally shows, El Paso
police have arrested 2,514 people for drunken driving. The city has
had 42 traffic fatalities this year; 18 involved alcohol.
</P>
<P>
   Maria Molina knows that drunk drivers are equal opportunity
killers. Her son, Mark Anthony, was 21 and serving in the Navy when
he was killed by a drunk driver.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone who comes to this country should obey the laws or
suffer the consequences,'' said Molina. ``If you are caught driving
drunk once or twice and you don't learn from that, why would you
learn the next time? Do you learn the fourth time? Or do you have
to kill or injure someone first?''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
