<HEADER>
A6649 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCHOOL-UNIFORMS-HNS &LR;      10-14 0732
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCHOOL-UNIFORMS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEXAS DISTRICT ASKS FEDERAL COURT TO HEAR SCHOOL UNIFORM LAWSUIT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JEANNE RUSSELL  
 c.1998 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   EAGLE PASS, Texas _ Lawyers for the city school district, the
first in Texas to require students to wear uniforms, have asked
that a lawsuit challenging the fairness of the khaki-and-white
outfits be moved to federal court.
</P>
<P>
   Eagle Pass School District officials are accused of allowing
children of politically connected parents to opt out of the uniform
requirement.
</P>
<P>
   A state court hearing on the issue was canceled Tuesday when
school attorneys requested that the case be moved to federal
jurisdiction, where a separate lawsuit challenges the
constitutionality of the uniform requirement.
</P>
<P>
   Whether the two lawsuits are consolidated or are heard
separately, the courtroom bouts are sure to be watched closely by
school administrators in other cities where uniforms now are the
rule.
</P>
<P>
   ``First you need to define whether it's a constitutional right
to determine what you wear to school,'' said Oscar Trevino, an
Austin attorney representing the district.
</P>
<P>
   Eagle Pass attorney David Riojas, representing 13 parents, said
he planned to ask the federal court to return the lawsuit to the
state court.
</P>
<P>
   ``All of my claims are state law claims. They have nothing to do
with the federal courts, federal laws or federal statutes,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   The courts also may need to resolve the meaning of a 1995 Texas
law allowing school districts to grant uniform waivers for ``a bona
fide religious or philosophic objection.''
</P>
<P>
   This is where parents of children who were denied waivers say
politics stained the Eagle Pass khaki and white.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not against the uniform policy in itself. We're just
against the dirty way in which they were granted,'' said Juanita
Martinez, a district employee and mother of twin girls.
</P>
<P>
   A year ago, Eagle Pass became the first Texas school district to
adopt a mandatory uniform policy. School board trustees heralded
the outfits as the key to fewer fights, better attendance and
savings for financially strapped parents in this border city 140
miles southwest of San Antonio.
</P>
<P>
   About 97 percent of the district's 10,200 students complied with
the uniform requirement, district officials estimate. And support
remains, including a grandfather who stopped off at the courthouse
to call the uniforms the greatest thing ever for poor children.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, about 338 students received waivers. Another 119
requests submitted late were denied.
</P>
<P>
   This year, the school board reviewed each waiver request and
granted 51 of a total of 432 submitted.
</P>
<P>
   The lawsuit over fairness alleges the board rejected waivers
worded identically to those granted.
</P>
<P>
   School officials say they sought to draw a tough line so as not
to erode the effectiveness of the uniform.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you look down the road, if you continue to have that many
people, high school kids basically, asking for a waiver, pretty
soon you'll have no one wearing the uniform,'' district spokeswoman
Johnnie Lee Gonzalez said.
</P>
<P>
   The fairness issue resonated at the district's high school
campus, where most students shed their uniforms when State District
Judge Ray Perez issued a temporary restraining order last week that
puts the uniform policy on hold.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, the Eagle Pass superintendent asked parents and
students to continue to voluntarily comply with the uniform policy.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's all about politics here in Eagle Pass,'' said Eagle Pass
High School junior Danny Hernandez, taking a lunch break on the
school steps Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``People get the waivers because they know people,'' Hernandez
said.
</P>
<P>
   Parents said political and school leaders have received waivers
for their children.
</P>
<P>
   Trevino said he only knew of a waiver given to former school
board member Marcial Reyes.
</P>
<P>
   ``They should either make everybody wear the uniforms or
nobody,'' Alejandra Barreto, 16, said.
</P>
<P>
   The teens complained of detention and in-school suspension for
refusing to wear or being out of uniform.
</P>
<P>
   Parent Rafael Hernandez Jr. said he had taken to eating lunch
with his kindergarten son Rafael because the boy was separated from
students as punishment for not wearing a uniform.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's 5-years-old and he's being treated like a criminal,''
Hernandez said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
