NYT-10-14-98 1450EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981014.0160 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-14 14:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6650 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PLANE-SAFETY-BOS &LR;      10-14 1412
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PLANE-SAFETY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HIS SECOND STARTUP EXPECTED TO ENHANCE SMALL-PLANE SAFETY
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JERRY ACKERMAN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LEXINGTON, Mass. _ Dan Schwinn already was courting a new love
long before he said goodbye to Shiva Corp., the pioneering computer
networking company he helped start when he was just two years out
of college.
</P>
<P>
   That love was flying, and last week, Schwinn, now 37 and three
years removed from Shiva, put on display the outcome of this
romance _ an electronic aircraft navigational device &UR;  &LR; that gives
small airplanes some of the same high-tech safety features big jets
have enjoyed for years.
</P>
<P>
   Called a Flight Situation Display, or FSD, the device is the
product of Avidyne Corp., a company Schwinn incorporated in 1993,
as he was getting ready to exit Shiva. At the time, he said he got
more pleasure out of starting a company than running one.
</P>
<P>
   Shiva was a leader in introducing telecommuting to the world,
with its software that let remote computers connect over telephone
lines with the mainframe at corporate headquarters.
</P>
<P>
   The company, which is still in business but has shifted to
encryption software, went public in 1994. Investor demand doubled
Shiva's share price on its first trading day. Schwinn and Frank
Slaughter 3d, his partner in launching Shiva in 1985 _ both were 24
and just two years out of the Massachusetts Institute of Technology
_ were rich overnight.
</P>
<P>
   Schwinn wouldn't say how much he ultimately netted from his 18
percent share in Shiva before selling the last of those shares
about a year and a half ago. But of those proceeds, almost $6
million has gone into Avidyne, he said. He expects to personally
invest more, while also recruiting outside investment.
</P>
<P>
   Avidyne's product is a shoebox-sized unit that fits into the
instrument panel of a small airplane and displays flight
information in a way that was never available to &UR;  &LR; small-plane
pilots.
</P>
<P>
   Push a button and its multicolor flat-panel screen shows a map
of where the plane has been and where it is heading. The map image
crawls slowly across the screen as the plane flies on, synchronized
by signals from global positioning satellites circling the Earth
overhead.
</P>
<P>
   Push another button and the screen shows the same information in
a form suited for flying when visibility is too low for ``visual
flight rules.'' Another button pops up data about weather ahead.
Another identifies thunderstorms. Another tells how far and which
way to the nearest airport.
</P>
<P>
   The FSD is based on personal computer technology, using Windows
NT hardware and software. Sized to fit into crowded cockpits, it
has a base price of $7,500, plus software at around $1,000 per
function. Installation starts at around $3,000.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; if,,.3l &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Schwinn sees a big market among owners of the nearly 230,000
private and corporate aircraft now flying in the United States _
almost all of which depend on dials and gauges that sometimes date
back to the Korean War.
</P>
<P>
   About 100 units have been sold so far, Schwinn said. Three
manufacturers of private planes have agreed to offer Avidyne units
as optional equipment on new aircraft beginning next year, Schwinn
adds.
</P>
<P>
   The Avidyne FSD, which promises pilots a new view of the skies,
also offers a peek at how Schwinn, who in his final days at Shiva
admitted dislike for executive life, looks now at doing business.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; Interviewed inside a hangar at Hanscom Field in Bedford,
Schwinn was casually dressed in a blue short-sleeved knit shirt,
khaki trousers, moccasins and no socks. Rain had spoiled his plan
to take writers and photographers aloft in his own 1980-model
Mooney single-engine plane. But that allowed time to talk about
Avidyne's history and goals, linking them with lessons he learned
in building Shiva.
</P>
<P>
   Schwinn said he finds satisfaction in making tangible products
that are sold directly to consumers, after a previous life spent
developing software that &UR;  &LR; was incorporated into other applications.
</P>
<P>
   Building products, he emphasized, means that ``you have to think
about making your customer happy.'' He continued, ``We did a lousy
job at that in the early days of Shiva. Now I say, whatever you
have to do to make the guy happy, do.''
</P>
<P>
   He said Avidyne's goal is to be ``a company that manufactures a
technologically advanced product that satisfies real customers and
makes real profits, we hope, while doing it.''
</P>
<P>
   He contrasts this with the emphasis high-tech entrepreneurs are
putting on Internet applications _ observing that enticing venture
capital sources to invest in Avidyne may be difficult because ``a
lot of them are so focused on the Internet. We're a solid business,
but we're not a go-go company.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I like to try things that are new and different,'' he added.
Schwinn's turn to aviation stems from a boyhood dream that he might
someday be a pilot. That hope was renewed at MIT, where as a
freshman he applied for the Air Force Reserve Officer Training
Program _ only to be turned away because of his vision.
</P>
<P>
   Then, in 1987, two years after he and Slaughter founded Shiva
but before real growth began, Schwinn began flying lessons at
Hanscom.
</P>
<P>
   Winning his pilot's license that year, he began to see, while
flying to Florida or the Bahamas on vacations, how different his
instrument panel was from those that he would see through the
cockpit doorway when boarding a big jet.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know how to build technology-based devices and I couldn't
understand why some of what I saw was so primitive,'' he said.
``Why doesn't this other stuff exist for light planes?''
</P>
<P>
   Schwinn incorporated Avidyne in mid-1993, and from then on was
intent mostly on hiring a successor as Shiva's chief executive so
he could move on. Frank Ingari, from Lotus Development Corp., took
the job in September that year and Schwinn retreated to serving
only as Shiva's chairman.
</P>
<P>
   In July 1995, he quit that post, too, to spend full-time on
Avidyne. He hired a small group of programmers to develop the
product. Progress was slow because avionics software must meet
exacting Federal Aviation Administration rules. This took 2 1/2
years, Schwinn said, twice as long as he had expected. Out of that
experience, though, came an unexpected and perhaps profitable
collateral benefit _ specialized software that puts the FAA's
voluminous regulations into programming language. Avidyne has
applied for a patent on the software and hopes to sell it.
</P>
<P>
   Pilots who have tried the FDS, which has a liquid crystal screen
just a little bigger than a playing card, say they like it. Stunt
pilot Michael Goulian, who teaches flying at Hanscom, points out
that its moving map means that pilots no longer have to use
cumbersome large paper maps while in flight. &UR;  &LR;  Aaron Galvin, a
retired business executive who spends summers in Cambridge and
winters in Florida, says he owns the first Avidyne FSD sold. His
favorite feature is the constant display of numbers indicating
distance and direction to the nearest airport.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you get in trouble you can just look at it. If you know the
magnetic direction and the distance, you can get there damn fast,''
Galvin said.
</P>
<P>
   Additional software, due out next year, will offer more
in-cockpit views _ of the terrain below, of aircraft in surrounding
airspace, and same-screen display of radar readings.
</P>
<P>
   Avidyne sold its first units in August 1997. Predictably,
initial sales were slow. Revenues for all of 1997 were about
$400,000, Schwinn said. Sales for the first nine months of this
year reached $800,000, he said, and Avidyne expects to end the year
with total revenues of about $1.6 million.
</P>
<P>
   While breaking new ground, Avidyne is not alone. The Aircraft
Electronics Association, based in Missouri, says eight other
companies now offer instrument-panel display units for private
aircraft.
</P>
<P>
   Schwinn said &UR;  &LR;  Avidyne's plan is to ward off direct competition
by licensing its technology to others _ an arrangement borrowed
from the the computer industry. At the same time, Avidyne would
continue to sell under its own name. Its units now are made under
contract by Electronic Designs Inc., of Westborough.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to take us 18 months,'' Schwinn said, to build the
arrangements he envisions.
</P>
<P>
   Accustomed to fast turnarounds in the computer industry, he
said, ``that seems like a long time. But I guess in the auto
industry it takes five years to get a car out.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
