<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-14 14:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6658 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PROFILE-SEIDMAN-BOS &LR;      10-14 1604
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PROFILE-SEIDMAN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SEIDMAN, WHO CONTAINED US BANKING CRISIS, REFLECTS ON JAPAN
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KIMBERLY BLANTON  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NANTUCKET, Mass. _ The man who was an instigator of Japan's bank
rescue proposal removes the black cap from his freckled, bald head.
He reads aloud the large button pinned to the cap: ``Lifetime
Permit (NU)318 for taking shellfish and eels.''
</P>
<P>
   L. William Seidman finds time for clam digging in September as
summer winds warm Nantucket's beaches, time he did not have a
decade ago. As chairman of the Federal Deposit Insurance Corp. and
the Resolution Trust Corp. until 1991, he closed an astonishing
1,000 financial institutions, containing a banking disaster that
had engulfed Texas, flared in New England, and threatened to spread
around the country.
</P>
<P>
   Now Seidman has discovered his unique expertise is in high
demand halfway around the world. The man who probably knows more
than anyone about fixing insolvent banks is advising Japanese
business and political leaders on how to solve the biggest banking
problem ever encountered: a banking system steeped in up to $1
trillion of bad loans, a system that is at the center of a global
financial crisis.
</P>
<P>
   The harsh prescriptions Seidman laid out for Japanese leaders
will be a test of whether a US-style bailout can solve a financial
quagmire in a country with vastly different business mores.
</P>
<P>
   Seidman, a former Naval officer who fought in the Pacific during
World War II, spoke bluntly to lawmakers in a country known for its
understatement: Japan must quickly find a solution to the financial
crisis saddling the second-biggest economy _ and the world economy.
</P>
<P>
   ``I said, `Take back the message the world is going to be very
upset if you don't get started for two years,''' Seidman recalls
saying.
</P>
<P>
   Revealing some impatience with Japan's slow progress, Seidman,
who served as assistant for economic affairs under President Ford,
believes that tough measures _ Japan calls his solutions a ``hard
landing'' _ are long past due.
</P>
<P>
   ``They clearly won't be able to get their economy going until
their banking situation is on a viable basis,'' Seidman says,
looking out at Nantucket Harbor from the rooftop deck of his
vacation home, which was built by a seaman in 1830.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, Seidman is in no way singularly responsible for the
bill now being arduously crafted in Japan. The gargantuan plan has
been labored over for months inside Japan's legislature, the Diet.
A remedy was urged on by Federal Reserve chairman Alan Greenspan
and was partly shaped by dozens of advisers, including people like
Robert Glauber, a professor at Harvard University's Kennedy School
of Government who helped draft legislation to bail out US savings
and loans.
</P>
<P>
   Though Japan has yet to enact it's own legislation, warring
factions made progress last week in lurching toward a compromise.
The proposals advocated by Seidman in June are the heart of the
fight between an intransigent Liberal Democratic Party seeking to
protect a business elite with much to lose, and opposition parties
in the Diet pressing for tough solutions.
</P>
<P>
   Invited to Tokyo last summer, Seidman laid out his plan to Diet
members, the central bank governor, and Ministry of Finance
officials just days before US Deputy Treasury Secretary Lawrence
Summers would arrive.
</P>
<P>
   When Seidman gave a speech to key LDP members in the Diet,
``people listened. The LDP drafted a law after the speech. He
helped the process,'' says Seidman's host and client in Tokyo, Iwao
Tomita, the influential founder of Deloitte Touche Tohematsu, a
large Tokyo accounting and consulting firm affiliated with the US
firm Deloitte &AMP; Touche.
</P>
<P>
   When he retired from government, the lively Seidman apparently
could not stop working. At age 77, he is a paid business
commentator for the CNBC cable network in Washington, his primary
residence. He wrote a book, ``Full Faith and Credit: The Great S&AMP;L
Debacle and Other Washington Sagas.''
</P>
<P>
   He cares for his wife, Sally, who requires intensive physical
rehabilitation after hitting her head in a fall two years ago.
Seidman, one-time dean of the business school at Arizona State
University in Tempe, also raises cattle on his ranch in the
foothills of the Sangre de Cristo mountains of New Mexico. And he
is in contact with six children, who live in California, New
Mexico, Nebraska, and Vermont _ and 11 grandchildren.
</P>
<P>
   His June visit to Tokyo was not his first to Japan and won't be
his last _ he was invited to give a speech there in December.  &UR;  &LR; In
September, he went to China, where he discussed reform of the
state-controlled banking industry &UR;  &LR; with top government officials.
</P>
<P>
   Tomita, a prominent Japanese businessman with high-level
connections _ he arranged Seidman's meeting with his high school
classmate, Bank of Japan governor Masaru Hayami _ is known as a
crusader for American-style accounting standards for Japanese
business. He credits Seidman as being a forceful ally in persuading
key government officials that the only way to deal with the problem
was through a ``hard landing.''
</P>
<P>
   That means writing off bad loans, forcing weak banks to raise
capital on their own, and closing insolvent banks that threaten the
entire system. It is a solution that runs counter to the Japanese
system of cozy business relationships and subsidies to businesses
in trouble.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; But Seidman's plan worked in the United States and became a
model for rescues that put the safety of a nation's deposits first.
Seidman ``is very well respected'' in Japan, says Richard Katz,
senior editor of Oriental Economist Report, who recently completed
a book, ``Japan: The System That Soured.''
</P>
<P>
   Upon arriving in Tokyo, Seidman says, he presented a five-part
plan to Diet members, the central bank governor, and Ministry of
Finance officials: establish an independent regulatory agency to
supervise banks; establish a separate agency to oversee the
bailout; establish an RTC-like agency solely to sell property
seized from failed banks to recoup the bailout costs; force weak
banks to raise capital in the public market; close insolvent banks
and nationalize them under a so-called ``bridge bank'' to ensure an
orderly transition while regulators go about the messy task of
cleaning up the books.
</P>
<P>
   A day after Summers and Japanese officials held a press
conference in which the officials vowed to act decisively, the
language of Seidman's FDIC began seeping into news reports out of
Tokyo: ``Japan Plans Bridge Bank for Failed Lenders,'' said a June
22 article in The Wall Street Journal.
</P>
<P>
   Seidman, a Republican appointed FDIC chairman by President
Reagan in 1985 (four years later, Congress appointed him to head
the RTC after creating the agency), is sympathetic to the
difficulties Japanese officials face. The bailouts of US savings
and loans cost US taxpayers $200 billion, though much of that was
recouped through the government's sale of real estate held by the
thrifts.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; cl10.8 &LR;
</P>
<P>
   The heated battles among the Japanese over who should pay _
taxpayers or bank shareholders or businesses _ is ``all part of the
process of democracy,'' Seidman says.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, Seidman's cool professionalism in handling US banking
problems enraged just about everyone with an interest in the
industry. With each bank closing, he choked off credit to wealthy
or influential customers. He angered taxpayers who complained he
spent too much. And he infuriated shareholders stripped of their
bank stocks.
</P>
<P>
   The failure of Japanese banks, too, would hurt deeply entrenched
political interests, especially in the powerful agricultural and
construction industries there. By its nature, the plan is an attack
on Japan's ``convoy'' system of doing business: Government and
corporations help and subsidize one another.
</P>
<P>
   In Japan, ``90 percent of the problem is political,'' explains
Jean Kertudo, head of financial analysis for the Bank of
International Settlements, which monitors lending among countries.
</P>
<P>
   As Tomita describes bank politics, ``the Ministry of Finance
tried to protect every weak bank. But (there are) so many weak
banks now (Japan) cannot afford to finance them all. That's why
Seidman said hard landing, not soft landing.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Japan's problems deepen. One of the country's largest
financial institutions, Long-Term Credit Bank, may be insolvent. A
report by Nomura Securities found that the 19 largest banks in
fiscal 1997 reported losses on bad loans of nearly 10.5 trillion
yen, or about $88 billion at current exchange rates. Losses this
year will be worse, analysts say. And Japan's financial troubles
extend beyond its islands: The country's banks hold nearly a third
of all loans to Asia's other contracting economies.
</P>
<P>
   Seidman fears that ``no one knows'' the extent of Japan's
problem. ``I mean no one. I don't think they know themselves.''
</P>
<P>
   The forced bankruptcy last month of Japan Leasing, a huge
subsidiary of Long-Term Credit Bank, is being hailed as a first
bold attack on the problem _ and may be a harbinger of
nationalization of the parent company. Seidman calls it ``a
positive sign.''
</P>
<P>
   But Seidman believes that Japan's banking problems are ``much
worse, much worse'' than those a decade ago in the United States.
``Those were regional problems for us, and Japan's are focused
right in the center'' of its economy.
</P>
<P>
   Ultimately, outsiders like Seidman will be unable to determine
the final outcome. In the end, he says, ``This is a Japanese
problem. It's got to be fixed by the Japanese _ nothing we can
do.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
