<DOCNO> NYT19981014.0162 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-14 14:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6661 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ONLINE-AUCTION-BOS &LR;      10-14 1711
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ONLINE-AUCTION-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CONSUMERS JUMP INTO BIDDING WARS ON THE INTERNET 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By HIAWATHA BRAY  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Tom Santos has a thing about his fax machine. It's not some
ordinary office fax, but a hulking behemoth designed for
``blast-faxing'' thousands of messages a day.
</P>
<P>
   ``When it was brand new,'' says Santos with a trace of awe, ``it
was $10,000.'' But Santos, owner of a San Francisco computer store,
got his refurbished unit for a little bit less _ $149, plus $75 for
shipping. ``I laugh every time I go use it.'' Santos bought his
beloved fax machine, and a great many other items, by hanging out
at Onsale, an Internet shopping site that auctions off merchandise
to the highest bidder. Entrepreneur Jerry Kaplan launched Onsale in
1995 with a charity auction for Boston's Computer Museum. Today,
the company said its site sells $700,000 worth of merchandise a day
to consumers and business people who love bidding on bargains
almost as much as actually finding one.
</P>
<P>
   Onsale has plenty of competition. The on-line auction business
is soaring, with dozens of companies building sites to solicit bids
on everything from live cattle to Beanie Babies. Buyers are
attracted by the bargains they find, the constant hope of finding
more, and the excitement of competing with shoppers scattered
around the world.
</P>
<P>
   Along with the sale of books and music, the on-line auction has
emerged as one of a handful of mass market uses of the Internet
that holds the promise of developing into a full-blown money-making
industry.
</P>
<P>
   Already, business-to-business auctions are generating big money.
Companies with excess supplies of industrial commodities, or firms
in desperate need of a few thousand extra computers, are turning
first to the Internet auctioneers. Forrester Research, a
Cambridge-based market research firm, found 50 leading Internet
auctioneers that had sold a total of $2.9 billion last year.
Forrester predicts that by 2002, the total business-to-business
auction market will top $52 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Accurate numbers on the consumer on-line auction market aren't
as easy to come by. But a glance at the financial data from two of
the top public auction sites shows a market in the midst of
dramatic expansion.
</P>
<P>
   Consider Onsale, which brought in $91 million in the first six
months, up from total 1997 sales of $88.9 million. Another popular
auction site, eBay Inc., went public last month _ its stock price
zoomed from $18 a share to $47 on the first day of trading. eBay
reported $14.9 million in revenue for the first six months of the
year, compared with $5.74 million for all of last year. &UR;  &LR; It closed
Friday at 30 3/4.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  The Home Shopping Network, which proved people would hunt for
bargains on their TV sets, has created an Internet site called
First Auction as a new outlet for its merchandise.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, major Internet ``portal'' sites that seek to attract
millions of regular visitors see the on-line auction as another way
to keep the Web surfers coming back. Yahoo Inc., owner of one of
the Web's most popular sites, has done a deal with Onsale to run
auctions at the Yahoo Web site. Another leading portal, Excite, has
acquired the Internet classified ads service Classifieds2000 Inc.,
and is using it as the basis of its own auction service.
</P>
<P>
   Then there are dozens of highly specialized auctions aimed at
narrow but lucrative market niches: sports enthusiasts, antique
collectors, classic car buffs.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; Onsale hooks its visitors with eye-popping prices. The site
commonly offers new computers with opening bids of $1. But prices
almost never stay that low. The cheap opening price is just to get
the bidding started, says Onsale spokesman Brian Fawkes. ``You find
the lower the starting bid, the tendency is that more people will
buy the product.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; cl10.8 &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Sure enough, someone soon bids $2, then $3 _ why not? It's still
a great price. And so the jousting begins.
</P>
<P>
   Computerization enables bidders to play a cat-and-mouse game
with one another. You can, for instance, preset the highest price
you're willing to pay _ say $500. If somebody bids $200, the
computer will automatically up your bid to $201. Someone else's
automatic bidder will offer up $202, and so on, till you've hit
your limit. Or you can sit in front of your computer all day,
watching the bidding and plunging in whenever you see something you
like.
</P>
<P>
   This isn't just bargain-hunting. On-line auctions can be fun,
and customers like Santos keep coming back as much for the
entertainment value as for the bargains. At Onsale, he purchases
items for his personal use, as well as merchandise so cheap that he
can resell it at a profit at his computer store.
</P>
<P>
   Onsale says it was the first company to dream up the concept of
Internet auctions, but it would certainly have occurred to somebody
sooner or later. The Internet enables buyers to reach thousands of
potential customers at very low cost, and makes it easy to provide
a lot of information about the product being sold. On the other
hand, potential buyers anywhere in the world can easily bid and
keep tabs on how much others are bidding.
</P>
<P>
   The on-line auctioneers have provided orderly, reliable systems
for bringing the buyers and sellers together. But these systems can
vary significantly from one auction site to another.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, sites like Onsale are similar to cut-price retail
stores, with merchandise provided by various companies for sale to
consumers. Onsale buys from the producer, and tries to auction off
the products at a higher price than it paid, turning a profit on
the spread.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, eBay sponsors auctions by individual sellers
as well as businesses. A Chicago tire distributor can sell on the
site; so can a baseball fan in Florida with an autographed Hank
Aaron bat. At eBay, both shoppers will be charged a fee for listing
the items at the site, as well as a percentage of the price they're
paid.
</P>
<P>
   Steve Westly, eBay's vice president of marketing and business
development, says even other on-line retailers can't match his
site's vast assortment of merchandise. ``Not only are there 800,000
items right now,'' Westly said, ``but if you come back tomorrrow
there will be over 100,000 new ones.''
</P>
<P>
   That may be why eBay can boast of something that Onsale and many
other auction sites can barely dream of: profits. The firm earned
$870,000 last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Clearly people like this service,'' said Forrester Research
analyst Kate Delhagen. ``It's a great way to unload a lot of stuff
that's been accumulating in their closet over the years, but it's
also a great way to find things.''
</P>
<P>
   But eBay may face a severe threat from Yahoo's new auction site.
It also offers listings to individual sellers, but unlike eBay,
Yahoo charges nothing to either the buyer or seller. The company
simply wants to encourage Internet users to keep coming back to the
Web site, thus allowing Yahoo to earn millions by selling
advertisements.
</P>
<P>
   Auction sites generally require the visitor to sign in and
provide a credit card number. The user is assigned a password and
is free to begin bargain-hunting. Auctions generally take two
forms: the standard kind, where the highest bidder wins; and the
Dutch auction, where the seller sets a price that goes down by a
certain amount every day until somebody buys the item. In a Dutch
auction, the buyer can hold off buying, day after day, in hopes of
a lower price _ at the risk that someone will come along who's
willing to pay the higher price.
</P>
<P>
   Many items _ including some of those eye-popping bargains _ have
a ``reserve price,'' the lowest acceptable bid for an item. That $1
computer likely has a $1,000 reserve on it, so if the price stays
at $1, it won't be sold.
</P>
<P>
   When two bids come in at the same price, the one received first
gets priority. Quantity can also play a part. If you bid $50 for a
lot of 10 items, somebody else could bid $70 for only five. The
high bidder gets the five items, while you get the remaining five
at the lower price.
</P>
<P>
   Bidders can have second thoughts and retract a bid while the
auction is in progress. But once the hammer falls, a binding
contract exists, and the bidder must pay the agreed price.
</P>
<P>
   When dealing with a site like Onsale or First Auction, customers
have little reason to worry about fraud. They're buying directly
from the auctioneers, and both firms guarantee satisfaction. But
what about a user of eBay or Yahoo, doing business with a total
stranger a thousand miles away? Do buyers pay first and hope the
merchandise shows up? Do sellers ship the goods before the money
arrives?
</P>
<P>
   It's no idle worry. The National Consumers League, a consumer
group in Washington, D.C., says on-line auction fraud has become
the most common kind of Internet fraud. And eBay and Yahoo don't
guarantee that buyers and sellers are trustworthy.
</P>
<P>
   However, there are services like I-Escrow, at www.iescrow.com.
I-Escrow works with both buyers and sellers. The seller won't ship
the product until I-Escrow receives the buyer's payment. And
I-Escrow won't hand over the payment to the seller until the buyer
has received the merchandise. I-Escrow charges 5 percent of the
value of each transaction.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, eBay and Yahoo feature rating services, in which
customers are asked to rate the quality of goods purchased from
particular sellers. Complaints from previous customers are
prominently displayed next to the names of sellers, and sellers
with a reputation for rip-offs are kicked out.
</P>
<P>
   The sites also contain message boards where shoppers compare
notes on interesting bargains. The message board on eBay, the eBay
Cafe, has become a hangout where many bidders visit simply for the
companionship.
</P>
<P>
   So on-line auction sites are entertaining and reasonably safe.
But can buyers really save money? Only if they keep their heads.
Santos warns that some bidders have so much fun, they drive the
price too high.
</P>
<P>
   ``People get pumped, they get excited, they get the adrenaline
flowing, and they become idiots,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   But if you know exactly what you want to pay, and stick to it,
Santos adds, consumers can bid their way to some exceptional
bargains.
</P>
</TEXT>
