A6663 &Cx1f; tic-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IMPOSTERS-MOVIE-AZR &LR;      10-14 0433
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMPOSTERS-MOVIE-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TUCCI HAS THE TOUCH FOR COMEDY IN `IMPOSTORS' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB FENSTER  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNDATED - Two out-of-work actors face the thespian's nightmare:
having to get a real job. Their plight sets off a chain of
silliness in ``The Impostors,'' a throwback comedy that attempts to
reinvent the theatrical farce _ and mostly succeeds.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Impostors'' is set in the 1930s but is approached with a
'90s sensibility, which works to amusing effect in all but two
glaring instances.
</P>
<P>
   Arthur (Stanley Tucci) and Maurice (Oliver Platt) are two
bumbling actors who stumble from one mishap to the next, eventually
landing on an ocean liner as accidental stowaways.
</P>
<P>
   While Maurice and Arthur try to escape from a mad British ham
(Alfred Molina) who wants their hides, they bump around a ship full
of fools, con artists, femmes fatales and revolutionaries.
</P>
<P>
   Written and directed by Tucci, ``The Impostors'' begins as a
warmhearted comedy, much like his first delight, ``Big Night.''
</P>
<P>
   But then ``The Impostors'' veers off into farcical realms. The
movie gets sillier and sillier, until it's a full-blown,
in-one-door-and-out-the-other kind of farce, all told with a rush
of slapstick and flip repartee.
</P>
<P>
   A surprising cast of supporting players includes a couple of
cameos I won't give away here and some unexpected character actors
having fun: Steve Buscemi (``Armageddon'') as a suicidal lounge
singer, Hope Davis (``Next Stop Wonderland'') as a mournful
romantic, Campbell Scott (``TheSpanish Prisoner'') as an overwound
ship steward, and Billy Connolly (``Mrs. Brown'') as an athlete who
is too much of a man's man.
</P>
<P>
   They all take turns carrying the comic load, while Tucci and
Platt (``Bulworth'') transform themselves into a '90s version of
Laurel and Hardy.
</P>
<P>
   As a hangdog comic, Tucci is impeccable. But as writer and
director, he slips twice:
</P>
<P>
   (1) He throws in too much anachronistic cursing, which is
unnecessary to the comedy.
</P>
<P>
   (2) He lets the sexual situations slip from the risque into the
raunchy.
</P>
<P>
   Since ``The Impostors'' is a comic throwback to Hope/Crosby road
picture nonsense, seniors are potentially a large part of the
audience.
</P>
<P>
   People who would appreciate the amusing virtues of an
old-fashioned farce would probably find the R-rated movie funnier
if it had not resorted to profanity and over-the-line sexuality.
</P>
<P>
   Still, if you enjoyed the elevated nonsense of ``Radioland
Murders'' and ``The Hudsucker Proxy,'' don't miss ``The
Impostors.'' 3 stars. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
