<P>
   THEN AND NOW: CHANGES SINCE THE 1973 ARAB OIL EMBARGO
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Imports, 28 percent of total U.S. oil consumption in 1973,
have risen to 48 percent.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Members of the Organization of Petroleum Exporting Countries
(OPEC), which supplied 54 percent of the world's crude oil, now
provide 43 percent.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Inflation-adjusted retail prices have risen 6.5 percent for
gasoline and 7 percent for electricity in those 25 years.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  The inflation-adjusted price paid by refiners for crude oil
has risen by 58 percent.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  The inflation-adjusted price of natural gas as it comes out of
the ground has increased by 187 percent.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  U.S. consumption of petroleum is up by 13 percent, though the
nation's growing population means that on a per-person basis, it is
down by 14 percent.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Improved exploration and development technology has cut the
cost of finding new oil and gas wells by 68 percent.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  The average car then got 14 miles per gallon, compared to
today's 28.5 miles per gallon for a car and 20.4 miles per gallon
for light trucks -- including minivans, sport utility vehicles and
small pickups.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Today's average car or light truck has 25 percent more
horsepower than its equivalent in 1973.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  The 31 percent share of homes heated by oil has dropped to 17
percent. The main reason: The 54 percent share of new homes heated
by natural gas has risen to 69 percent.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Electric utilities, which got 17 percent of their power from
oil before the embargo, get only 2.5 percent from oil today.
Natural gas, then 18 percent of fuel for utilities, fell to 9.5
percent. To make up the difference, coal rose from 46 percent to
nearly 57 percent of utility fuel, and nuclear rose from 4.5
percent to about about 20 percent.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  While U.S. energy consumption has increased by 27 percent
since the embargo, energy use has grown so much faster in other
countries that the U.S. share of the world's energy consumption has
dropped from 31 percent in 1973 to 25 percent today.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
