</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OIL-MIDEAST-$ADV18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    LOW OIL PRICES COULD LEAD TO CRISES IN MIDEAST OPEC COUNTRIES
 &HT;    EDs: Optional add begins at 600 words.
 &HT;    With OIL-EMBARGO-$ADV18.
 &HT;    Moving in both the (i) International and (k) Commentary
categories.
 &HT;    For Use Sun., Oct. 18 And Thereafter.
 &HT;    By LARRY KAPLOW 
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   KUWAIT CITY, Kuwait _ There has never been so much available
oil, which is good news for motorists at gas pumps just about
everywhere -- but here.
</P>
<P>
   Oil prices are dropping. So, nervous officials in this oil-rich
sheikhdom might raise the price of gasoline in their own land to
raise money for the government-sponsored lifestyle of free
health-care, full employment and air-conditioned comfort.
</P>
<P>
   High-priced gasoline would be a reversal of fortune for Kuwait.
It's oil reserves make up nearly one-tenth of the world's supply
and gushes up through drill holes to the desert surface without the
pumps needed elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   ``It looks odd and peculiar that, at a time when many countries
are cutting the prices at the gas stations, you're increasing it in
Kuwait,'' said Kuwaiti Oil Minister Saud Nasir Al-Sabah in a recent
interview with Cox News Service. ``That's absurd . . . I don't
think this is something that's acceptable to us now.''
</P>
<P>
   Life is still good here. Car dealerships are busy every night
and young Kuwaitis can still count on a job in the bloated
government bureaucracy.
</P>
<P>
   But Kuwait and its oil-producing neighbors, from wealthy Saudi
Arabia to giant and volatile Iran, are struggling with the
ramifications of low oil prices.
</P>
<P>
   Twenty-five years ago, the so-called Arab oil embargo shocked
the West. Attempting to keep the U.S. from backing Israel, these
countries threatened to cut oil supplies -- particularly to the
U.S., where frightened Americans rushed to line up their
gas-guzzling automobiles at pumps despite rising prices.
</P>
<P>
   The panic in the West brought a windfall in the Gulf, which
became awash in cash as well as oil. Big countries like Iran and
Iraq could bring their people modern social services, roads and
education. Small countries, like Kuwait, could luxuriate.
</P>
<P>
   It raised the gulf countries' world clout. Arabic became an
official language at the United Nations. The United States started
selling sophisticated military airplanes to the Saudis.
</P>
<P>
   But, prompted by the higher prices, new competition in oil
production took off from Mexico to Russia. And, oil importers --
especially the United States -- found ways to conserve.
</P>
<P>
   Today, oil prices are about as low, adjusted for inflation, as
they were before the embargo in 1973. More oil is produced than
ever -- 73 million barrels a day.
</P>
<P>
   So, while Persian Gulf oil exporters still sit on 65 percent of
the world's supply, it is losing value. The 11-member OPEC cartel
(including three nations outside the Mideast) will see revenues
drop by a third this year -- down about $40 billion. Since 1980,
the per capita income in Saudi Arabia, Kuwait and three other
oil-producing monarchies has dropped by more than 50 percent.
</P>
<P>
   A continued decline in oil prices could cause hard times here,
leading to radicalism -- or worse, instability -- even among
stalwart American allies like Kuwait and Saudi Arabia.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Kuwait has just 1.8 million inhabitants and nearly 10 percent
of the world's oil. But, Kuwaitis are edgy about the soundness of a
system that provides free health-care, subsidized utilities and
charges no income or sales taxes.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  More vulnerable is Saudi Arabia, with about 18 million people.
It is also cutting back benefits -- like the low-income housing
loans for newlyweds -- while trying to calm a restless minority of
have-nots and religious fundamentalists. Unemployment is rising.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  More volatile still is Iran. A regional giant with 68 million
people, Iran's government deficit and economic recession could
undercut nascent steps toward detente with the West.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Iraq is another story. Its oil production has been limited by
economic sanctions and industrial disrepair following the Persian
Gulf War. But, should things improve -- and Russia and China have
their way -- its production will kick into gear and add to the oil
glut.
</P>
<P>
   (EDs: Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   Zalmay Khalilzad, director for Strategic Studies at the Rand
Corp., warns that the United States is still dependent on Persian
Gulf oil supplies. If Americans want low prices, he said, they may
have to be ready to help quell the resulting unrest in the region.
</P>
<P>
   The oil producers tend to make the problem worse. Most have
refused to make tough cuts in benefits.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Gulf countries, unfortunately, are still dreaming that the
welfare state will last forever,'' said Kuwaiti political scientist
Shamlan al-Essa(CQ).
</P>
<P>
   Instead, they just try to raise money by pumping and selling
more oil. That lowers the price even more.
</P>
<P>
   Far from controlling the market, OPEC members now are struggling
just to keep their organization together.
</P>
<P>
   ``The whole situation is very different than it was in the
past,'' Al Sabah said. ``We have to be extremely careful about
mixing oil and politics.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
