<HEADER>
A6679 &Cx1f; tic-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GADJODILO-MOVIE-AZR &LR;      10-14 0443
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GADJO </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GYPSY GEM: FILM TELLS PASSIONATE TALE OF LONGING, BELONGING 
</HEADLINE>
 DILO-MOVIE-AZR   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB FENSTER  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNDATED - Don't think of ``Gadjo Dilo'' as a foreign film
forcing you to read subtitles.
</P>
<P>
   Think of it as a marvelous movie through which you can journey
into the world of Romanian Gypsies for only $6. You won't get a
better deal on a more rewarding and exotic journey this year.
</P>
<P>
   Gypsy filmmaker Tony Gatlif explores his heritage in this sly,
subtle tale of self-discovery and passion.
</P>
<P>
   Stumbling on both is Stephane (Romain Duris), a young Parisian
traveling by foot through the barren plains of Romania.
</P>
<P>
   He has come to this wasteland on a mission both personal and
vague: searching for a Gypsy singer whom his recently deceased
father loved.
</P>
<P>
   His search is transformed when he begins recording a variety of
village musicians, some of them startlingly good.
</P>
<P>
   One night, Stephane falls in with an old drunkard, Izidor
(Isidor Serban), who brings the young man home to his Gypsy
village, where Stephane is looked upon as a crazy outsider (the
``gadjo dilo'' of the title).
</P>
<P>
   The superstitious villagers fret that Stephane will put a curse
on them and steal their chickens and their women, in that order of
concern.
</P>
<P>
   Stephane intends to spend only one night. But he finds himself
caught up in the lives of Izidor, a fiddler who plays at
celebrations, and Sabina (Rona Hartner), a dancer whose energy and
provocative beauty draw Stephane into the Gypsy life.
</P>
<P>
   You'll be drawn in, too, as the wild music and dancing of the
weddings, parties and funerals is irresistible.
</P>
<P>
   Out of these slender threads, director Gatlif weaves a tale
about what it means to belong to a culture as apart and demanding
as the Gypsies. Gatlif evokes the great joys and great sorrows of a
people who remain a persecuted minority wherever they live.
</P>
<P>
   ``Gadjo Dilo'' is also a surprisingly raunchy film, with a
seduction scene so original and erotic that a dozen Hollywood
directors are probably scheming at this moment how to imitate it.
</P>
<P>
   Gatlif, a Spanish Gypsy who works in France, has explored Gypsy
themes in two previous movies, ``Latcho Drom'' and ``La Terre Au
Ventre.''
</P>
<P>
   He's discovered a secret about great filmmaking: Film something
you love and show the world.
</P>
<P>
   French actor Duris (``When the Cat's Away'') and Hungarian
actress Hartner (``Double Ecstasy'') create one of the hottest
romantic couples in years.
</P>
<P>
   Unrated, ``Gadjo Dilo'' contains profanity, nudity and sex. It
is in Romanian and French with English subtitles. 4 stars. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-14-98 1503EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
