   &UR; HOME &LR;  (``l'' code)
</P>
<P>
   MAIN-STREET (Undated) _ The flap of American flags on lampposts
and the pages of a paperback flipped by a shop owner on a bench
outside her antiques store were the only things moving on a recent
afternoon in downtown Marceline, Mo. There was one customer and one
waitress down at Mom's Coffee Shop. Both were smoking. It was a
landscape out of ``The Last Picture Show,'' except for the new
street sign. It read ``Main Street USA,'' beneath a halo of mouse
ears. A light year away in Fort Collins, Colo., the pedestrian mall
known as ``the old town'' was thriving with after-school activity.
There was a line to use the phone at the Paris on the Poudre cafe;
teen-agers painted each other with trial-run Halloween makeup
outside an Aveda bath shop. Pool balls clacked in the back room of
the new cigar bar. This is a tale of the two main streets that
inspired the ultimate urban fantasy: Disneyland's Main Street, USA.
By Julie Iovine.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   HERBAL-VILLAGE (Fulton, Md.) _ About a month ago, I stopped by
Jim Duke's garden to check out the little six-acre spread he calls
Herbal Village. Fulton is one of those little burgs off the
interstate, where the farms have given over to ranch houses, with
guys out on their power mowers every Saturday, riding herd on their
lawns. But Duke's place is as different as the man himself, who
looks more like a 69-year-old hippie, standing barefoot by his
kudzu vine, than an eminent botanist, with 20 books and 200
scientific papers under his belt (if he wore one with his cutoffs).
Last August, with the help of a few friends, Dr. Duke planted about
200 medicinal herbs, in 80 plots, each devoted to some disease or
ailment. By Anne Raver.
</P>
<P>
   WENGE-FURNITURE (Undated) _ Naomi, Kate, Shalom, Claudia, wenge?
It came down the runway two seasons ago in Milan. Now wenge
(pronounced WEN-geh) is the deep, rich darling of the
furniture-design moment, the bittersweet chocolate-brown muse of
the new minimalists _ from reigning sultans like Christian Liaigre
to young turks like Spencer Fung. If ever there was a wood that
was, it's wenge. It's so there, it could be over. By William L.
Hamilton.
</P>
<P>
   DEMETER-FRAGRANCES (New York) _ ``Techno fragrances are the
coming thing,'' said Christopher Broisus of Demeter, the company
whose line of fragrances won the best of show award last week at
Extracts, the trade show at the Javits Center. Demeter offers
little bottles of real-world fragrances like Rubber, Dirt and
Vinyl. The company is working hard on Gasoline, a fragrance that
offers less the raw smell of petrol than ``the idea of gasoline,''
Brosius said. By Phil Patton.
</P>
<P>
   SOLOMONOFF-HOME (New York) _ Over the last decades, work has
increasingly invaded the home and changed the way Americans view
the domestic landscape. Wing chairs, mantelpieces and newel posts
make little sense for houses that double as offices: cozy images
send unprofessional cues to clients, and cocoon people into
thinking their workday never starts. ``Baking cookies and ironing
shirts was not the image I had in mind,'' said Galia Solomonoff, an
architect who recently bought a former karate school to transform
into a live-in Manhattan workplace. ``I wanted to construct a house
around the way we actually live, not with cliches, and the most
important thing was that domesticity not interfere with my work.''
By Joseph Giovannini.
</P>
