<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-14 15:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6689 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HATE-LAWS-BOS &LR;      10-14 0739
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HATE-LAWS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HATE-CRIME LAWS A CONTINUING SOURCE OF DEBATE
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ANNE E. KORNBLUT  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Within a day of his son's death, less than a week after
his son was beaten and tied to a fence post in near-freezing
temperatures, Dennis Shepard issued a quiet warning against ``just
passing all kinds of new hate crime laws.''
</P>
<P>
   It was, to some, an odd comment at that hour. Elsewhere in the
country, the beating death of the 21-year-old gay Wyoming student
sparked anti-bias demonstrations and vigils, and both Sen. Edward
Kennedy and President Clinton immediately called for a broader
federal law punishing violent racial and sexual attacks.
</P>
<P>
   But to some free speech activists in Boston, particularly those
who objected to expanded state hate-crime legislation enacted in
1996, Shepard's remark was a natural response to the increasing
number of such laws, which add substantial penalties to existing
offenses if they were accompanied by statements reflecting bias
against a protected group.
</P>
<P>
   The father's comment also raised crucial questions: Does
singling out slurs as potential incitements to violence really
work? And where, exactly, is the line between a hate crime and an
unpopular point of view?
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a very hard problem,'' said Wendy Kaminer, a public
policy fellow at Radcliffe College. ``On the one hand, I think that
law has some symbolic value...But I'm also troubled by a law that
says an assault is worse if we don't like the attitude behind it.
It's a kind of thought policing.''
</P>
<P>
   Throughout the country, 40 states have passed hate crime laws in
order to mete out harsher punishment to crimes committed with bias
in mind. Definitions vary; in nearly half the states with such
laws, homosexuals are not among those protected against bias crime.
</P>
<P>
   In Wyoming, where on Monday police charged Russell A. Henderson
and Aaron J. McKinney with first-degree murder in Shepard's death,
there is no hate crime law _ despite several attempts to pass one.
</P>
<P>
   In the wake of the murder, Gov. Jim Geringer urged legislators
to pass one, even as Shepard's father said he hoped the killing
would not be twisted into a political platform. Sen. Kennedy also
pushed ahead with his proposed federal hate crime legislation,
which would widen the definition of possible hate crime victims to
include gays, women or the disabled.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am hopeful after the tragedy in Wisconsin, which has shocked
the conscience of the nation, that Congress will pass the Hate
Crimes Act before adjourning for the year,'' he said in a prepared
statement.
</P>
<P>
   But in Massachusetts, where such laws have included broad
definitions since 1996, questions remained about the effectiveness
of singling out one particular sort of violent crime. Even Gary
Busek, executive director of the Boston-based Gay &AMP; Lesbian
Advocates &AMP; Defenders, a gay-rights group, admitted ``the laws
certainly don't mean that hate crimes don't continue to happen.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The existence of the law is a good thing, but it isn't a
silver bullet,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Even more troubling than its possible ineffectiveness, according
to Boston attorney Harvey Silverglate, is the slippery nature of a
law that punishes unpopular thought.
</P>
<P>
   If someone is convicted of beating a man at random, the prison
sentence could be up to ten years; if the same crime is found to
have been fueled by bias, then it can be considered a ``triple
felony,'' carrying up to 25 years in prison. Arguing against that
standard, Kaminer pointed out that ``all murder is horrible,'' and
Silverglate agreed.
</P>
<P>
   The author of a recent book on freedom of speech on campuses,
where codes attempting to prevent hate speech have been applied
across the nation since the late '80s, Silverglate said he is
especially angered by Clinton's renewed call for expanded
hate-crime legislation.
</P>
<P>
   He said he planned to devote most of a scheduled lecture at the
Boston Public Library to arguing against such measures, claiming
they would have had no effect in discouraging Shepard's murder.
</P>
<P>
   ``The current legislation should be repealed,'' Silverglate
said. ``We have laws against murder, we have laws against
desecration of property, we have laws against threats. To begin to
single out certain people because of certain characteristics is
dangerous. ... Equality before the law is the only thing that saves
us.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
