<HEADER>
A6695 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FASHION-MISHAREV-BOS &LR;      10-14 1000
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FASHION-MISHAREV-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UKRAINIAN IMMIGRANT MAKES HIS MENSWARE DEBUT
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SUZANNE C. RYAN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CAMBRIDGE _ Yuri Kroutskikh has nerve.
</P>
<P>
   A Ukrainian immigrant, his English is iffy. His job _ a tailor
at Saks Fifth Avenue in Boston _ is low profile. And his name,
Kroutskikh, is, in his own opinion, unpronounceable.
</P>
<P>
   So why does this guy think he's got the stuff to become a famous
fashion designer?
</P>
<P>
   He runs a mean sewing machine. So mean, in fact, that he demands
$1,600 for the business suits he creates. And he's getting it.
</P>
<P>
   Tonight, Kroutskikh (who prefers to be called by his
grandmother's maiden name Misharev) will make his official Boston
debut as part of Boston Fashion Week, which is designed in part to
educate the public that this city does generate fashion talent.
Misharev joins more than 20 local designers who are showing their
wares on various catwalks this week.
</P>
<P>
   Misharev, who was born, raised, and trained in the Ukraine,
stands out from the pack. His menswear show will feature striking
garments such as a reversible three-quarter-length coat that is
tweed on one side, leather on the other. A full-length raincoat is
transparent to show off the clothes underneath.
</P>
<P>
   The designer is expecting about 50 people to visit his showroom,
where models will walk through informally, not on a runway. Of
course, it's doubtful he'll be seeing influential buyers from
stores like Neiman Marcus or, alas, even his employer Saks.
``People won't accept new names,'' says the slender, 6-foot-1,
33-year-old, in a heavy accent. ``But I like the competition
because I'm very skilled.''
</P>
<P>
   Misharev, the son of a university professor and an accountant,
grew up a long way from high fashion. ``In the former Soviet Union,
everyone wore drab colors _ black, blue and gray,'' he says (at a
time when those weren't the ``in'' colors). ``We didn't have
access'' to world-class fashion shows or magazines.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Misharev was crazy about clothes. He attended a
vocational school for pattern-making and equipment use, and a
fashion design school in Kiev, his home city.
</P>
<P>
   Five years ago, Misharev _ with his wife Yanina Zabrodina, a
doctor _ followed some friends and moved to Boston. ``We left the
Ukraine because it wasn't a good time economically and politically.
I couldn't establish myself as a designer there,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   In Boston, in contrast, he says people stop him on the street to
ask where he buys his clothing. When he explains the clothes are
his creations, ``Sometimes they don't believe me.''
</P>
<P>
   After working in the alterations department at Saks for about
four years, Misharev mustered the nerve to start his own business
last year _ selling custom suits, jackets, and other menswear out
of his apartment via word of mouth. ``Most of the collection I did
at night,'' drafting patterns on a pool table.
</P>
<P>
   And customers came, despite an average suit price of $1,600 and
outerwear for $350 to $400. Some of them had heard of his skill at
Saks. Others saw his handiwork on friends. ``When I got to his loft
and saw the suits, it took me about a millisecond to decide that I
wanted one,'' says Keith Hanson, a Norwood resident who initially
approached Misharev for some alterations.
</P>
<P>
   A regular shopper at Neiman Marcus and Saks, Hanson was struck
by Misharev's craftsmanship. He quickly ordered a $1,200 suit and
three pairs of trousers for $900. He liked the details like
reversible pleats on the pants (achieved by buttoning a flap in one
direction or another, completely changing the look), jacket cuffs
cut at an angle, and back pockets slanted on the trousers. ``Not
too many people pay attention to detail in pants. This is taking it
to another level,'' says Hanson.
</P>
<P>
   Some of Misharev's other signatures include: suit jackets made
with front vents for easy access to pockets; coat collars adorned
with faux fur; and long suit jackets tailored to emphasize the
body. His fabrics, mostly wools and silks that customers select
themselves from look books, come from France, Italy, Portugal,
Japan, Korea, and New York.
</P>
<P>
   Although Misharev has never shown his work in Boston, he did
unveil a collection of about 20 outfits to 50 retailers (including
Lord &AMP; Taylor) and editors during men's fashion week in New York
this summer. It was a bold move, since most of the designers who
show there are in the big leagues, like Donna Karan and Tommy
Hilfiger.
</P>
<P>
   ``We sent our portfolio to 7th on Sixth (the organizers), and
they accepted us, after the deadline. We were lucky,'' says
Zabrodina, who manages the business's finances in addition to
working part time as a researcher at Harvard University.
</P>
<P>
   ``We sewed all the clothes ourselves and found some models to
model free,'' adds Misharev. ``Some friends helped backstage, and a
makeup artist worked for free. It was great.''
</P>
<P>
   The company, called Y&AMP;Y Apparel Inc., didn't receive any orders
after the show, but Misharev is satisfied; it was strictly a debut.
``I have a timetable of three to five years to establish my name,''
he says. ``I believe in myself. I'm going to be famous.''
</P>
<P>
   Next week, Misharev plans to show his clothes in a booth at a
retail trade show in New York. His agenda is to return luxury
dressing to the everyday lifestyle. ``I'd like to see gentlemen
(dress) more elegantly,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, Misharev has a long way to go. He has only 20
regular customers. He can't slash his prices because, with no
manufacturing help, he can spend more than 30 hours on one
hand-sewn suit. The designer says a few investors have approached
him about buying into his company, but that would mean reduced
control, something he's not ready for. ``It's hard to start a
business, basically from zero,'' says Zabrodina.
</P>
<P>
   But Misharev is hopeful. ``America is a wonderful market, if you
can prove yourself.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; uftagline &LR;
</P>
<P>
   For information on the show, call 617-621-8087.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
