<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-14 15:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6707 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BERRY-GROWER-BOS &LR;      10-14 0805
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BERRY-GROWER-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW ENGLAND CRANBERRY GROWERS ARE EDGED OUT BY WISCONSIN
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LYNNLEY BROWNING  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CARVER, Mass. _ For cranberry grower Clark Griffith, the red
tide of enthusiasm that led droves of farmers to try their hand at
cultivating the tart berry in recent years can't turn too quickly.
</P>
<P>
   Cranberry-scented air fresheners. Cranberry wine.
Cranberry-flavored horseradish. Space-age, freeze-dried cranberry
powders for flavoring and coloring almost anything imaginable.
They're all out there.
</P>
<P>
   After the collapse of an industry plan to use an avalanche of
new berries to give red M&AMP;M candies their crimson color, some
growers began thinking they might have been looking at the world
through rose-tinted glasses.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are just too many cranberry growers these days,''
Griffith said, standing near a bog bobbing with berries being
harvested. ``The only way to solve the problem is to get out there
and make people want more.''
</P>
<P>
   Here in tiny Carver, in the heart of Massachusetts'
cranberry-growing country, cultivators of the jewel-red fruit who
gathered yesterday at the Massachusetts Cranberry Harvest Festival
found themselves standing at a crossroad.
</P>
<P>
   Once the king of cranberry producers, Massachusetts has been
edged out in recent years by Wisconsin, where bogs are now as
ubiquitous as barns. Other states, including New Jersey and Oregon,
have also cranked up output.
</P>
<P>
   For Massachusetts' 500 or so growers, more than half of whom
belong to the Ocean Spray Cranberries Inc. cooperative, the past
two years have had disappointing harvests. Thanks to a soggy
spring, the state's harvest this year, expected at around 200
million pounds, or a third of the national total, will be 5 percent
below last year's haul.
</P>
<P>
   While cooperative growers get paid for every berry they produce,
a leveling off in consumer demand and general oversupply have kept
the prices they receive from rising.
</P>
<P>
   This year, growers are looking at $60 a barrel, about the same
as last year. (A barrel holds 100 pounds). At the height of the
cranberry craze in 1996 and 1997, independent growers not allied
with Ocean Spray were paid up to $110 per barrel amid fierce
skirmishes for supplies.
</P>
<P>
   Competitive rivalries are still afoot in bogs across the
country. For proof, look no further than the red royalty that
traveled all the way from Wisconsin to check out Carver's festival,
which continues through Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ``In Massachusetts, the proceeds from this festival go to the
growers, but we take money from our festivals and give it back to
the community,'' said June Potter, a cranberry grower from Warrens,
Wisc., population 400. ``And the marshes here are much smaller and
more irregular,'' she said. ``Ours are straight and
laser-leveled.''
</P>
<P>
   A fresh-faced teenage girl standing next to her nodded solemnly.
``Ours are perfect,'' said Amy Nemitz, 17, the Warrens Cranberry
Festival Queen, who sported a diamond tiara that attracted
inquisitive looks.
</P>
<P>
   Ocean Spray, based in Lakeville and Middleborough, is to
cranberries what South Africa's De Beers is to diamonds. Owned by
grower-members, it accounts for 70 percent of all domestic
cranberry production. The cooperative was responsible for creating
new demand in recent years, with splashy advertising campaigns that
fueled a consumption craze and new products and inspired a fresh
generation of growers.
</P>
<P>
   While cranberries may be reaching their application limits in
this country, Ocean Spray says it's not reaping a bitter harvest.
But it admits it may have created a sour pill to swallow. ``We have
the acreage we need right now,'' said Irene Sorensen, Ocean's
Spray's head of grower relations, meaning that the cooperative is
no longer expanding by admitting new members.
</P>
<P>
   Growers insist that changing supply and demand isn't about to
turn bog cultivation into trench warfare. ``Whatever's good for the
cranberry is good for all of us,'' said Carolyne Gilmore, a
Rochester grower who also publishes a trade newsletter called
Cranberries.
</P>
<P>
   While brimming with Midwestern friendliness, Potter isn't so
sure. ``There's getting to be oversupply,'' she said, shaking her
head as golden trees stood drenched in the gray distance.
</P>
<P>
   Now the cranberry's mission lies overseas. Growers are scouring
the globe to see whether the British, Taiwanese, and Lithuanians
could be persuaded to develop a hankering for the acidic berry, one
of only three fruits native to North America. (Concord grapes and
blueberries are the others).
</P>
<P>
   ``The craze here has tempered a bit,'' said Carol Gifune,
marketing manager for Carver-based Decas Brothers Cranberry Sales,
a prominent independent grower and a rival to Ocean Spray. ``The
race is on to find new markets.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
