<HEADLINE>
ONCE A PARIAH, SINN FEIN LEADER SNAGS ACCOLADES AND CASH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By PAUL GRONDAHL  
 c.1998 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ For an Irish leader who shoulders such a heavy
burden of his island's troubled past, Sinn Fein leader Gerry Adams
traveled light on a fund-raising visit here.
</P>
<P>
   Yet he will need a large, empty suitcase to carry back all the
U.S. dollars he has raised.
</P>
<P>
   In the midst of a six-city tour that will gross $500,000 for
Sinn Fein in less than a week's work, Adams, the reed-thin,
bespectacled political philosopher behind the explosive brawn of
the Irish Republican Army was given the kind of welcome normally
reserved for another Irish import _ Bono, the rock star of the band
U2.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was an honor just to be near him. The guy's a legend now, a
world leader,'' said Brendan Mayer, 22, of Yonkers, who commutes to
a job with the state Department of Environmental Conservation in
Albany.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just shook his hand and said, `You're our only hope,''' said
Pat Gioia, a middle-aged upstates New York woman who is an advocate
for the rights of crime victims.
</P>
<P>
   Swarmed over by politicians and business people in pinstripe
suits at a $100-a-ticket fund-raiser at the Omni Hotel and bathed
in the strobe flash of a hundred photo opportunities, Adams has
transformed himself from the fear and loathing of his terrorist tag
into a bona-fide political celebrity.
</P>
<P>
   Adams smiled and made small talk Tuesday with the supplicants
who wanted a photo souvenir.
</P>
<P>
   ``All those years, he was portrayed as a terrorist, a devil, and
nobody would pay attention to him. This is like a dream come
true,'' said Jean Murray, who, with her husband, Paul Murray,
organized Adams' visit. The couple have raised tens of thousands of
dollars over the past two decades for Sinn Fein through their
leadership roles in New York State Irish Northern Aid.
</P>
<P>
   ``To use a Belfast term, it was magic,'' said Paul Murray, who
estimated the 250-person Omni event and a $20-a-head reception at
the Polish-American Citizens Club in Albany that drew an estimated
600 would bring in about $35,000 for Sinn Fein.
</P>
<P>
   Sinn Fein is the political arm of the IRA. Under Adams'
leadership, the organization has embraced peace after years of
violently opposing British rule in Northern Ireland.
</P>
<P>
   The stamp of legitimacy this time around _ compared to Adams'
1995 visit to Albany when last April's historic Good Friday peace
accord in Northern Ireland was just a dream _ created a striking
contrast for those with a long memory.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you see business people and the corporate community
signing $100 checks to Friends of Sinn Fein, that's when you know
we've turned the corner,'' said Murray, who stood with Adams in the
salad days and now munched on fancy hors d'oeuvres at the Omni.
</P>
<P>
   Lawrence Downes, the New York City-based fund-raiser for Friends
of Sinn Fein, said the group has raised $3.5 million in the United
States in the past three years and more is on the way. Smaller
cities are consistently bringing in $25,000 and more at events as
the political party's geographical reach expands.
</P>
<P>
   Next spring, Sinn Fein expects to make a fund-raising swing
through the South. Invitations also have arrived from Hawaii and
Montana. ``There's not a state in this country where we couldn't
hold a successful event,'' Downes said.
</P>
<P>
   Where does the money go? After travel and event expenses, Downes
said it is used to fund lobbying activities in a Washington, D.C.,
office with three paid staff members, a New York City office with
one staffer and efforts to modernize the Belfast operation.
</P>
<P>
   ``For the first time, people in this country have heard clearly
what Gerry Adams and Sinn Fein has to say and like it,'' said Rita
O'Haire, Sinn Fein's lobbyist in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Having friends in high places is a new experience for Sinn Fein,
which seemed to handle it in stride. Adams excused his tardiness at
the reception because he was on the phone to the White House,
explained he got the private plane from Pittsburgh at the last
minute with help from Rep. Michael R. McNulty, D-N.Y., and huddled
with Gov. George Pataki in a private room.
</P>
<P>
   Adams joked he went to Albany as ``both a democrat and a
republican (as in Northern Ireland freedom fighter). But he was
deadly serious about the work that needs to be done to nurture the
fragile peace.
</P>
<P>
   ``My visit is to motivate people to keep focused on the prize.
And the prize is a just and a lasting peace,'' Adams said. ``We
want the people of Ireland to live in a united, independent Ireland
at peace with ourselves: Catholics, Protestants and dissenters. And
it is my conviction we will achieve those objectives.''
</P>
<P>
   Adams reached into Ireland's anguished past: ``We want to see a
healing process for all of the pain of the last 30 years and
decades and centuries before that. For hurt done, for hurt
inflicted and for hurt suffered.''
</P>
<P>
   He touched on the hard-fought immigrant stories of Irish
Americans. ``You people here are the survivors,'' he said,
describing a placard he keeps that reads, ``No Irish Need Apply.''
</P>
<P>
   ``You must want to be people who can sit back and talk to the
ghosts of your grandparents and great-grandparents and say to them,
`When Ireland needed me, when the children of Ireland needed me,
when those wanting peace and justice needed me, I helped,''' Adams
said.
</P>
</TEXT>
