<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-14 15:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6790 &Cx1f; tie-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CIR-OLGA-CYBERMERCHAN     10-14 0521
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-OLGA-CYBERMERCHANT-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 UNDATED: and edited. 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Ms. Tereshko initially invested about $500 in inventory. She
already had the computer equipment so did not have to invest in
hardware or software.
</P>
<P>
   She does not want to release her sales figures. She has the
advantage of not needing to generate an income herself so she can
afford to put the money she makes back into the business, a luxury
not every entrepreneur can manage.
</P>
<P>
   ``I kept investing enough to grow for the next three months or
so, just to see how products were selling, to get a feel for what
was needed in the catalog,'' she said. ``I do things on an
intuitive basis and don't have a business plan. I don't write
things out on paper. I just tend to get a feel for things and then
just do them.''
</P>
<P>
   In the last month, her Web site has had about 10,000 visitors a
week, she said.
</P>
<P>
   While Ms. Tereshko is finding that many women appreciate her
online business, Karen Miller, the owner of a walk-in shop for
mothers and babies, says the problem with ordering on line or by
catalog is that things cannot be tried on. Her shop, Boing Boing,
which she opened in Brooklyn in December 1996, caters to nursing
mothers and their babies with clothing, bras, pumps, slings and
diapers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a believer in seeing the stuff,'' Ms. Miller said. But she
realizes that for mothers who don't live near her store, or a store
like hers, it isn't easy to find all the items they need in one
place.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anywhere they can find information to help them nurse their
babies is great,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Both Ms. Miller and Ms. Tereshko say the women who are their
customers want to talk and get the support of other women with
breast-feeding experience.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Tereshko has begun branching out in her online ventures. In
the spring of 1996, she began Just-So Postcards (www.just-so.com)
as a hobby. Visitors to the site can pick out postcards and send
them over the Internet free.
</P>
<P>
   Just-So combines art and literary sayings, many French and
Russian, reflecting the backgrounds of Ms. Tereshko and her
husband. Ms. Tereshko's parents left the Soviet Union for the
United States when she was 4; she and Sasha speak Russian. Dr.
Servan-Schreiber lived in France until he was 18; Sasha will start
taking French classes this week. The postcards quote authors like
Baudelaire, Dostoyevsky and Lewis Carroll. The sender just has to
pick a card and write a message.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want Just-So to have commercial or mass appeal,'' Ms.
Tereshko said. About 500 postcards a day are now being sent. Ms.
Tereshko said she believed that people should invest their time in
things they have emotions about, as she is doing with her ventures.
</P>
<P>
   A Little Koala postcard for new mothers that can be reached
through the Just-So main page is of a Picasso painting, ``Mother
and Child,'' which shows a nursing mother gazing calmly down at her
contented baby. ``People have to do something they have knowledge
of and have a strong passion for,'' Ms. Tereshko said. ``Customers
will pick that up. If you have a passion and a commitment, people
pick up on that.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
