<SLUG> BC-COCKFIGHT-ART-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`CITY PEOPLE' BLAMED FOR ANTI-COCKFIGHTING CAMPAIGN  
 (ART ADV: PHOTO IS BEING SENT TO NYTNS CLIENTS)  
 (ADV: WITH COCKFIGHT-PROP) 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK SHAFFER  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   DEWEY, Ariz. _ Dale Dunivin got a little misty-eyed as he
remembered the first time he hauled his fighting cock, Ol' Blue, to
the pits in Quartzsite three years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Seems that Ol' Blue was paying way too much attention to loving
and not enough to fighting, when a rather effeminate-looking
``henny cock'' took to the center of the ring.
</P>
<P>
   ``He thought he had himself a new girlfriend,'' Dunivin said.
``But that other cock got on top of him and cut down through his
back, cutting his ribs loose.
</P>
<P>
   ``We thought we were going to lose him.''
</P>
<P>
   But Ol' Blue rallied, put some moves on his foe, and managed to
dig his spurs into the heart of the other fowl. It was all over but
the shouting as the bleeding enemy slumped to the ground.
</P>
<P>
   Then, as usual, Ol' Blue, who actually is reddish brown, pecked
off the downed cock's head.
</P>
<P>
   After three months on the mend, Dunivin's fighting rooster went
on to six more wins and retired to stud service.
</P>
<P>
   It's fond memories like those that make Dunivin downright angry
about what the ``city people'' are trying to do to him and his kind
with the anti-cockfighting Proposition 201 on Arizona's Nov. 3
election ballot.
</P>
<P>
   The proposition would make even attending a cockfight a
misdemeanor, and it would leave only four states where the blood
sport is legal _ Louisiana, New Mexico, Oklahoma and Missouri.
</P>
<P>
   Dunivin, 51, a retired heavy-equipment operator, calls it a
``full-scale attack on rural America by people who have only seen
trees in parks.''
</P>
<P>
   If the proposition passes, he vows, he'll sell his 70 acres in
this small ranching community east of Prescott and move to western
New Mexico, where he can legally continue the much-maligned sport.
</P>
<P>
   After all, it was a way of life handed down to Dale Dunivin when
he was 12 by his miner father, Roy. Dale's son, 20-year-old Gabe,
has continued the tradition, raising fighting cocks in his spare
time while managing a Prescott Valley sandwich shop.
</P>
<P>
   The Dunivins definitely aren't in it for the money, Dale says.
In a good year, he barely covers the cost of feed. When
cockfighters get together on the weekends, he says, they normally
don't bet more than $20 on their birds.
</P>
<P>
   Nor is his a large operation, Dunivin says. He has 50 cocks, and
he fights about eight of them a year. About 100 hens are fenced in
against the area's large population of coyotes.
</P>
<P>
   Dunivin says he doesn't understand what all the fuss is about;
roosters, after all, are ``way down there on the food chain.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I mean, these are primitive birds that come from the jungle,''
said Dunivin, a man with a full belly; brown, leathery face; and
tightly braided ponytail snaking down his back. ``No one ever said
they saw a smart rooster. They don't do tricks, crow when the house
is on fire or walk the kids to the school bus.''
</P>
<P>
   About the only thing they do well is explode into an orgy of
violence when they see another rooster. Fighting cocks are paired
off in the ring when they weigh 4 to 6 pounds, and they battle to
the death, which usually comes well within the 20-minute time
limit.
</P>
<P>
   Tactics are few, Dunivin said. Some birds will do a feint and
sidestep an aggressive rooster flying in at them. Others, called
shufflers, are especially effective because they throw their legs
out in front of them, with the razor-sharp blades attached to their
claws.
</P>
<P>
   Dunivin said it's a struggle to keep them from killing one
another even when the blades are removed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've seen them peck one another to death through knotholes,''
Dunivin said, watching two roosters try to go at it in his pen,
ropes taut as their necks strained toward the other.
</P>
<P>
   ``They've been bred for this for hundreds of years.''
</P>
<P>
   They sure aren't much for eating, Dunivin says. After fights,
dead roosters are generally just thrown in the trash.
</P>
<P>
   ``These things are just a big chunk of muscle, like boxers after
road training,'' he said. ``You could put them in a Crock Pot for
hours and they wouldn't be tender enough to eat.''
</P>
<P>
   All of which means _ to him _ that a rooster biting the dust in
battle is no big deal.
</P>
<P>
   True, fighting birds may eventually die in the ring, but
meanwhile, some of them may enjoy something approaching a life.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had this one ol' cock, you could pick him up and pet him and
he would purr like a baby,'' Dunivin said.
</P>
<P>
   ``He died of a heart attack at 10 years old.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
Mark Shaffer can be reached at mark.shaffer(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
