<SLUG> BC-COCKFIGHT-PROP-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COCKFIGHTERS MOUNT NOVEL DEFENSE  
 (ADV: WITH COCKFIGHT AND PHOTO) 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By MIKE MCCLOY  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNDATED - Trailing 3-1 in the polls, Arizona cockfighters are
huddling behind a ``Mount Rushmore defense'' against a proposed ban
on their sport.
</P>
<P>
   Presidents Washington, Jefferson, Jackson and Lincoln all were
cockfighters, David Harris says in a publicity pamphlet for the
Nov. 3 general election. Proposition 201 would be a slap in the
face of the nation's founders, Harris, a cockfighter, claims.
</P>
<P>
   James Massey, head of Citizens Against Cockfighting, was
skeptical of Harris' claims. But just to be sure, he asked an ally,
the Humane Society of the United States, to put an investigator on
the case.
</P>
<P>
   Sure enough, a check with historical agencies in the home states
of all four presidents found no chicken blood in the background of
Jefferson or Lincoln.
</P>
<P>
   But Washington and Jackson? That was another matter.
</P>
<P>
   Washington's correspondence mentions that the future president
attended a cockfight when he was 19.
</P>
<P>
   Cockfighting was the least scurrilous of the accusations hurled
against Jackson in the 1828 presidential campaign, and it had some
substance. To defend himself, Jackson had scrawled a handwritten
message at some point during the campaign protesting that he had
not been to a cockfight ``for the last 13 years.''
</P>
<P>
   The sport was banned in Jackson's home state of Tennessee in
1881. In fact, 31 states outlawed cockfighting by the beginning of
the 20th century. Going into the next millennium, only Arizona,
Oklahoma, Louisiana, Missouri and New Mexico still allow it.
</P>
<P>
   After two dozen defeats in the Arizona Legislature, Massey's
group gathered more than 150,000 signatures of voters for the
initiative. The Arizona Game Fowl Breeders Association lost a court
challenge to keep the measure off the ballot last month.
</P>
<P>
   Of 811 voters polled statewide Oct. 3-6 by ``The Arizona
Republic,'' 59 percent said they definitely would vote for the ban
and 8 percent said they probably would. Thirteen percent were
definitely against the ban, and 8 percent said they probably would
vote against it. Twelve
</P>
<P>
   percent could not decide.
</P>
<P>
   Association members are providing most of the money for
television commercials and bumper stickers that call for a ``no''
vote on Prop. 201, proclaiming that cockfighting is not a felony.
</P>
<P>
   It would be if the ban is approved. Anyone who even raises a
rooster with intentions of entering him in a fight could face a
two-year prison term. Fans caught in a cockfighting pit could be
put in the pokey for six months on a misdemeanor charge.
</P>
<P>
   Claiming the sport is no worse than commercial butchering of
chickens, cockfighters say steel blades attached to a fighting
rooster's legs speed up death in the pit, making it more humane
than battling with bare claws.
</P>
<P>
   But in an interview, Warren Glick, president of the association,
did not deny that cockfighting is cruel.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you don't like, it, you don't have to attend,'' he said.
``We just want to be left alone.''
</P>
<P>
   Massey said he is not a meddler.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe in civil liberties as much as the next guy,'' he
said. ``I just don't believe animal abuse is their right.''
</P>
<P>
   While 10 Arizona sheriffs endorse the ban and claim a link
between cockfighting and homicide, rape, gambling and drug
possession, the Maricopa County Sheriff's Office reports no such
experience.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not illegal, therefore we don't have a code for it,''
Maricopa County Sheriff's spokesman Dave Trombi said. ``So there's
no way to check the computer. It's a non-issue unless the law
changes.''
</P>
<P>
   With more than 40 cockfighting pits and 18,000 breeders in the
state, Glick estimates that law enforcement could cost more than $1
million a year.
</P>
<P>
   Although Proposition 201 says police could arrest only those who
raise roosters for fighting, ``we're scared that they're going to
come onto our place like the Gestapo and take our property,'' Glick
said. ``We're looking at a lot of litigation.''
</P>
<P>
   If cockfighting goes, Arizona's economy will suffer, Glick
added.
</P>
<P>
   ``Believe it or not, there's a lot of tourism involved,'' he
said. ``People come here from states where it's not legal.''
</P>
<P>
   He estimated 18,000 Arizonans are raising about 100 fighting
roosters each, feeding each one a pound of grain a day. ``The
economic impact is probably several million dollars,'' Glick said.
</P>
<P>
   Massey was not convinced.
</P>
<P>
   ``Cockfighting boosts the economy?'' he questioned. ``If we
don't win, will that help Arizona's image?'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
Mike McCloy may be reached at mike.mccloy(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
