<HEADER>
A6847 &Cx1f; tic-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SNOWBIRDS-ART-AZR &LR;      10-14 1574
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SNOWBIRDS-ART-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SNOWBIRD FLOCK THINS, WORRYING ARIZONA BUSINESSES  
 (ART ADV: PHOTO IS BEING SENT TO NYTNS CLIENTS) 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By MAUREEN WEST  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   MESA, Ariz. - Silent autumn. Where are the snowbirds?
</P>
<P>
   A recreational-vehicle park in Mesa that usually comes alive by
mid-October looks like a ghost town. Bridge tables remain empty in
nearby Leisure World.
</P>
<P>
   Canadians, traditionally the first snowbirds to arrive, are
missing from Arizona's mobile-home parks, condos, restaurants and
roadways.
</P>
<P>
   Like miners who suddenly notice the silence of their safety
canaries, or botanists who can't find frogs in the streams, Arizona
migration experts are worried: Dwindling snowbirds could indicate
serious peril for small businesses that rely on the seasonal influx
of retirees.
</P>
<P>
   Last winter, Canadian and U.S.-citizen retirees didn't return in
the numbers economists have come to expect, and this year the
economists fear the seasonal flocks will be even thinner.
</P>
<P>
   The estimated 350,000 winter visitors pump $1 billion into
Arizona cash registers, according to Arizona State University's
Center for Business Research.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last year, even though the economy was booming, the numbers of
visitors were down _ I am worried about this year,'' said economist
Timothy Hogan, an expert on snowbird migration and director of the
research center.
</P>
<P>
   The number of Arizona winter visitors declined 6 percent last
season _ the first drop since the recession of the early 1990s,
according to a survey by the ASU business center. That's an
estimated 20,000 to 25,000 people who didn't make the Valley of the
Sun, as the metropolitan Phoenix area is called, their home last
winter.
</P>
<P>
   But growth continues in smaller, more rural areas such as Lake
Havasu, Benson, Willcox, Douglas and Casa Grande, where new parks
are being built and where living costs are lower, Hogan said. Yuma,
which has become a big Southwest retirement destination in recent
years, also gained 500 part-time households.
</P>
<P>
   At the Golden Vista RV park in Apache Junction, property manager
Jay Burland is worried. By this time of year, his park normally has
as many as 200 residents, building to more than 2,000 by January.
</P>
<P>
   ``But the place is still looking like a ghost town,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   This time of year, Joe Stofsick, 76, and his bridge pals at
Leisure World in Mesa can usually count on having 10 or 11 tables
of bridge players as the Canadians start rolling in for the season.
This year they have only had enough people for six or seven tables.
</P>
<P>
   Even with the growth of winter visitor facilities in rural
Arizona, the net number of Arizona visitors is down.
</P>
<P>
   If fewer snowbirds come to the Phoenix area, it is more a
reflection of economic conditions elsewhere, said Hogan, whose
center has tracked annual visitor patterns since the mid-1980s. The
problem was masked last year in Phoenix because the rest of the
economy was doing so well.
</P>
<P>
   The whole farm economy is down, he said. Many winter visitors
are from small agricultural towns in the Midwest and Upper Plains.
Other snowbirds are from Oregon and Washington where economies are
feeling the effects of the Asian financial crisis.
</P>
<P>
   Apart from the world economy, Canadians have some problems of
their own, Hogan said.
</P>
<P>
   Canada's dollar, now worth only 64 U.S. cents, is causing some
Canadians to cancel or shorten their U.S. winter visits. Canada's
national insurance program, which penalizes extended residency
outside of Canada, is keeping many at home. And some Canadians are
choosing to retire in resort areas in Canada.
</P>
<P>
   Last season, Canadians represented 15 to 20 percent of Arizona's
snowbirds, said Tom Rex, research manager for the ASU center.
</P>
<P>
   Jay Burland, property manager of Golden Vista RV resort, hopes
the jittery stock market doesn't change the plans of his U.S.
retirees.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're the generation from the Great Depression. They know
the value of a dollar and are very conscious of changes in the
economy,'' he said. ``If the economy continues in the direction
that it is going, it might put a little scare in them.
</P>
<P>
   ``We won't know until January _ the peak season _ how badly we
will be affected.''
</P>
<P>
   That's also when Hogan will begin doing calculations for this
year's season. The number of winter visitors in metropolitan
Phoenix is calculated largely from mobile-home and RV park
populations, estimating two people in each household. An estimated
50 percent of seasonal visitors traditionally stay in mobile-home
and RV parks. But Hogan admits it is an imperfect system because
many visitors live in apartments and hotels or with family. Other
factors may also be skewing the visitor statistics, especially in
urban areas.
</P>
<P>
   Many Phoenix-area parks have been full this past year, but not
with winter visitors. Arizona's strong economy, which is attracting
young workers into the state, may be soaking up affordable
apartments, mobile homes and even RV spaces in metropolitan areas,
preventing winter visitors from finding suitable quarters.
</P>
<P>
   New mobile-home parks are rare in the Phoenix metropolitan area
and many older ones have been demolished and replaced with other
development.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to mobile home spaces, a significant number of
condominiums, townhomes and single-family homes are owned by
part-time residents, including many of the homes in developments
such as Leisure World and Sun Lakes. But if Stofsick's experience
with his missing bridge players at Leisure World is any indication,
even those who own more expensive homes are staying away longer.
</P>
<P>
   One of Stofsick's Canadian neighbors at Leisure World is Phyllis
Hallatt of Saskatoon, Saskatchewan. One of her Canadian friends in
Arizona sold his Leisure World home after he had a heart attack and
couldn't get health insurance in Canada for more than 61 days away
from home. She knows of others who will be wintering in Victoria,
British Columbia, instead of Arizona. It's not as warm, but they
will be covered by the Canadian medical plan and will be spending
Canadian dollars at full value.
</P>
<P>
   The Canadian health care system has undergone severe cuts this
decade. Winter visitors, who used to have full health care coverage
even when in the United States, now must pay big money for
travelers' policies that cover little more than emergency
procedures. A five- or six-month supplemental travelers' insurance
policy can cost $1,000 to $4,000, depending on age and previous
health problems.
</P>
<P>
   Canadians also are asked to reside in their home provinces at
least 182 days a year or forfeit health benefits for three months.
That rule is being more stringently enforced.
</P>
<P>
   Rex believes it would be a mistake to blame the decline in
winter visitors only on the changes in Canada. The Phoenix area's
sprawl, traffic and pollution could be taking their toll, not only
on travel plans of Canadians, but also on snowbirds from small,
clean and quiet Midwestern towns, who account for almost 70 percent
of traditional Valley winter visitors.
</P>
<P>
   The East Valley is also suffering from congestion and crime, and
has changed its urban form and pace dramatically during the past 10
years.
</P>
<P>
   The numbers of snowbirds were down on the west and east sides of
the Valley.
</P>
<P>
   In the East Valley, including Mesa and Apache Junction, 43,000
RV and mobile-home spaces were filled by snowbirds last year, a
drop of 4,000 from the previous year. In the West Valley, which
includes Surprise, Peoria, Goodyear and Buckeye, there were 6,000
RV spaces occupied by snowbirds, down from 8,000 the year before.
</P>
<P>
   The decline in snowbirds was twice as severe in the Tucson area
as it was in Phoenix. In 1997, Pima County passed an RV tax of 50
cents per space per night to finance new baseball spring training
facilities. According to Hogan, word of the tax spread through the
ranks of retirees, many of whom chose other destinations. The tax
that was expected to generate $800,000 per year fizzled at
$300,000.
</P>
<P>
   Weather may have played a role in last year's drop. Rain in
Phoenix meant some U.S. retirees stayed a shorter time, Hogan said.
Last year's mildest Canadian winter on record may be a significant
reason why many Canadians stayed home. The forecast for this
winter, however, is a return to deep-freeze conditions.
</P>
<P>
   A harsh winter and old habits will keep many Canadians coming to
Arizona, said Chris Rydall, Arizona's Canadian tourism
representative stationed in Toronto. They won't be spending as much
money, however, he predicts.
</P>
<P>
   ``Instead of going out to eat four times a week, they will go
out three times. They are looking for whatever ways they can cut
corners,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   To attract more Canadians this winter, a major incentive program
has been launched in Toronto, Ottawa and Montreal by the Arizona
Office of Tourism, Rydall said. The ``Canadian Cactus Days discount
program'' offers discounts at 350 Arizona businesses, from RV parks
to dude ranches to five-star resorts. Participating car-rental
agencies, restaurants, Jeep tours and retailers are offering 5 to
50 percent discounts, and some are accepting Canadian dollars at
face value.
</P>
<P>
   For Valley residents who have long been tested by snowbirds'
driving, the change in migratory habits may be welcome.
</P>
<P>
   But for others, the snowbirds' fading song, like the silence of
the miners' canary, may be cause to worry. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-14-98 1627EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
