<DOCNO> NYT19981014.0221 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-14 16:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6874 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-COURT-BALLOT-HNS &LR;      10-14 0711
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COURT-BALLOT-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SUPREME COURT REVIEWS COLORADO REGULATIONS ON BALLOT INITIATIVES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MARK HELM  
 c.1998 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A Colorado law regulating the circulation of
petitions to put voter initiatives on the state ballot came under
tough scrutiny Wednesday by the Supreme Court.
</P>
<P>
   The law, which allows only registered voters to circulate the
petitions, violates the First Amendment right to free speech,
according to the American Constitutional Law Foundation, a public
interest group that filed suit against the state seeking to
overturn the statute.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly half the states allow voter-initiated ballot questions,
and voters increasingly are bypassing their legislatures and making
law through such grass-roots efforts.
</P>
<P>
   The court's decision, expected by July, could help determine how
rigorously states are allowed to regulate that process.
</P>
<P>
   In oral arguments before the high court, Colorado state Attorney
General Gale A. Norton told the justices Wednesday that the state's
law is needed to fight fraud by petition circulators.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to know who these people are and to be able to find
them later if we discover voter fraud has taken place,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   But several justices seemed unconvinced.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why is it easier to deal with fraud better with registered
voters?'' asked Justice Antonin Scalia, adding sarcastically, ``Do
you think Coloradans are more honest than non-Coloradans?''
</P>
<P>
   Norton insisted that permitting only registered voters to be
circulators allowed the state to keep track of them in case fraud
charges arose after the election.
</P>
<P>
   Scalia then asked how many people the state has prosecuted for
voter fraud in the last few years. No one recently, Norton
answered.
</P>
<P>
   Justice John Paul Stevens asked why the state could not just
require circulators to give their names and addresses to a state
election office.
</P>
<P>
   Norton answered that allowing only registered voters to
circulate petitions ensured that they were residents of Colorado,
which meant they could be subpoenaed in the event of a fraud case.
If a petition circulator were allowed to be a resident of another
state, she explained, Colorado officials could not enforce the
subpoena.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to Stevens and Scalia, Justices Sandra Day O'Connor,
Ruth Bader Ginsburg and David H. Souter each raised concerns about
Colorado's regulations.
</P>
<P>
   O'Connor said she failed to understand why a person who is not a
registered voter couldn't circulate petitions ``just as well as a
registered voter.''
</P>
<P>
   Ginsburg questioned why the state didn't just ask the companies
that hired the petition circulators to supply their names and
addresses when needed.
</P>
<P>
   Souter questioned whether the Colorado law didn't violate a
previous Supreme Court decision.
</P>
<P>
   The state adopted the law in 1993, a year after 10 initiatives,
a record number, were placed on Colorado's ballot. Besides
requiring petition circulators to be registered voters, the law
says they must wear badges identifying themselves as paid or
volunteer workers. It also says initiative backers must file
reports with the state identifying all paid petition circulators
and the amounts they were paid.
</P>
<P>
   In 1997, after the law foundation and a group of state residents
challenged the law, the 10th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals struck
it down.
</P>
<P>
   Neil O'Toole, a Denver lawyer representing the challengers, said
the state law attacked the ``very core of free political speech.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Those regulations had a chilling effect on the state's
political process,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But Justice Anthony M. Kennedy said, ``Having a person wearing a
badge saying they are paid or unpaid is something that I believe
promotes free speech because it gives the voter more information.''
</P>
<P>
   To get a measure on the Colorado ballot, supporters must collect
the signatures of at least 5 percent of the total votes cast in the
most recent race for secretary of state.
</P>
<P>
   Colorado's appeal is supported in a friend-of-the-court brief
submitted by the Council of State Governments and 13 other states _
Alaska, Arizona, California, Idaho, Iowa, Kansas, Maine,
Mississippi, Oklahoma, Ohio, Oregon, South Dakota and Washington.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
