<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CPT-COMPUTERS-BOMBAY-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HACKERS HAVE BETTER THINGS TO DO 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)  By DR. EMILIO BOMBAY  
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   DEAR DR. BOMBAY: You really blew it with that reader hearing
door noises, Bombay! Hackers have a program called Back Orifice
that lets them control anybody's computer, including making weird
noises.
</P>
<P>
   _ Know It All
</P>
<P>
   DEAR ALL: Dial the paranoia down a notch, OK? Back Orifice is a
remote administration tool released by the self-aggrandizing hacker
group Cult of the Dead Cow. For BO to work, you have to install a
host program on the computer under ``attack.'' True, hackers can
disguise the host or tack it onto a real program, but anybody
stupid enough to run unknown software from an untrusted source
pretty much deserves what they get.
</P>
<P>
   Assuming the host is installed, the hacker still has to find
where, precisely, the computer is attached to the Internet, and a
bunch of other stuff has to be in sync before anything can happen.
Do you really think a true hacker is going to waste time just
playing a stupid sound file after all that?
</P>
<P>
   DEAR DR. BOMBAY: I had to laugh when I read the letter from
Haunted II. I thought anybody with half a peanut for a brain knew
that America Online plays sounds when anybody on your Buddy List
signs on or off. A creaky door opens when they sign on, then slams
when they sign off.
</P>
<P>
   _ Hearing Things
</P>
<P>
   DEAR THINGS: That certainly makes more sense than a rampaging
band of wild-eyed hackers terrorizing complete strangers. I'd
really like to thank the hundreds of AOLers who wrote in to point
out what a pinhead I am for not knowing the answer immediately. You
folks can now go back to hanging around chat rooms posing as
teen-age nymphomaniacs.
</P>
<P>
   DEAR DR. BOMBAY: Following your description of how to launch the
Excel 97 ``flight simulator,'' I am unable to achieve the results
described in your article. Will you please send me the routine to
follow in case there was a misprint in my paper?
</P>
<P>
   _ No Luck Yet
</P>
<P>
   DEAR NO: Don't start blaming copy editors. Sure, their jobs seem
duller than anyone could possibly describe, but I don't think even
they would stoop to snipping out random bits of information or
arbitrarily changing the odd word here or there solely for their
own amusement.
</P>
<P>
   Some of these tricks are for specific versions of software.
Maybe you don't have the right one, or you got a step wrong. It
happens. Don't make yourself crazy if they don't work. Go on to the
next one. Speaking of which ...
</P>
<P>
   STUPID SOFTWARE TRICK: A tip o' the sombrero to Dorothy for this
Word 97 time-waster.
</P>
<P>
   Open a new document, type in ``Blue'' (without the quotes) and
highlight it. Click on the Format menu, then Font. Choose bold for
the font style and blue for the color, then click OK. Put a space
after the word, then click on the Help menu and pick About
Microsoft Word.
</P>
<P>
   In the splash screen that appears, there's a vertical graphic on
the left. Hold down Control and Shift while you left-click on it.
Yes, that really is a pinball game next to the scrolling list of
Word developers. Use Z and M to control the flippers.
</P>
<P>
   I hear that Word 95 contains the same surprise, minus the
pinball. Aren't you glad you spent all that money to upgrade?
</P>
<P>
   (Noted computerologist Dr. Emilio Bombay offers occasionally
accurate advice about most things electronic. He can be reached on
Internet at drbombay(at)star-telegram.com; via snail-mail at Fort
Worth Star-Telegram, Box 1870, Fort Worth 76101; or fax: (817)
390-7257. His real name is Michael Gerst, editorial systems manager
for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram. Visit the Star-Telegram's online
services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-10-09-98 1616EDT &QL;
</P>
