<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-14 17:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6994 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CPT-COMPUTER-COLUMN-H     10-14 1010
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CPT-COMPUTER-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DIRECT BUYING PUTS PC MAKERS ON ALERT
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)  By DWIGHT SILVERMAN  
c.1998 Houston Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Buying a PC for the home used to be so simple. You walked into
an overcrowded electronics or computer store, dealt with a
salesperson who may or may not know more than you about computers,
settled for what's in stock and then hoped you could get it home in
the back seat of your compact car.
</P>
<P>
   Today, you can still have that _ ahem! _ thrilling shopping
experience, or you can buy your PC direct from the manufacturer: by
phone or over the Internet. Increasingly, those who've owned their
first or second PCs are buying direct, a trend that has alarmed
computer makers who push their goods through retailers.
</P>
<P>
   In response, the traditional PC manufacturers _ Compaq, IBM,
Hewlett-Packard, NEC/Packard Bell _ are adopting the tricks of the
direct trade. You can buy some of their systems online, and in some
cases they've set up kiosks in stores for direct ordering. Buyers
pick the features they want and the custom-built PCs are shipped
directly to their homes. No more cramming 17-inch monitors into the
back seat of a Chevy Cavalier.
</P>
<P>
   Here's a look at two high-end PCs, each sold using some form of
direct marketing. One's from a traditional PC company, and the
other's from the most non-traditional computer maker around.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Enthusiast 2 _ $2,863, iDot.com.
</P>
<P>
   You knew this was destined to happen. With the success of
businesses like CDNow and Amazon.com _ which sell music and books
on the Web, respectively _ someone was bound to start a Web-only
PC-sales operation. And iDot.com is it, at www.idot.com.
</P>
<P>
   Austin-based iDot sells PCs built out of brand-name components
and aims them at knowledgeable computer users. The company targets
gamers, computing enthusiasts, home/- &QL; 
small office buyers and students. It offers base configurations for
each of these niches, which a buyer can tweak online at will.
</P>
<P>
   I tried the Enthusiast 2 model, which comes with a 450-megahertz
Pentium II chip, 128 megabytes of memory, a 10-gigabyte hard drive,
a 40X CD-ROM drive, a 56K fax modem, 3-D audio, Advent speakers
with a subwoofer, a 19-inch monitor and an Intel i740 AGP graphics
card. I upgraded the video by replacing that with an 8-MB Matrox
Millenium G200 card, and added a 12-MB Voodoo2 graphics card for
3-D games.
</P>
<P>
   The iDot system arrived with some problems, some of which were
easily solved. Others I'm still living with.
</P>
<P>
   The video card, for example, was not seated properly so the
system wouldn't even boot up when I first turned it on. At first I
thought the system was dead on arrival, but reinserting the card
was the easy fix.
</P>
<P>
   Then, I discovered that if connected to America Online via
dial-up, the computer rebooted when I signed off. I downloaded new
modem drivers, but now I'm having difficulty dialing in to my
Internet provider. I can get through, but it takes several tries
before the Lucent fax modem connects.
</P>
<P>
   (In general, I've had problems with Lucent modems, which are
used in other brands of computers. iDot offers a 3Com 56K fax modem
as an option, and it's one worth taking.)
</P>
<P>
   Otherwise, this is a slick, fast machine. Its zippiness has a
lot to do with its massive amount of high-speed memory and its
snappy hard drive, which spins at 7,200 revolutions per minute.
Like most systems sold direct, there is very little in the way of
glitzy add-ons to slow it down. It comes with Windows 98, some
games on CD _ you install 'em yourself _ and that's about it. It's
an excellent game system, particularly with the Voodoo2 card
installed.
</P>
<P>
   If you want top speed, want to be able to design your own system
and already have the software you need to be productive _ or have
fun _ then iDot's PCs are worth considering.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Presario 5600 _ $2,499, Compaq Computer Corp.
</P>
<P>
   You can buy this high-powered Presario, which just bristles with
bells and whistles, either at Compaq's Web site or in a store. At
those retailers who are participating in Compaq's Built-for-You
program, you can configure one and have it shipped to your door.
</P>
<P>
   The 5600 series is Compaq's attempt to compete with direct PC
sellers. Many of its components, such as the modem and the video
card, can be easily replaced, and the internal design is greatly
simplified. When you open it up, there's lots of room to work
inside and plenty of free expansion slots.
</P>
<P>
   The 5600 I tried had a 450-Mhz Pentium II chip, 128 MB of
memory, a 16.8-GB hard drive, 3-D sound, a 56K Rockwell fax modem,
a DVD-ROM drive, a built-in Ethernet connection, an ATI Rage Pro LT
video card and an internal Iomega Zip drive. The price quoted here
doesn't include a monitor.
</P>
<P>
   Like all Presarios, it comes with a keyboard with four buttons
that take you to various Web sites. While the software that
configures the buttons is easier to use than its initial version,
it's still not quite simple enough.
</P>
<P>
   This is also a speedy computer, but it lags behind the iDot
because its hard drive is not as fast. I added a 12-MB Voodoo2 card
to this system, and it ran demanding 3D games without a hitch.
</P>
<P>
   The Presario is a good choice if you're interested in working
with digital video. It includes a Firewire connector _ also known
as IEEE 1394 _ which lets it link up with newer video and audio
components. It also has video-out jacks so you can plug it into a
TV set _ particularly handy given that this computer has a DVD
drive.
</P>
<P>
   While the hardware in this system may be streamlined, Compaq
continues to make the software environment a messy place. There are
too many programs that run in the background, including one that
checks an Internet server for software upgrades and the
Internet-button controller. Fortunately, if you want a cleaner
system, you can disable these. In computing, simpler is almost
always better.
</P>
<P>
   Got a comment or question about computing? Send e-mail to
dwight.silverman at chron.com &QL; 
XXXXEND OF STORY
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-10-09-98 1410EDT &QL;
</P>
